<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICINE-LAUGHS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY HOPES TO SHOW HEALING POWER OF LAUGHTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ROBERT MONROE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pediatrician Lonnie Zeltzer knows well the
hypnotic power of TV cartoons on kids, her own included.
</P>
<P>
   That is why she has joined Comedy Central and the University of
California, Los Angeles, to prove that the medicinal value of TV
reruns and classic comedy routines is no joke.
</P>
<P>
   With help from the likes of Bugs Bunny and Charlie Chaplin, the
doctor and a partner at UCLA's Jonsson Cancer Center are
researching whether laughter can help sick kids get better faster.
</P>
<P>
   The study they launched last week could find evidence for the
old saw that laughter is the best medicine, while disproving the
one that says TV rots your brain.
</P>
<P>
   Research in this area is about as scarce as talking rabbits. The
number of bona fide papers Zeltzer and partner Dr. Margaret Stuber
have for reference is exactly two.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing is that no one's taken something that seems so
obvious and taken a scientific look at it,'' said Zeltzer, director
of the Pediatric Pain Program at Mattel Children's Hospital at
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Cousins, the late magazine editor who coined the phrase
about laughter being the best medicine, gave the idea credence when
he decided in 1964 to battle a degenerative spinal disease from his
hotel bed while watching reruns of the television show ``Candid
Camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Cousins so believed laughter cured him that he funded studies on
the subject and even taught in UCLA's psychiatry department. He
died in 1990 after a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   For Comedy Central, proof of the cable network's curative powers
would easily repay its $75,000 investment, said Tony Fox, the
network's communications chief who sold the idea to his boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if comedy and Comedy Central in particular is good for
you?'' Fox said, thinking of his brief conversation with Chief
Executive Officer Larry Divney. ``It took all of 10 minutes to
convince him this is something worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first phase of the UCLA study, they'll screen comedy
snippets for healthy children ages 5 to 16 to help pick what works.
So far, the pair's endeavor hasn't caused any snickers among their
colleagues, a surprise to the researchers, but possibly a sign that
medicine is ready to get serious about comedy, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's making fun of it,'' Stuber said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers want to start with the classics: Abbott and
Costello, Chaplin and ``I Love Lucy.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeltzer loves the one where Lucy's on the chocolate factory
assembly line ``where she's trying to handle it and put it in her
mouth. The candy's going down. She's got to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeltzer and Stuber aren't ruling out modern comedy either. If
Abbott and Costello's ``Who's on first'' routine doesn't get
cackles, maybe they will find success with Bart Simpson's ``Don't
have a cow, man.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Rx Laughter'' study is the brainchild of former CBS and
ABC executive Sherry Hilber, who brought the idea to Stuber, a
psychiatrist at Jonsson Cancer Center. The Beverly Hills resident
said she had always wondered what might be happening physically to
the studio audiences she would watch guffawing at ``Roseanne''
tapings.
</P>
<P>
   What Zeltzer and Stuber turn up might bolster evidence that
laughter prompts the brain to release endorphins, the body's
version of morphine.
</P>
<P>
   They will also test the effect of comedy on the autonomic
nervous system, the brain-body connection that governs the
fight/flight response to scary encounters and affects functions
ranging from heart rate to saliva production.
</P>
<P>
   It is relatively untrod territory.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what sparse research there is comes from Dr. Lee Berk, a
neuroimmunologist at Loma Linda University Medical Center in Loma
Linda. Using funds from Cousins, he found that laughter, by means
unknown, suppresses the body's release of cortisol, a hormone that
adrenal glands dump into the bloodstream in times of high stress
that weaken the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   It's Berk's belief that there's so much going on chemically
during a good belly laugh that the Food and Drug Administration
would have to regulate crackups if it only knew.
</P>
<P>
   The medical establishment, though, has treated humor therapy as
a laughing matter, Berk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicine is too arrogant. It does not realize the efficacy or
therapeutic impact of humor. In America we tend to look for the
pill,'' Berk said.
</P>
<P>
   Stuber and Zeltzer agree that television has a certain, say,
mind-numbing effect on children. They are both parents after all.
</P>
<P>
   And Zeltzer found in studies in the late 1970s that when
children were placed under hypnosis and asked to go to a ``happy
place,'' they invariably ended up in front of the TV.
</P>
<P>
   And what were they watching? Cartoons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
