<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICASCUP-USLOSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH PRADA SINKS US HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The quest began in 1983 in Newport,
R.I., when a sailing team from Sardinia, Italy, with more style
than skill, showed up to take on the best sailors in the world.
That group went home early.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, some 17 years later, Italy knocked America out of the
America's Cup for the first time in the event's 149-year history.
</P>
<P>
   In an uneventful, anticlimactic race on the Hauraki Gulf course,
Luna Rossa, the boat of the Prada campaign from Milan, turned on
the midrange boat speed and simply sailed away from Paul Cayard's
AmericaOne from San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Luna Rossa beat AmericaOne by 49 seconds to win the series, 5-4.
It was the closest America's Cup challenger series in history.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Cayard skippering of Il Moro in 1992 that
brought Italy her greatest sailing moment before Saturday as Il
Moro won that Louis Vuitton Cup over New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   This year, after coming from a 3-1 deficit to a 4-3 lead in the
Louis Vuitton Cup, Paul Cayard, tactician John Kostecki, and a boat
that was just slightly off the pace in winds of 12-14 knots, ran
out of tricks, and Cayard's miraculous comeback of the last week
fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, as the champagne sprayed the Prada boat and crew,
Cayard was standing alone at the helm of AmericaOne as it headed
for home one last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of what AmericaOne did here,'' said Cayard, whose
$30 million budget is less than half of Prada's, and whose campaign
started a year later. ``We put our best foot forward and did our
best against Italy's $100 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat a lot of entries from the US,'' he said, noting again
his belief that too many challengers from the United States dilutes
the resources. ``We're proud to have beat the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   For Prada, three years of hard work in the boat paid off as
Francesco de Angelis and his tactician, Torben Grael, were able to
sail the kind of race that first propelled them to the top of the
list of 11 original challengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team has worked very hard every day,'' said de
Angelis. ```Everyone is part of the win in this series. We are very
happy today, but we are not yet at our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning of the October trials, there were five entries
from the United States hoping to challenge New Zealand in the Cup
match, which will begin Feb. 19. Now there are none. The
high-budget Prada team has been sailing in Auckland since January
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The silver boat with the scarlet stripe got ahead before the end
of Leg 1 Saturday and was able to sail as a front-runner, picking
the shifts at will, and sailing easy, loose cover around the
18-mile course.
</P>
<P>
   While Grael watched AmericaOne maneuvering behind him, looking
for an attack that never came, de Angelis kept Luna Rossa on a
familiar track _ smooth and steady. Soon it was clear, the gray
boat with the lime trim would have no attack move.
</P>
<P>
   The five-minute prestart was unusually cautious for the skippers
who have mixed it up in the past. Near the end, Cayard was able to
squeeze between Prada and the committee boat, taking the right,
which Kostecki thought was favored.
</P>
<P>
   But after a long drag race out to the right side, followed by
several tacks, Prada opened up its lead at every tack, finally able
to cross AmericaOne on port as the wind shifted back and forth.
This signaled Luna Rossa's commanding position, and it swung
through the top mark with a 34-second lead.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a slight speed advantage downwind, AmericaOne could
find no attack lanes. At first, Cayard positioned to the right, but
the wind, veering left, favored Luna Rossa, and it stretched the
second-leg lead another five seconds despite AmericaOne's attempt
to blanket its air.
</P>
<P>
   Back up the beat, Luna Rossa stretched out the lead yet and,
sailing with ever more confidence, stretched it to 47 seconds at
the halfway point.
</P>
<P>
   From that point, despite everything Cayard and Kostecki could
think of, there was simply no match race contact, and the last 9
miles turned into a sad parade for the thousands of lime-green flag
wavers in the spectator fleet of more than 1,200 boats.
</P>
<P>
   The day started out with a 7 a.m. subplot. Prada's boss,
Patrizio Bertelli, let loose with the song ``Luna Rossa (Red
Moon)'' dozens of times for three straight hours. Prada's compound
speakers were placed as close as possible to the fence between then
neighboring camps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
