<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0005 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8146 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CROUSE-GATHERS-LA     02-06 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-GATHERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LMU'S BASKETBALL FORTUNES PLUMMETED FOLLOWING GATHER'S DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 
w/BKC-LMU-GATHERS, BKC-GATHERS, BKC-KIMBLE-GATHERS 
ATTN: Philadelphia (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ten years after Hank Gathers' death, it remains
true what his college coach Paul Westhead said at the time: ``It's
the unexpected moments when it hits you.''
</P>
<P>
   The awful reminder of what happened on the Gersten Pavilion
floor on March 4, 1990, ambushed me while I lay drifting off on the
couch, lulled to sleep's edges by Regis Philbin's voice on ``Do You
Want to be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Philbin asked the contestant if he could identify the device
used to restore a heart's rhythm and my eyes flew open. Suddenly I
was wide awake. Reflexively as a scream, the answer escaped my lips
before it popped upon the screen.
</P>
<P>
   A defibrillator. You know, the device that was supposed to be
Gathers' lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   For me, defibrillator will always be a word that restores my
heart's ache. I can't hear the word without thinking of Gathers'
death and all the grief and goodwill and guilt and gallantry it
triggered.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question, I'm wiser for having chronicled for another
newspaper the Greek tragedy that commenced when Gathers crumpled to
the ground near midcourt with 13:34 remaining in the first half of
a West Coast Conference tournament semifinal game against the
University of Portland, a game that Gathers' Loyola Marymount Lions
were leading 25-13.
</P>
<P>
   An hour and 40 minutes later, outside the emergency room at
Daniel Freeman Marina Hospital, Gathers, a gargantuan talent, was
pronounced dead. Over the next few months, those of us assigned to
the story would get a crash course in medicine and law.
</P>
<P>
   We would learn much about cardiac arrhythmia and court
procedures; defibrillators and depositions; human nature and the
human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   In death, so many life lessons were gleaned.
</P>
<P>
   From the player who couldn't outrun his own wildly racing heart,
Jeff Fryer learned to listen to his own heart, the better to follow
it.
</P>
<P>
   Fryer was the third-leading scorer on a 1989-90 Lions team that
led the nation in offense. He was to 3-pointers what Gathers was to
dunks: Money in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   During the NCAA Tournament, which followed like a rainbow the
emotional storm of Gathers' death, Fryer played as though divinely
inspired. Along with Gathers' best friend Bo Kimble, Fryer helped
the Lions pick off New Mexico State and defending national champion
Michigan and Alabama before they were snuffed out by eventual
champion UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   After his graduation from LMU later that year, Fryer kicked
around in the European pro leagues before returning to his alma
mater to work in its summer camps program. He had moved on to UC
Irvine's fund-raising department when he had, not long ago, one of
those unexpected moments when it hits you.
</P>
<P>
   Fryer was pushing papers around on his desk, a slave of
convention working 9 to 5, when he realized he didn't need to be
chained to an office; not yet, anyway. A few weeks later he was on
his way to Dusseldorf, Germany, to play for the Neuwerk Lions (no
small irony there) of the German West Regional League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that God has blessed me with the ability to play
basketball so why not make the most of it?'' Fryer said by
telephone from Germany. ``What happened to Hank makes me want to be
in a way more adventurous. I want to see the world while I can
because you never know what's going to happen tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Fryer hadn't been back in Germany very long when he had another
one of those unexpected moments. A Dutch teammate invited Fryer and
a few other players to his apartment to watch a television movie
about Gathers and Kimble.
</P>
<P>
   It was surreal for Fryer, re-living the unspeakable in a
Dutch-subtitled film in the middle of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just brought back memories of (Gathers' death) and reminded
me of how full of energy Hank was,'' Fryer said. ``It was kind of
sad in a way, the way they made the story out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   It was sad, how lawyers retained by Gathers' family made good
people such as Westhead and LMU trainer Chip Schaefer out to be.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer was one of the first to reach Gathers after he
collapsed. He began administering cardiopulmonary resuscitation
immediately. Schaefer had been especially close to Gathers. And
yet, in one of the first multimillion-dollar lawsuits filed by
Beverly Hills attorney Bruce Fagel on behalf of Gathers' mother,
three brothers, aunt and son, he was among those deemed culpable in
the player's death.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer was accused of negligence because he didn't use a
defibrillator on Gathers until after the player had been
transported on a stretcher out of view of the 3,000 horrified
spectators.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Schaefer is nagged by guilt, though not for the
reasons outlined in the lawsuit that was settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that's made it hard for me is I had a
relationship with Hank on a personal level,'' said Schaefer, in his
first year on the Lakers' training staff after spending eight years
with the Chicago Bulls. ``One of the things I live with is that
perhaps he may have taken chances with his medication, thinking,
`If anything happens, Chip has my back.'''
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy report on Gathers listed the cause of his death as
cardiomyopathy and showed sub-therapeutic levels of Inderal, the
heart-stabilizing drug the player's doctors had prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard that the autopsy indicated he had a dosage in him
below what had been prescribed, that's what made me feel like maybe
because of the level of trust we had built up he was taking chances
with his medication,'' Schaefer said before a recent Lakers game.
``That's one of the things that haunts me, that he may have been
doing things with his medication that I could have stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   It would come out after Gathers' death that he had blown off at
least one of his weekly treadmill tests in the days leading up to
the WCC tournament. It was no secret the Inderal made Gathers feel
sluggish and that he felt the medication was hampering his play.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys for the player's family would accuse Westhead of
leaning on Gathers' doctors to reduce his medication because it was
affecting the strapping senior forward's performance. All Westhead
said he did was ask Gathers' doctors if there were other
medications the player might be able to take that would leave him
less sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   That he was blamed for the death of a player he treated like a
son was devastating to Westhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the legal world, things get turned, twisted, chopped,
patched and re-patched,'' he said at the time by way of defending
himself. ``Suddenly what was done with caring and concern can be
twisted into something appearing uncaring and selfish.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about all Westhead would say to try to patch up his
wounded reputation. The years haven't loosened his tongue much.
Over the telephone last week Westhead said, ``I thought it was a
very indelicate situation involving Hank,'' and left it at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to respond back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You can hear the sadness in his voice even before he articulates
it. ``I don't think my hurt for the loss of Hank will ever
diminish,'' he said. ``It certainly had a strong impact on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Westhead left LMU in the fall of 1990 to become the head coach
of the Denver Nuggets. After being forced out of Denver in 1992, he
coached four years at George Mason University. He assisted P.J.
Carlesimo at Golden State until the Warriors purged their coaching
staff in December. Westhead, who continues to do scouting for the
Warriors, is back in Southern California where he has been a
virtual stranger since leaving LMU and the lawsuits related to
Gathers' death in his rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Westhead says it's not the ghost of Gathers that has kept him
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some career decisions based on choices that were
available,'' Westhead said. ``I probably would have made the
decisions regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth? For those bound by the tragedy, the ghosts will
always be there, whether or not we choose to acknowledge them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 0050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
