<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8147 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-KIMBLE-GATHERS-LA     02-06 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KIMBLE-GATHERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LMU'S BASKETBALL FORTUNES PLUMMETED FOLLOWING GATHER'S DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 
w/BKC-CROUSE-GATHERS, BKC-GATHERS, BKC-LMU-GATHERS 
ATTN: Philadelphia (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bo Kimble is back in the old neighborhood. He's
back in a lot of rundown neighborhoods, like the one he grew up in
with Hank Gathers in north Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Kimble had been searching for a place, for a new vocation, since
he finally faced up to end of his professional basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 12 months I'm been pretty much just trying to
find out what out what I wanted to do when basketball was over,''
Kimble said. ``Now that I'm retired, I wanted to do something where
you could feel a direct impact from what you were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   His search took him back to the rough streets of Philadelphia,
to the slums from which he and Gathers had vowed to each other they
would one day escape.
</P>
<P>
   Their means was basketball and it took them from Dobbins Tech
High, to USC, and to the national spotlight at Loyola Marymount.
There, Gathers' dream ended too soon, when he collapsed on the
court and died shortly after of a heart disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Kimble went onto fame and fortune, if not all the success he had
envisioned in the NBA. Still, after being selected eighth overall
in the 1990 draft by the Clippers, he signed a $7.5 million
contract that is still paying out, well past his three-year NBA
career.
</P>
<P>
   But after bouncing around the CBA, after playing for several
teams in Europe and visiting 35 countries with a touring team,
Kimble saw limited opportunity and a bad back doubling up on him,
pointing him toward the end of his playing career.
</P>
<P>
   And so he has gone back, now 33 and married, to the blighted
areas of Philadelphia. Last fall he started the Kimble Foundation,
a nonprofit organization that buys abandoned and foreclosed homes.
The Philadelphia Housing Authority provides matching funds to
refurbish the homes and then helps find an underprivileged family
to buy or rent the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine how many homes in Philadelphia are abandoned
and dilapidated,'' said David Spencer, who as an assistant coach
with the Trojans recruited Kimble to USC, later became his agent
and now works for the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable how much needs to be done in that city.
Sometimes you drive around looking to find these homes, and you go
in them and see what kind of shape they're in, and you start
thinking they ought to just tear it all down. It's scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's kind of like the corny idea of giving something back.
And he's doing it kind of quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer said Kimble either already owns or has bids in on
approximately 30 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Kimble doesn't plan on stopping there, either. He wants 100
homes by the end of summer. He wants to add restaurants and other
retail shops. He plans to take his program nationally and hopes to
persuade other athletes and entertainers to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Bo wants to do something, I think, `That's not
going to work,''' Spencer said. ``Then I think, if I was Bo, I
probably think it would because everything I've touched has worked.
He has that kind of attitude and it helps him make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those, though, that claim his NBA career never worked.
Certainly, it did not to the extent Kimble had long dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   Kimble turned into something of a national sensation when he led
Loyola to an improbable NCAA postseason run following the death of
Gathers. He had become more than just the nation's leading scorer:
an almost beloved figure.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers selected him with their first pick, put him on the
media-guide cover with Danny Manning and Charles Smith, and started
him as a 6-foot-4 rookie shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   Within two months, he was on the bench and his NBA career would
never recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Bo and Magic in L.A. for a time there,'' Spencer said.
``People just loved Bo, because of everything that happened at
Loyola. They bench Bo and this guy (Jeff Martin) comes in and
doesn't do squat. Bo has to adjust to coming off the bench and
doesn't handle that well.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they're not going to the playoffs. If I'm (Clippers coach)
Mike Schuler, I play him the whole year no matter what. You're
paying him that much and he's a rookie, I'm going to give him every
opportunity to make the adjustment. He just hadn't found his timing
to get his shot selection down. He wasn't used to having any shot
selection.''
</P>
<P>
   And that might have been part of Kimble's problem. At Loyola,
Kimble had excelled at running Paul Westhead's fast-paced, all-out
press, running style.
</P>
<P>
   But Stan Morrison, Kimble's former coach at USC, said the style
of play that made him such a national sensation might have been his
undoing at the NBA level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible to watch, but the reality of it is, that
style doesn't provide all the carryover skills for playing in the
NBA,'' Morrison said. ``Bo was the one who got a shot at it. And
all of a sudden he swallowed really hard because he didn't have the
foundation of skills and fundamentals that are part of the NBA game
needed to survive. That doesn't mean he didn't have the talent, it
just means he didn't have that base that everybody else gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you played quarterback at Oklahoma under Bud Wilkinson and
ran the option and get drafted in the NFL by a team that runs the
I-formation, you're dead. That's the reality of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimble started 22 of the Clippers' first 23 games, averaging
11.9 points. But he shot only .380 percent from the field. By the
time the season ended, he hadn't gotten off the bench in 11 games
and was on the injured list for the final nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have had an opportunity,'' Kimble said.
``Unfortunately, the Clippers, most of the NBA fans, and myself,
missed out on some of the great things I was able to do in Loyola.
We were robbed of that opportunity to do that in the NBA. I had no
doubt if I was able to be developed with a good organization, like
the Lakers are doing with Kobe (Bryant), there would have been a
better outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my biggest mistake was trying to fit in, when I should
have just been the player I was at Loyola. If I could rewind the
tape nine years, I'd love to take care of that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The next season, Kimble appeared in only 34 games, averaging
just 3.4 points per game. He was disappearing. The next season, the
Clippers forced the Knicks to take him in a trade for Smith. He
spent one season on the Knicks bench, playing in just nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing Kimble would never play in New York, Spencer
negotiated a buyout. Kimble said he has another seven years left on
the buyout and is set financially. But his NBA career was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured he'd make it in the NBA and do well,'' said Jeff
Fryer, a former Loyola teammate. ``Every day in practice he'd have
the most incredible moves. He'd come out with something new every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer said it bothers him that many view Kimble as a
disappointment because he was never able to become an impact player
in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing thing,'' Spencer said. ``He's scored more
points in a single college season than all but two human beings. He
was an All-American, he signed a contract for $7.5 million, made
more than $10 million overall. He played in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet there are many people out there who see Bo as a failure
because he didn't really make it or become an All-Star or whatever
in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have mattered little, of course, what Kimble accomplished
in the NBA. He was destined to forever be known at the player who
lifted his unheralded team from the heartbreaking loss of Gathers,
to one game from the Final Four. As the player who saluted his
former teammate by shooting his first free throw of each postseason
game left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bo was pretty wonderful,'' said Brian Quinn, the former Loyola
athletic director. ``He was very strong. He was very positive. He
was a pillar of strength through everything, all the way to the
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I know it was terribly difficult for him. But he was the
strength, the backbone, he became the leader. Hank was the man
before, then Bo took that role and led all of us and I think gave
all of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall Kimble was part of a touring team, which included
former UCLA star Charles O'Bannon, that played colleges in the
preseason. Now 33 and knowing his back pain was limiting him,
Kimble decided this tour would be his last professional gig. The
team's final game was at USC, where his and Gathers' college
careers had begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this is the place where I first started, it would be
ironic that this is where I played my last game,'' Kimble said. ``I
felt good about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 0052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
