<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8148 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-LMU-GATHERS-LADN     02-06 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LMU-GATHERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LMU'S BASKETBALL FORTUNES PLUMMETED FOLLOWING GATHER'S DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 
w/BKC-CROUSE-GATHERS, BKC-GATHERS, BKC-KIMBLE-GATHERS (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Four starters graduated. Three key reserves either
transferred, quit or were suspended. The player who stepped up to
become the leading scorer broke his foot.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions, once the jewel of the West Coast Conference, are one
of the nation's worst teams, with just two wins in their first 19
games.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this weekend's games at Portland and Gonzaga, the
Lions' ranking in the Ratings Percentage Index was 315 - out of 319
Division I teams.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before the school retires the numbers of two of its
greatest players Hank Gathers and Bo Kimble - the team is last in
the WCC in offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' LMU athletic director Bill Husak said.
``We've got some talented kids. Our kids are trying hard. I know
our coaches are still putting forward a good effort.''
</P>
<P>
   After barely beating tiny Cal Baptist (78-74) in its season
opener, LMU lost its next 11 games. A win over another small
school, Occidental College (69-50), was followed by a six-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a program in the country that can handle it when
starters get injured and when starters transfer,'' said former LMU
assistant Gib Arnold, who is now at Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the team's only problem, however. Only three of LMU's
12 players from last year are on the team, and the Lions are headed
for their fourth consecutive losing season.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1989-90 season, when coach Paul Westhead had the Lions
scoring more than 100 points a game and Kimble shot his free-throws
left-handed in the NCAA Tournament, the program is 67 games under
.500.
</P>
<P>
   Some have felt the LMU administration, in the wake of Gathers'
death and reports of recruiting violations, didn't like the
negative attention and de-emphasized the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard those stories when I came in, that the university and
the program wanted to take a deep breath and evaluate things,''
Husak said. ``Since I've been here, there's been a very strong
commitment to athletics on the part of the university.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior forward Elton Mashack is the only starter who played
significantly last year, and he's struggled. Rupert McClendon, a
senior guard, was averaging a team-leading 11.2 points prior to WCC
play before a stress fracture in his foot sidelined him
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Slaughter, a 6-foot-7 sophomore guard, has been one of
the season's few bright spots, averaging 11.7 points and four
rebounds a game. Slaughter only played in 12 games last year,
starting none.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Wolfe, a senior forward who was being counted upon this
season, was suspended just before Christmas. Robert Davis, who
averaged 7.1 points last year, transferred to a junior college in
Arizona over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WCC is a real tough conference with really tough
coaches,'' said Dave Fehtre, an LMU assistant under Jay Hillock
from 1991 to '94. ``You've got to get some players and be ready to
play every night. I don't care who you are. You've got to have
bullets in the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   If coach Charles Bradley is around to help rebuild is anyone's
guess. The Lions were 7-20 and 11-16 in Bradley's first two
seasons, and he's in the last year of the contract he signed after
coming to LMU from Denver's Metro State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Charles wants to win,'' Arnold said. ``It's just a
tough situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley isn't talking to the media. But those who know him or
have worked around him in the past speak highly of the man who was
a first-round NBA draft pick by the Boston Celtics in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always personable and he was great to have here,'' said
Ralph Zobell, who works in the sports information department at
Brigham Young, where Bradley was an assistant from 1989-94. ``I've
always found him to be positive and upbeat. He's a teaser.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Crookham, an assistant athletic director at Metro State,
said everyone liked Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things he brought to the table was his
experience,'' Crookham said. ``He knows the game inside and out.
Everybody enjoyed the whole time when he was here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley is working under a boss - Husak - who came to LMU in
1998 after almost 20 years of athletics success at Long Beach
State, particularly in men's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liken our program to a stagecoach with a team of horses and
the lead horse is men's basketball,'' said Husak.
</P>
<P>
   Husak said he will evaluate the program after the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 0052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
