r s BC-CAR-CUP-SHOCKS-TEX     02-06 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CUP-SHOCKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINSTON CUP DRIVERS GET A LIFT FROM NASCAR-ISSUED SHOCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASCAR has mandated a new treatment for Winston Cup drivers worn
out by the pain of qualifying around the Daytona International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   It's shock therapy, a program that will be in full force when
front-row Bud Pole Qualifying for the season-opening Daytona 500
gets under way on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to smooth out the ride, make the cars safer at
speed and cut costs, NASCAR has eliminated the use of custom-made
shock absorbers at the 2.5-mile DIS and 2.66-mile Talladega (Ala.)
Superspeedway. Those are the biggest and fastest tracks on the Cup
schedule. NASCAR began mandating use of carburetor restrictor
plates to reduce speeds at those two supertracks in 1988. Next
weekend, the sanctioning body will issue four shocks to each team
attempting to qualify at Daytona, as well as require a specific
spring rate.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers participating in preseason testing generally have
praised the new shock rule as the perfect cure for the
track-scraping, jaw-rattling hot laps they have endured for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the feel of it,'' Jeremy Mayfield said after testing
the new package at Talladega. ``We went from sore backs and jaws
and headaches to feeling pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember going out and running tests, and it used to
beat you to death. You couldn't even talk on the radio. You'd turn
sideways and bounce up and down. You'd be sore in the ribs. Next
day you'd get in the car and say, `Man, I dread this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The rough ride Mayfield described was the product of
``designer'' shock technology bordering on the letter of the rule
book. For the last three or four years, specialists have been
building qualifying shocks that allowed the rear ends of the
3,400-pound cars to drop down at speed. As the rear end lowered,
the rear spoiler faced less resistance from the air, reducing drag
and allowing the car to run faster. But the cars often bottomed-out
_ jolting the driver at speeds of 190-plus mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started to get to the point where it was almost getting
dangerous,'' said three-time Cup champion Jeff Gordon, driver of
the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo, and
winner of last year's Daytona 500. ``Guys were getting the cars
down so much that the cars were almost more of a skidplate going
around the racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   Speedway veteran Jimmy Spencer said a qualifying run at Daytona
or Talladega had become unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just disgusting for two laps. It was a joke,'' said
Spencer, driver of the No. 26 Big Kmart/Route 66 Ford Taurus. ``Now
they do drive a whole lot better. I mean, there's no comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't believe the car owners could afford what they were
going through. And the crew chiefs were pulling their hair out,
trying to figure out how the hell to get the car another
quarter-inch lower. Now we're using a car where we don't have to go
with 10-inch-high frame rails and tricked-up shocks and special
coil springs and just a lot of money being wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kranefuss, owner of Mayfield's No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford, said
the biggest saving will be in time for the typical crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were running one car on Friday for qualifying which has
nothing to do with what you're racing on Sunday _ which is not very
intelligent,'' Kranefuss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, it took us five hours to rebuild the car after
qualifying,'' said Sammy Johns, crew chief for Ken Schrader and the
No. 36 M&AMP;Ms Pontiac Grand Prix. ``We won't have that with these
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the saving in man-hours, not every crew chief is
enamored with the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Pemberton, crew chief for Rusty Wallace at Penske Racing
South, was among the first to test what he derisively termed the
``government-issued shocks'' at Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've got is shock guys wandering around aimlessly,''
Pemberton said. ``But any new rule is hard to work through at
first, because you're trying to cheat like hell to get your
advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Makar, crew chief for Bobby Labonte at Joe Gibbs Racing,
said that in addition to qualifying, the mandated shocks are sure
to affect a car's race-day setup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little bit discouraging to me, because that's a big
part of what we do,'' said Makar, who oversees Labonte's No. 18
Interstate Batteries Pontiac. ``There's a lot of work to be done in
the shock area to tune the car to the driver's liking. If he likes
it, that's great, he can go do his thing. But if he doesn't, I'm
not real sure what we're going to be able to do to work on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Wallace, who finished eighth in last year's Daytona
500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Qualifying is going to be effortless ... like you're driving
down the highway, probably,'' said Wallace, driver of the No. 2
Miller Lite Ford. ``There'll be a lot of things you're going to try
to do to manipulate these shock and spring rules. I know that. I
also know that it's going to be a completely different story when
it comes time to race these things.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
