A8151 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     02-06 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE STOOGES MAKE CLIPPERS A JOKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So the Clippers decided Chris Ford wasn't the
answer. But then again, neither was Bill Fitch, Bob Weiss, Larry
Brown, Mike Schuler or Don Casey.
</P>
<P>
   We could go on, since that only covers the '90s. But justified
or not, the coach constantly takes the fall for the avalanche of
losses that continually mar this so-called organization.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that the players had given up on Ford. During
Tuesday night's embarrassing loss to Golden State, center Keith
Closs his arms up-and-down in an attempt to incite the crowd into a
``We want Closs'' chant.
</P>
<P>
   Closs showed how much he wanted to play at halftime, when he
strolled on to the court, shot a 3-pointer from outside the
baseline, then went and chatted with a friend for the rest of the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Is that Ford's fault? Yes and no. He lost control of the
players, but as a two-time loser and perennial retread, what did
the Clippers expect when they hired him?
</P>
<P>
   They were too cheap to hire Doc Rivers, who is the brightest
coach in the league with Orlando, so they settled on Ford, just
eight days before the lockout was settled. They waited that long
because owner Donald T. Sterling was too cheap to pay a coach for
not working.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sterling is paying two coaches today _ Fitch ($2
million) and Ford ($900,000) remain on the payroll through the end
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Morale is so low within the organization that in the past two
months, the front office has lost employees to the Portland WNBA
franchise and the upstart L.A. Avengers of the Arena Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the coach has nearly nothing to do with the
Clippers' problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing will change until Sterling, executive vice president
Andy Roeser and vice president of basketball operations Elgin
Baylor are held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   If this were New York, the media would have run all three out of
town years ago. But here in L.A., the fans' apathy and
non-confrontational media have ignored their transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   These three stooges have been the constant over the years, but
have you ever heard any of them take the blame for anything?
</P>
<P>
   Baylor certainly never said he made a mistake during the
countless coaching changes. And he's gladly blamed Fitch when a
draft ch Roeser, who actually wields far more power than Baylor, is
viewed within the organization as Sterling's eyes and ears. He has
alienated agents for years by delivering Sterling's penny-pinching
contr to players.
</P>
<P>
   When Fitch was fired, the old coach refused to accept the news
from Baylor, and made Roeser come to his office and personally
dismiss him.
</P>
<P>
   The best rumor floating out of the Big Apple these days is that
NBA commissioner David Stern wouldn't mind taking over control of
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sterling recently told the Wall Street Journal, ``I never
sell anything I buy,'' it's the only hope Los Angeles has for
rescuing this joke of a franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Error Jordan: Well, it didn't take long for Michael Jordan to
demonstrate it's easier to be ESPN's athlete of the century than a
competent general manager, or owner resident.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan fired Wizards coach Gar Heard by phone from Atlanta,
where he was attending the Super Bowl and tending to his true
passion, making money by promoting his new Internet venture.
</P>
<P>
   He then hired Warriors assistant Rod Higgins, a long-time crony.
No problem, except His airheaded-ness never realized Golden State
must be compensated and when it asked for a draft pick, Jordan had
to back off and hire Darrell Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors did what every other team in the league would do,
showing Jordan that he can't run roughshod over the league when
making his off-the-court moves.
</P>
<P>
   The only victim is Higgins, who lost a chance to become a head
coach, only because the interested party was Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Around the league: The Pistons got a good laugh this week, when
they asked Rick Pitino if Celtics forward Danny Fortson was
available. Pitino said yes, but asked for Jerome Williams, who has
become Detroit's most improved player.
</P>
<P>
   Fortson is still expected to be traded by the Feb. 24 deadline,
because Boston does not want to sign him to a long-term contract
and wants some salary-cap flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   A more likely trade has the Pistons shipping the retired Bison
Dele (Brian Williams), Don Reid and a first-round pick to the
Wizards for Ike Austin. Washington wants Dele's $5 million salary
slot, because it will be wiped off their salary cap after the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors are still searching for a point guard, but have
become so desperate that they are waiting for Milwaukee to release
Haywoode Workman.
</P>
<P>
   A real trade: The Magic-Nuggets deal earlier this week
demonstrated how much trades are meant solely for the purpose of
creating salary-cap maneuverability.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando received Ron Mercer, Chauncey Billups and Johnny Taylor
in exchange for Chris Gatling and Tariq Abdul-Wahad.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic wouldn't mind keeping Mercer, if he's not expecting a
$70 million contract, but the real reason they made the trade is
that all three players become free agents after the season, just in
tim Doc Rivers to make a run at Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets were just happy to get some warm bodies in return
for Mercer, whom they were sure they could not re-sign. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
