<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD WAS DOOMED FROM THE START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's not just a job, it's a misadventure.
</P>
<P>
   And it has ended for Chris Ford.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clippers' latest man overboard one of the league's truly
nice citizens was doomed from the beginning. Doomed by circumstance
and by himself.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances were accompanied by peril, because hiring Ford
was as ill-conceived as strapping a sunbather to the bow of Noah's
Ark. Let's just say that as a molder of young talent, this was no
``Pygmalion'' rip-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Chris would be better with a veteran team,'' said
third-year Clippers power forward Maurice Taylor, whose
less-than-giving nature on offense helped lead Ford to the rail.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the frugal philosophy of team owner Donald T.
Sterling prevented GM Elgin Baylor from negotiating with the likes
of George Karl, Paul Westphal, Doc Rivers and Kurt Rambis after
Bill Fitch walked the plank in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And Ford's Boston Celtics history pulled in Sterling's swing
vote when Baylor would have preferred to go with former Fitch
assistant Jim Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who was hired through the closing smoke of the NBA
lockout, inherited a team defined by chubby players in the getaway
season of their contracts. His second team is younger than the
demographic mesmerized by ``Buffy, The Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   With Ford behind the wheel, the two squads combined for 75
defeats in 95 games.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to Ford's culpability in his own demise.
</P>
<P>
   His first head-coaching gig (Boston) went well until the mileage
on Larry Bird, Kevin McHale and Robert Parish left the Celtics
hugging the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Influenced by such accomplished and self-aware performers,
Ford's Clipper practices were structured under the assumption that
his players already knew how to perform such tasks as defending the
pick-and-roll, throwing the outlet pass and deploying a serviceable
trap.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   When Baylor added Derek Anderson and rookie prize Lamar Odom,
Ford announced the Clippers would be a fast-break team. But in a
month of twice daily training-camp workouts, he didn't teach them
the fundamental steps that precede running.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also was a bit stubborn about his philosophy of half-court
offense. With an NBA rule change that basically allows zoning on
the strong side of a set, his many old-school isolation packages
didn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say this,'' said Taylor, who doesn't seem to hate
saying anything, ``but our attention span is not good enough to be
remembering 50,000 plays.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the giddy optimism of training camp was overruled by
the reality of early season defeat, selfish play took over. With
Taylor and Anderson lurching toward free agency, their interest in
sharing the ball seems to have evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   So why the delay in firing Ford? Guess.
</P>
<P>
   According to a league source, Baylor would have made a change a
long time ago, but was encouraged by Sterling who was on the hook
for one million scoots this season to teach Ford how to be a better
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Now the adventure begins for interim head coach Jim Todd, Ford's
loyal assistant whose 37-game audition began with Saturday's date
vs. Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a teacher,'' said Todd, who promises to implement an
attacking style after being unable to help sell Ford's conservative
tactics. ``They're young and they do need a lot of teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   If Todd's head-coaching honeymoon ends prematurely, coach-hiring
speculation will rise again.
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget to focus on the unusual suspects. They'll be
the guys in Sterling's price range.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Sterling put the Ford in affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Out of West Africa
</P>
<P>
   Spanning the globe to bring you a constant variety of NBA center
prospects, we stop in Cincinnati. OK, we also were required to pass
through Boubacar, West Africa, which is the hometown of Soumaila
Samake, the 7-foot-2, 230-pound pivot man for the IBL's Cincinnati
Stuff.
</P>
<P>
   According to one scout, Samake who will be 22 years old next
month is expected to be chosen late in the first round of the 2000
NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   The book on Samake: Played professionally in Slovenia last
season. His offensive skills are as raw as a bachelor party. But
he's a high-caliber athlete who leads the IBL in blocked shots
(swatting five in a game three times) and field-goal percentage
(62).
</P>
<P>
   He averages 9.4 points and 7.8 rebounds in his 27 minutes per
game.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Our tour also returns to China, where 19-year-old Yao Ming
prepares for what's expected to be a rendezvous with the 2001 NBA
Draft. According to eager scouts, the 7-foot-6 Ming may play with
an international team that will take on a U.S. prep all-star squad
at the Nike Hoop Summit. ... Any Laker fan dreaming of pairing
Shawn Kemp with Shaquille O'Neal should realize Kemp's current
contract will bring the corpulent forward $21.5 million for the
2002-2003 season and $25 million the following year. ... Clipper
Derek Anderson officially dumped rap star Percy ``Master P''
Miller's No Limit Sports representation firm and now is represented
by agent Tony Dutt. Dutt's many clients include Nuggets Nick Van
Exel and Antonio McDyess, who chose friendship over Phoenix in
signing with Denver last year. After trading shooting guard Ron
Mercer (another former No Limit client) to Orlando, the Nuggets
have Bryant Stith and Tariq Abdul-Wahad at the ``two'' spot.
Anderson, who will encourage the Clippers to take a swing at
offering him market value, wouldn't be a bad fit in Denver. But
until July, all we can do is project. ...
</P>
<P>
   According to league sources, DerMarr Johnson, the University of
Cincinnati's gifted 6-9 freshman shooting guard, may be
reconsidering his plan to enter the NBA Draft after this season.
Whenever Johnson leaves, he figures to be lottery bait. ... Two
threats to jump from junior college to the NBA are Indian Hills
(Ia.) standouts Corey Hightower, a 6-7 guard, and 6-11 power
forward Ernest Brown. While most scouts insist neither is ready (of
course, they say that about almost everyone), they are quite
impressed with Hightower, a talented playmaker whose lefty skills
invite comparisons to Pacer Jalen Rose. ... The next CBA frontcourt
trainee expected to get a shot at the big-time is 6-9 forward
Etdrick Bohannon of the Fort Wayne Fury. Bohannon, a San Bernardino
product whose travelogue includes stops at the University of
Tennessee, Arizona and Auburn University-Montgomery, had 21
rebounds in the CBA All-Star Game. ... With Dennis Rodman on the
way and Deion Sanders threatening to show up at training camp, new
Dallas Mavericks owner Mark Cuban seems to be a marketing whiz. His
next attention-grabbing move could be signing pop star Ricky Martin
to a 10-day contract. According to critics, Martin is the king of
crossover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
