<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8155 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     02-06 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE LOSS, TROJANS SOUND CONFIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After USC's disheartening loss at Long Beach State
in December, a few weeks before the Trojans opened the Pacific-10
season, coach Henry Bibby gave his student-athletes a pop quiz. It
was a test of whether the players still had the confidence in each
other that Bibby had in them.
</P>
<P>
   He handed them a USC basketball schedule and asked them to write
W's next to the conference games they realistically expected to
win. When the papers were turned in and the red pencil applied, the
most optimistic predictions had the Trojans going 15-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had us losing at Oregon, at Stanford and at Arizona,'' said
David Bluthenthal, the sophomore forward. ``I had us winning all
the home games.''
</P>
<P>
   That took some nerve, considering the Trojans were 7-11 in 1999,
and 15-3 would match their best Pac-10 record ever.
</P>
<P>
   So USC's home-court victory over Arizona, then second-ranked in
the nation, didn't surprise Bluthenthal. What surprised him was
USC's home-court losses to Cal on Thursday and to Stanford, now
second-ranked, by a 67-57 score on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A lost week at the Sports Arena, which might have been expected
for past USC teams, came as an emotional setback for this one. The
back-to-back losses left them 6-3 at the midpoint of the conference
season. They'll have to sweep their last nine games to match those
high-flying predictions.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, they'll have to win at least five to earn
selection to the 64-team NCAA Tournament, not as easy as it sounds,
since they must still face Stanford, Arizona, Oregon, Arizona
State, UCLA and Cal on the road. The game against UCLA at Pauley
Pavilion on Wednesday could kill the chances of one school or the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Now another test of confidence is in order for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night they took that oral exam. And passed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate losing any more games,'' freshman guard
Nate Hair said in the locker room when he was asked to do the math,
to figure out how the 13-8 Trojans can get to 18 wins overall.
``Something's going to have to go really wrong for us not to make
the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby and team leader Brian Scalabrine say they're not thinking
about their chances of making the tournament, something USC has
done only once, in 1997, in the past seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our next game is UCLA,'' Bibby said Saturday. ``We're not
thinking about any tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think too far ahead,'' said Scalabrine, the
junior front-court player. ``I think we were guilty of doing that
early in the year, and we got beat. We're thinking about UCLA.
That's our crosstown rival. That's a good place to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby and Scalabrine might be fibbing. That or they're alone in
ignoring the tournament speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys can say that if they want, (but) we're thinking about the
tournament,'' sophomore point guard Brandon Granville said. ``We
have short-term goals and we have long-term goals. The goal at the
end is to get into the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 6-3 at the break. Not too bad. Now we just have to go
out and do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   But four of those Pac-10 victories were achieved with the help
of Sam Clancy, a 17-points-a-game scorer, and sixth man Jarvis
Turner, the team's only senior. Both Clancy and Turner are lost for
the season with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   And the Jan. 22 victory over Arizona seems more mystical with
each passing Trojans loss. Surely Arizona let down in the USC's
first game after Clancy and Turner were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are 1-3 since then, including the flat effort
against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's defeat came not for lack of trying. USC, not the
deepest team even before the injuries, stayed in the game for the
first 12 minutes with scrambling defense that it couldn't sustain
for 40 against a Stanford roster that boasts seven potential
starters.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans, though, weren't happy with the performance. Too
much one-pass-and-an-outside-shot. There went any hope of getting
the Cardinal's big men in foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't happy with the whole week. Give them a schedule and
a quiz today and they'll agree on the road ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot,'' Bluthenthal said, ``have any more weeks like this
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
