<HEADLINE>
NEW COACH, SAME OLD CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The honeymoon pace typically granted a new NBA
coach was preempted Saturday by the poorly groomed Clippers, who
celebrated the event by serving beer in champagne glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Interim coach Jim Todd was hoping to discover a few alter egos
in his first date as Chris Ford's successor, but the same
single-minded Clips were clowned by the Dallas Mavericks, 119-106,
before 13,646 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's dowry to Todd was on gruesome display. The Clippers
(11-35), who supposedly were primed for a renaissance after
liberation from the deposed coach, continued their glacier-style
offensive movement. They were impressively selfish. They were
appreciably clueless in defense of the high pick-and-roll. They
surrendered a season-high 67 points in the first half to the Mavs
(19-27).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps by losing for the 17th time in 19 games, they were
preparing for tonight's war with the Chicago Bulls, a game with
severe draft-lottery implications. How nasty is this team? In
getting clouted, they came within just one point of equaling their
season high.
</P>
<P>
   The only unusual demonstration was presented by Todd, who played
everyone except Brian Skinner in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Taylor scored 17 and points and discovered 6 rebounds
before fouling out in the fourth quarter. Rookie Lamar Odom
scratched his way to 14 points, while center Michael Olowokandi who
seemed to be unusually animated at the start contributed 10 points
and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The equal-opportunity Maverick offense was kind to its point
guard, Erick Strickland, who pitched in 24 points and forward Dirk
Nowitzki, who bagged 20. Michael Finley and Cedric Ceballos each
scored 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the newest Mav, Dennis Rodman, reportedly was in
town, but not in the house. The only Dennis to show up was Johnson,
whose first game as a Clippers assistant coach failed to yield
enough excitement to inspire his new team.
</P>
<P>
   A defining moment occurred with 5:55 left before last rites,
when Clipper Derek Anderson's double-dip, roundhouse slam dunk
turned into a Dallas rebound.
</P>
<P>
   CLIPPER NOTES: Johnson's return trip to the NBA was no cakewalk
and it has nothing to do with his playing and coaching chronology.
``I'm trying to survive without any sleep,'' said the Clips' new
assistant coach, who joined the team Saturday afternoon after
coaching his last game with the CBA's LaCrosse (Wis.) Bobcats on
Friday night at Sioux Falls, S.D. That game went into overtime.
When it was over, Johnson made the five-hour drive back to
LaCrosse, then had to make airline connections through Minnesota
before arriving in L.A. at about 2:30 p.m. Johnson attended
Dominguez High before starring at Harbor College and Pepperdine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 0216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
