<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-KAPLER-TEX </SLUG>
 
Rangers' new guy in right field is due room to improve 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Let it be recorded that The Guy Who Will
Replace Juan Gonzalez batted .245 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler's rookie season in the major leagues didn't just
chew him up. It nearly swallowed him whole.
</P>
<P>
   He brooded. He pressed. He struck out a lot.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, he was traded. Lumped by the Detroit Tigers into
a multiheaded deal with the Rangers that included one of the game's
best players in Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler's reaction was typical of a young player who suddenly
realized that he had gone from poster boy to trade bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shock ... disbelief,'' he recalled. ``I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, of course, the feeling was mutual. The idea of
Gonzalez no longer being a Ranger still seems incongruous. Two-time
most valuable players, harvesting Hall of Fame credentials, aren't
supposed to be traded when a team considers itself a contender.
</P>
<P>
   But such are baseball's economics. When last we heard, the
Tigers were trying to get Gonzalez signed to an eight-year, $140
million contract. In effect, general manager Randy Smith wants to
make Gonzalez the show pony of the new Detroit Tigers _ new
stadium, new star, new reason to come cheer for the home team.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, however, Juan was never asked to be the only name on
the marquee. His clubhouse locker was snuggled into a corner, and
he seemed to like it that way. He also has never really become
comfortable with the English language, as the Tigers will learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't surprised that they had traded for Juan,'' Kapler
said this weekend in a visit to The Ballpark. ``Once I got over the
idea that I wasn't going to play anymore with the guys I came up
with, I realized that it's a special feeling to play for a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to lose. I hate to lose more than anyone you've ever
met.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler is 24 and, as the Tigers said, sometimes it shows. He
grew up in the San Fernando Valley area of Los Angeles _ a Valley
Guy _ and by his own admission was a self-styled high school
slacker. He once said that the only reason he even attended classes
during his senior year was because of a girl _ Lisa, who now
happens to be Gabe's wife.
</P>
<P>
   But the same thing happened at the first college stop, Cal
State-Fullerton, and Kapler ended up down the freeway at Moorpark
Junior College. Scouts were impressed, but wary, and in 1995 the
Tigers made Kapler their 57th-round draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   He rose quickly through the Tigers' minor-league system. In
1998, he had an eye-opening season at Double-A Jacksonville,
leading the minor leagues with 146 runs batted in and became ``The
Sporting News''' Minor League Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers didn't want to rush him to the majors, but Bobby
Higginson was injured and they felt they had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   In the month of June, Kapler batted .174, and his personal war
was on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how much I learned last year,'' he said. ``I
can't tell you how much I learned about the big leagues, about
myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refuse to beat myself up this year. I will not take one
at-bat into the next at-bat. I will not take one at-bat into the
field with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler pronounced himself guilty of taking his hitting struggles
out on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could get put on death row for that,'' he said, ``I'd
be a dead man by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Can he hit .320 every year and drive in 130 runs, as Gonzalez
could? Maybe not, but that won't be Kapler's job in Texas. Instead,
he will be asked simply to provide a solid bat in the lower half of
the lineup, and to bring his fiery attitude to the outfield, where
Kapler's hustle and range did draw favorable reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The word in Detroit was that he was stubborn and, once the
season began to sour, hard to be coached.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler disputed that, insisting, ``I would do whatever it takes
to be better _ whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Give him a chance, Kapler seemed to say this weekend. Consider
the intangibles. Weigh the earnest sweat on his brow.
</P>
<P>
   He talked this weekend to new teammate Royce Clayton about the
problems of following a local hero. Clayton had the burden in St.
Louis of being The Guy Who Replaced Ozzie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Detroit, I heard a lot of comments like, `Kapler, you're no
Brian Hunter,' so I'm sure I can plan on hearing things about not
being Juan Gonzalez,'' said the new Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   Just watch him play, Kapler urged. Measure the rug burns. Sense
the intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expects anyone here to forget Juan Gonzalez. The Guy Who
Will Replace Him just wants us to give the new man a chance.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 0238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8162 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-ISIAH-MAVS-TEX     02-06 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ISIAH-MAVS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC SAYS THOMAS WILL BE NEXT MAVERICKS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Magic Johnson is convinced that Isiah Thomas will
be the next Mavericks coach.
</P>
<P>
   And if Thomas doesn't get the job, Johnson said he would like to
have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got Isiah, and he will be a great coach,'' Johnson
said. ``Now he'll shake that whole town up.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who is the commissioner of the Continental Basketball
Association, told the ``Star-Telegram'' last month that he would
love to replace Don Nelson as the Mavericks coach after this
season. Mavericks owner-in-waiting Mark Cuban has said Nelson will
not be coaching the Mavericks beyond this season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Johnson, part owner and vice president of the Los
Angeles Lakers, insists that Thomas and the Mavericks are a perfect
fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you've got a young Jimmy Johnson, you've just got him in
basketball, because that's what Isiah is,'' Johnson said. ``What
Jimmy Johnson did for the Dallas Cowboys, Isiah can do for the
Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what Dallas needs. They don't need any more of this
makeshift stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said he hasn't yet made a list of possible coaching
candidates, and that he hasn't talked to Thomas about the vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the approved owner yet,'' Cuban said. ``So until that
occurs, I'm not in a position to go out and hire a coach yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban also had no comment about remarks Johnson made Friday
night, when he said the Mavericks will be better served by not
giving Rodman any special treatment. Johnson also said the
Mavericks players endorsed the Rodman Rules, because Cuban wanted
him on this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has something to say,'' Cuban said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Thomas being the next Mavericks coach, Johnson said:
``The city of Dallas would jump all behind it. He would make the
right moves, the right decisions, and he would bring the right
people in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a proven winner and a champion running your show, a
real basketball man. The best move they can make is to make Isiah,
who wants do to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said if Thomas doesn't get the Mavericks' job, he would
like to coach the team. But he is so convinced that the job will
eventually belong to Thomas, who, like Cuban, graduated from
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to do anything against my friend,'' Johnson said. ``But
if something happens and that breaks down, I'll be happy to talk to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson said he doesn't believe anyone else but Thomas will
get the Mavericks' coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be their best move,'' Johnson said. ``And it would
be just fantastic for Dallas.'' \Nsubheds:Smaller house Mark Cuban
said reports about Dennis Rodman living in his guest house are
correct. Except Cuban said the two-bedroom guest house is only
1,800 square feet _ not the 4,000 square feet that has been
reported.
</P>
<P>
   By those dimensions, the $3,000 Rodman is paying Cuban per month
seems a bit high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is,'' Cuban said. ``I wanted to make sure it was fully
above board. He's paying good money.'' \Nsubheds:Rodman update
Dennis Rodman traveled to Los Angeles on Friday and has been
working out with his personal trainer the past two days.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cuban said Rodman was scheduled to fly to Dallas today,
either commercially or on Cuban's private jet.
\Nsubheds:Remembering when Mavericks trainer Roger Hinds and Dennis
Rodman have a history that dates back almost 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hinds was the trainer at the College of Charleston when they
upset Rodman's college team _ Southeastern Oklahoma State _ in the
first round of the 1986 NAIA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Southeastern Oklahoma State was seeded No. 1 and
the College of Charleston was seeded No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked quite normal,'' Hinds said of Rodman. ``He didn't
have any tattoos, and he was a scorer, too.'' nn
</P>
