<HEADLINE>
WARRIORS TREATED ASSISTANT COACH SHAMEFULLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How would you like to be in Rod Higgins' shoes?
</P>
<P>
   Higgins is an assistant coach with the Golden State Warriors.
Last week, Michael Jordan called his employers to see if they would
release him from his contract so he could coach the Washington
Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Warriors owner Chris Cohan said, sure, Michael. But only if you
release the ``lottery protection clause'' on the first-round draft
pick that the Wizards own as a result of that controversial Don
Nelson trade that sent Chris Webber to Washington in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan refused, Cohan wouldn't let Higgins out of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it was a situation that I was prepared to go and
prepared to take,'' Higgins said. ``Unfortunately it didn't happen,
and while it's a disappointment, it's also business.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's business, that's a sorry way for the Warriors to run a
business, which might explain why they've been so pathetic since
the Webber trade. The Warriors should have released Higgins from
his contract with no strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   Not soon after the Wizards went after Higgins, the Warriors
hired former Charlotte Hornets coach Dave Cowens as an assistant
coach. Thus, the Warriors are grooming Cowens to replace Garry St.
Jean as the next coach, so there was absolutely no need for them to
keep Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   St. Jean, also the Warriors' general manager, was the one to
inform Higgins that he wasn't going to be released from his
contract. But this strong-arm negotiation tactics had Cohen's name
written all over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rough weekend because Rod Higgins is a very
special friend of mine, one of the best ones I've had in my 20-plus
years in the league, and Michael Jordan and I tried to do the right
thing,'' St. Jean said. ``We wanted Rod to be able to go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of us had it on the top of our head that we have
Washington's pick. That complicated the issue. I later had a
discussion with Bob Rowell \Rthe team's VP of business operations\S
and with Chris Cohan, and it then became a business decision that
it was in everybody's best interest that we wait until the end of
the year for Rod to make a move.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens, who also is president of the
National Basketball Coaches Association, said the Wizards moved so
quickly in hiring Darrell Walker as interim coach that the
association had no time to intercede in the Higgins case.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about it I immediately went to \RMichael
Goldberg, executive director\S, but it was too late,'' Wilkens
said. ``We talked to the NBA office, however, and expressed our
concerns. We don't want to see this kind of thing happening
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens said what the Warriors did to Higgins is absurd. He also
wants the NBA to set some guidelines so something like that doesn't
happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going after somebody's head coach, it's a different
story,'' Wilkens said. ``That's a lateral move.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when an assistant has a chance to make that step, it's
absolutely unfair to stand in his way like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Higgins will be making a move after this season. His contract
expires on July 1, and he'll likely replace Walker as the permanent
Wizards coach.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins, a class act, harbors no ill will toward his friend, St.
Jean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Garry a long time,'' he said. ``I don't have any
bad feelings as far as Garry's concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Higgins didn't say the same thing about Cohen.
AROUND THE EAST:
\Nsubheds:Sad situation Charlotte Hornets guard David Wesley was
charged last week with reckless driving and drag racing in
connection with the death of teammate Bobby Phills.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley has declined comment. But this clearly states that
prosecutors didn't believe they could have tagged the former Baylor
star with the more serious charge of ``death by vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockets staffers Dennis Lindsey and Melvin Hunt were teammates
of Wesley's at Baylor. Lindsey is the Rockets' director of player
personnel, and Hunt is the team's video coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see any friend or family member go through
anything like that,'' Hunt said. ``You have those mental pictures
that we store up in our minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I did a lot of praying for him. He's like a family
member. Seeing him hurt is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Hornets will retire Phills' No. 13 jersey when
Charlotte plays host to Phills' former team, the Cleveland
Cavaliers. Phills' widow and parents are expected to raise the
banner honoring Phills during the halftime ceremonies.
\Nsubheds:Tearful honor Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse fought back
tears after he learned he had been picked as a reserve on the
Eastern Conference All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even put into words what this means to me,''
Stackhouse said. ``It's an honor to be out there with those guys
and an honor to be selected by the coaches. It is very exciting for
me and my family.'' \Nsubheds:No trade for Walker Celtics coach
Rick Pitino wants everyone to know that, despite persistent rumors,
Antoine Walker is not on the trading block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antoine Walker will not be traded unless Michael Jordan
considers to come back,'' Pitino said. ``Then I would consider it.
All these rumors about Antoine Walker are false.''
AROUND THE WEST: \Nsubheds:Unhappy observer Los Angeles Lakers
guard Glen Rice was upset that coach Phil Jackson did not play him
for the last 3:51 of the third quarter and the first 2:15 of the
fourth period during last Sunday's loss to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was experimenting with a new three-guard lineup to match
up better with Houston's quick perimeter players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you sit over there long, it's going to take you a
minute or two to get warmed up,'' Rice said. ``It's always tough
for me to sit. I'm not an assistant coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson didn't take too kindly to Rice's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he didn't deserve any shots,'' he said. ``He was having
trouble putting it in anyway.'' \Nsubheds:Last-game goal Houston
forward Charles Barkley is optimistic that he can return for the
final game this season.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley ruptured the tendon in his left knee in December, and is
going through rehabilitation after having what was thought to be
career-ending surgery. Barkely had already announced his retirement
before the injury, but wants to come back and play one more game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going out there looking for 20 \Rpoints\S and 10
\Rrebounds\S,'' he said. ``I just want to be able to go out there,
play 10 minutes and walk off the court under my own power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would bother me if the last memory people have is
me being helped off the court like that.''
Scott Audette Orlando Magic fans like Betsy Ress have no love lost
for Penny Hardaway, who left for the Phoenix Suns last summer.
Hardaway says Orlando no place for a superstar
Penny Hardaway was a key fixture on an Orlando Magic team that
advanced to the 1995 NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the folks in Orlando despise him.
</P>
<P>
   Magic fans believe Hardaway dogged it and sat out most of the
past two seasons with injuries he could have played with. Hardaway,
who signed last summer with the Phoenix Suns, said the constant
criticism of him not playing with pain has hurt his image beyond
repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I've got advice from a doctor, I'm not going to take a
chance on playing two months and then being down the rest of my
career rather than waiting when I've got another 10 or 11 years
left in me,'' Hardaway said. ``That's what I don't understand about
this whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's fair about that? It's sick. It's sick what this city
did to my image.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway also said because of the way the Magic fans turned on
him and Shaquille O'Neal, Orlando will never be an attractive place
for superstar players like Tim Duncan and Grant Hill and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't be able to \Rget a big-time free agent\S,''
Hardaway said. ``It's written. Anyone thinking of coming here will
ask Shaq. They will ask me, and I'll tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This town can't handle a star. It just can't for whatever the
reason. It's just a known fact. They can't handle a guy here who
would get a lot of national attention. They would expect him to be
Michael Jordan every night. And when he has 20 straight games of 20
points, then slides for three games, he better watch out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway said the Magic are wasting their time clearing money
under the salary cap, and the way he was treated will backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why anyone would want to come here,
anyway,'' Hardaway said. ``Just because they have cap room and some
lottery picks?
</P>
<P>
   ``After Shaq is gone, after all the stuff that happened to me,
it's just not a fair place for a superstar or a great player. They
want a blue-collar worker, so they don't have to say anything
negative about him. Anyone with status in this town will get
ripped. I just don't think this town is ready for a superstar.''
</P>
