<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Selig delivered some of what Rocker deserved 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From sea to shining sea, from bunkers in Boston to Grand
Prairie, colleagues rushed last week to rip into baseball
commissioner Bud Selig for coming down too hard on poor John
Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   As if that could be humanly possible.
</P>
<P>
   Sports columnists across the country sputtered and fumed that
Selig's decision to fine Rocker $20,000 and suspend him until May 1
was downright un-American. It is our God-given right, they ranted,
to be ignorant, hateful and bigoted. And in this country, they
declared, we by gawd still have the constitutionally guaranteed
right to let everyone know how ignorant, hateful and bigoted we
really are.
</P>
<P>
   And then, like Rocker, most of them set about proving it. At
least the ignorant part.
</P>
<P>
   I say, if anything, Selig didn't slap Rocker nearly hard enough.
I say it's good to finally have a commissioner who will step up and
demand that his players be role models and that his game is willing
to accept its responsibility to society for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Media critics, when they weren't howling about First Amendment
rights (which, in reality, don't really exist in a private
enterprise like Major League Baseball) were quick to point out
Selig's inconsistency. How, they wondered, slapping their heads,
could the same commissioner allow former American League president
Gene Budig to give Robbie Alomar only a five-game suspension for
spitting in an umpire's face, and then hit Rocker like this just
for being incredibly stupid?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these were the same media critics who were screaming
at the time that Alomar's punishment was way too light. They seem
to see no inconsistency on their own part as they clamor that poor
Rocker's rights have now been violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what the commissioner did was fine,'' said former
Rangers president Tom Schieffer. ``We all know that the Alomar
situation wasn't handled right. That doesn't mean that because that
decision was bad baseball has to keep making bad decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   And have you heard any players stepping up to defend Rocker? Any
of his teammates? On the contrary, Braves starter and player
representative Tom Glavine told the ``Atlanta
Journal-Constitution'' that the Players Association may have acted
too fast in filing a grievance on Rocker's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I didn't want them to \Rfile a grievance\S. I
just asked them to be mindful of how much \Rof a reduction\S they
were trying to get, because I think it was important, especially to
our guys, to see that some sort of punishment was paid,'' Glavine
said. ``I think from the guys' standpoint now, the message has been
sent that a stiff price has been handed down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's part of me that thinks it would have gone a long way
toward showing remorse if John would have just said, `OK, forget
it. That's the price I'm going to pay, and I'll pay it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Can Selig police every ignoramus in baseball? Can he punish
every bigot who tells a racially insensitive joke in a dugout? Can
he, on his own, erase racism in his sport? Of course not. But he
can darn sure slap the bejesus out of someone brainless enough to
make an issue of it in a national magazine.
</P>
<P>
   He not only has the authority as the overseer of his game, he
has the moral right as a human being.
</P>
<P>
   Evil flourishes when good men do nothing. I don't know who said
it, but he must have had people like Rocker in mind.
</P>
<P>
   You go, Bud.  &LR; subheds:VOTE OF CONFIDENCE  &LR; body:Uh oh. New
Cowboys head coach Dave Campo has been endorsed by the man he once
worked for as defensive coordinator: Barry Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year I was there I spent 90 percent of my time in
the defensive meetings,'' Switzer told the ``Daily Oklahoman''
after Campo's hiring. ``From that evaluation, the interaction, the
thought process that came out of game-planning, all those variables
made me believe Campo was the right man.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as being qualified, there's no question Dave Campo is
an excellent coach. He and I had a great working relationship. I
like him not only as a football coach, I like him as a person''
</P>
<P>
   OK, great. Sort of like being endorsed by Bill Clinton maybe,
but naturally Switzer couldn't stop there. He had to try and defend
owner Jerry Jones, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry is not a factor in coaching the football team,'' Switzer
insisted. ``He has done some things that the media takes and
creates into controversy that he sometimes circumvents the head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes a few head coaching decisions. They don't have
anything to do with offense, defense or special teams, evaluation
or drafting. Jerry doesn't meddle in the big things.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Switzer added, ``When I say things, people don't want to
believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now I wonder why that is.  &LR; subheds:WHAT ABOUT ROBBY?
