<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8165 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFFENSE-T     02-06 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' NEW OFFENSIVE COORDINATOR LOOKS TO FUTURE BY DRAWING ON
PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Jack Reilly is more than just the Cowboys' new
offensive coordinator. At 54, he is something of a pass-offense
historian.
</P>
<P>
   His influences in the game include Sid Gillman, Don Coryell,
Ernie Zampese ... and Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly was hired by owner Jerry Jones and coach Dave Campo for
one reason: To restore the Cowboys to an attacking style of
downfield offense, which better suits Troy Aikman's needs and
skills, as evidenced by three Super Bowl rings in four years during
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman and the Cowboys flourished under two different offensive
coordinators _ Norv Turner and Zampese _ who ran the same basic
``Air Coryell offense'' that Reilly is bringing back for 2000.
Jones now admits that he made a mistake by hiring Chan Gailey with
the notion of bringing in something ``exciting and fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Jones is banking on familiar and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation still is that former Cowboys offensive coordinator
Zampese (1994-97) will join the team in an advisory capacity.
Reilly and Zampese have worked together the past three seasons at
Dallas and New England.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also is hoping that backup quarterback Jason Garrett, who
turns 34 next month, will be willing to take an early retirement
and become the Cowboys' quarterbacks coach, a position held by
Reilly in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, a junior-college All-America quarterback at Santa Monica
College in 1964, has borrowed from many over his 32 years of
coaching. He worked one season (1994) for Davis with the Los
Angeles Raiders, where he learned the concept of ``going for the
throat'' via the vertical passing game. He also has studied the
theories of Gillman, whom Reilly calls ``the father of the passing
game,'' during the '60s and '70s as head coach of the Rams,
Chargers and Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   But the genesis of Reilly's offense, and the offense that the
Cowboys are going to run again after a two-year absence, can be
traced to Coryell, who is retired and living in the San Juan
Islands off the Washington coast. He last coached the San Diego
Chargers in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reilly is a product of many, he will be putting his own
stamp on the Cowboys' offense. Here are his thoughts on the Coryell
offense:
</P>
<P>
   The tight end postion: ``You want your tight end to be an
effective receiver in this offense. Kellen Winslow \RHall of Famer
who played for Coryell at San Diego\S was the originator and
probably the consummate tight end of the past 30 years, while Jay
Novacek came along and took the position to another level with the
Cowboys under Norv and Ernie.
</P>
<P>
   ``David LaFleur has the tangibles to be that guy for us. As
important as anything is that Troy has confidence in David, because
there has to be chemistry between the quarterback and the tight end
to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   The fullback position: ``You love the blocking fullback, but in
this offense the fullback also has to be able to run routes and
catch the ball. Robert Thomas, by everything I've seen, looks like
he has excellent hands. When we change personnel groups, this
\Rfullback\S position becomes maybe an Eric Bjornson as a second
tight end. This goes back to the Coryell teams with the Chargers,
who used Pete Holihan and Eric Sievers as second tight ends so
effectively. In St. Louis, Marshall Faulk became that guy this past
season for Mike Martz out of certain formations.''
</P>
<P>
   Offenses that seem to ``fit'' a quarterback when others don't:
``In San Diego \R1997\S, Kevin Gilbride tried unsuccessfully to mix
the run-and-shoot with the Coryell/Gibbs offense that already was
in place there. The run-and-shoot concepts are excellent. But the
quarterback in San Diego was Stan Humphries, and it didn't work.
Likewise, if Joe Montana had been drafted by a team other than Bill
Walsh and the 49ers, he probably wouldn't have been as great as he
was. He just fit that style.''
</P>
<P>
   Reason behind the longevity of the Coryell offense: ``It's
fairly simple. It's very easy to learn and comprehend. Basically,
it tells every players through a numbering system what he's
supposed to do on each play. There's not a lot of memorization
involved. The players just have to be able to know the technique
... and execute it. This enables them to feel comfortable, so they
can go out and just play.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the past nine Super Bowl champions _ Gibbs' Redskins
(1992), Turner's Cowboys (1993-94), Zampese's Cowboys (1995) and
Martz's Rams (1999) _ ran a version of the Coryell offense.
</P>
<P>
   While the 2000 Cowboys aren't exactly going to exactly mimic the
Rams because of differences in personnel, the terminology, the
philosophy and the attack-mentality are the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that sense,'' said Jones, acknowledging what the Rams did
with the NFL's top-rated offense this past season, ``what we're
doing here now has to give you some optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' first order of business going into free agency,
beginning Friday, and the April 15-16 NFL draft will be to find a
big-time receiver to line up opposite Rocket Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to fit the players into the system ... and make it
work,'' Campo has vowed.
</P>
<P>
   All that did for the Rams was win a Super Bowl.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
