</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RODEO-COMPUTER-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOY.COM: INTERNET CHANGING THE WAY RODEO COWBOYS PREPARE TO
COMPETE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ While Wall Street executives rise early and
surf the Internet to check their stocks, rodeo cowboys are
beginning to rise early and ride the Internet to check their stock.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Robert Bowers, a cyber cowboy who carries his laptop across
the North American rodeo circuit. The description of every bull
that Bowers has mounted from the Calgary Stampede to this weekend's
Fort Worth Stock Show Rodeo is logged in his computer.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough, Bowers has a small satellite dish attached
to the back of the camper of his shiny blue pick-up truck. Inside
the state-of-the-art camper, there's a TV and a stereo.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the circuit of a half-century ago, when cowboys learned
about the patterns of bucking horses and bulls by word of mouth,
cowboys now swap yarns about rodeo stock on the Internet through
Web sites and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, a 1999 National Finals Rodeo bull-riding qualifier who
was bucked off during yesterday's Stock Show matinee performance at
Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum, said he can learn about a bull he
has drawn by reading reports and commentary about star bucking
bulls on Internet sites such as the Professional Bull Riders
(pbrnow.com).
</P>
<P>
   After reading the reports, Bowers can find the answers to
questions: Is the bull tough or mediocre? Does the bull spin to the
right or the left? Has the bull been to the National Finals Rodeo
or the PBR Finals?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get on the Internet and learn that you've drawn a tough
bull, it makes me feel better about coming to the rodeo, and it
makes me more confident,'' he said. ``If I read that I've drawn a
sorry bull and the rodeo is far away, then I'm not going to buy a
$1,000 plane ticket to come and get on him if I don't believe that
I can win anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowers said he became computer savvy when he attended Montana
State on a rodeo scholarship. But Bowers, who is only a year away
from completing a bachelor's degree in business, is among only a
small percentage of competitors who carry computers on the road and
use them on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Though many cowboys are benefiting from computers, their wives
and girlfriends are the ones who sit at home and punch the keys.
While her fianc, Justin Daugherty, was en route to his first
National Finals Rodeo last year in bull riding, Sarah Busch said
she was on the PRCA's Web site every Tuesday afternoon to punch up
the weekly standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would print the standings out and put them up on the
board,'' Busch said. ``We used the standings as a goal setter.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana resident Kay Mortensen said she tracks her husband, Dan,
a five-time world saddle bronc champion, through the Internet. Many
of the rodeos that her husband enters, such as the Fort Worth Stock
Show, has a Web site and posts the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's home one day, and he's gone the next, so I can get on the
Iinternet and find out what's going on with him,'' said Kay, who
estimated that he is on the road more than 200 days a year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Internet, Kay also communicates with her
husband by cell phone from their remote hometown of Manhattan,
Mont., which is near Bozeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls me a lot when he's driving,'' she said. ``We'll pass
about 20 or 30 minutes a day on the cell phone. We're apart a lot,
so cell phones help keep the family together. Thank God for cell
phones!''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys also enter rodeos through a sophisticated computer
system called Pro-com. The Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association,
which has corporate offices in Colorado Springs, Colo., uses the
central entry system to schedule competitors in each of its 750
annual rodeos. A cowboy calls the office, requests the date that he
would prefer to compete in a rodeo and the computer attempts to
accommodate him after the entry deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Many rodeos now use computerized, electronic scoreboards to sort
scores and post the rankings, and large television screens to show
instant replays of the rides. At the Fort Worth Stock Show Rodeo,
television screens at both end zones of the arena flash the
contestant's name before each ride, and a camera zooms in as he
mounts his animal. After the ride, an instant replay is shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my father \Rthe late W.R. Watt\S ran this rodeo \R from
the 1940s through 1970s\S, he never dreamed of having instant
replay TV,'' Stock Show president and general manager Bob Watt
said. ``But its something that you need to have because most all
major sports venues have replays. When you see a football playoff
game, you expect to see exciting replays on a big screen. At our
rodeo, fans see the replays and get into the excitement of the
rides.'' \Ntagtop:Brett Hoffman, (817) 390-7163
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 0241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8167 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-NFL-CRIMES-TEX     02-06 2464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-CRIMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRESTS LINKED TO VIOLENCE DIM NFL'S SUPER BOWL GLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams and the Tennessee Titans treated 130 million
television viewers to one of the most exciting finishes in Super
Bowl history a week ago. The lasting image of the 1999 NFL season
should have been of the Rams celebrating their 23-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, last week was less about champions and more about
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl was only hours old when Baltimore Ravens
linebacker Ray Lewis was charged in the stabbing deaths of two men
outside an Atlanta nightclub. He is the second active player jailed
on murder charges in two months.
</P>
<P>
   If image truly is everything, the NFL is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIV featured 13 players _ including former TCU
offensive lineman Ryan Tucker _ charged with a total of 20 crimes.
Tucker, now with the Rams, pleaded no contest to a charge of
aggravated assault-serious bodily injury in a 1996 incident outside
a downtown Fort Worth nightclub in which Bryan Boyd suffered a
fractured skull.
</P>
<P>
   There is concern for the increasing number of crimes involving
NFL players, but no one has offered any solutions beyond what the
league already is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this year has been an unusual year in a lot of
ways,'' said Gene Upshaw, the executive director of the NFL Players
Association. ``We counsel players about their behavior, but
obviously it's still left up to the individual player to do the
right thing. I don't know how we can legislate morality to players.
I just don't see how you can do it. What we try to do is make sure
we have a support system that will help them get through any crisis
that they might have.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's crime policy, instituted in 1998, requires players
charged with violent crimes to undergo clinical evaluation and
counseling. Players convicted of violent crimes, including no
contest pleas and pretrial intervention, can be fined and/or
suspended without pay.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't deter the league's bad boys from giving the NFL a
black eye the past two weeks:
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Panthers running back Fred Lane was arrested on drug
and weapons charges in Jackson, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   In a Castle Rock, Colo., courtroom, Denver Broncos receiver Rod
Smith pleaded innocent to charges that he beat, choked and dragged
his common-law wife during a dispute in their suburban Denver home
on Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Chiefs players Tamarick Vanover and Bam Morris, who
unexpectedly announced his retirement, were linked to a federal
drug investigation in a federal court affidavit filed in connection
with drug distribution charges lodged against a Kansas City man.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Giants linebacker Lawrence Taylor, who was
inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame last year, was
sentenced to 18 months' probation for pleading no contest to buying
crack cocaine from an undercover police officer in St. Pete Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor in Indianapolis said Colts defensive back Steve
Muhammad will not face charges in connection with his wife's death.
Nichole Muhammad died Nov. 7 after injuries from a car accident
forced her into premature labor. The couple's baby was stillborn,
and Nichole Muhammad bled to death after the delivery. Muhammad had
been arrested 10 days before the single-car accident on three
misdemeanor domestic battery charges and will stand trial March 21
on those charges.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven other active NFL players were arrested for
serious crimes in 1999. Carolina Panthers receiver Rae Carruth
remains jailed in Charlotte, N.C., on charges he conspired to kill
his pregnant girlfriend. Cherica Adams, 24, delivered a son by
Caesarean section shortly after the Nov. 16 drive-by shooting. She
died 28 days later.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth, 25, is suspected of masterminding the murder with three
other men.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder the NFL has been derisively tagged the National
Felons League?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asked to hold athletes out as being special in a lot of
ways, and hopefully, that is based in positives,'' said Willie
Davis, a Hall of Famer who played from 1958-69. ``I would say to
you right now, we're almost experiencing the opposite of that,
where athletes are really turning into some of our biggest
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having grown up in a poverty-stricken way myself, I can
identify with almost every experience I have heard characterized
among athletes, from single families to whatever. But there's no
excuse for some of the behavior that's occurring in the league
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:`An American problem'  &LR; body:Despite the
public-relations hit the league has taken, the NFL is unlikely to
implement new policies to curb off-the-field violence.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual state-of-the-league address, three days before
Lewis' arrest, commissioner Paul Tagliabue said the NFL's
prevention programs, which include counseling, treatment and
discipline, are comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that you just can't be with them 24 hours a
day,'' said Bob Ackles, the Miami Dolphins' director of football
operations. ``They've got to be responsible for their actions like
anybody. If they choose to get in with the bad crowd or the wrong
crowd or be at the wrong place at the wrong time, I don't know what
you can do about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its crime policy, the NFL also has an annual
seminar for rookies, and, before every season, league officials
address all 31 teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens, Ray Lewis' team, held a seven-part lecture
series on personal conduct for players beginning in April. Topics
included personal and professional accountability, male/female
issues and drug counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such programs can help, but in most cases it's like putting a
Band-Aid on a gaping wound,'' said Lew Lyon, a Baltimore sports
psychologist. ``You're talking about a person who has high
self-worth and a lot of money. He's not going to listen. He's
thinking, `This won't happen to me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, the league has employed a full-time security
officer in each NFL city. Some teams have gone a step further.
</P>
<P>
   A series of off-the-field incidents prompted the Cowboys to hire
former running back Calvin Hill in 1997 to oversee their player
assistance and development. The team, which has passed on drafting
players with troubled backgrounds, has restored its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But Harry Edwards, a professor of sociology at the University of
California at Berkeley, a consultant to the San Francisco 49ers and
a former Olympic athlete, said the Cowboys were unfairly singled
out for their off-the-field troubles in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we find out that it's not the Dallas Cowboys,'' Edwards
said. ``It's the Kansas City Chiefs. It's the Baltimore Ravens.
It's the Carolina Panthers. It's the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what are we really saying? It is not any particular sport.
It is not any particular franchise. It is not any particular group.
This is not an NFL problem. It's not a black-athlete problem. It
most certainly isn't a black athlete as a Dallas Cowboys problem.
This is an American problem, and it is going to get worse before it
gets better.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL had three on-field incidents in a three-week span late
this season that involved players hitting or shoving officials.
Cleveland Browns left tackle Orlando Brown was suspended
indefinitely for shoving referee Jeff Triplette. Pittsburgh
Steelers left tackle Wayne Gandy was fined $20,000 for pushing
referee Tom White. Washington Redskins right guard Tre Johnson was
assessed a $50,000 fine and a one-game suspension for the first
game of next season for striking back judge Bill Leavy in a playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Eric Moulds of the Buffalo Bills and Willie
Whitehead of the St. Louis Rams were fined for making throat-slash
gestures during games late in the season. The gesture was banned by
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Most players, ex-players and experts reject the idea that
football's aggressive nature makes players inherently more prone to
off-the-field violence. Brown, Gandy, Johnson, Moulds and Whitehead
have not made headlines away from the football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you do on the football field, they'll put you in jail for
out in the real world,'' said Hall of Famer Randy White, who played
with the Cowboys from 1975-88. ``Surely every guy is aware of that.
There are rules in society and we have to live by those rules. If
we don't, then there's a consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, the sports sociologist, said the NFL has no bigger
problem than any other sport or any other business. Violence, he
said, has become a part of everyday life in America, and fans
shouldn't be shocked because the accused is an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be honest when we can't be right,'' Edwards said.
``These are things that are aspects of modern life in this society
and unless we're prepared to literally change the character of
American society drastically, we're going to live to a substantial
degree with these issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be serious about mopping the floor,
eventually we're going to have to turn off the faucet. If we're
going to be serious about cleaning up sports, eventually we're
going to have to get serious about cleaning up society.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:`Disconcerting'  &LR; body:Commissioner Tagliabue said the
``track record of our players is far better than society
at-large.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, based on several studies, the percentage of criminal
histories among NFL players is below that of the U.S. male
population as a whole. A 1981 study of FBI Uniform Crimes Reports
found the lifetime arrest rate for males in large U.S. cities was
23 percent. Other studies, including the 1993 National Youth
Survey, estimate it higher.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Benedict and Don Yaeger co-authored /Pros and Cons: The
Criminals Who Play in the NFL'', which was published in 1998. They
found that in 1996-97 as many as 21 percent of NFL players had been
arrested or indicted at some point in their adult lives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, professional athletes, whether they accept being role
models, are held to a higher standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we represent a microcosm of society or not. I
don't know if we can use that copout,'' said Charlie Waters, a
former Cowboys defensive back and a former Denver Broncos assistant
coach. ``There's just no way to justify some of the actions that
have gone on. No way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're human, and we make mistakes. But when there's judgment
involved, or lack of it, you start questioning what's happening
here. Are we breeding an athlete that can't think rational? It's
disconcerting.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams, like teams in other sports, are always eager to
forgive and forget past sins, regardless how grievous. Jimmy
Johnson, former coach of the Cowboys and the Dolphins, once claimed
he would draft Charles Manson if Manson ran the 40-yard dash in 4.4
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson still was in charge in April, the Dolphins gambled
a fifth-round choice on running back Cecil Collins, even though
Collins twice had been arrested for unauthorized entry involving
female residents in Baton Rouge, La. In December, Collins was
arrested on a burglary charge after neighbors accused him of
climbing through their bedroom window. The Dolphins suspended him
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Cecil Collins, we made a decision to draft him in the fifth
round,'' said Ackles, the Dolphins' director of football
operations. ``It's unfortunate that he can't seem to get over this
problem that he's got, because he's just throwing away a pretty
good career.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian Peter and Lawrence Phillips ran afoul of the law while
at the University of Nebraska, but both were given second chances
in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Peter, a defensive lineman, has a lengthy arrest record that
includes a history of assaults on women. The New England Patriots
drafted Peter in the fifth-round of the 1996 draft, but only a few
days later, after a furious public and media backlash, the Patriots
renounced his rights. Since signing with the New York Giants in
1997, Peter has stayed out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Phillips pleaded no contest to misdemeanor charges of
assault and trespassing after beating his former girlfriend, Kate
McEwen, and was sentenced to 12 months' probation. Still, the Rams
made him the No. 6 choice in the 1996 draft. In his 19-month stay
in St. Louis, Phillips was arrested three times, served 23 days in
jail and reportedly was fined more than 50 times by the team.
</P>
<P>
   NFL assistant coach Johnny Roland once said of Phillips,
``Everybody deserves a second chance, sometimes a third or fourth.
He didn't kill anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Waived by the Rams, the Dolphins and the 49ers, Phillips' NFL
career apparently is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like some of these athletes who are out there on the
field have a sense of entitlement rather than a sense of
gratitude,'' Charlie Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of starting in today's AFC-NFC Pro Bowl, Ray Lewis,
whose $26 million contract makes him the league's highest-paid
linebacker, sits in the Atlanta City Detention Center. At best,
Lewis is guilty of bad judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens officials reportedly had become concerned about Lewis'
social life and had planned to meet with him after he returned from
the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really shocked by what happened,'' Tampa Bay
Buccaneers coach Tony Dungy said. ``We talk to our players about
situations like that, when they're out late in crowds. We remind
them to be careful where you're going, who you're with and what's
going on around you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have been an innocent bystander. He may have had a
great deal to do with it. No one knows right now. But the fact is
that he's the only one anyone knows about. The national story is
Ray Lewis, rightfully or wrongly, and that's something you have to
be careful about.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:`Short memories'  &LR; body:The NFL has put on two faces
this season. At the same time Rams quarterback Kurt Warner, a
former grocery store stocker, was accepting his Super Bowl MVP
award Monday, Lewis was being booked for murder.
</P>
<P>
   The only question now is which will be the lasting image of the
1999 NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is important to recognize is that some of these
issues aren't new issues,'' Tagliabue said less than 72 hours
before Lewis was arrested. ``How many people know that 20, 25 years
ago, a player's wife killed a player in the NFL? How many people
know that? We tend to have short memories on many of these issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes life has a way of repeating itself. Sometimes we
have a way of getting all caught up today without understanding the
context in which these issues arise.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Philadelphia Eagles lineman Blenda Gay was found in his
apartment with his throat slashed. His wife reportedly had been
abused before she attacked her husband.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
