<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8237 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-OPERA-BOXOFFICE07-COX     02-06 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-BOXOFFICE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Opera touts successful '99 season
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Opera had a successful and profitable year,
according to tallies for the 1999 season just released by the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The number of opera subscribers crossed the 8,000 mark _ 1,200
more than in 1998 and a 123 percent increase over 1994 subscription
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Subscription revenue topped $1.5 million, and single tickets for
Atlanta Opera's four productions brought in another $500,000.
Ticket demand was so high for September's of ``La Boheme'' that the
company added a show. The popular Puccini opera played to a total
of 14,200 people. The season also featured ``Macbeth,'' ``The
Montagues and the Capulets'' and ``Samson and Delilah.''
</P>
<P>
   Earned income _ tickets, rehearsal hall rental and rentals of
sets, costumes and supertitles _ accounted for 56 percent of the
opera's $4.1 million operating budget for 1999. This compares more
than favorably with the national average of 50 percent earned
income for opera companies, according to Opera America, the
national service agency.
</P>
<P>
   Based on healthy season ticket sales for the 2000 season, which
begins April 6 with Verdi's ``Rigoletto,'' the opera projects 9,000
subscribers this season. The other operas for 2000 are Mozart's
``Cosi fan tutte,'' Donizetti's ``Lucia di Lammermoor'' and
Puccini's ``Turandot.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Atlanta Opera raised $6.4 million to renovate the
building on West Peachtree Street that became its new
administrative and rehearsal headquarters. The rehearsal hall and
other space in the building brought in rental fees from groups such
as Actor's Express, Ohio Light Opera and Theater of the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The opera says its outreach programs reached 54,000
schoolchildren in Atlanta and throughout Georgia. A three-year
$120,000 grant from the Goizueta Foundation enabled the company to
present opera to schools with high numbers of Latino students and
to collaborate with the Boys and Girls Clubs of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was at least one disappointment. Atlanta Opera
was featured in a segment of the ``Today'' show about the growth of
the opera in the United States, to be shown on Jan. 30, Super Bowl
Sunday. But the segment was pre-empted in the Atlanta viewing area
by ``Winter Storm Watch 2000'' coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a ton of fun working on the piece,'' said opera
publicist Amy Moudy, who spent the day after Thanksgiving
shepherding the NBC camera crew around the opera building. She said
WXIA, NBC's local affiliate, had agreed to run the segment on
``Peachtree Morning'' or ``Weekend News,'' provided the station
could get a copy from NBC. Its request is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
