<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Melba Moore's songs of trial and triumph
 &HT;    By Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ What a spin on the roller coaster of life!
</P>
<P>
   Entertainer Melba Moore has ridden from rags to riches to rags _
including a stint on welfare _ and back again. At a critical point
in her life story, Moore engaged in a marital dispute so tangled
and bitter, no amount of dispensation from this newspaper's libel
lawyers could have persuaded us to print the details.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the ideal subject for a cable television drama, or
maybe a musical, or better yet, a one-woman show with music _
``Sweet Songs of the Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to find out what happened to my life,'' Moore said
from her home outside New York City. ``I had to start over. This is
an opportunity to tell my story.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's childhood in New York and Newark, N.J., was not really
spent in rags. Her parents were musicians, but they lived close
enough to the edge to want their daughter educated for a better
life. So they encouraged her to become a teacher, and Moore went
through the motions, but what was she supposed to do with her
traffic-stopping, multi-octave voice and all those advantages of a
musical upbringing?
</P>
<P>
   To Moore, the answer was obvious: show business.
</P>
<P>
   After toiling as a backup singer during the 1960s, she joined
the cast of the rock musical ``Hair,'' eventually replacing Diane
Keaton in a lead role. Then it was her turn to launch a hit with
``Purlie,'' the gospel musical that won her a Tony Award for best
actress in 1970. People still talk about her soul-warming rendition
of the song ``I Got Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on to headlining New York and Las Vegas nightclubs.
Moore's property was so hot, she soon landed a television variety
show, shared with her then live-in, Clifton Davis. From the 1970s
through the '80s, she went from R&AMP;B to disco to rock to pop
recording careers, selling more than $15 million and coining
several gold records.
</P>
<P>
   She ruled her world. Or did she?
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s, in a replay of earlier fallings-out with a manager,
she and husband/manager Charles Huggins made a spectacular break
involving inflammatory accusations on both sides. Moore said she
was left with nothing but debts, and in 1993, she registered for
welfare, a move that was documented by thick tabloid headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really dealt with money (before),'' she said. ``I
ended up destitute and my only concern was my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Moore's first moves was to tell her story in the form of
a one-woman play, which was seen by an entertainment executive in
Florida. Before long, she was back on Broadway as Fantine, the
beleaguered mother in the musical ``Les Miserables.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to learn how to book myself. I couldn't bring my excess
baggage to an agent,'' she said. ``The response has been
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Moore regularly tells her story of personal trial and
triumph to all sorts of audiences.
</P>
<P>
   She credits religion with warding off the darkest nights. She
advises those facing similar problems to put spirituality at ``the
center of your world, no matter what trials and harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
