<SLUG> BC-MONDAYS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting over the Monday blues
 &HT;    By Julie Bonnin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Monday's child may be full of grace, but chances
are he didn't want to get up this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Got a classroom full of surly, unruly children? Half the office
called in sick? (Or, got an office full of surly, unruly office
workers? Half the classroom called in sick?)
</P>
<P>
   It's Monday. Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Littleton's Monday mornings start on Sunday nights, when a
knot starts churning in her stomach. She's contemplating what may
or may not happen the next day at Abiding Love Lutheran Child
Development Center, where she's been director since 1974. One of
the things that time has taught her is that if someone's going to
call in sick, it's going to be on a Monday morning. If the kids are
going to be clingy and anxious, it's going to be on a Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely recognize Monday morning,'' says Littleton,
comparing it to full moons and cold fronts as a dependable behavior
predictor. ``It's just a hard morning for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more proof.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, researchers found that people with
heartbeat irregularities have more problems on Mondays, even after
they've retired, suggesting that their bodies still jolt at the
memory of the start of the work week.
</P>
<P>
   And the soundtrack for a Monday has been burnt toast dark
throughout memory: Mondays in music are blue, black, stormy, gloomy
and bitter. The second day of the week is also an unlikely common
ground for musicians as disparate as jazz chanteuse Lena Horne
(``Get Rid of Monday'') and the '80s new wave band the Boomtown
Rats (``I Don't Like Mondays'').
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't have to be that way, especially if you spend any
time talking to the relentlessly upbeat Ann Fry, a social worker,
business coach and motivator with an answering machine message that
concludes, ``Now go and make it a very, very wonderful day!''
</P>
<P>
   Fry and Terrill Fischer, her partner in an enterprise called
Humor University, offered some tips for making Mondays better. Home
and business organizer Bonnie Henderson, whose business is called
The Solution, also pitched in ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Now go out and make it a very, very wonderful day!
</P>
<P>
   _ Figure out why you dread Mondays. If it's because there just
isn't enough time to do all the things you want to do on the
weekend, consider whether you could reschedule some of those
activities during the week (making weeknights something to look
forward to).
</P>
<P>
   _ If getting up on Monday is a drag because you're not looking
forward to work, the answer may be an attitude adjustment (or
career counseling). Monday may need to be the morning you treat
yourself to a doughnut or a latte.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make Mondays silly. Trade goofy wake-up calls with another
person or family. First thing in the morning, stand in front of the
mirror and let out a full-blown belly laugh. Do your whole routine
backward (but no clothes in the shower, please). The idea is to
force yourself out of the grumpy mode.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lobby the federal government for more Monday holidays.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't waste potential planning time on Fridays. Too many
workers succumb to weekend fever, rather than thinking about the
week ahead. But a to-do list on Monday morning will help things go
smoother.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't veer off schedule too much over the weekend. This is
especially true for young kids, but going to sleep and getting up
at about the same time during the weekend will make getting back
into the routine on Monday morning easier for adults, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prepare more on Sunday night. Have bags packed, or load up the
car the night before to ease the early morning demands. Families
with kids should get them involved as much as possible. They can
lay out their clothes ahead of time or put out breakfast cereals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pretend it's Tuesday. Or Wednesday, or whatever day that makes
you feel better.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDTRACK FOR A MONDAY:
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Monday,'' John Lee Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Monday,'' Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stormy Monday,'' Dirty Dozen Brass Band
</P>
<P>
   and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bitter Monday,'' Vic Bondi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloomy Monday,'' Miriam Klein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Don't Like Mondays,'' Boomtown Rats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Don't Do Mondays,'' D-Wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Rid of Monday,'' Lena Horne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Died One Monday,'' Just Trip.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
