<SLUG> BC-VALENTINE-TRIP07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whisk your sweetie away for Valentine's Day
 &HT;    By Ray Marcano
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Candy, dinner and flowers are among the more
traditional Valentine's fare. But how about something different
this year _ a short trip with memories that will last longer than
those overpriced and long-dead roses?
</P>
<P>
   With planning, there are all kinds of ways to show your
affection while staying within a budget.
</P>
<P>
   _ $500 and up: Take a three-day weekend out of town. Look for
the Internet bargain air fare specials and fly to several major
cities for as little as $79 round trip. The Web site
www.bestfares.com is terrific for tracking not only airline but
also hotel specials. The specials vary, but they're real bargains.
True, you won't know what's available until a few days before you
leave, but that's part of the romance and intrigue. Most of these
specials require travel Saturday and return Monday or Tuesday, so
make sure you have some extra time. (Valentine's Day falls on
Monday, Feb. 14, anyway). For hotels, it's always good to check the
Web, but then call the hotels in person to see if they offer
last-minute deals.
</P>
<P>
   _ $100 to $250: How about an evening at the symphony? Most have
programs on Fridays and Saturdays. Select your favorite restaurant,
call ahead and ask if they'll spruce up the table with some special
Valentine's decorations. And if you really know your mate, order
the meal ahead of time _ and sit next to him or her, not across the
table staring through a vase. Then make sure you have a little
something for Monday, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Less than $100: Lots of people don't have tons of money to
spend on Valentine's Day. That doesn't mean you can't have a good
time. If you can't travel, stay home. Surprise your special person
with his or her favorite meal _ home-cooked, of course, on Sunday
or Monday night. Go to a movie, or stay home and rent one. Get a
good bottle of wine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free: Tell your mate how much you care. And all you have to
do, in many cases, is travel across the living room to do that.
</P>
<P>
   _ Travel tips: Those who like to change flights by going
standby, beware. Your luggage might end up on your original flight,
and if it does, the airline might not bring it to you. Be sure to
ask the airline reps what happens if your baggage doesn't get on
the standby flight .... And to those who rent cars, beware hidden
charges. You could be hit with a hefty fee if you try to upgrade
your car from intermediate to large or domestic to import. At a
recent stop, an agent told me an upgrade from an intermediate to
large model would cost $3 a day, but the printed contract also had
a $14 per day upgrade fee that the agent never mentioned. After
complaining, I got the car for the $3 additional.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
