</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVMARY-RHODA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love isn't all around in `Mary &AMP; Rhoda'
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a memorable moment in the first episode of the
classic '70s sitcom ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' where TV newsroom
head Lou Grant asks job applicant Mary Richards her age. She's 30,
she responds without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that,'' Lou muses aloud. ``No hedging, no `How old do I
look'?''
</P>
<P>
   A brief pause, after which Mary asks a bit too casually: ``How
old do I look?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty!'' Lou barks dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   A show that in 1970 was considered funny and groundbreaking _ as
a single-by-choice, 30-something career gal with a hint of a sex
life, Mary Richards was pretty much a first for TV _ still is
beloved in reruns today, still for much the same reasons. The shock
value may be gone, but the acting still comes off as pitch-perfect,
the comedic writing as crackerjack.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, Mary always looks 30.
</P>
<P>
   All of which brings us to ``Mary &AMP; Rhoda,'' tonight's reunion
movie on ABC. Actually, executive producer and star Moore says it's
more a story about ``moving on'' than reuniting, which probably
explains why there's nary a mention _ let alone a glimpse _ of Lou,
Murray, Sue Ann or any of the other much-more-than-supporting
characters from the Minneapolis-based original series (Ted Knight,
who played the lovable lunkhead TV anchorman Ted Baxter, died in
1986).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we get the recently widowed Mary Richards and the
twice-divorced Rhoda Morgenstern Gerard Rousseau (Valerie Harper),
essentially starting their lives over again in big, bad
youth-obsessed New York City. And doing it without each other's
friendship and support, at least initially: Thanks to a falling-out
at Rhoda's second wedding (Mary caught the French groom pawing at a
bridesmaid), the duo haven't seen each other in years, which may be
the single most unbelievable part of a movie that otherwise tends
to wallow in gritty reality. Or at least what passes for the same
on television.
</P>
<P>
   Both women job-hunting again at _ gulp! _ the ripe old age of
60? OK, we can accept that.
</P>
<P>
   When Mary does land a job back in TV news, her first story
involves a gang shooting? Not exactly the '70s sitcom's
lighthearted territory, but, hey, it's sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary and Rhoda estranged from each other for however many
(they never really say) years? Please, no one who ever watched the
old series, who remembers how these two stuck together through
thick and thin, through liking the same guy and coveting the same
apartment, could possibly buy that one.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like a case of someone with a tad too much
affection for the original ``Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' I readily
plead guilty. And I suspect I'm not alone: Moore herself has said
that Les Moonves, president of CBS (where the original series ran)
warned her, ``Do you realize you're talking about possibly casting
a shadow on what I think was arguably the best situation comedy
ever on television?''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes shadows are too big to escape, no matter how
well-intentioned the effort. So while Moore gets credit for
stretching beyond the usual reunion movie fare (she and Rhoda have
even acquired college-age daughters, with all their attendant
problems), you might just end up wishing she hadn't bothered. Just
as 60 never looks as young as 30, no reunion movie could ever hope
to recapture the effervescent spirit of that pitch-perfect,
crackerjack sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   So, no hedging: Watch ``Mary &AMP; Rhoda'' once for curiosity or
sentimentality's sake. Then go back to watching ``The Mary Tyler
Moore Show'' reruns in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
