<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-STRIKE _ MEXICO CITY _ Thousands of Mexican police ended
the 10-month occupation of Latin America's largest university
Sunday, raiding the main campus and arresting more than 600
students. The police appeared to have full control of the campus of
the 260,000-student National Autonomous University of Mexico after
the 6 a.m. (CST) raid. Among those arrested were eight strike
leaders. The strike has been marked by sometimes violent
demonstrations that tied up Mexico City's most important streets.
Clashes occurred between students supporting and opposed to the
strike. Developing. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA _ INGUSHETIA, Russia _ As complaints of
atrocities by Russian soldiers mount, human rights groups prepare
to release on Monday the first report of possible war crimes
against Chechen refugees by the Russian military during its
three-month campaign against separatist rebels in the breakaway
republic of Chechnya. Developing. (Coker, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-SENATE _ Coverage of first lady Hillary Clinton's formal
announcement for the U.S. Senate race in New York. (Vejnoska,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CRAWFISH _ NEW ORLEANS _ You call that a crawfish? Looks more
like a fire ant. Louisiana's crawfish season normally peaks in
February, with plenty of fat, juicy mudbugs going from fishermen's
nets into propane-fired boiling pots. But crawfish farmers, fish
mongers and restaurant owners agree: This the worst season in
memory. (Koingsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
