<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Feb. 7:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-POLITICS (Zagreb, Croatia) _ Croatia votes on Monday for
only its second president in a tightening race that hinges more on
personality than on policy. But after the death in December of the
autocratic Franjo Tudjman, who ruled Croatia from its independence
in 1991, voters still seem likely to go for the man who has
presented himself as least ambitious and power-hungry, the
avuncular Stipe Mesic, 65. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-LABOR (Washington) _ President Clinton plans to ask
Congress to more than double the nation's spending on reducing
child labor overseas, administration officials said Sunday. By
Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   KOHL-KICKBACKS (Berlin) _ Prosecutors estimate that more than
$70 million was illegally paid in kickbacks to middlemen on the
sales of tanks and a dilapidated oil refinery during the rule of
Helmut Kohl, the former chancellor whose once glowing reputation
has already been battered by revelations of secret party financing.
By Roger Cohen and John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VIOLENCE (Mitrovica, Yugoslavia) _ A look at the violence
between Serbs and Albanians last week in the divided town of
Mitrovica, and the lives of the minorities on both sides. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) Developments. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-HAIDER (Berlin) _ Jorg Haider, the rightist leader whose
Freedom Party is part of the new Austrian government, said Sunday
that ethnic Germans expelled from what was Czechoslovakia at the
end of World War II should be entitled to the same compensation as
Austrian Jews persecuted by the Nazis. The statement reopened an
old, often suppressed grievance in the German-speaking world, and
it seemed certain to intensify international unease over Haider. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-HEZBOLLAH (Jerusalem) _ One Israeli soldier was killed
and six were wounded in a Hezbollah attack in southern Lebanon,
prompting Prime Minister Ehud Barak to promise retaliation the day
after Israel suspended even informal contacts with the guerrillas'
Syrian sponsors. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-STUDENTS (Mexico City) _ Thousands of Mexican police
ended the nine-month occupation of Latin America's largest
university Sunday, raiding the main campus and arresting 632
students. By Julia Preston.
</P>
