<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w BC-DEFENSE-BUDGET-$ADV07     02-06 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFENSE-BUDGET-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHITE HOUSE ADDS MORE MONEY FOR MISSILE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release 8 a.m. EST Monday, Feb. 7) &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The $291 billion defense budget the Clinton
administration is unveiling Monday boosts funds for a futuristic
weapon system that would link radars, space sensors and rockets to
protect the United States from a missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   The weapon, which is known as National Missile Defense, is a
high priority for both the administration and Republican-controlled
Congress. The budget, for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1,
includes an increase of $400 million over last year's National
Missile Defense funding level, and an overall increase of $2.3
billion through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   A senior defense official said the additional money ensures the
program will be sufficiently ``robust'' by increasing the number of
rocket interceptors from 20 to 100. The additional funds also allow
the Pentagon to upgrade early warning facilities and build a new
radar complex in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to decide this summer whether to
commit the government to deploying a missile defense system to
shield the 50 states against missile attack, a system that could
cost $12.7 billion. The goal is to have it in place by 2005. But
the cost could grow substantially if additional rockets and launch
sites are added later.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address on Jan. 27, Clinton said the
United States needs ``a system to defend against new missile
threats, while working to preserve our Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty with Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike President Ronald Reagan's vision of an elaborate
space-based shield to thwart hundreds of intercontinental ballistic
missiles, National Missile Defense is designed to hit only a few
missiles sent aloft by ``rogue nations'' like North Korea or a
missile accidentally launched by Russia or China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to deploy the system depends on two
variables: If there continues to be a growing missile threat from
potential foes, and if the Pentagon can achieve the technological
breakthroughs required so that this complex system of advanced
sensors, radars and missiles actually works.
</P>
<P>
   A major concern _ evident in a test failure of the weapon on
Jan. 19 _ is that it might simply be too difficult to track and
destroy a missile traveling several times the speed of sound and to
blow it up by ramming it with another missile.
</P>
<P>
   During the test failure, two infrared sensors failed to guide
the high-speed interceptor ``kill vehicle'' fired from a Pacific
atoll into a dummy warhead in space launched from Vandenberg Air
Force Base in California.
</P>
<P>
   But Defense Secretary William Cohen said that despite the
failure, Pentagon officials believe the technology will work,
asserting that the interceptor came within 100 feet of hitting its
target. ``I think the technology is certainly proving to be on the
right track,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to technology hurdles, the weapon faces political
obstacles. Cohen is worried that Russia and China are likely to use
European concerns about the missile defense system to drive a wedge
between Washington and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would anticipate that the Russians and Chinese will try to
dissuade our European allies from endorsing or embracing the
project, to try to find weaknesses and differences of opinion and
try to exploit those,'' Cohen said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China assert that such a weapon would violate the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty between the Soviet Union and
United States. The Europeans are concerned that such a weapon could
destabilize relations with Russia, while fomenting an isolationist
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he was hopeful of winning Russian agreement to amend
the ABM treaty to permit deployment of the system. If the Russians
do not agree, the president would be faced with the prospect of
withdrawing from the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   National Missile Defense has four major components:
</P>
<P>
   _ Space- and ground-based sensors to provide early warning of
attacking missiles;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ground-based radars to track the threatening warheads;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ground-based missile interceptors based in North Dakota and
possibly Alaska to collide with and destroy enemy warheads;
</P>
<P>
   _ A battle-management system that would link all the components
with military commanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
