<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Feb. 13)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Jan. 29 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Island, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and
</P>
<P>
   a missionary are brought together by a startling
</P>
<P>
   secret.
</P>
<P>
   2. A MAP OF THE WORLD, by Jane Hamilton. (Anchor,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) When a dairy farmer's wife makes a mistake
</P>
<P>
   one morning, her life falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   3. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE,
</P>
<P>
   by J.K. Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   4. VECTOR, by Robin Cook. (Berkley, $7.99.) A New York
</P>
<P>
   City cabdriver, once a Soviet expert in biological
</P>
<P>
   weapons, joins forces with a neofascist skinhead militia.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE GREEN MILE, by Stephen King. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A six-part thriller set on death row at Cold Mountain
</P>
<P>
   Penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   6. BITTERSWEET RAIN, by Sandra Brown. (Warner, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A young widow is pursued by her first boyfriend, who is
</P>
<P>
   also her stepson.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE COURTSHIP, by Catherine Coulter. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A strong-willed woman finds romance and adventure in
</P>
<P>
   Regency London.
</P>
<P>
   8. SOUTHERN CROSS, by Patricia Cornwell. (Berkley,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A former police chief is summoned to Richmond,
</P>
<P>
   Va., to clean up scandalous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   9. APOLLYON, by Tim LaHaye and Jerry B. Jenkins. (Tyndale,
</P>
<P>
   $13.99.) After the rapture of the saved, the world's
</P>
<P>
   remaining believers confront the Antichrist. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10. CELEBRATION, by Fern Michaels. (Zebra, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   After her conniving husband disappears with $8 million,
</P>
<P>
   an heiress falls for a banker.
</P>
<P>
   11. SNOW FALLING ON CEDARS, by David Guterson. (Vintage,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) A murder trial recalls the wartime internment
</P>
<P>
   of Japanese-Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   12. MANNER OF DEATH, by Stephen White. (Signet, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A psychologist investigates the seemingly accidental
</P>
<P>
   deaths of six people.
</P>
<P>
   13. STORMING HEAVEN, by Kyle Mills. (HarperPaperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A maverick FBI agent probes the murder of a
</P>
<P>
   millionaire and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   14. SEIZE THE NIGHT, by Dean Koontz. (Bantam, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Snow seeks to discover why children in
</P>
<P>
   his hometown keep disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14.) Five female characters narrate
</P>
<P>
   a novel set in the Belgian Congo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   4. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man
</P>
<P>
   who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   5. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a
</P>
<P>
   single crew.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $10.95.) The author of ``A Child
</P>
<P>
   Called `It''' recalls his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   7. BLIND MAN'S BLUFF, by Sherry Sontag and Christopher
</P>
<P>
   Drew with Annette Lawrence Drew. (HarperPaperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) American espionage by submarine, from the
</P>
<P>
   Cold War to the present.
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $13.) How a murderer helped James
</P>
<P>
   Murray compile the Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) THE ORCHID THIEF, by Susan Orlean. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) A journalist's account of a man who was caught
</P>
<P>
   pilfering 200 rare orchids.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor, $13 and
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest
</P>
<P>
   season in history.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) OUR DUMB CENTURY, edited by Scott Dikkers. (Three
</P>
<P>
   Rivers, $15.) Newspaper headlines making fun of the great
</P>
<P>
   events of the past century.
</P>
<P>
   14. GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) A celebration of life in the Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways
</P>
<P>
   to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. THE CARBOHYDRATE ADDICT'S DIET, by Rachael F. Heller
</P>
<P>
   and Richard F. Heller. (Signet, $6.99.) A program for
</P>
<P>
   weight loss. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. LIFE STRATEGIES, by Phillip C. McGraw. (Hyperion,
</P>
<P>
   $11.95.) How to find what matters in your life and
</P>
<P>
   what to do about it. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. PROTEIN POWER, by Michael R. Eades and Mary Dan
</P>
<P>
   Eades. (Bantam, $14 and $6.50.) Two physicians offer
</P>
<P>
   a protein-rich, low-carbohydrate plan for losing weight. (b)
</P>
