<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8308 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     02-06 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 13)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE YEAR OF READING PROUST: A Memoir in Real Time &LR;  By Phyllis
Rose. Counterpoint, $15. Actually, Proust plays a fairly small role
in this book, but serves as a guide for the author as she reflects
with humor and compassion on everyday life and her writing career.
Her free-ranging memoir is ``crisply written, disarmingly frank and
self-critical, rich in felicitous turns and well-told episodes,''
Victor Brombert wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMY AND ISABELLE &LR;  By Elizabeth Strout. Vintage Contemporaries,
$13. Set in a small New England town in the 1960s, this first novel
explores the love-hate relationship between a shy 16-year-old girl
and her prim mother, both of whom ache for a romantic life beyond
the drab one they are forced to settle for. The drama turns on the
teenager's sexual and intellectual awakening, which flows from her
infatuation with her math teacher. The result is ``one of those
rare, invigorating books that take an apparently familiar world and
peer into it with ruthless intimacy, revealing a strange and
startling place, Suzanne Berne wrote in The New York Times Book
Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LITTLE GREEN MEN &LR;  By Christopher Buckley. HarperPerennial, $13.
This political satire, set in Washington and featuring a rich array
of worthy targets, focuses on a supersecret government agency (even
the president doesn't know about it) whose mission is to stage UFO
sightings and alien abductions. The result is a ``witty,
high-spirited romp,'' Mordecai Richler wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BALTIMORE CASE: A Trial of Politics, Science, and
Character &LR;  By Daniel J. Kevles. Norton, $15.95. This account of a
dispute between self-appointed science police and a team of
researchers accused of fraud and arrogance but cleared 10 years
later is a cautionary tale about the perils of ultracompetitive
``big science.'' In 1998 the reviewer Roy Porter called this ``a
splendid study of a major contemporary scientific scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WAY OF THE WORLD: From the Dawn of Civilizations to the Eve
of the Twenty-First Century &LR;  By David Fromkin. Vintage, $13. A
historian squeezes the story of humanity into 222 pages, taking a
progressive, Western approach in which he sets forth eight stages
in universal history and finds that things have improved over time.
Last year William R. Everdell praised the author for tackling ``one
of the great literary challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEREWOLVES IN THEIR YOUTH: Stories &LR;  By Michael Chabon. Picador
USA, $12. These stories focus on small-scale situations _ a
baseball practice, a bris, a graduation party _ in which the
characters are caught during sudden moments of change and epiphany.
Last year the reviewer Michael Gorra found this to be an uneven
collection but admired the ``witty and resonant prose.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GHOST TOWN &LR;  By Robert Coover. Grove, $12. A master of literary
hypertext rips apart cinematic cliches in this anti-narrative about
the misadventures of an everyman cowpoke in a frontier town.
Pitching wildly between the lyrical, the silly and the violent, the
novel has ``moments that take us to the core of existential
American solitude,'' Sven Birkerts wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHOPIN IN PARIS: The Life and Times of the Romantic Composer &LR; 
By Tad Szulc. Da Capo, $16. This journalistic biography, focusing
on the Polish-born composer's many fruitful years in Paris, relies
heavily on memoirs, letters and journals, many of them previously
untranslated. The book's ``strength lies in ... its steady
accumulation of detail,'' Paul Driver said in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAHLER: A Biography &LR; , by Jonathan Carr (Overlook, $16.95),
sifts through a voluminous amount of Mahler scholarship to provide
a balanced portrait of the enigmatic Austrian composer. The result
is ``an intelligent, solidly based, up-to-date account of Mahler's
life interleaved with nontechnical but still perceptive musical
insights,'' John Rockwell wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLOSE RANGE: Wyoming Stories &LR;  By Annie Proulx. Scribner, $13.
The hardpan ranchers, battered cowboys and macho rodeo riders in
these stories are shaped by the harsh, unforgiving landscape of
Wyoming. ``Their lives are a futile uphill struggle conducted as a
downhill, out-of-control tearaway,'' Richard Eder wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFTER LONG SILENCE: A Memoir &LR;  By Helen Fremont. Delta, $12.95.
The author, who was raised as a Roman Catholic, discovered as an
adult that her parents were Ukrainian Jews who escaped the
Holocaust and invented new lives in America. She explores their
secret lives in ``a book that is part detective story, part
literary memoir, part imagined past,'' Thane Rosenbaum wrote in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EVENING NEWS &LR;  By Marly Swick. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $13.95.
When a 9-year-old boy accidentally shoots and kills his
half-sister, his family is forced to confront profound issues of
forgiveness, compassion and emotional survival. ``Provocatively,
this novel suggests that while joy can be shared, anguish can only
be endured alone,'' James Polk wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
