<HEADER>
A8315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      02-06 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WHEN BATTLING CANDIDATES AGREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Feb. 6:
</P>
<P>
   The intense battle among George W. Bush, John McCain, Al Gore
and Bill Bradley for their parties' nominations has brought with it
a striking thematic development. Despite their claimed ideological
differences, the candidates are often quite close together in
endorsing the need for improvements in education, health care and
programs for the poor. Although Bush's tax cut proposal has an
anti-government tinge to it, the candidates have defined an
unacknowledged consensus over the desirability of a strong federal
role in critical areas of domestic policy. Clearly, they are
responding to signals from the voters about governing from what the
pollster Mark Penn and others call the ``vital center.''
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkably short time, the campaign's hottest star, McCain,
has transformed himself from a single-issue candidate backing
campaign finance reform to one with a series of proposals that
alter some traditional GOP positions. The most distinctive of these
is his proposal to scale back on tax cuts and spend a large chunk
of the projected budget surplus on Social Security, Medicare,
various domestic programs and paying down the federal debt. Like
every major candidate, he also favors the right to sue health
maintenance organizations. McCain also wants prescription drug
subsidies for the elderly and health care for poor children. The
senator calls himself a Reagan conservative, but these are not
policies associated with conservatism for the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's tax-cut scheme is rooted in conservative dogma about
starving the federal treasury of revenue in order to keep the
liberals from spending it. But the governor is not as reflexively
anti-government as his tax cut would imply. He would set aside $8
billion in his first budget for anti-poverty programs, a
substantial sum. His ads promise to save Social Security, and he,
too, favors a prescription drug benefit for the elderly, though in
the context of linking Medicare to private insurance programs. On
education, Bush disdains an expanded federal role, but he wants
Washington to demand performance standards for students and rescind
aid if the standards are not met.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore trash each other's policies, but in truth both
are moderate or left-of-center Democrats who have studied President
Clinton's policy of bringing the party into the mainstream. Both
oppose the efforts of organized labor to block free trade. Bradley
has stirred the idealistic wing of the party by saying that the
next president must concentrate on reaching out to the poor,
especially for health care. He wants Democrats to think big
ambitious thoughts, but his health care program is not the sort of
radical approach that many liberals were advocating when Clinton
was mulling the issue in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, in fact, Clinton himself was more of a dreamer of big
dreams than he is today. In his State of the Union address, he
reminded Congress that ``the lesson of our history _ and the lesson
of the last seven years _ is that great goals are reached step by
step.'' The ``step by step'' approach is the one defended by Gore
in countless speeches. The vice president is also betting that
education _ the financing of new schools and teachers _ is perhaps
more compelling to voters this year than expanding health care to
the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's and Clinton's thinking seems to be in line with a new
survey by Penn, the Democratic pollster, which argues that
Americans are as resistant to ambitious left-wing domestic schemes
as they are to right-wing social proposals like banning abortion
and allowing prayer in schools. Penn says this ideology involves
``limited but activist government,'' balanced budgets, free trade
and traditional social values without any attempt to enforce those
values on Americans who may not agree. The four main candidates do
not accept all these principles all the time. But one of the
reasons this campaign has become so interesting is that all four
are avoiding thunderous ideological pronouncements about government
and responding to a maturing public demand for sound, flexible
policies that deal with the country's enduring problems in health
care, education and poverty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 1620EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0045 </DOCNO>
