<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNAL ESCALATES BATTLE WITH BRITISH RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal, long an also-ran to The Financial Times
in the competition for European consumers of financial news, has
begun marketing its way across the Continent to challenge its
rival's dominance _ and The Financial Times is responding in kind.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Journal will unveil its new Continental persona, a
newspaper that colors its name blue and abandons the pinstriped
look of the American edition in favor of a colorful, Web-influenced
design.
</P>
<P>
   More important, it will repackage and supplement its coverage of
technology and the new economy in a new section called Networking,
with specialized columns on subjects like advertising in Europe,
and add about 14 reporters, bringing the total to more than 80.
</P>
<P>
   It will also take advantage of its 6-month-old alliance with the
von Holtzbrinck Group, publisher of the German business daily
Handelsblatt, by increasing the number of Handelsblatt articles it
translates and publishes and trading news executives with its
German partner. In June, Dow Jones &AMP; Co., the Journal's parent,
took a 22 percent stake in Handelsblatt, while von Holtzbrinck
bought 49 percent of The Wall Street Journal Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Tofel, vice president for corporate communications at
Dow Jones, said the company intended to step up its challenge to
The Financial Times, which outsells the Journal 121,000 to 83,000
on the Continent. The Journal is aiming at a 140,000 circulation by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times currently trounces its American rival in its
home base of Britain, 200,000 to 67,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal's move comes little more than a year after The
Financial Times, which is owned by Pearson PLC, made an effort to
raise its salmon-pink profile in the United States, where its
circulation, now 102,000, has nearly tripled in three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times has Continental designs of its own. Lionel
Barber, the paper's news editor and second in command of the
newsroom, said on Friday that the start of The Financial Times'
German-language version, for which it has hired 120 journalists, is
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Barber also said that the newspaper had hired an additional 120
journalists in London and New York to write for its Web site,
ft.com. All their coverage can be used in any of the paper's print
or online editions.
</P>
<P>
   Tofel, for his part, said: ``They're not a serious threat to us
in America. We've won the game in Latin America. There is no game
in Britain _ they won. The game is in the continent of Europe.
We're going to step up and play the game much more aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   Quiz Show's Popularity Makes It a Weapon
</P>
<P>
   ABC has begun using its game show hit, ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' as a club, slotting it against potential hits on
other networks to squash them. The competing networks charge that
the slash-and-burn tactic could threaten the health of the
broadcast business.
</P>
<P>
   The most potent use of ``Millionaire'' took place last week. NBC
had believed it was building an audience for its own game show,
``Twenty One,'' on Wednesday nights. ABC sent in a special edition
of ``Millionaire.'' Even with minimum publicity, ``Millionaire''
pushed ``Twenty One,'' to its lowest rating ever.
</P>
<P>
   As one ABC executive said of ``Millionaire,'' ``We'll use it
both to launch our own new shows and to blunt shows the other guys
have.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC's next target: ``The Grammy Awards'' on CBS on Feb. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the other networks are, to say the least,
distressed. Garth Ancier, president of NBC Entertainment, said, ``I
think what they did to us was a cheap shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC's top entertainment executives declined to comment on the
strategy. But one senior ABC executive dismissed the criticism,
saying: ``This is business. We're playing hardball.''
</P>
<P>
   One executive noted that NBC had used the same tactic in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Moonves, president of CBS Television, called
``Millionaire'' ``an atomic bomb that they can use against
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancier said, ``If they continue to do this, at some point they
can do tremendous damage to this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancier said he believed ABC was making a potentially
self-destructive mistake in replacing so many of its entertainment
shows with ``Millionaire'' specials.
</P>
<P>
   ``They laughed when I said it was like crack for them, but it
is,'' he said. ``They're willing to take off two up and coming
comedies to put `Millionaire' on a Wednesday to try to hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancier noted that he had an upcoming show, ``Daddio,'' delivered
by the production company run by Walt Disney, ABC's parent company.
``I could put `Daddio' against `Millionaire' and damage a product
they own,'' Ancier said. ``I don't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does ABC. An ABC executive said ABC's stealth forays would
not be used against a show generated by the Disney television
studio.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Square Off Over Clinton Scandal
</P>
<P>
   Call it the battle of the welterweight Clinton-scandal authors.
</P>
<P>
   In this corner, Michael Isikoff of Newsweek magazine, a scrappy
reporter whose work ushered in the story about President Clinton's
relationship with Monica Lewinsky and author of last year's
``Uncovering Clinton: A Reporter's Story'' (Crown). In this corner:
Jeffrey Toobin, the telegenic ABC News commentator, contributor to
The New Yorker magazine and author of the recently published ``A
Vast Conspiracy: The Real Story of the Sex Scandal That Nearly
Brought Down a President'' (Random House).
</P>
<P>
   Isikoff is spitting mad about Toobin's book, which Isikoff
contends is unfair to him at every turn, portraying him as a
Clinton enemy motivated by the chance at a big-ticket book
contract.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated Jan. 14, his Newsweek editor, Ann McDaniel,
wrote to Ann Godoff, editor in chief of Random House, that Toobin's
``treatment of Michael Isikoff in `A Vast Conspiracy' is
egregiously unfair'' and that Toobin refused to interview Isikoff,
even though he wrote in detail about Isikoff's reporting in ``A
Vast Conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Isikoff was so angry that he has written an addendum to his
book, which will appear in the paperback edition of ``Uncovering
Clinton.'' In the addendum, he writes that Toobin's book is part of
``a continuing public market for nonsense.'' The book, he says,
``recycled ridiculous innuendo about me: I was, Toobin argued, one
of Clinton's longtime `enemies' who was supposedly motivated in my
reporting by my `greed' for a book contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Toobin said that he did interview Isikoff during the course of
writing his book and that it was Isikoff who made overtures to him
and not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic example of how American journalists can dish
it out but they can't take it,'' he said. ``I interviewed him. I
exchanged letters with him. He invited me to this now-infamous
lunch, and now he's whining like a child.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALEX KUCZYNSKI &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
