<HEADLINE>
TREASURY TO SELL BILLS AND NOTES THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word PLUS in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Treasury's schedule of financings this week includes
Monday's regular weekly auction of three- and six-month bills and
the government's quarterly refunding including five-year notes,
10-year notes and 30-year bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In when-issued trading, the five-year notes being sold Tuesday
are offered at a price to yield 6.67 percent, while the 10-year
notes being sold on Wednesday are offered at a price to yield 6.48
percent. The 30-year bond, which concludes the refunding on
Thursday, is offered at a price to yield 6.15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By the close of the New York cash market on Friday, traders
said, the rate on the outstanding three-month bill was 5.48 percent
and the rate on the six-month bill was 5.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The following taxable and tax-exempt fixed-income issues are
scheduled for pricing this week:
