<HEADLINE>
FCC DENIES SINCLAIR'S REQUEST TO MODIFY DIGITAL TV STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (js) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By a 5-0 vote, the Federal Communications
Commission decided on Friday to deny a petition from the Sinclair
Broadcast Group asking the commission to modify the nation's
digital television standard.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair, which is based in Baltimore and owns or operates 59
television stations, more than any other company, began complaining
last summer that the digital standard, which was adopted by the
government in 1997, included transmission technology that did not
work very well.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of tests, Sinclair showed that the digital
television receivers that are now on the market are often incapable
of receiving an acceptable television picture if the receiving
antenna is not within a direct line of sight of the transmitting
antenna. Sinclair, joined by 250 other television stations, filed a
petition in October asking the FCC to revise the standard so that
stations could choose to use a transmission technology that is
being used in Europe and that had shown in tests by Sinclair that
it worked better in many circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of additional stations later joined the petition or at
least expressed support for parts of Sinclair's goals. Sinclair and
the other stations had hoped the commission would put the petition
out for comment, allowing a broad industry debate. But a
spontaneous industry debate took place on its own, and most
mainstream broadcasting and consumer electronics groups said they
opposed Sinclair's request. Finally, on Friday, the commission
denied Sinclair's request.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Sinclair, the commission said numerous studies
had shown that the current transmission standard was adequate. ``We
do not find that Sinclair has presented any valid technical
information to refute'' those studies, the letter said. The
commission also said that shortcomings found in the
first-generation digital receivers now being sold would probably be
remedied in future products.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the FCC decision, Sinclair said only, ``We have
not yet seen the actual language of the order and will refrain from
making a detailed statement until we have had an opportunity to
review it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
