<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8337 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-REVISIONS-MAEWEST-NYT     02-06 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVISIONS-MAEWEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE SIDLED UP TO A MAN'S WORLD AND MADE IT HERS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Boldface word in first sentence should be italicized.) 
(nk) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No, I must disagree with Woody Allen: Mae West  &UR; is  &LR; a comic
genius. He rated her just below Chaplin and Keaton in a recent
interview, and it's true that she lacks their near-infinite
physical variety. She's a physical minimalist whose comedy depends
on words that incessantly praise and mock her own deeds.
</P>
<P>
   As for Allen's other designated geniuses, W.C. Fields and
Groucho and Harpo Marx, West is more daring than Fields, as smart
as Groucho and has no more interest in Harpo's puckishness than she
has in Chaplin's pathos or Keaton's stringent mournfulness.
</P>
<P>
   But she belongs in their band, as an original and an originator.
(What do men want? Dear God, what do they want?)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we could call her a less pure comic than Chaplin or
Keaton, a genius (like Groucho) at creating a theatrical
personality so potent it could make everyone else in sight look
like a footnote. With that shimmy-swagger, those lips that could
purse like a lady's or smirk like a gangster's, those raunchy
wisecracks spoken in a voice from some improbable zone, where white
Brooklyn met black Memphis. (``I used to be snow white, but I
drifted.'') Her characters are she-warriors of the underworld,
entertainers, prostitutes and kept women keeping close count of
everything they were owed, determined to climb, as she wrote in her
delicious memoir, ``Goodness Had Nothing to Do With It,'' ``the
ladder of success wrong by wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   We have been rediscovering Mae West since Madonna let loose her
own brazen blond performances in the 1980s. But she was there all
along, slimmed down and speeded up in the actresses who came right
after: young gold diggers like Ginger Rogers and Joan Blondell,
tough dames like Jean Harlow. (Even Claudette Colbert, as the
heiress on the lam in ``It Happened One Night'' offers a tribute
when she challenges Clark Gable's hitchhiking prowess with the
celebrated West line ``I've got a system all my own'' and hikes up
her skirt, bringing a car to an immediate halt.)
</P>
<P>
   Now West's movies are available on video (``She Done Him Wrong''
and ``I'm No Angel'' are the best), three of her plays have been
published in one volume, and two plays, one by and one about West,
are currently in Manhattan theaters. The rambunctious ``Sex'' (at
the Gershwin Hotel until Feb. 14) is being revived for the first
time since West wrote and starred in it in 1926, then went to jail
for it the following year when a New York court declared it
indecent.
</P>
<P>
   Rightly, the director, Elyse Singer, plays up its brazen mix of
melodrama and belly laughs. As Margy LaMont, Carolyn Baeumler gives
us a young, more fast-moving West (she should slow down when she
sings ``Shake That Thing,'' though), a West who is already turning
into her descendants. We get a bit of Harlow and Blondell, even
(what fun) a bit of young, tough Lucille Ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirty Blonde,'' written by Claudia Shear, is at New York
Theater Workshop until Sunday. (There's talk of its moving to
Broadway.) It's a charming piece about what it means to create your
persona so thoroughly that, as West conceded, you become captive to
it. But it's also about how that creation can help its worshipers
find themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Shear, as a struggling actress, and Kevin Chamberlin, as a timid
film librarian, know that loving West (or any star) gives one both
the contentment of requited love and the excitement of unrequited
love. Here, through playing West, they can become themselves and
love each other. Is this a fairy tale? Absolutely. West trafficked
in fairy tales, but she rewrote and restaged them. For one thing,
she was the hero and the heroine. And for another, she won her
happy endings through experience, not innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Both shows are quasi-musicals, as West's plays and movies were.
She was a fine singer, with bluesy phrasing and slow-drag wit. She
chose good songs, too, often from the pre-World War I period:
``Frankie and Johnny,'' ``Easy Rider'' and ``Memphis Blues,'' and
she also turned out a fine version of the torchy ``My Old Flame,''
backed by Duke Ellington's orchestra. (Over the objections of
Paramount studio heads, she insisted that Ellington supply the
music for her 1934 movie, ``Belle of the Nineties.'')
</P>
<P>
   These days we _ theater and moviegoers, music fans of all kinds
_ are on the hunt for something more than deft performers who give
us a pastiche of styles and cultural references held together by
ironic cool. When it comes to performers, postmodern can just mean
post-thrilling, post-great or post-risky.
</P>
<P>
   Al Jolson made an Off Broadway appearance in December. In
``Jolson &AMP; Co.,'' Stephen Mo Hanan (who was also the co-author of
the play) gave a performance that was spookily powerful. Hedwig,
the transvestite rock singer created by John Cameron Mitchell, is
still belting out songs and peddling her lurid life story Off
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   And on Broadway we have Dame Edna Everage, the creation of the
Australian actor Barry Humphries: Dame Edna, British housewife and
busybody turned superstar, who rules the stage in rhinestone
cat's-eye glasses and exquisitely frumpy gowns. I once heard a
cabaret singer ask with airy smugness, ``Didn't I turn that theater
into my living room?'' Dame Edna turns the Booth Theater into a
sublime romper room, where we are her charges and her worshipers.
</P>
<P>
   West learned from vaudeville stars. She stripped the
matronliness from Lillian Russell and the hysteria from Eva
Tanguay. She studied the artfully languid speech-song of the black
comic Bert Williams but shed his sadness. She learned from the
popular female impersonator Bert Savoy but made his grand
flourishes sly and neat. And she claimed the outlaw sexuality of
the blues but disclaimed its mixed moods and tragic undertones. She
made all this hers and she made it new.
</P>
<P>
   When have the French not been obsessed with American comics? In
1938, with West's movie career on the decline thanks to the Hays
Office censors, Colette wrote that West had invented something
utterly new: ``She alone has no parents, no children, no husband.
This impudent woman is, in her style, as solitary as Chaplin used
to be.'' West gives us, she writes, a character who is utterly
un-American: ``The woman without scruples, the female rival of the
male debauche, the brave enemy of the male, valorous enough to use
the same weapons as he.''
</P>
<P>
   West agreed in her own jaunty, high-handed way. Speaking of the
war between the sexes in her memoir, she declared: ``I did not
perhaps treat the subject as seriously as Havelock Ellis, or as
deeply as Freud, Adler, Jung or Dr. Kinsey, but I think if we all
could have sat down and discussed the subject fully, my ideas would
have been listened to with some sense of awe. They may have been
the generals, but I was in the front lines _ out in an emotional No
Man's Land, engaged in dangerous hand-to-hand, lip-to-lip raiding
parties. I have always found it's personal experience that counts,
not making fever charts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 1711EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
