r d BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-06 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S LOVE AFFAIR WITH CINNAMON KEEPS THE BUNS ROLLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ancient Romans treasured cinnamon as a love potion. They also
wore its essence as an irresistible perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Lovers in 21st-century America go to the shopping mall, stand in
front of the Cinnabon franchise and inhale. You can probably
arrange to have your wedding ceremony right in front of the serving
counter, except that the minister may not be able to pronounce the
liturgy with his mouth full of cinnamon roll.
</P>
<P>
   The origin of the American cinnamon roll can probably be traced
to an English baker and tea shop owner named Sally Lunn. Yr. Obdt.
Correspondent once visited the historic site. If memory serves me
correctly, you wander around the city of Bath until you come upon
the main cathedral. Go one block to your right, then three sniffs
to the left and you're there.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of Sally Lunn's sweet yeast bread followed the
colonists to the new world. Now every American has his or her
favorite bakery for cinnamon rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Some epicures, such as Bobbi Roumonada, have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   An Edmonds, Wash., resident, she lives just a couple of blocks
from Brusseau's restaurant, which might be described as our version
of the Sally Lunn shop. The original owner of Brusseau's helped
develop the Cinnabon product now sold nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But Roumonada and her husband, Jim, are also fond of the
atmosphere and the cinnamon rolls two blocks down the street at the
Edmonds Bakery, where the walls are lined with cookie jars.
</P>
<P>
   What makes matters even more complicated is that Roumonada lives
only about 15 minutes away from Third Place Books in Lake Forest
Park. And as any cinnamon roll freak can tell you, a Honey Bear
Bakery is now at the same site. Honey Bear's cinnamon rolls are
unsurpassed, in the estimation of thousands of loyal customers.
</P>
<P>
   So what does a confused and hungry citizen do, at about 10 a.m.
on a rainy morning. Well, Roumonada just may decide to stay at home
and cook up a batch of her own famous Sally Lunn-style sweet rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbi's Sweet Rolls
</P>
<P>
   2 packages active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar (divided)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup butter, melted (divided)
</P>
<P>
   3 and one-half cups flour (divided)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons grated orange rind
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream glaze (see below)
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl dissolve the yeast in water. Beat in half cup
sugar, salt, eggs, sour cream and 6 tablespoons melted butter.
Gradually stir in 2 cups flour. Beat until smooth. Did you wash
your hands before starting to cook? No? Shame on you. Because now
you are supposed to knead in the remaining flour. Cover the bowl
and let the dough rise for 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Time's up. Turn the dough out onto a lightly floured board and
knead 15 times. In you are a non-conformist, knead it 14 or 16
times instead. This is a kitchen, not a robot factory.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the dough in half then roll each portion into a 12-inch
circle. Brush each dough circle with more of that melted butter.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the remaining sugar with the orange rind and sprinkle
over the dough circles. Cut each circle into 12 equal triangular
wedges. Roll each wedge beginning with the wide end. Then plop the
dough, pointed side down, into a greased 9-by-13-inch pan. What you
want to do is to create 8 rows, with 3 pieces of rolled-up dough in
each row. Cover and let rise another 2 hours until the rolls double
in size.
</P>
<P>
   Brush the tops of the rolls with more melted butter, then shove
the pan into a preheated, 350-degree oven for about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When done, remove from oven and drizzle hot glaze mixture over
the top, saturating thoroughly. Separate the rolls with a fork, to
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Sour Cream Glaze
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup butter
</P>
<P>
   Mix ingredients in a saucepan. Place over medium-high heat and
boil 3 minutes, stirring continually with a wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   The cooked rolls can be frozen, then thawed and reheated in a
low oven when a flock of free-loaders descend upon your kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   If you inherited a powerful guilt complex from Puritan
ancestors, you are allowed to substitute this mid-morning snack
with your coffee or tea.
</P>
<P>
   Buttermilk Bran Muffins
</P>
<P>
   3 cups bran
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup molasses
</P>
<P>
   1 cup blueberries
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly mix the bran, flour, sugar, baking powder and baking
soda in a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl gloop together the eggs, buttermilk, oil and
molasses. Mix thoroughly, then add to the dry ingredients and stir
just until dry ingredients are moistened. Fold in the blueberries.
(Well, you don't actually fold the blueberries. That would take you
several days and involve a lot of swearing. Just incorporate the
blueberries into the batter, stirring carefully with a wooden
spoon. Well, in the legal definition I guess you don't actually
incorporate. Quit nitpicking or we're never going to eat.)
</P>
<P>
   Divide the batter among about 20 greased muffin cups and bake at
375 degrees for 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   You can substitute dried cranberries for blueberries. If the
public likes it, you may decide to start your own Patti Puritan
muffin franchise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
