<SLUG> BC-TRUFFLER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE FLY-TRUFFLER': GOING BENEATH THE SURFACE TO RETRIEVE A LOST
LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philippe Cabassac, the fly-truffler referred to in the title of
Gustaf Sobin's marvelous, mesmerizing new novel, is obsessed to the
point of madness.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every morning he walks out on the all-but-abandoned farm
in Provence owned by his family through eight generations. With a
little whisk broom whittled from a pine branch, he pats the
undergrowth in search of tiny insects that he calls, in the old
Provencal language he specializes in, ``lei mousco,'' the flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd spring, each time, like sparks, flying at random off
the flat, battered horns of some black anvil. Like keys, too, he
thought. Like tiny, golden keys. Claus d'aur, as he put it in that
nearly extinct idiom of his. For the flies, properly observed, not
only revealed where a buried truffle lay but, so doing, inaugurated
_ he'd recently discovered _ a whole, hallucinatory underworld unto
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabassac, nearing 50, is in mourning for his wife, Julieta, who
died two years earlier in her late 20s. They had met when she
attended his introductory lecture on Provencal linguistics at the
University of Avignon. He had taken her on field trips collecting
sounds _ ``breath relics,'' he called them _ and they had fallen in
love and married. She had become pregnant, had a miscarriage,
discovered that she would be barren ever after, and had wasted
away, perhaps of a cancer that had invaded her uterus and taken the
child.
</P>
<P>
   Grief-stricken, Cabassac neglects his classes, continues to sell
off pieces of his estate to make ends meet and obsessively hunts
for truffles, whose earthy taste, he has discovered, puts him in a
state, a ``dispousicioun,'' that allows him to have dreams about
Julieta, each of which picks up where the previous one left off. In
the last of those dreams _ the one concluding the previous year's
truffle season _ she has promised to tell him ``something
wonderful, perfectly marvelous.''
</P>
<P>
   You enter Cabassac's world as if falling into one of his dreams.
Everything makes perfect sense, from the effect on him of the
truffles, ``diced into generous black slices, then either mixed in
a salad of crisp, curly headed lettuce or fried _ but scarcely _
into an omelet,'' to the attraction of Julieta, with her ``tall
mineral forehead'' and her ``long, swanlike neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Every image is magnified into pulsing significance, from the
pigeons that once inhabited Cabassac's farm, whose ``wingbeats
sounded just like laundry,'' he tells Julieta, ``like wind hitting
a line of freshly hung, still dripping laundry,'' to the silkworms
that are the subject of Julieta's dissertation: ``Laid out on
wooden trays (levadous) that were stacked one on top of another
like beds of a bunk bed, they'd feed on ever-increasing quantities
of mulberry leaves. . . . The roar of their munching'' after the
fourth molting ``has sometimes been compared to a torrential
downpour in the midst of a dry deciduous forest.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Cabassac's love for Julieta surpasses the ordinary.
``Maybe it's not a person we fall in love with,'' he muses, ``so
much as a distance, a depth, which that particular person happens
to embody.'' Somehow the truffles he hunts beneath the earth,
``those black odoriferous tubers,'' assume the significance of the
subconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Sobin, an American expatriate who has lived in Provence for 35
years, writes in an English reminiscent of Nabokov's in its detail:
``He'd hear the squeak of Julieta's fingertips as they rubbed vapor
off the surface of the bathroom mirror, and could only imagine, as
he did, her tall, heart-shaped face emerging _ flushed from the
warm bath _ into the midst of that radiant oval.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobin's previous books include two novels, ``Venus Blue'' and
``Dark Mirrors''; a nonfiction work, ``Luminous Debris (Reflecting
on Vestige in Provence and Languedoc)''; and six volumes of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fly-Truffler'' ends in catastrophe, with the forces of the
modern world obliterating the ancient rural one, and with poor
Cabassac descending into ecstatic madness. Yet the book remains a
great pleasure to read.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of those rare, haunting novels that you consume in a
single sitting and that you put down wondering what day it is and
where you are, as if awakening from one of Cabassac's enrapturing
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE FLY-TRUFFLER'
</P>
<P>
   By Gustaf Sobin
</P>
<P>
   155 pages. W.W. Norton &AMP; Co. $19.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
