<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Monday, February 7 and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Larry Johnson on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8035.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-THEORY _ The rapidly growing World Wide Web now has about
1.5 billion pages, but some scientists think the size of the Web is
best measured not by pages but by the average number of connections
it takes to link any two random sites. Thus was born the ``19
clicks of separation'' theory of the Web. Then again, maybe what
counts isn't the average number of connections so much as the way
they're connecting. The Web is literally growing like a weed.
Mathematicians say its connections follow an organizing pattern,
similar to plant life in the wild. Nobody knows why. Weird.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN _ The origin of the American cinnamon roll can
probably be traced to an English baker and tea shop owner named
Sally Lunn. Yr. Obdt. Correspondent once visited the historic site.
If memory serves me correctly, you wander around the city of Bath
until you come upon the main cathedral. Go one block to your right,
then three sniffs to the left and you're there.
</P>
<P>
   By John Owen. (Story has moved in the ``d'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-PROTECTION-FAILURES _ Six times in three years, worried
neighbors, police and day-care workers reported to child protection
officials that the 22-year-old mother was neglecting her two young
girls _ locking them in a room of the filthy house, letting them
wander the streets and forgetting to feed them. Each time, state
workers failed to step in, dismissing the case as low-risk. When a
seventh report was made, a public health nurse finally got the
state's attention with a chilling discovery: the girls, ages four
and five, had been so badly neglected they had not yet learned to
talk. The children were removed from home. That's just one of
dozens of cases where the state has failed to protect children
suffering from chronic neglect despite repeated complaints of
maltreatment, according to a report to be released today by the
Office of the Family and Children's Ombudsman.
</P>
<P>
   By Ruth Teichroeb. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-SLEUTHS _ WASHINGTON, D.C. _ On the fifth floor of an
ordinary-looking office building here just off the National Mall,
supersleuth technicians for the NTSB are once again hunkering down,
looking for answers about a major U.S. air disaster. As they search
for clues for what caused Alaska Airlines Flight 261 to fall out of
sky a week ago and plunge into the Pacific, this time investigators
have an abundance of information from the plane and its crew to
help them solve the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-FAMILIES _ Many families of Flight 261 victims are headed
home after a long, difficult week of memorial ceremonies and
painful visits to the Southern California coast where the flight
went down. The Port Hueneme beach is strewn with the fresh flowers
people have thrown off the pier and planted in the sand. The NTSB
has spent the weekend videotaping the ocean floor, trying to piece
together a map of the underwater wreckage to glean answers about
what caused the plane to topple from the sky one week ago, killing
all 88 on board. Story will wrap up the week's activities and
hopefully preview the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   By Tracy Johnson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS _ Seattle Sonics play Suns in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
