<SLUG> BC-INTERACTIVE-TV-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO VIEWERS EVEN WANT TO INTERACT WITH TV? 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The companies working to bring interactive television to the
United States are endlessly optimistic that the big breakthrough
for their industry is just around the corner, despite nearly 50
years of miscast experimentation and failure.
</P>
<P>
   But at a large conference at the Waldorf-Astoria hotel in New
York last week, where several hundred industry executives gathered
to promote their industry and learn from one another, the
boosterism was tempered by frequent discordant notes and the
grudging consensus that nobody really knows what, if anything, the
public may want.
</P>
<P>
   And then, late in the day, a broadcaster offered the group the
verity he said they all would have to accept: people watch
television to be entertained, and anything that pulls them away
from that entertainment is likely to fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think people will want to stop and buy something in
the middle of that entertainment programming,'' said James M.
Moroney, an executive with Belo Corp., owner of 16 television
stations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive television is the catch-all term that applies to
numerous initiatives, both grand and modest, that allow viewers to
interact with their TV programming _ to order products during
commercials or television shows, participate in game shows, change
the programming to better suit the viewers' individual interests or
visit a Web site to view information related to the TV show.
Microsoft's WebTV system is one approach, and the company
demonstrated the system at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1950s, companies have been trying to find the
approach that would kick-start the industry. But for one reason or
another most of the efforts have sputtered or failed, like the
Teletext electronic publishing trials by Time Inc., NBC, CBS and
others in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Still, millions of Americans are likely to be given another
opportunity to sample updated interactive trials in the next year
or so, as cable networks continue rolling out new digital services
that come with advanced cable boxes. The companies showing their
products at last week's convention, and others not in attendance,
are busily striking deals with cable networks to include their
products among the cable services' new digital programming options.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these new interactive services take different
approaches; some stress easy access to movies and music, while
others take viewers to customized Web sites. So it is not clear
which, if any, will succeed. But for any of them to make it, said
Michael Collette, a senior vice president for ICTV, one of the
contenders, ``they are going to have to have a big, mass market.''
But he cited signs of a fractured marketing, noting that ``about
nine digital set-top boxes are about to ship into the U.S. market,
and they are all very different.''
</P>
<P>
   John Carey, a consultant who spoke to the group in the morning,
offered the rallying cry that has kept the industry's enthusiasm
alive, despite the stumbles. ``When you read that consumers have
rejected interactive television,'' he said, ``it's simply not
true.'' All of the failures, he contends, have been the result of
poor implementation or marketing.
</P>
<P>
   He offered as an example the first attempt, the early 1950s
Saturday morning children's show ``Winky Dink and You,'' which sent
children clear plastic sheets they were to stick on the TV screen.
When the show's cartoon character was about to fall off a cliff, as
an example, the viewer would stick the sheet over the screen, use a
crayon to draw a bridge and watch the character cross it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the kids didn't use the plastic screen,'' Carey said.
``They drew directly on the TV screen. Parents were furious, and
service was canceled.'' That was interactive television's first
implementation error. Many more followed, including a Time Warner
trial in Orlando, Fla., in the mid 1990s. The system cost so much
to operate that it almost didn't matter whether viewers liked it.
Time Warner shut it down in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only modest forms of interactivity seem to have won over
enough consumers to remain viable, and generally they do not pull
viewers out of the programs. Most are simply sophisticated ways to
order programming.
</P>
<P>
   On-screen program guides have proved popular. They come with
satellite television and some cable systems and provide a TV-guide
grid on the screen. A viewer scrolls through the guide and clicks
on the program he wants to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a big winner,'' said Robert Rosenthal, director of new
media projects for the Cablevision cable company. ``And there's
tremendous interest in video on demand'' _ the ability to order a
movie or other program at any time.
</P>
<P>
   But companies showing their wares at the conference,
orchestrated by Myers Forums, a research firm that puts on business
conventions, were promoting more ambitious services.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Wink, has enjoyed more success than most of the
others. The company has struck deals with the major television
networks and cable companies. Subscribers to the service, which is
free to the consumer, must have an advanced digital cable box. When
a small logo pops onto the screen, pressing a button on the remote
control calls up more information about a show that runs on the
bottom of the screen, or orders a sample product or brochure during
a commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already deployed in 10 cable markets in the U.S.,'' said
Allan Thygesen, a senior vice president for Wink.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, Intertainer, Inc., of Frederick, Md., offers a
system with a full suite of services, from ordering movies to
games, news, information and more. But the company is not content
to wait until interactive television takes off. Already it is
offering the service over the Internet to people who have high
speed, broadband connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big play is traditional TV,'' said Brendan Carney, a
company officer. But the PC version ``is being offered right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Lauder, a venture capital investor who has put money into
several companies in this field, including ICTV, thinks part of the
problem is that not every one still takes the industry seriously.
``The over promises have resulted in a loss of credibility,'' he
told the group.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem might be a shortage of new ideas. At the end of
the day, after dozens of speeches and demonstrations, a moderator
asked the group if anyone had heard or seen anything during the day
that they had not seen before. Not one person raised a hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
