<SLUG> BC-GQ-TITILATE-MEDIA-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHANGE IN GQ'S EDITORIAL FOCUS RAISES SOME EYEBROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GQ magazine, Conde Nast's sophisticated men's magazine, has been
known for its quiet good taste in fashion, snappy fiction by James
Ellroy, intelligent food writing by Alan Richman, thoughtful essays
by Andrew Corsello.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have been reading the magazine lately, you might have
been surprised to find headlines like this one in the December
issue, over a spread of a model wearing nothing but a garland of
flowers: ``What a gorgeous lei.''
</P>
<P>
   Or you might have been slightly taken aback by the cover
featuring the model Tyra Banks, wearing a string-bikini bottom, her
breasts just barely covered by two long swaths of hair. The cover
line pleaded: ``Tyra, Please Pull Your Hair Back!''
</P>
<P>
   Or this headline on an article about gift-giving: ``She Wants
It. Give it to Her.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa. Has GQ become Maxim, the sex-saturated title from Dennis
Publishing that features bikini-clad models, more flatulence jokes
than a fraternity house and a circulation of more than 1.6 million
copies an issue? Bowing to pressure placed on the entire men's
magazine field by Maxim's success, GQ has with the past few issues
appeared to have ramped up the explicitness of female sexuality on
its pages.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes may backfire, as have efforts to remake Conde
Nast's Details magazine in the Maxim image.
</P>
<P>
   The prime mover behind the salacious new edge is S.I. Newhouse
Jr., the 73-year-old chairman of Conde Nast, a subsidiary of
Advance Publications. Newhouse _ who was close friends with the
late Alexander Liberman, Conde Nast's longtime editorial director
and a paradigm of detached elegance _ had apparently been so
charmed by the success of Maxim that he not only hired its editor,
Mark Golin, last spring to become editor in chief of Details, but
he also urged Art Cooper, GQ's editor in chief for 16 years, to
insert a little Maxim-style oomph into GQ's pages.
</P>
<P>
   The new direction at GQ has alarmed advertisers, who have
complained to GQ's publisher. And it has momentarily bewildered
some members of GQ's staff, several of whom said they had conceived
of GQ as one of the last men's magazines with literature and
urbanity, not solely seminude swimsuit models, as its editorial
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a temporary case of Maxim-envy,'' said Gene
DeWitt, the president of DeWitt Media, a New York media agency that
places ads for clients like BMW. ``It's the classic situation when
you have a well-established brand and some brash upstart comes into
your category. It's very dangerous because it's taken years to
build the GQ brand and what could have happened is that the
magazine would wind up alienating its readers.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWitt said that he had spoken to GQ's publisher, Thomas A.
Florio, and mentioned that the magazine was in danger of alienating
some of DeWitt Media's clients.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast, the bastion of elegant magazine publishing and home
to stylized titles like Vogue, Architectural Digest and Gourmet,
may have temporarily been bitten by the Maxim bug _ but whether the
Maxim bug will have any positive effects on Conde Nast's bottom
line is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The big push at GQ came after it published a special football
issue in September 1999, and Newhouse, who is known for his
distaste of sports, issued an edict to Cooper to run at least six
covers a year in the spirit of Maxim, featuring women, according to
publishing executives at Conde Nast and several GQ staff members
who said they discussed the edict with Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   GQ has previously shied away from women-only covers, running
three a year in 1997 and 1998, two in 1999 and only one a year from
1989 to 1994. In 2000 alone, two covers have already featured
women.
</P>
<P>
   The move has been a critical one for Cooper, who has been openly
disdainful of the Maxim ethos. In 1998, when Maxim began to emerge
as a successful suitor for readers' attention, Cooper called it ``a
magazine for men who not only move their lips when they read _ they
drool when they read'' and compared Maxim to ``Dumb and Dumber.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the magazine industry, the health of newsstand sales
determines what goes on the cover. GQ's newsstand sales were
hurting _ down by 13 percent for the first half of 1999, according
to the Audit Bureau of Circulations _ when Newhouse issued his
edict. The magazine has a rate base guaranteed to advertisers of
700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ad pages from 1998 to 1999 were down by 7.5 percent, to 1,880
pages from 2,035 pages, according to the Media Industry Newsletter,
which tracks magazine advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper declined to be interviewed but said through a GQ
spokeswoman, Mary Wible, that he had decision-making authority over
who appeared on GQ's covers.
</P>
<P>
   After Florio told Newhouse of advertiser complaints three weeks
ago, Newhouse compromised, lowering what might be called his
babe-cover minimum to just four a year, said staff members who were
told of the discussion. Cooper had been planning to feature Rebecca
Romijn-Stamos, a swimsuit model, on the May cover and last week
decided to cancel the shoot in favor of featuring a male celebrity
on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   What about Details? A Conde Nast publishing executive said that
Newhouse was concerned about Golin's performance so far because
sales are sluggish and advertising is down.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Internal reports of newsstand sales from the Details publishing
department show that the first four issues published with Golin's
name on the masthead performed poorly, each selling significantly
less than the comparable issue during the previous year. Newsstand
sales for the first four issues bearing his name were down: July by
24.8 percent, August by 8.7 percent, September by 6.7 percent and
October by 11.8 percent. Figures for subsequent issues are not yet
available.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine guarantees a circulation rate base to advertisers
of 500,000, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations. For the
first six months of 1999, before Golin's arrival, newsstand sales
were up by 11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising pages were down by 21.7 percent from 1998 to 1999,
according to the Media Industry Newsletter, to 880 in 1999 from
from 1,125 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Madden, a spokeswoman for Details, said that Golin
would not comment about newsstand sales or Newhouse's concern.
``Details is a work in progress,'' Madden said. ``It takes time to
convert an audience. Mark never said that would be an immediate
thing. He's continuing to move and grow and tweak the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while Conde Nast may have flirted with the beer-and-babes
formula, it appears that the magazine group's culture is holding
the Maxim mentality at bay, for the moment, and spurring some
second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, when Cooper unveiled the cover of his March issue
_ featuring Harrison Ford and Tom Hanks _ at the print-order
meeting where publishing staff members determine how many copies of
a magazine to print, the staff began to applaud.
</P>
<P>
   Several GQ staff members said that they applauded because the
cover was an image true to the spirit of GQ; Wible said the
applause was celebrating the increased advertising for the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
