<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OSCARS-PREDICT-2TAKES     02-06 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-PREDICT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SURE BETS FOR THIS YEAR'S ACADEMY AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It is one measure of the dizzy uncertainty of this
year's Oscar race that one of the handful of sure bets for a
nomination goes to a screenwriter, Alan Ball, who came from
television to write the dark and acidly funny ``American Beauty.''
He seems more likely than most to hear his name read at the Academy
of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences at the hideous crack of dawn on
the morning after Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little overwhelming, actually,'' Ball said. ``There's a
certain amount of stress involved. I never expected this movie to
get made, much less get made by a major studio and much less be at
the center of Oscar speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 a.m. Los Angeles time on Feb. 15 _ 8:30 a.m. on the East
Coast, for the convenience of the morning news programs _ the names
of the nominees in 23 categories for the 72nd Annual Academy Awards
will be read aloud.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination balloting closed on Friday in 16 categories
(some, like documentaries and foreign-language films are handled
separately), and two teams of accountants are tabulating the
results. On March 26, after a subsequent round of voting, the
winners will be announced at appallingly glamorous ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Last year by this time, a titanic struggle was already under way
between the forces of ``Saving Private Ryan'' and the minions of
``Shakespeare in Love,'' the dueling Oscar favorites for best
picture. (``Shakespeare'' eventually took it.) The year before it
was clear sailing for ``Titanic'' all the way.
</P>
<P>
   But this year there is no clear favorite; there are not even
dueling favorites. In fact the race could go in any one of a
half-dozen directions, as uncertain as particle physics, and the
whole thing is a little unnerving to many people in the movie
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any year I can remember, there is absolutely no way
of predicting who is going to win this year in any category,'' said
Peter Bart, editor of Variety, entertainment columnist and a former
studio production executive. ``Usually by this time there's almost
always a clear betting favorite in every category. But not this
year. This year it's going to be all surprises at the Oscar
ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing there is to a favorite this year would be
``American Beauty,'' the first film from the veteran stage director
Sam Mendes, starring Kevin Spacey and Annette Bening. It won the
recent Golden Globe Award for best dramatic movie of 1999 and has
also taken its share of the year-end critics' accolades.
</P>
<P>
   A critical favorite and a modest box-office success, the film
was also often cited, favorably, as exemplifying a trend among the
studios to experiment with the kind of harder-edged,
character-driven stories more commonly seen in independent films.
</P>
<P>
   But for every proponent of ``American Beauty'' there seem to be
others who wonder whether the more than 6,000 members of the
academy _ notoriously older and more conservative than the average
American moviegoer and more inclined to favor films that reflect
well on the movie industry _ will bring themselves to give their
highest award to a movie about dysfunctional families, homophobia,
dope smoking and voyeurism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' proponents respond. They gave it to ``The Silence
of the Lambs,'' a movie about a serial-killing cannibal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk about five nominees, then `American Beauty' is
certain to be one of them,'' said Marvin Antonowsky, a marketing
consultant and former studio marketing executive. ``But the
ultimate winner? I don't know. I really don't. There is no favorite
at this point, nothing like a `Titanic' or a `Schindler's List.'
There is no 300-pound gorilla.''
</P>
<P>
   But if not ``American Beauty,'' then what? ``Toy Story 2'' won
the Golden Globe for best comedy film, but it is notoriously
difficult for an animated feature to get a best-picture nomination,
and none has ever won the award. ``The Insider'' by Michael Mann, a
thriller about a whistle-blower's collision with big tobacco and
big media, is considered a likely nominee, despite a lackluster
box-office performance.
</P>
<P>
   And many consider Anthony Minghella's ``The Talented Mr.
Ripley'' a likely nominee, though a few note that it has proved
much more likely to be an also-ran than a winner in the postseason
awards and that its cast failed to garner a single nomination in
the Screen Actors Guild awards, perhaps pointing to shallow
support.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, take your pick. Those who rely on the conservative
nature of the academy's voters say that more traditional films like
Norman Jewison's ``Hurricane'' and Frank Darabont's ``Green Mile''
might turn up in the final five. Both are also aided by being
currently in theaters, in the heat of their initial advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hurricane'' is considered all but certain to draw a
nomination for Denzel Washington for his portrayal of the wrongly
imprisoned boxer, Hurricane Carter, but less certain to win a
best-picture nod.
</P>
<P>
   And ``The Green Mile,'' despite widespread buzz last fall in
Hollywood that it was the movie to beat, was released to a chorus
of critical raspberries that labeled it pretentious and overlong.
Audiences have not seemed to notice, as it has earned over $130
million and continues to play well.
</P>
<P>
   Some even predict that the unexpected success of ``The Sixth
Sense'' might be rewarded with a best-picture nomination, though
nominations for M. Night Shyamalan for writing or direction (or
both) are considered more likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Kings,'' David O. Russell's adventure of the Persian
Gulf War, was once considered an Oscar hopeful, though it seems to
have fallen out of the speculation with the influx of more recent
releases. But in a year like this, some say, it can't be counted
out.
</P>
<P>
   As for dark horses, publicists and Oscar-campaign specialists
all over Hollywood are sensing an opportunity and tossing out name
after name _ ``Being John Malkovich,'' ``The Cider House Rules,''
``The Straight Story,'' ``Topsy-Turvy,'' ``Boys Don't Cry, ``The
End of the Affair,'' ``Magnolia'' _ in hopes of building enough
momentum to make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually by this time of year those who pay attention to these
things can pretty much pinpoint the five or six pictures we'll hear
announced that morning,'' said Tony Angellotti, a publicist who has
been instrumental in Oscar campaigns for 15 years, the last eight
for Miramax Films. ``My colleagues this year are shrugging their
shoulders and saying, `Well, we'll see.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And that's just for best picture. Similar uncertainty rules in
the other major categories. For best actor it is widely expected
that Spacey, Washington and Russell Crowe (who plays the
whistle-blower in ``The Insider'') will get nominations.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, numerous names are being floated, from Matt
Damon in ``Mr. Ripley'' to Jim Carrey in ``Man on the Moon'' to
Richard Farnsworth in ``The Straight Story'' to the perennial
favorite Tom Hanks in ``The Green Mile.''
</P>
<P>
   For best actress, perhaps the most narrowed-down of the
categories, the relative newcomers to movies Hilary Swank and Janet
McTeer are expected to draw nominations for ``Boys Don't Cry'' and
``Tumbleweeds'' (both won Golden Globes, and Swank has taken most
of the year-end acting awards), as is Bening in ``American
Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   The final nominees, many believe, will come from among Meryl
Streep in ``Music of the Heart,'' Julianne Moore in ``End of the
Affair,'' Reese Witherspoon in ``Election'' and Sigourney Weaver in
``A Map of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   The same story can be told in the other categories, from
supporting performances to music, makeup, sound: two or three
likely nominees but no sure winner in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year there were definitely two contenders, and the year
before it was `Titanic' all the way,'' Antonowsky said. ``But it's
a very odd year. No one wants to definitely put any money on it
being one thing or the other. It could all turn out to be very,
very surprising. I think the Vegas oddsmakers are going to have a
very difficult time of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Managing the Buzz: The Oscar House Rules
</P>
<P>
   Here is how the game is played: Most Oscar-bait films are
released in the last three months of the year and are accompanied
by publicist-stirred buzz about them as potential winners.
</P>
<P>
   In December the critics groups release their choices for the
year's best films and performances, which are trumpeted in
advertisements in trade and general newspapers throughout the
lucrative holiday movie season.
</P>
<P>
   When the Golden Globe nominations are announced late the same
month, these join the fray. (The sponsoring Hollywood Foreign Press
Association gives out twice as many nominations as the Oscars,
doubling the number of films that can use the nominations to
attract audiences and build Oscar momentum.)
</P>
<P>
   ``For your consideration'' ads begin to appear in Variety and
The Hollywood Reporter. How big the ads are, how often they appear
and who is named in them are all indications of what the studios
believe are likeliest to draw nominations. This year, with so much
up in the air, the ads have been more numerous, and the struggle
for the best space (like the covers of the trade papers) is more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had so many Oscar ads,'' said Peter Bart, editor
of Variety.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, he said, the studios might send academy members
videotapes of the films in elaborate boxes with lavish
presentations. This year the screeners have all come in plain
cardboard boxes, although this probably has more to do with the
mood of corporate cost cutting that has infected the major studios
in the last year than with the unusually large number of
Oscar-contending films.
</P>
<P>
   Academy members can also attend numerous screenings in Los
Angeles or New York of films that are in contention. It is these
academy screenings, closed to the press, that offer the final burst
of prenomination buzz from studio executives, publicists for
individual artists and consultants hired by the studios.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a certain amount of negative campaigning. (The
competing film is too dark, performed poorly at box office, is too
quirky, is not quirky enough, has just the right amount of
quirkiness but nobody likes quirkiness this year.)
</P>
<P>
   The current races' being so wide open, of course, only heightens
the importance of managing the buzz, if possible. If any dark horse
stands a chance, then why not give it a shot? Concoct a scenario,
link it to a year-end award, however obscure, bad-mouth the
competition and see what happens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
