<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investor Group May Provide Emergency Funds to Iridium
</P>
<P>
   A group of investors led by Craig McCaw, the cellular telephone
pioneer, is expected to provide at least $20 million of emergency
financing to Iridium, the troubled global satellite telephone
company which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection last
August, according to people close to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The investment, which is expected to be announced early this
week, would allow Iridium to continue to operate its network of 66
low-orbit satellites for the next few months while McCaw and his
team of investors negotiate to take control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Koch Helps Put Legal Advice Online
</P>
<P>
   TheLaw.com, which bills itself as a legal Web site for
consumers, opens for business Monday. It will provide information
on legal topics like divorce, bankruptcy and real estate contracts.
The site will sell ads and directory listings for law firms. Ed
Koch, the former mayor of New York and a co-founder of the site,
plans to do online chat sessions for an hour or two each week.
</P>
<P>
   Official Promotes New Bond Policy
</P>
<P>
   A top Treasury Department official sought to assure bond
investors that they would be able to adjust to the government's new
policy of reducing the supply of Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Denies Sinclair Petition
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission denied a petition from
Sinclair Broadcast Group that asked the commission to modify the
nation's digital television standard. Sinclair had said the digital
television receivers that are on the market now are incapable of
receiving an acceptable television picture in any circumstances
that are less than ideal. The commission said studies had shown
that the current transmission standard is adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting the One Gigahertz Chip
</P>
<P>
   The International Solid State Circuits Conference meets in San
Francisco this week, allowing microprocessor manufacturers and
semiconductor engineers to swap technical papers and contemplate
the arrival of a once unthinkable milestone: a chip that cycles a
billion times a second. Both Intel and IBM will present papers
describing complete microprocessors that operate at one gigahertz
speeds, and both say they will introduce production chips with that
capability in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Literature Begins to Move Online
</P>
<P>
   Early on the notion of authors putting their work directly
online captured the imagination of venture capitalists but now it
is also drawing the attention of some prominent authors and
literary agents, who are beginning to place short works or
out-of-print books with online Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Business Journals Clash in Europe
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal, long an also-ran to The Financial Times
in the competition for European consumers of financial news, will
unveil a newspaper that abandons the pinstriped look of the
American edition in favor of a colorful, Web-influenced design. The
Financial Times said the start of its German-language version, for
which it has hired 120 journalists, is imminent.
</P>
</TEXT>
