<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONK-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONK': ONE-MAN SHOW FAILS TO REVEAL SOUL OF MUSICIAN 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(jw) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Words don't cut it. That's another reason I don't
talk too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a paradoxical statement for a character in the midst
of a 90-minute monologue.
</P>
<P>
   That the character is Thelonious Monk, the brilliant, troubled
and enigmatic jazz pianist, only complicates the dramatic problem:
how to animate, in language, a man whose eloquence was both
indisputable and wordless.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of ``Monk,'' a sincere and reverent one-man show,
written by Laurence Holder and performed by Rome Neal, that opened
on Thursday in the homey cabaret space at the Nuyorican Poets Cafe
in the East Village, is largely to substitute speech for music. In
this very low-budget production (scheduled to run through March
26), there is a piano onstage, and Neal (a skillful actor, but
evidently not a musician) fiddles occasionally with the keys.
Recorded snippets of Monk classics like ``Straight, No Chaser'' and
`` 'Round Midnight'' punctuate the narrative, but a musical evening
it isn't. Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   A more serious disappointment is the play's failure to reveal
the mind of the musician. Monk, who lived mostly in New York City
and died at 64 of an aneurysm in 1982, was, after all, a composer
of extraordinary originality. As a boy he was a gifted
mathematician, and his music had a stark, mathematical cast.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote in rhythmic staggers, was prone to sudden dissonant
wrenches on the sweetest melodies, and, conversely, to mellifluous
arpeggios that reclaim the bitterest series of chords. His music
bespoke eccentricity, a divisiveness of mind. He was, through much
of his life, plagued by mental illness, including depression, an
inner chaos that seems expressed and controlled in his work.
</P>
<P>
   But Holder's script makes scant effort to correlate the music
and the man; he has Monk, who was mostly self-taught and disdainful
of musical convention, explain his art unenlighteningly, as pure
idiosyncrasy: ``Dig, good music fits your ear and sometimes an
eight-bar bridge is too long, so I shorten it to 5{ or 3{ bars. If
it's what sounds good.''
</P>
<P>
   The play focuses on the biographical events, often presented as
indignant recollections, that contributed to Monk's mounting
alienation: the lack of public acknowledgment, early in his career,
even as contemporaries like Miles Davis and Dizzy Gillespie were
lionized; his 1951 arrest on a false drug charge (he was protecting
his friend, the pianist Bud Powell), which resulted in a 60-day
jail sentence and the revocation of his cabaret card, depriving him
of his livelihood; the resistance of producers to allowing him to
record his own compositions, and a resentment of racial bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   These are offered as the spurs for Monk's disabling headaches
and spells of despair. But embittering as they no doubt were, their
rendering here fails to distinguish Monk from the generic pool of
misunderstood and unappreciated geniuses. Yes, Monk was a proud,
innovative, slow-to-be-rewarded black man with love in his heart.
And? You leave the theater certain that Monk was more interesting
than that.
</P>
<P>
   Neal, a solidly built actor, finds an effective range of motion
to convey Monk's imposing, heavy-lidded presence. Nattily attired
in gray, with a black and red tasseled skullcap, and swigging from
a whiskey bottle, Neal comes closest to the mystery of the man with
his physical turns: the slow, dancing twirls Monk performed on the
bandstand, or his emergence from an apparent daze with the vigorous
swipe of an arm.
</P>
<P>
   The actor brings the play truly alive in its rare moments of
present-tense anecdote. In one, he enacts an argument Monk had with
Powell, after he had pretended to be Monk to impress a young
actress who, it is suggested, was Marilyn Monroe. In another, Neal
gives an exquisite imitation of Louis Armstrong expressing his
bafflement at Monk's music: ``I don't know what they're playing. Is
it Chinese?'' In such scenes, you can see Monk's amusement,
irritation, frustration. Something secret is revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Monk's secrets, for good or ill, remain encoded in
the music.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MONK'
</P>
<P>
   By Laurence Holder; directed by Rome Neal and Holder; production
stage manager and sound by Triple-5 (William J. Vila); assistant
director, Jennifer Cummins; sets by Jechibea Adu-Peasah; lighting
by Neal. Presented by the Nuyorican Poets Cafe, Miguel Algarin,
executive producer. A Holder/Neal production. At 236 E. Third
Street, East Village.
</P>
<P>
   With: Rome Neal (Thelonious Monk).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
