<HEADER>
A8364 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     02-06 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CHEFS CELEBRATE THE FINEST ARTISTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Conceptual artist  &UR; Don Celender &LR; , whose yearly projects usually
involve asking experts in some field about admired icons of another
field, has this year asked 400 nationally famous chefs which famous
artists they would most welcome at their tables, and what the menu
would be. The names mentioned most often were &UR; Pablo &LR; 
 &UR; Picasso &LR; ,  &UR; Claude Monet &LR; ,  &UR; Andy Warhol &LR; ,  &UR; Michelangelo &LR;  and
 &UR; Leonardo Da Vinci &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But Personals' favorite response was from  &UR; Nancy Lee Spilove &LR; ,
who runs a soup kitchen, the Cooperative Feeding Program, in
Sunrise, Fla. She chose  &UR; Georgia O'Keeffe &LR;  (subject of an
exhibition that opens this month at the California Palace of the
Legion of Honor in San Francisco).
</P>
<P>
   Spilove said she would serve tea, because she wouldn't want to
be in the kitchen to take time away from being with her visitor.
``Knowing what gave this woman the strength to forge ahead in a
direction uncommon to other women of the day would be of great
interest. It would be interesting to know why she took the hearts
of the flowers and filled the canvas with them instead of using the
entire flower. ... What gave her such peace of mind to enable her
to seek out the desert in solitude? With this self-imposed
isolation, how did she keep so worldly? ...''
</P>
<P>
   The letter goes on to describe O'Keeffe's pride in her work.
Then there's a P.S.: ``I also think it's great she went for a
younger man!''
</P>
<P>
   The responses to Celender's query are displayed at the O.K.
Harris Gallery in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Just inside the front door at City Hall in the midst of a
rainstorm last week, &UR; Ken Maley  &LR; was given a plastic bag to prevent
his umbrella from dripping on the floor. The Brown administration,
he said, is the ``Nordstrom of city government.''
</P>
<P>
   - Driving on Oahu,  &UR; David Greenlee  &LR; saw a lady driving a ``very
shiny new E420 Mercedes'' with a license plate that read PRAYER,
but she looked ``very staid and earnest,'' he writes, nothing like
 &UR; Janis Joplin &LR; . And searching the DMV personalized licensed plate
Web site,  &UR; Matt White &LR;  discovered that DEAD CAT and DEAD COW had
already been taken, but IM RICH and CHP4EVR are still available. In
other automotive news,  &UR; Todd Leone &LR;  reports that the parking rate
at Embarcadero Center was recently raised to $27 a day.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Alas poor Snoopy,'' says  &UR; Andrew Demcak &LR; , reporting that a
quickie-mart in Berkeley is selling 99-cent ``beagles with creem
cheeze.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MESSAGES LEAD TO FIRINGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Twenty-two people in the New York Times business office in
Norfolk, Va., were fired just after Thanksgiving for sending each
other e-mail that included sexual images and jokes intolerable in a
workplace. Before the investigation that led to the firings, said
the Wall Street Journal, staff members thought the office was ``a
comfortable, easygoing place to work,'' where camaraderie was
common.
</P>
<P>
   There were no complaints from staff members about the messages,
which are said to have included jokes about men and women, about
blondes and Ebonics. ``I don't speak that way,'' said one fired
woman, who is African- &LR;  American. ``Who's to tell me what I should
be offended by?''
</P>
<P>
   The firings were necessary, said  &UR; Nancy Nielsen &LR;  of the Times.
``This is not a First Amendment issue. There is no First Amendment
right to transmit pornography over the company's e-mail system, or
to view pornography in the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHOPPING OPPORTUNITIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Dining in a restaurant in St. Petersburg recently,  &UR; Gladys &LR; 
and  &UR; Simon Palmer &LR;  were handed a Russian shopping brochure inviting
``Dear Sir'' to ``stop by our shop, browse through our extensive
catalogs and choose a woman to suit your tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   The catalog attached includes color photos of 19 women, and data
on each one's age (from 19 to 45), height (5-foot-2 to 5-foot-8)
and weight (105 to 150). Accompanying prose promises a woman who
``will not be scarred by hardship. She will accept you as you are.
Do you want to find someone responsive and interesting, a friend
and caring mother for your children, wonderful woman and wife? Take
the first step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening and shutting its jaws, something all morays do to pump
water over their gills, it is the scariest-looking thing I've seen
outside of a Grateful Dead concert.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Bruce Watson  &LR; in a Smithsonian magazine story about the
wonders of eels.
</P>
</TEXT>
