<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-MARY-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-06 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARY AND RHODA': SITCOM ICONS, PUSHING 60, CAN'T SHAKE THEIR 30S 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Broadcast notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television characters age differently from other fictional
people, and not only because in Hollywood cosmetic surgery is more
common than tap water. In endless reruns characters repeat the same
actions and recite the same words until we know them by heart. You
would have to be insanely obsessed with a book or movie to have its
characters seared in the memory as precisely as Archie Bunker is,
forever telling Edith to stifle herself, or Samantha Stephens
twitching her nose.
</P>
<P>
   Old shows enter the present with a changed context, of course.
``The Brady Bunch,'' played seriously at the start, was embraced by
a new generation as camp comedy and transformed into a cultural
touchstone. But the characters never change, and the more popular
they are, the more difficult it is to wrench them out of the frozen
past. Would we really want to? Who needs an updated ``Happy Days''
with Fonzie as a grandpa?
</P>
<P>
   Yanking Mary Richards and Rhoda Morgenstern into the present is
the most basic of many problems with the misbegotten movie ``Mary
and Rhoda.'' Valiantly trying to look ahead instead of backward,
the film reintroduces the classic characters, now pushing 60, as if
they were friends we've been out of touch with for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But we haven't been out of touch: we've been replaying that
endless loop in which Mary's voice still quavers endearingly when
she says, `` Mr. Grant,'' Rhoda bounds into a room wearing a
psychedelic bandana on her head, and it is always the 1970s. ``The
Mary Tyler Moore Show'' holds up beautifully as comedy, but it may
be more meaningful as cultural comfort food: familiar, reassuring,
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Though the new ``Mary and Rhoda'' replaces the cozy original
version of the ``Mary Tyler Moore'' theme (``Love Is All Around'')
with Joan Jett's rock version, the film is tone deaf to the
difference. The Jett cover was a homage to a groundbreaking show,
which had to ask, ``How will you make it on your own?'' Women make
it on their own all the time today, thanks partly to Mary's
example. Yet the film ignores Mary's power as an icon and simply
picks up the characters as if they have gone on living and changing
without us. It would have taken a far more inventive, vibrant
script to pull off something so audacious. Nostalgia is the only
reason to watch ``Mary and Rhoda,'' which comes across as the
characters never did, a little sad.
</P>
<P>
   Here Mary Richards is the recent widow of a New York
congressman. Having left a producer's job at ABC News years before
to raise their daughter, she is surprised to find she has been left
with no money and has to go back to work. With Moore's body as thin
as Calista Flockhart's and her face almost as taut, this older Mary
does not seem youthful so much as fragilely in control. Beyond what
Mary's widowhood can explain, it's as if she had morphed into
Moore's tightly wound character from ``Ordinary People.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda, recently divorced from a philandering French husband, has
returned from Paris to New York, where her daughter is in college.
Valerie Harper's Rhoda doesn't look much different from her former
self, but she has aged more naturally than Mary, so she seems more
credible. Rhoda was always the more broadly written and played
character; given the easier role, she remains an engaging sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   The contrived script never gives anyone much hope at
believability, though. First the story cooks up an estrangement.
The friends haven't spoken for years, since Mary saw Rhoda's
husband make a pass at a bridesmaid at their wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to find each other again, the women meet in a scene
that evokes the old show: Rhoda spots Mary getting into a taxi and
chases the cab down Central Park West. (This is the same Rhoda who,
dressed in her bridal gown, hopped a subway to her first wedding.)
</P>
<P>
   The film displays some gentle charm as the friends sit in the
sun and catch up. A confident Rhoda has taken up photography and
hopes for a New York show. Mary has a hard time imagining life
without her husband. But the comedy is flat; unable to adjust the
air-conditioning in her apartment, Mary appears wrapped in what
looks like a rabbit costume.
</P>
<P>
   The film becomes more strained when Mary and Rhoda's grown
children appear. Mary's child, Rose, wants to be a stand-up comic;
the character is a middle-aged idea of wacky youthful rebellion.
Rhoda's daughter, Meredith, plans to be a doctor. Neither is more
than a lame excuse for chats in which the mothers come to
understand their daughters better.
</P>
<P>
   And the stories of Mary and Rhoda's jobs are predictable.
Rhoda's is played for laughs as she schleps bagels for a fashion
photographer. Mary goes to work for a 33-year-old who runs a
tabloid television channel and teaches him a lesson about real
journalism. Abruptly the film's tone turns earnest, as Mary
interviews the parents of a teen-ager involved in a gang murder.
It's too jarring a transition for one little movie to pull off.
</P>
<P>
   There are small echoes of the old show; Mary still has a big M
on her wall. But the large differences matter more. This time when
Mary's voice quavers while talking to her boss, there is no joy of
recognition, just the sense of an actress competing with her own
legend.
</P>
<P>
   And the film bluntly makes the point that Mary has been hired to
ward off an age-discrimination suit, carrying its messages like a
cudgel. The old ``Mary Tyler Moore Show'' wore its issues so
lightly it hardly seemed to have any. Ted insulted Mary on the air,
she got a $50 a week raise and along the way made a point about
equal pay for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and ``Rhoda'' are still in their
endless loop. Monday, starting at 5 p.m., TV Land will show four
episodes of ``Mary'' followed by two of ``Rhoda.'' Then Monday
through Friday, from 2 to 6 a.m., Nick at Nite will present
back-to-back ``Mary Tyler Moore'' episodes. Between 5 and 6 a.m. on
Tuesday (Mary never had a VCR, but we do) there are two of the
best: the one in which Mary fantasizes about being married to Lou,
Ted and Murray, followed by the one in which Lou and Mary have a
date. Here is the virtue of reruns: These episodes send Mary back
to the past, where she lives.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MARY AND RHODA'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. (ET) Monday on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Mary Tyler Moore and Susan B. Landau, executive producers;
Cecilia Kate Roque, producer; written by Katie Ford; directed by
Barnet Kellman; music by David Kitay; edited by Jeff Wishengrad. A
production of Fox Television Studios.
</P>
<P>
   With: Mary Tyler Moore (Mary Richards), Valerie Harper (Rhoda
Morgenstern Gerard Rousseau), Joie Lenz (Rose), Marisa Ryan
(Meredith), Elon Gold (Jonah Seimeier) and Christine Ebersole
(Cecile Andrews).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 1823EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
