u e BC-ARTEMIS-MUSIC-REVIEW-     02-06 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTEMIS-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTEMIS QUARTET: YOUNG MUSICIANS FROM BERLIN, NOTABLE FOR
MATURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Given the number of fledgling, often worthy string
quartets that are trying to gain a footing in a terribly
competitive field, it is difficult for a new ensemble to stand out.
The Artemis Quartet, which made its New York debut at Weill Recital
Hall on Friday night, is an exciting exception.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians, three Germans and one Russian, met as students in
Luebeck, Germany, 10 years ago and are now based in Berlin. This
concert was part of their second American tour.
</P>
<P>
   The Artemis plays with the requisite well-blended tone and
technical command. Though the players think as one, their
individuality comes through.
</P>
<P>
   The violinists Heime Mueller and Natalia Prischepenko alternate
on first violin; his playing is marked by lustrous tone and
incisive rhythm, hers by rhapsodic lyricism. Eckart Runge, the
cellist, brings great character to his work. And whereas many
violists are the good-sport member of a quartet team, Volker
Jacobsen is an arresting performer.
</P>
<P>
   But what finally distinguishes these young artists is the
maturity of their musicianship, which was evident not just from how
but from what they played.
</P>
<P>
   The program began with Beethoven's String Quartet No. 16, the
last of the seminal late quartets, an oddly compact and fascinating
work. The Artemis' vibrant performance made the music seem at once
lucid and mysterious. The conception was so strong that even a
brief crisis, when a tuning peg on Prischepenko's violin slipped,
and the performance stopped while she solved the problem, hardly
disrupted the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Before the next work, Gyorgy Ligeti's String Quartet No. 2, a
landmark work from 1968, Jacobsen delivered some avuncular and
edifying comments on the music that lasted nearly as long as the
20-minute work itself. He focused on the wondrous coloristic
effects of the instrumental writing and Ligeti's inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the musicians demonstrated a passage where squiggly
figures of oscillating intervals in all the instruments move more
and more quickly as the intervals become narrower and the dynamics
softer. The result is magical: Though the tempo is actually getting
faster, the music seems to be getting slower. When his talk was
over, the well-primed audience listened raptly to a riveting
account of a challenging contemporary piece.
</P>
<P>
   The program ended with a work that most other ensembles would
have placed first: Mozart's String Quartet No. 15 in D Minor. The
idea, it seemed, was to make the Mozart seem as substantive and
daring as the preceding works, and this spacious, organic
performance did just that.
</P>
<P>
   Even the encores were aptly selected. First came the breakneck
fugato of Beethoven's String Quartet, Op. 59, No. 3, dispatched
with nimbleness and humor. Finally, since one movement of Ligeti's
work is a homage to the pizzicato movement of Bartok's Fourth
String Quartet, the Artemis performed the Bartok: an imaginative
way to end an impressive debut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 1825EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0089 </DOCNO>
