<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIAN-CHINESE-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S CHINESE WIN A HAPPY NEW YEAR AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Two years ago Sri Hariati hid in a bedroom
as rioters shouted and burned buildings in Jakarta's Chinatown.
This past weekend the noise and crowds and smoke told a very
different story: For the first time in more than 30 years,
Indonesia's Chinese were allowed to celebrate their New Year in
public.
</P>
<P>
   The racket of drums and cymbals was deafening, and the dancing
lion hopped among the tiny stalls and storefronts as Hariati, a
seamstress, stared from her doorway at a tradition that had been
denied her since she was a girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night at the temple I prayed for a better future for my
children,'' she said. ``I was crying, but I think it was because
the smoke from the incense was stinging my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two years _ since the May riots that helped bring down
President Suharto _ have been filled with tensions, trauma and
violence. Communal and separatist conflicts have turned some
regions of the country into battlegrounds.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Indonesia is becoming more liberal and humane
in many ways as the harsh policies of Suharto's 32-year rule are
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration of the Chinese New Year was banned in 1967 as
part of a policy of repressing ethnic identities in this nation of
210 million. Members of the tiny Chinese minority of less than 4
percent were designated to serve as financial brokers to those in
power. Ethnic Chinese citizens were forced to take Indonesian names
and were virtually barred from politics, the military and
government service.
</P>
<P>
   And when the government needed a scapegoat, as it did during a
communist scare in 1965 and during the financial crisis in early
1998, it turned on the Chinese, fomenting terror and riots.
</P>
<P>
   Now, under the new liberal president, Abdurrahman Wahid, there
is hope that things are changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, all this is so unreal that for some people it has
not registered,'' said Wimar Witoelar, a television commentator.
``Some of the changes that are going on, like the treatment of
minorities, are so fundamental that people don't appreciate what
has happened. Now we can realize that as a people we are not racist
_ or not any more racist than other nations.''
</P>
<P>
   The wounds do not heal quickly. In the Chinese sections of
Jakarta, where hundreds of buildings were burned in the 1998
rioting, few repairs have been made. For blocks on end, buildings
still stand blackened and empty. Even their smashed windowpanes
have not been covered over.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money that the Chinese Indonesians transferred to
foreign banks because of the unrest has not returned, and wealthy
families who sent their children abroad to school have in many
cases not brought them home.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still waiting for more political stability,'' said
Arief Budiman, a political analyst of Chinese ancestry. ``They know
that in any kind of riots they can be victims. They are called a
triple minority: You are Chinese, you are non-Islamic and you are
rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the country's Chinese are Buddhists or Christians. And
although most of them are not really wealthy, some Chinese tycoons
are among the most prominent of Indonesia's rich elite.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Wiryadinata, vice chairman of a social group called the
Chinese Indonesian Association, is one of the leaders who have been
warning their compatriots to tone down their New Year celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people, to be honest with you, right now they are not too
happy about this,'' he said of the anti-Chinese prejudice that
continues. ``So for the past two weeks I've been telling people,
don't get too excited, keep it within the family, don't get
overexposed. Best to wait another two or three years or maybe five
years.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, on the island of Bali, where many Chinese fled for a
safe haven two years ago, a campaign of intimidation appears to
have resurfaced. The local military commander confirmed that just
as they had in Jakarta in 1998, unknown people had painted crosses
on the fronts of some Chinese homes and stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Jakarta Post said anonymous leaflets had been found stating
that crosses in red meant that the buildings were to be burned,
while crosses in green signaled that the property would be
vandalized and looted.
</P>
<P>
   For months after the riots in Jakarta, the city's Chinatown was
repeatedly gripped by fears of new attacks and rumors of new
stigmata painted on Chinese homes.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of an emerging new confidence that many people
here had to be reminded to tone down their celebrations this week.
In the narrow alleyways around the 500-year-old Vihara Dharma
Bhakti Temple, the celebration was unbridled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never forgotten how to do this, and now we're teaching
our younger generation to do it too,'' said Apuk Udin, 66, peering
out from within his lion costume. ``For us it's nostalgia. For them
it's something they've never seen before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
