<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-NYT     02-06 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMARKS BY RIGHTEST LEADER AGAIN STIR AUSTRIA 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Jorg Haider, the rightist leader whose Freedom Party is
part of the new Austrian government, said Sunday that ethnic
Germans expelled from what was Czechoslovakia at the end of World
War II should be entitled to the same compensation as Austrian Jews
persecuted by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   The statement reopened an old, often suppressed grievance in the
German-speaking world. It centers on the expulsion from their homes
or the imprisonment in the Soviet Union of millions of Germans in
the aftermath of Hitler's war and the lack of compensation for
their losses or suffering.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks of the Freedom Party leader seemed certain to
intensify international unease over Haider, whose intermittently
revisionist views have included statements _ later apologized for _
praising aspects of Hitler's rule.
</P>
<P>
   By equating the suffering of the Sudeten Germans with Jewish
victims of the Holocaust just a few days after signing a
declaration saying that ``the crimes of the Holocaust are without
precedent in history,'' Haider appeared likely to heighten
international concern that his word is worth little or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A patriotic government should be able to draw the consequences
of the past by compensating Sudeten Germans,'' Haider said in an
interview with German television, adding that the compensation
should be similar to that received by Austrian Jews for their
persecution in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Germans of the Sudetenland constituted over 22
percent of Czechoslovakia's population before the war. This large
German minority, many of them Nazi supporters, provided the excuse
for Hitler's dismemberment of Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned by its Western allies at Munich, Czechoslovakia first
bowed in 1938 to Hitler's demand that the Sudetenland be ceded to
him. The next year, it capitulated to Nazi forces.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the Czechoslovak government mercilessly drove out
the Sudeten Germans, most of whom settled in Germany but many of
whom went to Austria. The German foreign minister, Joschka Fischer,
is descended from Sudeten Germans.
</P>
<P>
   The issue caused intermittent tension between what is now the
Czech Republic and Germany, but at a ceremony last year the two
governments reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   Haider was clearly addressing the still powerful lobby of
largely aging Germans and Austrians who lost property after the war
and who feel that the enormity of the Holocaust and Hitler's crimes
should not obscure their own losses.
</P>
<P>
   During the negotiations last year on compensation for victims of
Nazi forced labor, some German officials asked privately why
Germans forced to work in Siberia and other parts of the Soviet
Union after the war should not be similarly compensated. But such
feelings never found public expression.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has downgraded its relations with Austria,
and the United States is recalling its ambassador for consultations
to protest the Freedom Party's presence in a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   In the same interview Sunday, Haider suggested that the European
campaign against Austria had been orchestrated by President Thomas
Klestil, who reluctantly swore in the government on Friday. Haider
added that he might try to start a parliamentary inquiry into
``high political treason'' by the conservative president.
</P>
<P>
   Haider accused the former Social Democratic chancellor, Viktor
Klima, of taking part in the same ``treasonous'' acts. It is widely
known that both men were in frequent contact with their European
partners in the days leading up to the European Union's
announcement a week ago of its punitive measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 1830EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ARIZ-MCCAIN-ART-725&AMP;A     02-06 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-MCCAIN-ART-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING THE `FAVORITE SON' IS NOT MUCH OF A FACTOR FOR MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ There is a history in presidential campaigns of
candidates winning their home state primaries by hefty margins,
often by more than 40 percentage points. Outsiders seldom can
overcome the ``favorite son'' factor.
</P>
<P>
   So Sen. John McCain of Arizona, on a roll elsewhere, has little
to worry about when this state holds its Republican primary on Feb.
22, right?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, McCain is running a bit scared at home.
</P>
<P>
   For months most polls have had him leading Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas by sometimes less than a half dozen points. At least one
poll briefly had Bush slightly ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Poll takers and political consultants have cited several reasons
for Bush's early strength in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   First, they say, before his loss in New Hampshire, he was seen
as the inevitable winner of the Republican nomination, and very
possibly the presidency. Next, they say, he has pushed hard from
the start in Arizona, establishing phone banks and mass mailing
operations early on, just as McCain did. He then won early backing
from Gov. Jane Dee Hull. Finally, they note, Bush has been running
television advertisements in the state for almost two months, a
period in which McCain, with far less money, has run none.
</P>
<P>
   Also, said Bruce Merrill, the director of the Arizona State
University Poll, what has been a strength for McCain elsewhere may
hurt him a bit in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that John McCain, though his job approval rating
in Arizona hangs around 70 percent, is nevertheless viewed by a
significant number of Arizonans as too much of a maverick and
outsider, too outspoken, too combative,'' Merrill said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Minnaugh, the chairman of the Arizona Republican Party,
said the state is up for grabs. ``I'm neutral in this, but
ultimately you have to give John the edge in this race, just on the
basis of the favorite son factor,'' Minnaugh said. ``But there's no
room for complacency by either of them.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's narrow edge over Bush in Arizona may have widened in
the last few days, if the bounce the senator got in South Carolina
polls after his victory in the New Hampshire primary is an
indication.
</P>
<P>
   But the McCain camp remains wary about Arizona. His aides are
concerned that McCain may be forced to divert precious campaign
resources to defend his home turf. For the moment, the Bush camp is
talking upset, looking for a fallback position here and in
Michigan, which also votes on Feb. 22, should things go badly for
Bush in South Carolina's primary on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We concede we're in a tough fight, but we remain confident of
victory,'' said Wes Gullett, McCain's Arizona campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hull, Bush's campaign manager here and the governor's son,
concedes nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see opportunity, and we're working this state like crazy,''
Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   There should not be any significant difference in the nature of
the debate here. And while Christian conservatives are numerous,
they are not as organized as in Iowa or South Carolina, where they
helped to make abortion a more prominent issue.
</P>
<P>
   Neither candidate has spent much time in Arizona. And, with the
South Carolina primary just three days before the Arizona and
Michigan votes, both candidates find themselves in a time squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Just how tight is that squeeze?
</P>
<P>
   As of this weekend, Bush had not set a date for his next visit
to Arizona. McCain was in Phoenix on Sunday but after that had no
plans to return before Feb. 21. He last was in the state in late
December.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have been forced to rely heavily on surrogate
campaigners _ Bush on Hull and members of the Bush family,
including Barbara Bush, his mother, and McCain on his wife, Cindy,
and an array of Arizona officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gained wide coverage when Hull endorsed him, something of
an embarrassment for McCain. But the political fact is that McCain
has the support of most of the state's Republicans in Congress,
most Republicans in the Legislature and most of the state's
big-city mayors and county officials.
</P>
<P>
   Hull argues that Bush can lose in Arizona and yet still ``win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All George W. has to do is make a real contest of it,'' he
said. ``And he's already doing that, no small achievement in the
other guy's home state.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hull said the Bush campaign planned to step up its advertising
campaign in the next few days and expand its mail and telephone
operations. Arizona is one of the few states that allows voting by
mail, and those outreach operations are crucial in persuading
supporters to do so early, a proven way, past Arizona campaigns
have found, to give a candidate a lift.
</P>
<P>
   Gullett said the McCain campaign also planned to expand its
telephone and mail operations and would soon begin a television
advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded phone and mail operations could be of unusual
importance to McCain when it comes to turnout. Independents, who
voted heavily for him in New Hampshire and who, he hopes, will do
the same in South Carolina, cannot vote in the Arizona primary. So
if he is to make up that difference, he must dig deeper into the
ranks of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, who spent heavily here in 1996 and won the
primary, has 10 full-time campaign workers assigned to Arizona _
compared with two paid workers each for the Bush and McCain
campaigns. But he has yet to reach double digits in most Arizona
polls.
</P>
<P>
   While Alan Keyes has based his national headquarters in Phoenix,
his staff said he was not campaigning in Arizona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
