<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GRAHAM-PROFILE-ART-NY     02-06 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOCAL CELEBRITY STUMPS FOR MCCAIN IN SOUTH CAROLINA
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAUFORT, S.C. _ He has been signing autographs for the past
year, but Lindsay Graham knew he became a celebrity for sure just
last week. Not everybody, after all, is invited to a celebrity
quail hunt.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not his quail-hunting ability that prompted the offer.
The South Carolina congressman enjoys slipping into his brier pants
and orange vest every once in a while to go hunting, but he rarely
gets a bird. Instead, it is that big case up in Washington that got
Graham noticed, the one he's still talking about a year later even
though he lost and the defendant got off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank Bill Clinton for doing more for my career
than anyone,'' Graham said the other day at a campaign rally for
Sen. John McCain. He said the words in a joking way, but he wasn't
really joking.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment case, which he helped prosecute as one of the
team of Republican House managers, is now inextricably linked to
the young, plain-spoken Graham. It has turned him into a sensation
in the South, and prompted him to put himself up as Sen. Strom
Thurmond's replacement should Thurmond not seek re-election in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   It has also given Graham powerful symbolic importance in the
Republican presidential race. Graham's home state is the next
battleground as Gov. George W. Bush of Texas seeks to thwart
McCain's insurgency. One of Bush's strategies has been to paint
McCain as a closet liberal, a Clinton clone, a man unfit to
represent conservative interests. Graham is having none of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody got Clinton fatigue?'' Graham asked several hundred
McCain supporters at a recent rally, with the candidate at his
side. ``Ladies and gentlemen, I've got the antidote right here on
these steps.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during the impeachment hearings in the House that McCain
first called Graham up to ask for his support in a presidential
run. The two had never met before. McCain told Graham he liked his
feisty free spirit, which was on ample display during the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to see that feistiness rear up again as the Feb. 19
primary nears.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who is 44 and single, is no country-club Republican.
He's more a beer-joint Republican, albeit a teetotaling one.
</P>
<P>
   His father owned such a joint, a popular bare-bones hangout that
offered only takeout service to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up around some real interesting people,'' he says of
those days. ``The wives would call up wanting to know if Harry's in
and I'd run up and say, `Your wife's calling.' He'd say, `Tell her
I'm not here,' and I'd run back, at 9 years old, and say, `He said
he's not here.' So I learned diplomacy at a young age and I've
heard the song `Satin Seats to Lie On and Satin Pillows to Cry On'
about 10 million times.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Graham's parents died of natural causes when he was
finishing college, leaving him to help raise his 13-year-old
sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is not always like the TV shows,'' Graham said. ``On the
Ozzie and Harriet shows, Mom and Dad don't die and you don't have
to worry about raising a teen-age sister. But that's life. It does
change you. You can either feel sorry for yourself or you mature
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham chose the latter. He went off to law school. He worked
for a time as an Air Force prosecutor. He did well, and won a seat
in Congress as a reformer in 1994. He is now in his third term and
as popular as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Never has he forgotten his roots, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Graham says he's not proud that his family bar did not serve
blacks until the early '70s. That was wrong, he says, but the way
things were.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Confederate flag hanging above the Statehouse, an
issue McCain and other Republican candidates have danced around,
Graham understands why black people would despise it. But he also
sees why others want it to keep flapping.
</P>
<P>
   He is not afraid to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a guy out there named Bubba,'' said Graham. ``He grew
up when public schools got integrated. He goes to work every day.
There are women and African-Americans in the workplace and he's
fine with that, but he thinks the whole world is against him and
has rights he doesn't have. He thinks the flag is the last thing he
has going for him and he's not going to take it down. I don't want
to step on Bubba's feelings. There are no groups sticking up for
the Bubbas of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be little Graham is afraid to talk about.
Impeachment is now a taboo topic among most politicians in both
parties. But not for Graham, who seems to at least refer to the
case in every public utterance.
</P>
<P>
   But do not get him wrong. Graham is no one-dimensional
politician. He went to Congress to help topple the liberal
establishment and to bring some common-man sentiment to an
institution he thinks is far too elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be remembered as the impeachment boy. That
shortchanges who I am,'' Graham said. ``I know the first line of my
obituary is going to be that. Bill Clinton's obituary will mention
it, too. I'm no more happy about it than he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
