u i BC-CROATIA-POLITICS-NYT     02-06 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROATIAN VOTERS LOOK TOWARD LARGE-SCALE CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia _ Croatia votes on Monday for its second
president in a tightening race that hinges more on personality than
on policy. But after the death in December of the autocratic Franjo
Tudjman, who ruled Croatia from its independence in 1991, voters
seem likely to go for the man who has presented himself as least
ambitious and power-hungry, the avuncular Stipe Mesic, 65.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are pro-Western and relatively liberal, favoring
membership in the European Union and NATO, and both are part of the
six-party opposition coalition that won parliamentary elections a
month ago, defeating Tudjman's once dominant Croatian Democratic
Union.
</P>
<P>
   But Mesic, whose positions are less overtly nationalist than
those of his rival, Drazen Budisa, 51, has been hurt by accusations
that he lacks substance, that his campaign has mysterious financing
and that he was once an informer for the Yugoslav secret police,
allegations Mesic rejects.
</P>
<P>
   The last polls show Mesic with about 45 percent of the vote and
Budisa about 40 percent. But the percentage of undecideds is high.
In an interview Sunday, Mesic said the race was ``closer, but
there's enough margin for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesic supporters, including Ivo Pukanic, the editor of the
weekly investigative newspaper Nacional, say that the charges have
been fomented with the help of Tudjman's weakened party, which sees
Mesic as the biggest threat to Croatia's interests in
Bosnia-Herzegovina, where the party remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   Mesic has been blunt on the need for Croatia to treat Bosnia as
an independent state, stop allowing Bosnian Croats to vote in
Croatia and stop spending up to $150 million a year to support the
Bosnian Croats and their army.
</P>
<P>
   Mesic said: ``I sent the blunt message to the Croats in
Bosnia-Herzegovina that that they have to turn toward Sarajevo,
they must lose all illusions that they will one day be part of
Croatia. That's why I was hit hard, but Croatian citizens realize
that this is the only real solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Budisa and Mesic were jailed under Tito for pro-Croatian
activities in the early 1970s, but Budisa is the more ardent
nationalist, while more socially conservative on issues like drug
use and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Mesic was the last Croatian representative to the collective
presidency of Yugoslavia as the old Communist federation fell apart
in 1991. He was a close aide and ally to Tudjman and served as
prime minister and parliament speaker, finally quitting in 1994
over policies toward Bosnia. Mesic opposed the Tudjman policy of
financial, moral and military support for a separate Bosnian Croat
entity and army in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   While Mirko Galic, editor of Globus magazine, said Mesic left
too late, after Croatia committed some of its worst deeds in
Bosnia, Mesic did suffer political ostracism for his stand.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Mesic said he started to pull away from
Tudjman in the spring of 1991, after a meeting between Tudjman and
Slobodan Milosevic, then the Serbian president, when the two men
agreed to divide up Bosnia between them. ``If I left then, I
wouldn't be in politics now,'' Mesic said Sunday, insisting that
his efforts to change policy from inside failed only three years
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his disagreement was in 1991, and he's a man of character,
why didn't he leave immediately?'' Galic asked. ``Mesic remains an
unknown variable for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Igor Mirkovic, a respected television journalist, said: ``I've
followed Mesic for 10 years and I still can't tell you what his
political beliefs are.''
</P>
<P>
   But Budisa, the leader of the Social Liberal party and the main
ally of the new prime minister, Ivica Racan, has not been much more
explicit about his plans for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Both men vow to cooperate with Racan and parliament to cut the
vast executive powers of the Tudjman presidency, incorporated both
in the Constitution and the law, while wanting to retain the
position of commander in chief and an important role in foreign
policy and domestic oversight. But neither man has been specific
about how these new relationships should work.
</P>
<P>
   Although 14 years younger than Mesic, Budisa is stiffer and more
formal, awkward in campaigning and in front of television cameras,
which love the folksy Mesic. But in a last set of debates, Budisa
did better, appearing more relaxed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
