<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-MEDIA-NYT     02-06 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H., S.C.)  
 MCCAIN WINS THE NEWSWEEKLIES' TRIPLE CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The publicity avalanche set off by his New Hampshire victory
swept Sen. John McCain onto the covers of the three national
newsweeklies Sunday, a rare journalistic hat trick that capped a
week of the kind of attention that might make a Nobel Prize winner
or even a Person of the Century feel a little underexposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's Big Mo,'' Newsweek declared on its cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McCain Mutiny'' is how Time characterized the senator's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Attaching even grander significance to his triumph in the first
Republican primary, U.S. News &AMP; World Report asked, ``Can He Win It
All?''
</P>
<P>
   Some weeks, with the pressures of an ever-quickening news cycle,
picking a cover is not easy. Last week, it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't agonize over it,'' said Walter Isaacson, Time's
managing editor, after putting a beaming McCain out front, his
second appearance there in two months. ``It wasn't a tough
decision. The guy wins New Hampshire by 19 points, blowing away the
front-runner. He's pretty clearly the story of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   The unanimity among the weeklies was a reflection of a virtual
across-the-board sentiment by editors and reporters around the
nation that McCain had upended conventional wisdom and overnight
moved from insurgent to potential front-runner. ``It was clear,''
U.S. News observes in its cover story, ``that he was fast becoming
the hottest political commodity since an obscure southern governor
named Bill Clinton dubbed himself the `comeback kid.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If the media seem moonstruck about the McCain campaign _ ``It's
a virtual tidal wave of positive communication about John McCain,''
said Greg Stevens, the senator's media consultant _ aides to Gov.
George W. Bush are eager for the honeymoon to end.
</P>
<P>
   In new media outlets and old, from online magazines to newsstand
staples, the story this past week was of two contravening
trajectories.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's the Real McCoy in N.H.'' is how The New York Post
described the senator's ascension. ``Bush Whacked,'' said Salon,
the Web political magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press is obviously in full metal swoon,'' Ari Fleischer, a
spokesman for the Bush campaign, said Sunday. ``But the press is
also well known for its rhythms, and I have enough respect for the
press to believe that they will be the best judges of whether they
are sacrificing scrutiny for a seat on the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   There is even talk in South Carolina of a local movement to rile
Republican voters by encouraging the image of McCain as a darling
of the generally disliked press. ``Don't be surprised if you see
bumper stickers that say, `Support the Media: Vote for John
McCain,''' said one Republican political operative.
</P>
<P>
   Across the political spectrum, commentators on the morning talk
shows over the weekend expressed awe at McCain's victory _ analyses
of his victory pushed discussions of Vice President Al Gore's
triumph to the sidelines _ and the criticisms tended to be muted.
Even Robert Novak, the hard-line conservative columnist, seemed
apologetic in offering a dissenting view. ``Pardon me for saying
something bad about a war hero,'' Novak said on CNN's ``Capital
Gang,'' ``but he is in with the Washington lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, with his well-publicized, seemingly all-hours
availability to reporters, has made no effort to hide his glee at
the tone of the coverage. At town hall meetings in New Hampshire
over the past two months, for instance, McCain referred voters
often to the favorable cover piece Time ran about him around
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacson said he felt no guilt about the amount of exposure
McCain had received from Time, which ran a cover on Bush several
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think McCain is getting more of a bounce than a lot of
previous candidates,'' Isaacson said, ``but that's partly because
the size of his victory was so amazing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 1914EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
