<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-VIOLENCE-ART-9     02-06 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VIOLENCE-ART-935&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS ATTACK ALBANIAN FAMILIES IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 5, 6, 7, 8 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ Gani Gjaka buried his wife, Nerimane, on
Sunday, laying her shrouded body in a muddy field on the southern
edge of this tense and bitterly divided town, where Mrs. Gjaka was
one of the eight Albanian victims of an eruption of violence by
local Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gjaka died in a hospital on Saturday from extensive
shrapnel wounds received in a Serbian assault with guns, explosives
and grenades on 11 Albanians huddled in a three-room apartment in
the wrong part of town on Thursday night. Her 13-year-old-daughter,
Emine, is still in the hospital, unaware of her mother's death,
according to her father.
</P>
<P>
   The two Gjakas were wounded when some of the 9,000 Serbs who
live in the northern half of Mitrovica went on a rampage. One
Serbian cafe was firebombed the same night in the worst violence
Kosovo has seen since NATO's bombing war ended in June and foreign
troops arrived in the province. Two other Albanian teen-agers, a
16-year-old girl and 13-year-old boy, were among the others
wounded. The boy, Nderim Ayete, later died.
</P>
<P>
   Gani Gjaka, a factory worker, had taken his wife and daughter to
a neighbor's apartment that night, thinking that there would be
safety in numbers. They lived on the north side of Mitrovica, part
of the 2,500 Albanians among the Serbs, and they were braced for
trouble after a rocket attack on a bus full of Serbs killed two
people near Mitrovica on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The town has been Kosovo's most divided since NATO troops
arrived. Grenade attacks and demonstrations are frequent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt tense after every incident, thinking something would
happen. But we never thought it would be like this,'' Gjaka said.
Five of the people in his neighbor's apartment were under 16. Just
before 10 p.m. some Serbs knocked at the door, and a voice demanded
that they open up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `We want you to leave the flat _ we are Serbian
police,''' Gjaka recounted. His neighbor refused to open the door
and told them to leave the people inside alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that moment, the man shot at the door with a handgun,'' he
said. ``We had pistols so we shot back. We had weapons to defend
ourselves, but this was a completely unprovoked attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I heard them putting something on the door. I moved all
the women and children back, warning them something might happen.
There was a strong explosion; the door was totally destroyed and
even part of the wall. Then they threw in a hand grenade.''
</P>
<P>
   Deafened by the blasts and fumbling in the dark, Gjaka grabbed
the telephone and called the NATO-led peacekeepers and the U.N.
police for help. Then he called a friend and begged him to get
help, saying their lives were in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``French troops were stationed 60 to 70 yards from our
building,'' he said. ``But we never got any help from them.'' A big
man, he sat in an armchair in his sister's apartment, and began to
cry.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs threw in a second hand grenade, he said, and followed
it with gunfire. A couch they had pushed across the doorway caught
fire, which filled the apartment with smoke. ``Then they threw in a
third grenade,'' he said. ``It hit the barricade we had made and
fell into the room where the women and children were.''
</P>
<P>
   The grenade ripped into his wife and daughter and two other
children. ``My wife called for help, but I could not get to them,''
he said. ``They were shooting nonstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly a Serb appeared at the door, holding police
identification, and told them he would guarantee their safety if
they left. ``How can I leave, when my wife's lying there with her
entrails spilling out?'' Gjaka shouted back. ``Let her die here,
but save yourselves,'' he quoted the Serb as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The man left, and the Serbs lobbed in a fourth grenade. The
smoke was suffocating them, and Gjaka heard his daughter's voice.
``She cried: `Please rescue mom. And please don't lose me too,' She
couldn't feel her leg,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He dragged his wife toward the window and telephoned his sister,
who lived on the south side of Mitrovica, telling her that they
were wounded and desperately needed help. It was that call that
worked. His sister, Fatime Munoglli, lost her husband and two sons
last year when Serbian paramilitaries rounded up and shot all the
men from the street where she lived.
</P>
<P>
   She rushed down to the U.N. building to demand assistance.
Eventually at 2:30 in the morning, four and a half hours after
their ordeal began, she found a policemen who would listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an American policeman with a mustache,'' she said. ``He
saw the state I was in, and when I said there were wounded there,
he took some men and immediately went.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans made their way through a crowd of 300 to 400
Serbs, she said, and climbed to the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   They shouted in English, but at first Gjaka thought they were
Serbs trying to trick him. Then he spotted the American flag on
their sleeves and pulled down the barricade, raising his arms in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   The police immediately worked to evacuate the wounded. Then they
took those who were not hurt, warning them, Gjaka said, to avoid
``any wrong gesture because there is a possibility we could all
lose our lives.'' As they left, he said, the Serbs applauded and
then threw stones.
</P>
<P>
   It was close to 4 a.m. when they reached a military hospital on
the southern side of the city. Two of the children underwent
amputations, and at 6 a.m. his wife went in for a four-hour
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, the boy, Nderim, died. Gjaka's wife regained
consciousness, but her condition deteriorated, and she died 24
hours later.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gjaka and his family had managed to stay in their home even
during the expulsions and killings of last spring's Kosovo war, and
had resisted repeated threats in the months since NATO-led
peacekeepers took control of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has joined at least 300 Albanians who fled their homes in
northern Mitrovica last week. Families were still arriving over the
weekend, pushed out by gangs of Serbs who were going from apartment
to apartment on Sunday, even after extra peacekeeping troops had
arrived to impose order and enforce a curfew.
</P>
<P>
   Halit Berani, an Albanian who runs the Mitrovica office of the
Council for Human Rights and Freedoms, said the families had called
him as they were being evicted. ``There were 35 families in that
building, and after today there are none,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gjaka is missing much more than an apartment. ``I lost not only
a wife but a good friend,'' he said after the funeral. ``We were 20
years together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0100 </DOCNO>
