<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8391 &Cx1f; tad-z
b i BC-MEXICO-STRIKE-0207-2N     02-06 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-STRIKE-0207-2NDLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in lede, corrects to read 'the world's biggest . . . ' sted
of 'word's . . . '
 &HT;    MEXICAN POLICE RAID UNIVERSITY AND ARREST HUNDREDS OF STRIKING
STUDENTS
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Thousands of unarmed federal police swarmed the
campus of Mexico's national university shortly after dawn on
Sunday, arresting 632 students and crushing a strike that had shut
down one of the world's biggest public universities for nearly 10
months.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred strike activists, who were protesting an attempt
to impose a dramatic tuition increase at the traditionally free
institution, were still in the midst of an all-night meeting in the
campus' Che Guevara Auditorium when police rousted them reportedly
without injuries or major resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Some students escaped by running and climbing over the
barricades they had erected when they occupied the campus last
April. But most surrendered peacefully and boarded police buses,
grimly flashing peace signs or weeping, according to televised
reports by select media allowed to accompany the police onto the
campus of the National Autonomous University of Mexico _ known here
as the UNAM.
</P>
<P>
   The police carried only shields and billy clubs _ a strategy
designed to avoid bloodshed and comparisons to Mexico's infamous
1968 Army massacre of hundreds of students marching for greater
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Radio stations were flooded with calls of support for the
federal government's decision to finally re-take the university.
But scores of angry parents and university employees who share the
students' fear the university will no longer be affordable gathered
outside the sealed campus and police headquarters shouting insults
at Mexican TV reporters and demanding that authorities release the
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``A democratic society cannot allow the kidnapping of the
national university,'' said Mexico's Interior Secretary Diodoro
Carrasco, who announced the police action with Mexican Attorney
General Jorge Madrazo at a news conference Sunday. Police were
dispatched after a judge issued a court order to re-take the campus
where more than 270,000 students normally study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government is convinced that this step is not
enough to resolve the conflict,'' Carrasco added, but he called it
``indispensable'' for allowing the traditionally autonomous
university community to settle the dispute over its future.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where more than half the population lives in
poverty, UNAM administrators shocked students last spring by
proposing to raise the virtually free tuition at the public
institution to about US$140 a year. A few months into the strike,
however, under pressure by many quarters of Mexican society, the
administrators announced the fees would be ``voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   Demanding guarantees that tuition would not be imposed at a
later date, an increasingly hard core of students refused to budge.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's raid followed a week of tumult here related to the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday 37 people were injured and 247 were arrested after
anti-strike students and employees tried to break into a
university-run high school occupied by strikers.
</P>
<P>
   Arrest warrants were issued Friday for 430 activists who are
being charged with vandalism, theft, and rioting. The university's
rector met Friday with representatives of the students' strike
committee and after an all-day session failed to come to an
agreement for how to end the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   After initially restricting press access to the campus on Sunday
morning, police allowed more reporters onto the university after
most students had already been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested two strike leaders, Mario Benitez, an economics
professor who worked with the students, and Alejandro Echevarria,
who went by the nickname, ``El Mosh.''
</P>
<P>
   Both reportedly tried to hide in closets on the campus when the
police began to sweep through buildings. Police said they found
five Molotov cocktail bombs and several marijuana plants on the
campus.
</P>
<P>
   In a surreal scene, about 2,500 Mexican Federal Police officers
dressed in gray anti-riot gear lined the entrances to the campus
and stood outside the Che Guevara Auditorium at the Humanities
Faculty.
</P>
<P>
   The auditorium has long bore a mural and the name of Guevara,
the Argentine socialist revolutionary who fought in Cuba with Fidel
Castro and was embraced by Mexico's government.
</P>
<P>
   The striking students claim their government _ which has often
espoused socialist ideals _ is selling out Mexico's poor by trying
to impose fees for this country's premier institution for public
higher education. The students view the attempt to impose tuition
as a bow to globalization and the controversial transformation of
Mexico's economy to a more free-market system with fewer government
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the huge mural of Guevara that shapes part of the
faculty's symbol, strikers had scrawled, ``Slaves to the
International Monetary Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillermina Cabanas, whose 24-year-old son had been arrested,
agreed with the strikers' fears that Mexico is being pushed into
``privatizing'' the public university.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're oppressing kids who are fighting for their rights,''
she said. ``We are people who can't afford private schools and high
tuition.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the many Mexicans who supported the non-violent raid,
however, was Guadalupe Rodriguez, a business secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the news. It was just for the conflict to come
to an end. It's a shame the students won't be able to return to
classes soon because they're going to have to repair all the damage
that's been done to the installations,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that for once our government has done something good,
although it took a long time to do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon de la Fuente, the university's rector, issued a statement
after the raid saying he ``lamented'' that police had to be used to
take back the UNAM.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university community has struggled to resolve this by
ourselves,'' he said, ``and we would have succeeded if allowed to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He blamed groups that ``don't belong at the university'' for
leading the strike. He wasn't specific, but in the past de la
Fuente has hinted that a shadowy armed anti-government group _ the
Popular Revolutionary Army _ was involved in the conflict. The
students have vehemently denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   De la Fuente said he has asked for minors who are in custody to
be released to their parents as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the parents who supported the strike lashed out at
Mexico's two top TV networks after the police raid, blaming them
for focusing on acts of violence and vandalism rather than the
issues that caused the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get out of here, liars,'' shouted a woman who was approached
by a reporter on live TV.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
