<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8396 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-WEB-CLICKS-SPI &LR;      02-06 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-CLICKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE`RE ALL NEIGHBORS ON THE WORLD WIDE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rapidly growing World Wide Web now has about 1.5 billion
pages, but some scientists think the size of the Web is best
measured not by pages but by the average number of connections it
takes to link any two random sites.
</P>
<P>
   Thus was born the ``19 clicks of separation'' theory of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe what counts isn't the average number of
connections so much as the way they're connecting.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is literally growing like a weed. Mathematicians say its
connections follow an organizing pattern, similar to plant life in
the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows why. Weird.
</P>
<P>
   But first, consider the 19 clicks.
</P>
<P>
   Like the celebrated ``six degrees of separation'' that
supposedly can connect any two people on the planet, researchers at
Notre Dame University recently estimated that any two randomly
selected sites on the Web are connected, on average, by 19 clicks.
</P>
<P>
   The original six degrees notion, based on a sociological theory
popularized in the 1960s, posits that each person on the planet is
linked to any other person through no more than five mutual
acquaintances. Out of the total six billion people on Earth, you
can get from one person to anyone else in at most six people.
</P>
<P>
   The Notre Dame team says, on average, you can get from one site
on the Web to any other randomly selected site in about 19 clicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on this kind of information, we can construct more
effective search engines,'' said Hawoong Jeong, one of the Notre
Dame scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Today's search engines typically cover less than one-fifth of
all publicly indexed sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But others don't think trying to quantify the Web will amount to
much of anything useful. Academic aerobics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares?'' responded Oren Etzioni, developer of the search
engine Metacrawler and a University of Washington computer
scientist on leave while working as chief technology officer at the
Web company Go2net.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether the Web's diameter is 11 or 19 or 7.5 might be a fun
academic curiosity, but that's not how people use the Web,''
Etzioni said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more interesting to everyone, including Etzioni, is not
so much the size of the Web as its structure.
</P>
<P>
   When the Notre Dame researchers attempted to find a meaningful
way to describe the diameter of the Web, they also demonstrated
something mysterious about its growth and development.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, they found the Web is a lot like a living plant. For
some unknown reason, it is developing along the same mathematical
principles that govern the organic development of plants in the
natural world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a complete surprise for us,'' said Albert-Laszlo
Barabasi, a physicist at Notre Dame and principal investigator for
the team that reported their finding on the Web's 19 clicks of
separation. It was reported last fall in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Barabasi and his students, Jeong and Reka Albert, last year set
loose a ``robot'' search engine on portions of the Web to tally
links and measure how far away each of the links encountered were
from each other. The robotic search engine was a computer program
that traveled the Web documenting its encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Barabasi said everyone expected the robot to encounter a simple
exponentially increasing number of links based on the assumption
that the links on the Web are distributed randomly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, the data clearly showed the links are
distributed according to a more sophisticated and self-organizing
mathematical principle known as the ``power-tail law.'' Nobody
knows why.
</P>
<P>
   Another team of researchers, Bernardo Huberman and Lada Adamic
at Xerox Palo Alto Research Center, found the same growth pattern
on the Web through a different method of analysis. Their findings
were also reported in Nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like the growth of a tree,'' Huberman said. ``The
more pages a site has, the more likely it is that more pages will
be added to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the number of branches on a tree limb is greater near
the trunk than out at the tip, growth on the Web takes place so
that links with more associated links (or branches) end up closer
to the Web's ``trunk.'' This cyber trunk is perhaps best thought of
as the main flow of information on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Web doesn't exist in physical space and its
``branches'' always re-connect rather than spread out into thin
air, the tree analogy isn't perfect. But the point is that the
Web's growth appears to follow some of the same natural laws at
work in ecological systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most interesting is how the Web's structure has evolved
without any central authority,'' said Steve Lawrence, a computer
scientist at Princeton University and at NEC internationally
recognized for his work on Web information distribution and access.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ending up with a high degree of structure,'' Lawrence
said, and it's somehow creating that structure on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's fascinating here,'' agreed Etzioni. Trying to
pin down the size of the Web is much less relevant than figuring
out how it is structured, he said, and why it develops according to
the power-tail law.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Barabasi and his students showed, efforts aimed at
quantifying the Web can aid in the effort to better understand its
structure. The Notre Dame researchers play around in the field of
``topology'' _ a branch of mathematics where number and shape are
the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Etzioni said he's pretty sure the 19 clicks finding won't help
in the ongoing effort to improve search engines, not yet anyway,
but he said you never know where things may lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of science shows there's a lot of value to
curiosity driven work,'' he said. And the findings are certainly
driving the curious.
</P>
<P>
   Usama Fayyad, head of the data mining group at Microsoft
Research, said he was disappointed to learn the Web supposedly had
19 clicks of separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have expected it to be less than that,'' Fayyad said.
``It might suggest the web is a bit less interconnected than we'd
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the finding is worth pursuing because of its
implications for networking on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Etzioni said he's not surprised to learn the Web has an average
of 19 clicks of separation, more than the six degrees for people.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people do you know?'' he said. The average Web page
has seven links, he said, while the average person knows hundreds
of other people. The more links per person makes for easier
connecting.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of Web pages increases over time, Barabasi said,
the Web's size _ degree of separation _ can be expected to increase
slowly. It won't increase as fast as might be expected based on
simple exponential growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If it operates according to the power-tail law, Barabasi said, a
ten-fold increase in the number of pages on the Web would likely
result in just a small increase in Web size (again, size being the
degree of separation between links).
</P>
<P>
   But again, Etzioni said, so what if it does? The real trick here
is to make more efficient and accurate search engines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical search engine today only indexes about 16 percent
of the Web,'' Etzioni said. ``That fraction keeps getting smaller
as the Web increases in size.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to getting better search engines, many of these Web
meisters say, is to better understand how the Web is organized _
why it's growing like a weed _ and how to use that knowledge to
improve our ability to find the information we seek.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 1954EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8397 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-CHILD-PROTECTION-FAIL     02-06 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-PROTECTION-FAILURES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CITES FAILURES IN STATE EFFORTS TO PROTECT CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH TEICHROEB  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six times in three years, worried neighbors, police officers and
day-care workers reported to Child Protective Services that a
mother was neglecting her two young girls _ locking them in a room
of the filthy house, letting them wander the streets, forgetting to
feed them.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, state caseworkers failed to step in, dismissing the
case as low-risk.
</P>
<P>
   When a seventh report came in, a public health nurse finally got
the state's attention with a chilling discovery: the girls, ages 4
and 5, had been left alone so much that they were malnourished and
hadn't even learned to talk.
</P>
<P>
   The children were removed from the home 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of dozens of cases investigated by the Office of the
Family and Children's Ombudsman in which the state failed to
protect children suffering from chronic neglect, despite repeated
complaints of mistreatment, according to a report to be released
Monday by that office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has truly been an invisible problem,'' said Vicki Wallen,
state ombudsman. ``It doesn't necessarily result in dead children.
But more often you have severely damaged children whose potential
as human beings is destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   In many of the chronic neglect cases reviewed by Wallen's office
since 1997, children suffered serious delays in physical and
emotional development by the time the Department of Social and
Health Services finally intervened, Wallen said.
</P>
<P>
   Chronic neglect is defined as ongoing, serious deprivation of a
child's basic physical, emotional or developmental needs. That can
mean inadequate nutrition, a lack of supervision or failing to
interact with a child.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is highlighted in Wallen's 77-page report, submitted
recently to Gov. Gary Locke and members of the Legislative
Children's Oversight Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Wallen's report also raises concerns about the state's serious
shortage of foster care and group homes, a problem documented in a
Post-Intelligencer special report last September, and chastises
some community professionals for failing to report child abuse and
neglect as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Spears, spokeswoman for DSHS, said the child-welfare
system is working to improve its response to cases involving
serious neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only recently has the research been available to help us
understand the long-term effects that neglect has on child
development,'' Spears said in a written statement. ``So there is no
doubt that the system as a whole needs improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   DSHS is experimenting with pilot projects that intervene earlier
in neglect cases to provide intensive family supports, Spears said.
</P>
<P>
   But caseworkers also face the barrier that a ``pattern of
neglect'' must be established in order to prove that children are
at risk of imminent harm before the state can legally intervene,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the 11,000 children in state foster care were
removed from their families because of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caseworkers do intervene eventually, but not until many
reports have been filed,'' Wallen said. ``My main concern is the
timeliness of those interventions, and the impact on children.''
</P>
<P>
   Her office has investigated cases where as many as 21 reports of
neglect and abuse had been made before children were removed from a
home.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons caseworkers have been slow to act in chronic
neglect allegations is that they have traditionally viewed such
incidents as low priority compared to physical or sexual abuse,
Wallen said.
</P>
<P>
   A single neglect report often doesn't convey the cumulative harm
being done to a child, especially when previous reports are not
considered, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But new research on children's early brain development has shown
that chronic neglect can delay physical and mental development and
undermine the ability to bond emotionally with parents or other
caregivers, Wallen said.
</P>
<P>
   DSHS is trying to improve its handling of neglect cases by
revising the risk-assessment tools used by child protection
workers, she said. The new tools will give more weight to chronic
neglect, and should be in use later this year.
</P>
<P>
   A legal hurdle is that it's much harder to prove children are at
risk of imminent harm in physical abuse or sexual abuse cases than
with chronic neglect, she said. ``That's a major barrier,'' Wallen
said. ``The legal standards may be too high to intervene in some
chronic neglect cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, children who are chronically neglected usually come
from families with a multitude of problems, from substance abuse to
domestic violence. Those families need a wide range of treatment
that is often not available, leaving social workers with few
options until a crisis erupts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her recommendations to improve the handling of chronic neglect
cases include:
</P>
<P>
   Chronic neglect should be treated as a serious risk factor
during child protection investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Caseworkers should verify parents' compliance with voluntary
services in neglect cases and intervene when they fail to follow
through.
</P>
<P>
   DSHS and the state Attorney General's Office should develop
written guidelines describing the legal evidence needed to remove
children suffering from chronic neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Judges, attorneys and social workers need to be trained about
the long-term damage caused by chronic neglect.
</P>
<P>
   On the statewide shortage of foster care and group homes,
Wallen's report recommended that an independent review be done to
collect accurate data on existing resources and to assess what
additional placements are needed.
</P>
<P>
   She said the recent recommendations of the DSHS Foster Care Task
Force don't go far enough in tackling the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern is that they are only addressing pieces of a
much larger issue,'' Wallen said. ``They need to take a much-needed
step back and look at this very important issue in a strategic
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Her report cited many of the concerns raised last September in a
Post-Intelligencer report on the foster care crisis, including
children being forced to sleep in a state office building or being
shuttled between emergency overnight homes while awaiting
placement.
</P>
<P>
   The third area of concern raised by Wallen's report was that
professionals, including doctors, teachers and dentists, have
failed to report child abuse in at least 10 cases which have come
to her attention over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, two physicians at a rural hospital did not notify
child protection after a 14-year-old girl delivered a baby late
last year. Five weeks later, the infant was readmitted to hospital
suffering from malnourishment, stomach ulcers and a failure to
thrive. The state was finally contacted and the baby was removed
from the mother.
</P>
<P>
   Wallen's office plans to file a complaint with the state's
Quality Medical Assurance Commission about the doctors' failure to
report the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to send a message to professionals that it's their
legal responsibility to report,'' Wallen said.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to report child abuse or neglect is a gross misdemeanor,
but Wallen said few cases are ever prosecuted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
