<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8398 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-MEDI     02-06 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL PUBLISHERS ENTICING AUTHORS, BOTH UNKNOWN AND ESTABLISHED 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The demand for Arthur C. Clarke's science fiction novel about a
malevolent computer named HAL has endured for three decades, but
interest was rather tepid for the author's six-page, double-spaced
essay about ``TV's Time-Travel Future.''
</P>
<P>
   So last month the British author of ``2001 _ A Space Odyssey''
plunged into the infant market for electronic books _ ignoring the
risk to his prestige. He posted his November speech to a U.N.
conference for a four-figure advance paid by an Internet newcomer
with an irreverent name and approach, Fatbrain.com.
</P>
<P>
   The essay was too brief for conventional book or magazine
publishers, but not so for one of the new houses of virtual
publishing that eagerly accepts just about any words that move in
bytes. Clarke's observations about television and the ``Global
family'' were transformed into a $2 electronic title instantly
available for downloading, reading online or sputtering out on the
pages of a printer.
</P>
<P>
   Fatbrain is an online computer bookstore turned digital
publisher at the vanguard of a new electronic book market that has
spawned other players like 1stBooks and iUniverse.com, which entice
writers with the editorial equivalent of: Who Wants to Be an
Author?
</P>
<P>
   Fatbrain has sold more than 10,000 titles since November with
its titles tilting to the popular side; more than 60 percent of the
books explore consumer themes, Chris MacAskill, the company's chief
executive and owner of the original cramped Silicon alley garage
office. Customers are still drawn to books about computers and
business, with more than 50 percent of sales in the professional
category. And the average price of the e-books sold is about $3.47.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts are optimistic about Fatbrain's core online
bookselling business _ mail order computer and technical titles _
although the company has yet to turn a profit. But they do not know
whether ``e-matter'' will gain popularity. ``I like their base
business, which is really a business to business supplier of
technical information and training materials,'' said Dalton L.
Chandler, an analyst with Needham &AMP; Co. ``They've built a really
blue-chip clientele. Their e-matter is potentially a huge idea, but
it's still very early to judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the notion of virtual titles by virtually anybody
captured the imagination of venture capitalists even though some
top publishers scoffed that this highly democratic system would
evolve into a vanity press profoundly flawed by the absence of
professional vetting and high quality writing.
</P>
<P>
   But lately there are signs emerging that the traditional
literary community is warming to a new alien form; Time Warner
Trade Publishing wants to post chapters or excerpts from coming
books on the Fatbrain site and the company's chief executive,
Laurence J. Kirshbaum, calls the concept ``brilliant.'' And some
prominent authors and agents are beginning to place short works or
out-of-print books on the site, which is already a literary refuge
for amateur writers yearning to share their oeuvres _ ``Psoriasis _
My 35-Year-Itch That Vanished'' or ``Did Russia Send Us AIDS?''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Lanigan and Richard Bach _ novelists whose books have
been transformed into films or occupied the rarified real estate of
The New York Times best-seller list _ are posting electronic titles
scorned by traditional publishers for reasons that range from
brevity to quirky themes. Clarke published his speech with Fatbrain
because there was no other forum, said his agent, Russell Galen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to be seen,'' Galen said. ``He wants to be read. If I
had a young author whose career I was trying to build I'd rather
have a hundred dollars from The New Yorker than a thousand from
Fatbrain. But with my 82-year-old author, my concern is reaching
readers. He doesn't need money. He doesn't need prestige. He just
wants to change lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely literary patrons of this publishing effort are
investors like Paul Allen, the co-founder of Microsoft, and
Highland Capital Partners, who have backed Fatbrain with more than
$35 million to nurture the market for what the company calls
``e-matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatbrain's roots are as deep as the cold cement of the Mountain
View, Calif., garage where it was founded in the summer of 1995
with the more sober name of Cbooks Express.
</P>
<P>
   Its existing list of some 6,000 titles is so varied that there
is room for the musings of Clarke and the lifework of Matthew J.
Burtless, 5, a San Diego kindergartener whose forte is coloring an
adventure series about a wandering monkey named ``Tyco.'' (His
older siblings take care of the writing.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is no surprise that some top publishing executives do
judge the books by the lack of a cover _ and editing. But Fatbrain
also has its defenders in mainstream publishing who say the concept
has the potential to create a market for short, immediate
literature that can be constantly updated or revised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a revolution,'' said Joni Evans, a literary agent at
the William Morris Agency, who is publishing the work of some of
her writers like William L. Ury, a co-author of the best-selling
book ``Getting to Yes.'' ``I think democracy is going to come to
book publishing in an interesting way where anybody can have a book
available.''
</P>
<P>
   When Fatbrain created its e-matter publishing program, it
expected unglamorous and dutiful offerings _ titles top heavy with
professional and technical themes that reflect the specialty of its
thriving online bookstore, which caters to computer professionals
and corporate accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it has drawn amateur novelists struggling to find
readers and willing to pay Fatbrain a $1 monthly storage fee for
posting manuscripts online. To nurture the infant electronic book
market, Fatbrain is paying some professional writers advances of
about $10,000 to post shorter pieces or excerpts of coming books.
In addition, the professional writers get a generous 60 percent
split of the royalty on the price of a book while self-published
writers get half.
</P>
<P>
   The kicker is that somebody has to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we didn't expect is all the fiction,'' said MacAskill.
``Our model does have the potential of ushering a whole new
distribution channel for things that never had an economic model
before. What about short stories and speeches and white papers and
things that are in depth?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the electronic books should not run higher than 100
pages. But authors follow their own muses, setting prices and page
counts that sometimes reflect no particular logic.
</P>
<P>
   Ten dollars buys three pages of advice exploring Gary Kelly's
solution for psoriasis. The free-lance writer Marla Hoover Doty
offers a staggering deal _ $150 for a one-page short story on
menopausal misery called ``Wake Up and Smell the Birthday Cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Kelly is not impressed with the reception for his
breathlessly written psoriasis cure; many Fatbrain titles are
simply ignored, but readers have vigorously attacked his remedies
as quackery. ``I've had very little success with my material,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But some established writers contend that virtual publishing is
appealing because it offers an opportunity to experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Lanigan, the author of almost 20 books including ``Romancing the
Stone,'' said she was typecast in the romantic suspense genre. She
could not find a publisher for her ``Miracles Are Golden,'' a
61-page Christmas novella about a little boy who is reincarnated as
a golden retriever to comfort a dying child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishers tell me that we don't do children's books and we're
certainly not going to publish one for you _ you're niched,'' she
said. ``There's a lot of writers who would like to do something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Lanigan also posted more than 15 of her books,
including out-of-print titles that she has priced at $6 or less. It
is too early to evaluate sales, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other writers are ``so paranoid about e-publishing,'' Lanigan
said. ``They're afraid of it and fear that someone is going to take
all their money. And there are others that think that it doesn't
have any respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of literary regard stems from an obvious weakness:
There is no software for fixing dangling modifiers or slashing
purple prose.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Romanos, president and chief operating officer of Viacom's
Simon &AMP; Schuster, said that he does not understand the logic behind
a ``slush pile'' business model that invites any writer to publish
without benefit of an editor or a staff to promote the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``What seems to be missing from the Fatbrain model is any
semblance of publishing,'' Romanos said. ``Publishing is everything
from perfecting a work to the creation of a market for that work.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Fatbrain has tried to address the issue by
hiring a small staff of editors that is expected to grow. But the
priority is name authors. ``I must admit that when a top author
submits something, we have stepped in and done some editing,''
MacAskill said. ``We're not trying to get into that business, but
we felt it would reflect poorly on e-matter if we didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one major publisher, Warner Books, is talking with
Fatbrain about posting chapters from seven coming books. Kensington
Books, the romance publisher, is also posting installments of a new
Kate Austen mystery by Jonnie Jacobs at $2 for 65 pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that inside every nonfiction book is a much smaller
book with the core information that many readers are seeking,''
said Kirshbaum of Time Warner Trade publishing, a Time Warner unit
that includes Warner Books and Little Brown &AMP; Co. ``Inside every
health book is theory and practice. Some people just want the
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic chapters may also create excitement in the lull
before the print version is published, Kirshbaum said. To test
these theories, Warner Books has come up with a list of titles for
e-matter that range from a self-help book about breast-feeding to a
chapter from a James Patterson novel.
</P>
<P>
   The last book on Warner's list should be required reading for
the investors in Fatbrain, which has yet to turn a profit _
``Confessions of a Venture Capitalist: Inside the High-Stakes World
of Start-Up Financing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
