<SLUG> BC-NYFASHION-POSTCARD07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Puffy look: Full-length furs, pinkie rings and Adidas
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You too can dress like a hip-hop mogul. Bad Boy
Entertainment honcho Sean ``Puffy'' Combs staged a star-studded
unveiling of his fall menswear collection Saturday night, and most
of the outfits looked unmistakeably like the ``big-baller'' (aka
``high rollers'' in the last century) garb that Combs usually wears
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Most pieces in the collection were stamped with his Sean John
logo, and the way models strutted down the floodlit runway in them
elicited high-pitched squeals from women in the audience. But some
in attendance noted that the full-length furs, gem-encrusted jeans
and leather coveralls appeared far too expensive to ever be
mass-produced for wide distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Sean John creative director Heather Thomsom designed
with showmen like her boss, not the common man, in mind. Notables
such as chart-topping rapper Jay-Z, basketball stars Patrick Ewing
and Alonzo Mourning and New York Yankees infielder Derek Jeter
grinned approvingly from their front-row perches along the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Slouchy denim separates _ accented with silver top-stitching and
rhinestone studs _ dominated the collection. And nearly every
outfit was accessorized with faux diamond-encrusted chokers,
bracelets and pinkie rings. Customized white Adidas sneakers served
as the footwear, even with the boxy, three-button suits.
</P>
<P>
   The color scheme was a cautious mix of indigo, gray, cream,
brown and black, with a few red pieces thrown in as accents. Such
caution was thrown to the wind when it came to lavishing the models
in leather and fur.
</P>
<P>
   Hooded parkas were trimmed in fox. Knee-length mink coats were
cut to Bigfoot proportions. Leather pants, jackets and coveralls
were tailored loose enough to accommodate not just one B-Boy, but
two.
</P>
<P>
   The show demonstrated how the fledgling brand has advanced
passed logoed caps and sweatshirts. It prompted Jay-Z, who has his
own sportswear line, called Rock-A-Wear, to admit, ``I'm just a
beginner.'' And overall, the presentation was such a celebrity
spectacle that it even lured Tommy Hilfiger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never go to other designers' shows,'' said Hilfiger, who
escorted onetime ``Mod Squad'' star Peggy Lipton to the show. ``But
Puffy's been such a great supporter of mine that I had to come and
support him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other celebs in attendance included a pink-wigged,
pale-blue-eyed Lil Kim, comedienne Sandra Bernhard and R&AMP;B
balladeer Luther Vandross, who looks thinner than ever and has dyed
his hair burnt orange.
</P>
<P>
   Combs' girlfriend, singer-actress Jennifer Lopez, was a
conspicuous no-show.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
