<HEADER>
A8411 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NYFASHION-SHOWS07-COX     02-06 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYFASHION-SHOWS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Subdued Hilfiger gets back to basics _ in plaid
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tommy Hilfiger signaled a safe, stylish return to his
roots with a collection, best described as ``postmillennial
preppie,'' that he showed Sunday at the Roseland Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The fall/winter clothes for both men and women were much tamer
than the wild, Western motif Hilfiger offered in his spring 2000
collection. And the presentation was scaled back dramatically from
the live rock performance that accompanied the Madison Square
Garden show last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger's restraint could be attributed to the fact that he's
had a reality check of a fiscal nature: Last week he announced
plans to close his signature boutiques in Beverly Hills, Calif.,
and London, where his highest-priced merchandise has been sold.
</P>
<P>
   This new collection was dominated by plaids, and Hilfiger said
before the show that they were inspired by a trip he took with his
wife and children to his ancestral home in Scotland. Bold tartan
pants, tops, dresses and coats emphasized the designer's newfound
affinity for the Scottish Isles, and plaid linings and trim also
accented the suede, leather, cashmere and chiffon clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes _ mainly red, blue, green, black and white _
recalled the look of Hilfiger designs from the start of his rise in
the industry in the mid-1980s. He simply uses better fabrics now
than he did then.
</P>
<P>
   His innovative spirit hasn't been tamed entirely. For men, he
proposes slacks that flare out from the knee, cardigan-turtleneck
twin sets and patent leather shoes for everyday wear.
</P>
<P>
   The collection looked clean and modern, however reminiscent it
was of days gone by.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S ABBOUD TIME: The way Joseph Abboud seems to see things, a
bronze age is beginning. The fall menswear collection he presented
was replete with new fabrications in tones of shiny browns and
other metallics. His suits _ worn variously with turtlenecks or
tone-on-tone shirt and tie combinations _ were soft in structure
and somewhat glossy, but still undeniably masculine. Abboud's
jackets sloped gently off the shoulders, and most of his pants were
cuffless, creaseless and pleatless. In a nod to his career-long
commitment to finer sportswear, many of Abboud's suits featured
pants with cargo pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think men are most comfortable with themselves when they
wear the kind of clothes that women like,'' Abboud said.
</P>
<P>
   In the audience, as always, was one of Abboud's best customers
and best friends, CBS' Bryant Gumble, who sat cuddled with the new
love _ a buxom blonde _ in his life. Actor Danny Aiello was also on
hand. ``I love the clothes. I'm tall enough to wear them,'' he
said. ``I just don't know if I'm thin enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
