<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8412 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-870&AMP;AD     02-06 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO EMPHASIZE PROTECTION OF MEDICARE IN BUDGET MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will propose a $1.84 trillion
federal budget for next year on Monday and will call for using much
of the projected budget surplus over the next decade to strengthen
and expand the Medicare system of health insurance for the elderly,
administration officials said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan calls for spending on government programs outside
of Social Security and Medicare _ the third of the total budget
that Congress revisits each year _ to grow 3.9 percent next year,
and at slightly less than the rate of inflation over the next
decade. The administration projects that inflation will be about
2.6 percent a year over the period.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming such a growth rate in so-called discretionary spending,
the administration calculated that the budget surplus outside of
Social Security over the next 10 years would total $746 billion,
considerably lower than the surplus projections likely to be
adopted by the Republican-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's approach is certain to set off a partisan
election-year clash over spending levels, tax cuts and how to
define the size of the surplus. With the Republicans in control of
both houses of Congress, Clinton's budget stands no chance of being
enacted in anything close to its current form.
</P>
<P>
   But because the president takes the first step in the annual
budget process, heget a chance to frame the debate, and the
administration's emphasis this year is on defining the size of the
pot of money available to the two parties as they push their
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is trying to take a chunk of the surplus off the table
by earmarking it up front for what administration officials said
were realistic and prudent spending increases over the next 10
years for general government operations encompassing everything
from Head Start to new fighter planes. In doing so, he is formally
abandoning the spending limits required by the 1997 balanced budget
act. Those limits have been all but ignored by both parties for the
last two years as the government has shifted from deficit into
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The administration plan would allocate much of the surplus to
shoring up Medicare's deteriorating finances and to adding
prescription drug coverage to the program. Altogether, $432 billion
out of the administration's projection of a $746 billion surplus
would go to Medicare over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The administration would also use the surplus to help pay for
giving poor children and their families better access to health
insurance, to pay for modest tax cuts and for programs like aid to
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is proposing $350 billion in tax cuts over a
decade, offset in part by $100 billion in tax increases from
closing corporate tax loopholes. Republicans are sure to seek far
larger tax cuts, as they have done in each of the previous few
years.
</P>
<P>
   To make its numbers add up, the administration is also counting
on $66 billion in revenues over the next decade from a
25-cents-a-pack cigarette tax and penalties on tobacco companies
that do not reduce teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The administration would use all of the surplus generated by
Social Security _ around $2 trillion over the next decade _ for
reducing the national debt, with a goal of eliminating the $3.6
trillion in debt held by the public by 2013.
</P>
<P>
   ``By starting with a realistic projection of the surplus and
making decisions and tradeoffs on priorities, it's possible to
accomplish a great deal and remain on the path of fiscal
discipline,'' said Jacob J. Lew, the director of the White House's
Office of Management and Budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led budget committees in the House and Senate are
only beginning to put their proposals together. But they are
expected to start with far lower spending assumptions than the
administration and far bigger surplus estimates, allowing more room
for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office projected last month that the
non-Social Security surplus over the next decade could be as little
as $838 billion using assumptions similar to those adopted by the
administration, and as much as $1.9 trillion if spending were cut
for the next few years before beginning to grow again. Republican
leaders have indicated that they will chose a number in between.
</P>
<P>
   Rehearsing a theme that they are sure to stress on Monday, when
Clinton's budget is formally unveiled and sent to Congress,
Republicans criticized the White House plan on Sunday as bloated
and developed with an eye more toward the fall election than toward
getting legislation enacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we know of this budget, it would appear that the era
of big government is back with a vengeance,'' said Robert G.
Stevenson, the spokesman for the Senate Budget Committee. ``It's
one thing to invest smartly in needed government programs. This
budget throws open the vault and says let's spend it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Holt, the spokesman for the House Budget Committee, said
that by building spending increases to the budget each year,
Clinton was proposing government by autopilot, and that his
extensive spending proposals were political in nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a laundry list of promises to groups that Al Gore
will need to get elected president,'' Holt said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Republicans said it was bad policy to assume that discretionary
spending will increase each year at around the rate of inflation.
In setting surplus projections, they generally prefer to assume a
spending freeze, saying that Congress should decide each year how
much money gets spent and which programs deserve to be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger surplus projections like those favored by Republicans
would also leave more room for big tax cuts. Republicans passed a
$792 billion, 10-year tax cut last year, and in the presidential
race, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is pressing for a 10-year tax
cut of $1.3 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month Clinton has unveiled a host of initiatives
that will be included in his budget, from an increase in the
program of tax credits for the working poor to more money for AIDS
research to an expansion of programs to enforce gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the initiatives are likely to go nowhere on Capitol
Hill. But there is some prospect of action this year on a few big
issues, including adding prescription drug coverage to Medicare.
Clinton's plan would cost $168 billion over 10 years, including $98
billion out of the budget surplus and another $70 billion from
savings within the existing Medicare system.
</P>
<P>
   While many Republicans also favor adding drug coverage to
Medicare, they would prefer a smaller program than Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
