<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MILITARY-HOUSING-ART-     02-06 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-HOUSING-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY'S NEWEST OBJECTIVE IS LIVABLE FAMILY HOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Texas, Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MEADE, Md. _ For Amanda Rowan, wife of an Army staff
sergeant, just as for Sgt. Flora Wilson, housing on this base is
the worst part of military life.
</P>
<P>
   When Rowan moved here two years ago with her husband, William,
and their baby daughter, she left behind a ``huge, huge home'' in
Monterey, Calif., for a cramped duplex here. Her husband's study is
a closet without a door, and her small living room also serves as
dining room and family room.
</P>
<P>
   When Wilson first walked into her apartment on the base, she
said, she felt cold chills down her spine because it reminded her
of the dilapidated projects of her native Baltimore. With several
buckets of paint she made the place livable. Wilson said she wanted
to remain on base, close to the military clinic where her children
are treated for their chronic asthma.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Pentagon is starting to redress the old problem
of military housing, a major reason, along with the military's
health care, that midcareer service members leave the armed forces.
The Pentagon budget that is being unveiled on Monday includes a $3
billion increase over five years for housing allowances.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Pentagon's plan, military housing would become a major
selling point for staying in the service rather than a reason for
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department is pushing ahead with a pilot project to
privatize housing here and at two other Army posts. Developers will
be awarded contracts to build new housing, rebuild the bases'
substandard units, and add community centers, landscaping, sports
facilities and whatever else it takes to remake the posts in the
mold of middle-class communities.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts are to be awarded by August, and construction is
to begin next year. If the project works, it could be a model for
privatizing housing at other bases.
</P>
<P>
   The contract for the housing at Fort Meade could amount to $2
billion, a sum normally associated with military contracts for jet
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The program is so ambitious that military housing is being
singled out by investors as a major emerging market. Moody's
Investors Service, a bond-rating company, has said that any bonds
to finance the housing projects would be eligible for an A rating,
one of the top three categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the military has a trump card over civilian
society,'' said Charles Moskos, a sociologist at Northwestern
University who studies the military. ``The military can never offer
more pay than civilian society, but they can give young families
the decent housing and good schools that their civilian
contemporaries can't afford.''
</P>
<P>
   The military is also attracting men and women who have larger
families _ having three children is common _ at earlier ages. They
need the type of help that bases are especially good at providing
while a father or a mother is away for an operation or training.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Pentagon persuaded the White House and Congress to
approve a hefty raise for military personnel, the first in more
than a decade beyond cost-of-living raises.
</P>
<P>
   This year Secretary of Defense William Cohen says he wants to
attack the housing problem, bolstering the housing allowances for
those who live off base and improving housing on the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good housing is a top priority,'' Cohen said. ``It augments
our ability to attract and retain the quality individuals America's
military needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Meade is the smallest of the three bases to be privatized
this year. The largest is Fort Hood, Texas, and the other is Fort
Lewis, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Developers of the pilot projects will be awarded 50-year leases
by the Army, and their return over that period will be from rents
from the units. The Army's cost will be in housing allowances paid
to the soldiers occupying the units, which average about $2,000 a
month each. At present, only military personnel living off the
posts are given a housing allowance, while those on base live rent
free.
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Meade, the monthly rent from soldiers comes to around
$2.1 billion over 50 years. The developer will come up with the
money for the capital investment, raising the initial construction
costs from investors.
</P>
<P>
   The developer here will have to tear down and replace 2,488
houses and apartments that were built in the 1950s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Only two kinds of family housing will be left standing: historic
houses like those where Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower and Gen. George
S. Patton lived when they trained here before World War II, and a
cluster of 256 houses that were built in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial response from the business community has been
positive,'' said Mahlon Apgar IV, the assistant secretary of the
Army for installations and environment, who is in charge of the
effort. ``But we need them more than they need us.''
</P>
<P>
   Apgar estimates that if the Army stuck to its old system of
military construction, it would take 100 years to replace the
substandard housing on these bases. The privatization plan would
also cost much less, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A former real estate developer, Apgar was recruited by the Army
two years ago to take over the project. He said he persuaded senior
Army officials to take a new approach to get developers.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than drafting minute housing specifications and requiring
1,000-page bids as it normally did, Apgar said, the Army provided
20-page brochures describing the qualifications. The developer
submitting the best offer would then work with officials and
families on the base to create the final design.
</P>
<P>
   To inform officials who Apgar said ``had no background in real
estate development whatsoever,'' he organized a trip to Columbia,
Md., one of the United States' most successful planned communities.
There, he said, Gen. John M. Keane, the vice chief of the Army, and
several other officials walked through the development with him
like soldiers walking a battlefield to understand what brought
victory to one side and defeat to the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understood,'' Apgar said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the horror stories of sharing cramped quarters with no
privacy, the waiting list of young military families trying to get
housing on base is growing. They are the families of the youngest
soldiers who have three, four or five children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine living like this?'' said Rowan, the
24-year-old mother, as she stirred rice in an electric cooker
propped on the washing machine in her crowded kitchen. ``But I
can't live anywhere else, since my husband is gone so much _ 10
months out of the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Pregnant with her second child, Rowan is surrounded by neighbors
who baby-sit for her 22-month-old daughter, Brianna, help with
shopping, and shovel the snow from her driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is the mother of four children and the wife of a civilian
truck driver who works erratic hours. She feels she had no choice
but to live on base. When she protested that her apartment was
unacceptable, she was told she could get on the waiting list for
the new houses, behind families with seven children and greater
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I said we'd stay, because we don't have enough
money to live off base,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
