<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     02-06 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OUT OF AFRICA, BUT NOT OUT OF CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ A U.S. Embassy employee held up a sign during
the Davis Cup doubles match here Saturday. It said: ``Hi Mom. Send
Diesel.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's wife, Grace Mugabe, was said to be furious over
this highly public and televised reference to the fuel shortage
that has rocked Zimbabwe. She proceeded to snub the U.S. Tennis
Association president, Judy Levering, and didn't return for the
third and last day.
</P>
<P>
   These things happen when countries mix and when crowds come out.
It also puts the presence of John McEnroe into a necessary broader
perspective. He apparently wasn't the only source of binational
irritation here this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It only seemed that way, every time a call went against the
United States and McEnroe rose from his captain's chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disgraceful,'' Wayne Black said Sunday after McEnroe's U. S.
team had claimed the first-round competition, defeating Zimbabwe,
3-2, after winning both reverse singles matches. ``They've got a
great team full of great guys. I think if they don't win the cup,
it will be largely due to McEnroe.''
</P>
<P>
   It was pointed out to Black that the American players had all
marched into the interview room at the Harare Sports Center to
proclaim their devotion to the man they had asked the USTA to give
them. Alex O'Brien called McEnroe ``the best coach in the world.''
Chris Woodruff credited McEnroe for teaching what it takes to
compete under rabid road conditions. Andre Agassi reiterated that
he had grown tired of the milquetoast mind-set, and that McEnroe,
more than anyone, had the passion to galvanize more interest in the
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lose the feeling, you're just asking for another week
on the road in brutal conditions,'' Agassi said. ``I don't need
that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Black conceded that he only had the outsider's view of McEnroe,
and there likely was more to the situation than meets the ear.
</P>
<P>
   There always has been. As a young player, McEnroe tormented
officials and opponents, but when other players jumped at the
opportunity to earn big bucks in South Africa during the apartheid
era, he simply said no.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arrival in Harare, he was charming dinner guests and
promising sneakers for the barefoot children with whom he had hit
tennis balls on hardcourts in the economically ravaged township of
Chitungwiza. Then he was infuriating the host Zimbabwe team and
sprinkling his news conferences with his special brand of colorful
rebuttals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys were giving us a hard time and then pretending like
I'm being difficult,'' he said, in summary. ``As difficult as I
supposedly was, I guarantee that those guys were giving my
teammates a tougher time.''
</P>
<P>
   When they announced McEnroe as Davis Cup captain, people should
have known they weren't getting a public-relations executive. He
could feel persecuted in a soup kitchen, and is about as subtle as
an Agassi forehand. ``Big deal,'' was his ambassadorial commentary
on the fact that the U.S. government had built one of the four
hardcourts in Chitungwiza.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe has crossed the line of reasonable comportment enough
times but on my personal Mac-o-meter, his performance here was
barely enough to make people wince, the equivalent of a sign that
said: ``Send Diesel.'' He argued calls, which in his mind comes
with the territory. When Black revealed what had set him off
against McEnroe during the doubles, veteran Mac attack chroniclers
looked around and said, ``That's it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm serving 5-6, and there was a shuffling with the balls,''
Black said. ``I thought it was a new ball. So I said, `Are these
new?' He said, `You should be so lucky.'''
</P>
<P>
   Black said he couldn't believe his eyes during the fourth game
of his match with Woodruff Sunday, when McEnroe stood up and yelled
just as Woodruff was about to hammer a forehand winner. They played
a let. ``I would go crazy if my captain did something like that,''
said Black, missing the point.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, who sheepishly apologized, was so excited he couldn't
contain himself. ``I was jumping out of my pants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hypocrites who wait for McEnroe to so much as sneeze to call
him a brat usually go skipping off to watch managers kick dirt on
umpires or hockey players slap each other around with sticks. More
than anything, McEnroe has always seemed like an athlete who got
lost as a youngster and wandered into a country club. For 20 years,
he has extolled the virtues of the Davis Cup. This being my first
competition in another country, I can better understand him. Those
of us who came to Harare, the players included, didn't sit in gas
lines, or worry about dinner. But this was a refreshing change from
the sterility of tournament tennis, of the luxury-suite-driven
sports industry in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have the experience to get a lot out of it,''
Agassi said when asked what Pete Sampras had missed by pulling out.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Sampras did everyone a favor. It gave Zimbabwe a
chance. It gave Woodruff a chance. It gave McEnroe a cause. He and
his players left here Sunday night feeling like Duke surviving in
the first round of March Madness. They did it without holding up a
sign that said: ``Send Pete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
