u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT &LR;      02-06 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS CAPTURE WHAT REMAINS OF GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Nearly five months after he dispatched Russian forces
to Chechnya, Acting President Vladimir V. Putin announced Sunday
that the Russian military had captured its capital, Grozny, and
that the Russian tricolor was flying over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A short time ago, the last stronghold of the terrorists'
resistance was taken: the Zavodsky district of the city,'' Putin
told the ORT television network. ``So we can say that the operation
for the freeing of Grozny has ended.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the Kremlin's celebration, that does not signal
an end to the war.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen militants suffered heavy losses when they blundered
into a Russian minefield and ambush after fleeing the city last
week. But hundreds appear to have escaped and are trying to make
their way to the Chechen highlands in the south, where as many as
7,000 more of their fighters are believed to be operating.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Moscow made the seizure of Grozny a political
requirement. Grozny was the scene of some of the Russian military's
most humiliating defeats during the earlier war in the secessionist
southern region, from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In their quest to even the score, Russian generals brushed aside
suggestions that they limit themselves to a quarantine of Chechnya.
Capturing the capital was also important to Putin, who is facing a
presidential election on March 26 and whose popularity has risen,
apparently because of popular support for the war.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the city had its costs, though. Since Russian forces
entered Chechnya on Oct. 1, more than 1,000 soldiers have been
killed and almost 3,400 wounded. Many of those casualties occurred
during two hard-fought attempts to storm the city.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from Grozny say many civilians have also been killed by
Russian rockets, artillery and bombs. And Human Rights Watch, the
international human rights organization, says it has documented 22
cases in which civilians were killed by vengeful Russian troops
after they began to re-occupy Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television reports show the city in ruins. So many
buildings were destroyed in the bombardment that the Russian
military has found it difficult to find an adequate office for the
city's new commandant.
</P>
<P>
   With the cost of rebuilding the city estimated at more than $1
billion, Russian officials have suggested that Grozny will probably
never be restored, leaving it as a symbol of retribution, not
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   With most Western correspondents blocked from reporting from
Chechnya, it is difficult to verify the Russian account of the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Russian account, a Russian counterintelligence
officer approached rebel field commanders and offered to arrange
the militants' escape through the nearby settlement of Alkhan-Kala
for a $100,000 bribe. The militants were said to have trusted him
because he had previously arranged the exchange of Russian and
rebel bodies.
</P>
<P>
   To convince the rebels that they could find a gap through the
Russian lines, small groups of militants were allowed to escape in
recent weeks, Col. Gen. Viktor G. Kazantsev, the commander of
Russian forces in the north Caucasus, said in a recent interview
with ORT.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military also broadcast fake radio reports
suggesting that its troops were moving away from the area, the
newspaper Kommersant reported. But when the main rebel force
decided to make its escape, it found the path to Alkhan-Kala mined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laid a dense field of mines, because we knew they would try
to go out on the night of Feb. 1,'' said Kazantsev, who asserted
that the Russian military had informers among the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   As the militants raced through the minefield and a nearby
pathway to the village, Russian troops fired mortars while
helicopters blasted the rebels from overhead. Kazantsev asserted
that as many as 500 rebels were killed.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to confirm that account, and Russian television
has not shown large numbers of corpses. The militants say they had
serious losses, including several top commanders who led the
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Russian television broadcast a film showing
doctors amputating the right foot of Shamil Basayev, the Chechen
warlord. The rebels apparently allowed the gruesome film to be made
to demonstrate that their leader was wounded but still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not even the Russians insist that this is the end of the
fight. Gen. Valery Manilov of the Russian general staff said 6,000
to 7,000 militants were in the Argun and Vedeno gorges of the
Caucasus mountains in southern Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen field commanders have vowed to take the war to the
Russian heartland, a rebel television broadcast said.
</P>
<P>
   But the attacks, they said, ``will not do any harm to the
Russian people or to Russian officials whose hands are not stained
with the Chechen blood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
