<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-BARKLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S TAKES A DAY OFF, BUT ONLY FROM PRACTICING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Saturday St. John's earned a 59-58 victory over
Boston College without Erick Barkley, who had been declared
ineligible by St. John's after the NCAA said the star guard had
violated an NCAA rule. After the game, in a fiery news conference,
the school's athletic officials expressed their frustration with
the NCAA and now they wait for college sports' governing board to
rule whether Barkley will play Tuesday when the Red Storm plays
Providence.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's coach Mike Jarvis gave his team off Sunday and
remained optimistic that Barkley would return to the lineup. He
reiterated the university's belief that Barkley had done nothing
wrong and was unfairly singled out with an interpretation of a
regulation governing benefits for students who are athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis also said that he had no regrets about harshly
criticizing the NCAA, comparing it to the Gestapo and calling for
it to be abolished, adding that he felt ``as if someone had come
into my house and raped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis said by phone Sunday, ``This is still America, isn't
it?''.
</P>
<P>
   According to a university official and an associate of another
university official, the infraction the NCAA cited was of bylaw
12.1.1.1.6, which is labeled, ``Preferential Treatment, Benefits or
Services.'' It bars ``preferential treatment, benefits or services
because of the individual's athletics reputation or skill or
pay-back potential as a professional athlete, unless such
treatment, benefits or services are specifically permitted under
NCAA legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The alleged infraction involves a vehicle Barkley is driving;
though Barkley usually drives a late-model Jeep Cherokee, he
recently traded with a family friend to drive an older but bigger
Ford Explorer, according to the official and the associate. They
said the unidentified friend has known Barkley since he was a child
_ long before he showed talent as a professional basketball
prospect. They also said no money had changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, St. John's athletic director Ed Manetta Jr. made it
clear that the university believed it had made a strong case
defending Barkley and said he was assured by the NCAA that a ruling
would be made Monday. In fact, Manetta said he believed Barkley's
suspension would last only until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that there is absolutely no reason why he
shouldn't be playing as soon as possible for St. John's
University,'' Manetta said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He was unavailable for comment on Sunday, as was Barkley. Jarvis
said the sophomore was handling the negative attention well but was
eager to have the situation behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting an education in life that I expect will be
valuable in the wonderful and productive career he has in front of
him,'' Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   Manetta and Jarvis, citing the NCAA restrictions, have not
disclosed the nature or what specific regulation Barkley has
allegedly violated.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA, as policy, does not confirm or deny whether its
enforcement division is conducting an investigation. Wally Renfro,
the NCAA spokesman, was not available for comment Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall in a similar case, the NCAA ruled that Jake Voskuhl of
Connecticut did not violate the improper benefits rule when he
borrowed a friend's car to drive to classes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2019EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8417 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-R-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-06 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McENROE AND AMERICANS SAVE THEIR BEST FOR LAST  
 (REPEATING for all needing.)  
(rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ The American no one expected to faint almost
did, and the one whom many believed would shrink stood tall.
</P>
<P>
   More predictably, the U.S. Davis Cup captain irritated the
umpire and infuriated his opponents, but he ultimately landed on
his feet, instead of his hard head.
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe's maiden Davis Cup team achieved what Arthur Ashe's
first team did 19 years ago, when a wild-haired and stormy tempered
guy named McEnroe won the fifth match against Mexico's Raul Ramirez
in Carlsbad, Calif., and rallied the United States to a first-round
victory from a 2-1 deficit. This setting was, well, different, and
the end-game hero was a 27-year-old journeyman, not a budding
legend.
</P>
<P>
   As far as a relieved and subsequently jubilant McEnroe was
concerned, Chris Woodruff was himself, Jimmy Connors and Pete
Sampras all rolled into one Sunday at the Harare Sports Arena. With
a barrage of winners and powerful first serves, he battered Wayne
Black to clinch a 3-2 victory over gritty Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff's 6-3, 6-7 (2), 6-2, 6-4 mastery of Black came with one
rather important member of McEnroe's team back at the hotel, under
a doctor's care. In the process of trying to close out Byron Black
in straight sets, Andre Agassi was overcome by cramps and nausea.
He held on in a third-set tiebreaker, vomiting behind the baseline
just before and into a basket right after his 6-2, 6-3, 7-6 (4)
decision over the elder Black brother.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi repaired to his bed for treatment by George Fareed, a
member of the team's medical staff, and watched on television as
Woodruff emerged from the cocoon, in which he was so tightly
wrapped Friday during a straight-set surrender to Byron Black.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has so much heart and character,'' said McEnroe, grateful
that Agassi showed up here at all after winning the Australian Open
and being on the road since Dec. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a great example for these guys,'' McEnroe said.
McEnroe suddenly slipped into his television announcer's skin and,
extending his arm toward Woodruff, said, ``How about a round of
applause for this guy?''
</P>
<P>
   There might have been a temptation to respond with a favorite
expression of McEnroe's _ big deal. Wayne Black, in the world of
singular achievement, is ranked in the mid-100s. Yet, under these
extreme conditions, in a cacophony of noise and a cauldron of heat,
the day pretty much began with this economically roiled nation of
13 million believing that the fifth-match victory was all but
assured.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff had looked stiff and even scared against Byron Black.
He had little control of his strokes on the fast hardcourt, in the
thin nearly mile-high air. The most vociferous local fans from the
Mufakose Supporters Club thus had Zimbabwe's national sports anthem
_ ``Yave Nyoma Yekugocha'' (This meat is ready for roasting) ready
and rehearsed, in the indigenous Shona tongue.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a sanctioned team psychologist, however,
Woodruff had received counseling and support from a variety of
sources, including McEnroe, his teammates and a couple of Davis Cup
veterans from back home.
</P>
<P>
   There was, on Saturday, an e-mail from Jim Courier wishing him
luck, and then a telephone chat with Todd Martin, whose viral
infection _ along with Sampras' injury _ was the reason the
6-foot-4-inch Tennessean found himself in this delicate situation
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you have any fun Friday?'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a bit of fun,'' Woodruff said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin reminded Woodruff that, contrary to what it felt like on
the court, the Wayne Black showdown was going to be only another
tennis match against a player he was better than. And when Woodruff
took the court Sunday, what he soon began to realize was that the
first match, if nothing else, had prepared him for the second. He
was comfortable with the environment, familiar with the chanting
and the conga drum. He was more than ready for Jojo the clown.
</P>
<P>
   He also quickly demonstrated he had more than enough weaponry,
too much power, for the quick, resilient but undersized (at 5-7)
Black.
</P>
<P>
   All Woodruff had to do was measure his ground strokes, apply
enough topspin to keep them from flying and generate a good
percentage of first serves. That he did, dominating the first set
and going up an early break in the second, before Black began to
run everything down, send it back and wait for the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Black broke back in the fifth game, won the tiebreaker, and
broke again for 2-0 in the third set. This was about the time,
Woodruff said, he began to feel the humidity, and had trouble
taking air into his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Never has this been a problem for McEnroe, who laced into his
player, or as Woodruff put it, ``got into my kitchen.'' Coincidence
or not, Woodruff was soon whipping up a souffle of winners that
would carry him to a two-sets-to-one lead, up a break in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff seized control of the match in the fifth game, breaking
again with two heavy forehands. Including the last two points of
that game, he went on a Sampras-like roll, winning 22 of 25 points
and eight straight games.
</P>
<P>
   He noticed that Black was chewing tablets during changeovers.
Black later said he was ``maybe a step slow,'' at least. He had
lost in straight sets to Agassi Friday, and won the five-set
doubles Saturday with Kevin Ullyet. Shumba, his Shona nickname
paying tribute to his ``heart of a lion,'' was one tired cat.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff, who had 73 winners to Black's 23, finished him off
with his 15th ace, down the middle. He tossed his racquet so high
it crashed against the overhead light structure. McEnroe rushed the
court, into his arms. ``Eighty four,'' McEnroe would say when asked
when the last felt this good _ the year of his last Grand Slam
title.
</P>
<P>
   Unimpressed, Black would later say that McEnroe's match behavior
was ``disgraceful,'' and that the umpire, Bruno Rebeuh, should have
tossed him for excessive whining.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Americans were dancing in Harare and on their
way to the second round, against the Czech Republic in April.
Agassi, by evening, was feeling better and saying, by phone, that
he was ``so proud.'' And all things considered, it didn't turn so
badly for Zimbabwe either.
</P>
<P>
   Its next opponent in the relegation round is none other than Old
Mother England. As they say here, Yave Nyoma Yekugocha.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
