<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8418 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-HILLARY-SENATE07-COX     02-06 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SENATE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First lady makes case for U.S. Senate post
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The words were nearly as inevitable as the
waiting had felt interminable, and still, Hillary Clinton pulled
off something memorable here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was slightly past 4 p.m. when Clinton formally announced her
candidacy for the U.S. Senate from New York, thereby becoming the
first first lady ever to run for national office _ let alone do it
with her husband still in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The carefully orchestrated event here on a state university
campus featured President Clinton uncharacteristically relegated to
the supporting cast and finally ended seven months of
all-but-official campaigning by a first lady who'd conducted
statewide ``listening tours,'' bought a house in nearby Chappaqua,
and at one point even brought the press together simply to announce
her intention of announcing later.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fact that all of the nearly 2,000 people present knew
what she was going to say did little to dilute the drama of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   With a power lineup of New York Democrats to publicly mark her
as one of their own, a biographical video produced by a Hollywood
producer friend and an audience that ranged from Hispanic
supporters shouting ``Si! Si! Hillary!'' to Linda Tripp confidant
Lucianne Goldberg, Clinton probably knew she couldn't get away with
merely confirming that she was running.
</P>
<P>
   She also had to say why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people are asking why I'm doing this here, and
now,'' Clinton said early in a 27-minute speech delivered from a
temporary stage erected in the Purchase College gymnasium. ``That's
a fair question. Here's my answer _ and I hope you'll put me to
work for you. I may be new to the neighborhood. But I'm not new to
your concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, much of her speech _ and indeed the entire program _
seemed designed to address two common criticisms of candidate
Clinton: that unlike her presumed Republican opponent, New York
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, she is too new to the state to really
understand it, and too unwilling to get specific about what she
would do if elected.
</P>
<P>
   At least one person who lined up two hours early on the snowy
Purchase campus to get a good seat in the bleachers said she knew
little about Clinton beyond her work in Washington as first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it was history and I should be here,'' said Nicole
Silvers, 22, a Purchase student who got a ticket through a campus
lottery and hadn't yet decided who to vote for. ``I'm really
curious to see what she has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton said, with a greater degree of specificity than she
had before, was that she was for stricter gun control, including
licensing all new handgun owners; she wanted to improve public
school education by hooking all classrooms up to the Internet, and
by fighting against school vouchers; and that she would continue to
fight for a Patient's Bill of Rights, and to modernize Medicare
with new prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   She also played to the audience in her new home state _ those
gathered in the gym, or watching the live coverage on C-SPAN and at
500 ``house parties'' organized statewide by her campaign.
Recalling a 1998 bus tour of historic sites she took in her role as
first lady, she said she realized then that New York was ``more
than just a great state.
</P>
<P>
   ``To people all over the world, it represents the best of
America, the golden door, the gateway to tomorrow,'' Clinton said.
``New York deserves a future worthy of its past.''
</P>
<P>
   For her kind words, Clinton got a visible show of support from
New York Democrats. The would-be senator was escorted onstage by
current U.S. Sens. Charles Schumer and the retiring Daniel Patrick
Monynihan. Walking several steps behind were President Clinton, who
made no public remarks, his mother-in-law Dorothy Rodham and first
daughter Chelsea Clinton. Seated among the dignitaries in folding
chairs on the floor were 12 members of the New York congressional
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   One, U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel (D-N.Y.), had already taken to the
stage to defend Clinton, whom Giuliani had depicted as an arriviste
on several of the Sunday morning talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have people who are jobless, helpless and homeless,
you don't put 'em in jail, you give 'em hope,'' Rangel said in a
none-too-veiled reference to Giuliani's recent plan to jail
homeless people who won't work. ``When you have the best person for
the job, you don't ask where they come from, you ask `Are you
available?!''' Goldberg, who said she attended to gather material
for her weekly radio talk show, pronounced herself unimpressed
afterward. She seemed to be in the distinct minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' audience member Roger Kent said afterward. ``It's clear
from this she's going to work so hard. She's going to make
history.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she already had.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
