<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8421 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEMS-CAMPAIGN-840(2TA     02-06 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CAMPAIGN-840(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BRADLEY, IT'S MUST-WIN TIME 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Fla., Calif., Wash. N.J., N.Y., N.H., Iowa, Mo., Ohio,
Ga.)  (jw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Bradley said flatly Sunday that he must win
primaries in several states on the next big day of voting, March 7.
And to do so, he said, he must sell his agenda more powerfully to
hard-core Democrats who streamed to Vice President Al Gore in the
Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he expressed optimism about his prospects for the
presidential nomination, Bradley seemed to concede what many
prominent Democrats, including his own supporters, said in
interviews. That is, that the race will be effectively over in four
weeks if he does not emerge with significant victories.
</P>
<P>
   These Democrats said that although Bradley had the money to
match Gore in future contests, his pair of losses made him a
significantly less potent contender than Gore. And, they said, that
despite his close second-place finish to Gore in New Hampshire, a
less than decisive victory for the vice president, Bradley faces a
considerable struggle to muster sufficient support to threaten the
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats said Sen. John McCain's surge after his
triumph over Gov. George W. Bush in New Hampshire has also
complicated Bradley's game plan. While Gore is drawing far more
loyal Democrats than Bradley, McCain is taking a far larger share
of independents, who in some states can vote in the primary of
their choice, from Bradley _ and is even intriguing some Democrats
who might have backed Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bradley acknowledged, the contests on March 7 in
California, New York, Missouri, Ohio, Georgia and several other
delegate-rich states present a political imperative on a day when
roughly a third of the convention delegates will be selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to take off on March 7,'' he said on the NBC News
program, ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I believe that the key thing is to win a number of
those races. And I believe that that's what I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that voters will see the differences between him and
Gore on health care, gun control and other issues, he said, ``I
think I will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also said he needed to step up his appeals to loyal
Democrats and portray himself as a fighter _ something Gore has
done for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to communicate better to the Democratic base,'' he
said. ``If you take a look at what I'm proposing, if you take a
look at access to quality affordable health care, I mean,
African-Americans, 30 percent, don't have health insurance; Latino
Americans, about 24 percent, don't have health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of Bradley's supporters say his challenge is far deeper
than retooling his massage. Simply put, the fear they articulated
is this: He peaked too soon. For weeks, Bradley, a former senator
from New Jersey, outpaced Gore in polls in New Hampshire, and his
face was emblazoned on magazine covers. But now at a more crucial
time, when actual voting has begun, it is McCain who is on the
covers of Time, Newsweek and U.S. News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley needs a positive galvanizing moment like McCain had in
New Hampshire,'' Robert Reich, a former labor secretary in the
Clinton administration who supports Bradley, said in an interview
Sunday. ``Bradley is better positioned than McCain in terms of
money and people on the ground. But he's not nearly as well
positioned in terms of a galvanizing event. Insurgent movements
have to be built around surges; that's the only thing they have.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that if McCain continues to draw such immense
national publicity _ overshadowing not only Bradley but the entire
Democratic contest _ it will be even more difficult for Bradley to
say or do anything to change the current dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Gore camp is so flush with confidence that on
Sunday he took his first day off from the campaign trail this year.
His advisers said they had turned to a strategy to pile up enough
convention delegates to bury Bradley by mid-March. Had Bradley won
New Hampshire, Gore aides said, they would now have embarked on a
more narrow calculus of pumping greater resources into California
and southern states where they thought they had the best chances to
halt his insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a significant shift in the campaign once you've
proven you're capable of winning,'' said one senior Gore aide. ``It
gives you the luxury of assembling enough delegates to put this
thing away as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark A. Siegel, a Democratic authority on delegates who is
neutral in the race, said that since Bradley was from New Jersey he
needed to demonstrate on March 7 that he had ``some real stuff
outside of the Northeast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley could do very very well in the Northeast,'' Siegel
added, ``and in New York he has a home-state advantage.'' Beyond
that, he said, ``the best places for him are California and
Washington state.''
</P>
<P>
   Aggravating Bradley's challenge are polls showing that one of
his central selling points has vanished: that he would be a tougher
rival for Republicans in November. A battery of fresh polls now
show that Bradley would be no more daunting for Republicans than
Gore.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As part of his drive to better reach the party's base, Bradley
on Monday plans to travel to Tampa, Fla., for a major speech on
race. And Sunday, he struck a combative tone when he invoked McCain
to argue that the senator might greatly scar Gore by bashing him
for his fund-raising conduct in the 1996 campaign, including Gore's
appearance at a Buddhist temple near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has to explain more thoroughly than he has what was
happening at the Buddhist temple, for example,'' Bradley said in
the NBC interview. ``I mean, if he didn't know it was a
fund-raiser, then he was spectacularly naive. If he did know it was
a fund-raiser, then he really did something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Murphy, a Democratic strategist who is neutral, said
turning up the attacks might not be enough. ``The challenge for
Bradley is to communicate a rationale for denying the nomination to
Gore,'' he said. ``I don't think you can accomplish that with just
a bitter personal battle. Now, it's put up or shut up for
Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, prominent Democrats are beginning to lean on Bradley to
turn things around on March 7, or step aside. Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., who has not endorsed either candidate, said
Sunday that he wanted his party's contest to ``come to a conclusion
relatively soon'' to avoid strains among Democrats. But speaking on
the CBS News program ``Face the Nation,'' he said, ``Democrats at
the moment feel united, and at the moment there has not been a
compelling interest to motivate Democratic primary voters to defeat
Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   After enduring months of discord between Gore and Bradley, many
Democrats are savoring the Republicans' unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would revel be too strong a word?'' asked one top Gore aide.
</P>
<P>
   But Reich warned Democrats not to be too gleeful. McCain, he
said, would be more formidable than Bush in a general election.
``I'm far more worried about McCain,'' he said. ``McCain is
capturing the imagination of the American public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
