<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HEZBOLLAH-ART-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI SOLDIER KILLED IN LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ An Israeli soldier was killed and seven were wounded
Sunday in southern Lebanon in the latest of a series of deadly
guerrilla attacks that have intensified pressure on Prime Minister
Ehud Barak to mount a significant retaliatory strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, took
responsibility for the attack, in which the soldiers were attacked
with a bomb, mortar rounds and rockets near an Israeli position
several hundred yards inside Lebanon. The guerrillas are fighting
to oust Israel from a nine-mile-wide zone in southern Lebanon that
the Israelis have maintained as a buffer strip to prevent attacks
across their northern border.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's death brought to five the number of Israeli soldiers
killed in southern Lebanon in the last two weeks, posing an urgent
problem for Barak, who has so far favored restraint in the face of
rising losses.
</P>
<P>
   He is eager to resume peace talks with Syria, which were
suspended last month, and seems reluctant to unleash a large-scale
military strike that could hurt chances of returning to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a growing clamor in the army and the news media and
among ordinary Israelis for a far-ranging response to what many
here perceive as an escalation in Hezbollah attacks. Graphic
television images broadcast Sunday night showing bloodied soldiers
with shattered limbs being taken on stretchers to helicopters
heightened the alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that sentiment, Barak warned Sunday that Israel
would strike back. But he avoided pointing a finger at Syria,
which, as the main power broker in Lebanon, is believed to wield
considerable influence over Hezbollah. ``We will continue to hit
those who hit us, and Hezbollah will pay a heavy price for any
attack on Israeli soldiers,'' the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, ``Eye contact must be maintained with
the overall goal of achieving agreements that will ensure a secure
future for Israel. We shall carry out this mission, not according
to the mood of the moment, not according to the pain and biting of
the lips when we have casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's attack, a bomb went off near a group of soldiers who
were heading for an outpost not far from the Israeli-Lebanese
border, and when a rescue team was dispatched to the scene, the
troops came under mortar and rocket fire. 1st Sgt. Yedidia Gefen,
20, was killed, and seven soldiers were wounded, four seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The attack followed a failed Israeli attempt on Friday to
assassinate Ibrahim Aqil, Hezbollah's top military commander in
southern Lebanon. Israeli helicopters fired rockets at Aqil's car,
but he managed to escape with slight injuries. Five civilians were
also slightly wounded, including an infant. That attack was in
retaliation for the killing of the second-in-command of the
Israeli-backed militia in southern Lebanon a week ago in a
Hezbollah bombing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As Barak struggled to chart a course of military action in
Lebanon that would not harm prospects for further negotiations with
Syria, he tried to shore up his diplomatic flank with a short visit
to Jordan and a meeting with King Abdullah. The king reportedly
urged Barak to remove obstacles blocking Israel's separate talks
with the Palestinians, which have bogged down in a dispute over the
area for a further Israeli troop withdrawal on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians called off another round of negotiations with
Israel on Sunday on a framework agreement for a permanent peace, a
week before a goal of Feb. 13 for the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have been at an impasse since Thursday, when at a
meeting between Barak and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
the Israelis objected to handing over some West Bank villages near
East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians claim as their future
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Barak acknowledged that the Feb. 13 date was unlikely to be met,
saying Sunday that ``it cannot always work according to the exact
date.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, for his part, went to Cairo, Egypt, for a meeting with
President Hosni Mubarak, and accused Barak of failing to carry out
signed accords while expanding Jewish settlements more than his
rightist predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's foreign minister, David Levy, also arrived in Cairo for
discussions with the Egyptian foreign minister, Amr Moussa; the
Palestinian planning chief, Nabil Shaath; and the Jordanian foreign
minister, Abdallah al-Khatib, on the future of Palestinians
displaced by the Arab-Israeli war of 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Levy declared that there ``is no crisis'' in the talks with the
Palestinians. ``There are debates,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
