NYT-02-06-00 2036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8424 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-NHL-ALLSTAR07-COX     02-06 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-ALLSTAR07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bures bury North Americans
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Two days earlier, he and a few other members of the
NHL's current elite were driven to a frozen lake on the outskirts
of this city to tape a television commercial. But when Pavel Bure
stared across the lake at Wayne Gretzky, Gordie Howe and Mario
Lemieux, it seemed like more than a spot for a pre-game show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant a lot to be around those guys,'' Bure said Sunday.
``I felt like a part of hockey history. It wasn't just a
commercial. It was something bigger that would make history. It was
like changing generations.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no overstatement. Bure's performance in the 50th All-Star
Game on Sunday at the Air Canada Centre reaffirmed two things about
the NHL's current state: Europe is turning out more elite players
than Canada or the U.S., and Bure has few peers. The fleet Florida
Panthers' winger scored three goals and added an assist to lead the
World team over North America, 9-4, before 19,300 attendees, who
clearly weren't thrilled with Canadians taking a beating in their
home sport.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the absence of the league's best goalie (Dominik Hasek)
and best all-around player (Peter Forsberg), the World team carried
enough top athletes to slam three North American goalies _ Curtis
Joseph, Martin Brodeur and Mike Richter _ for nine goals and 48
shots. This follows European dominance in the Winter Olympics, the
World Championships and even the World Juniors.
</P>
<P>
   Bure, who has 37 goals and 61 points in 44 games for Florida,
seemingly kicked his game to an ever higher level Sunday. One
reason: The 28-year-old Russian played on a line with his younger
brother, Valeri, of the Calgary Flames. The two had not played on
the same team since the 1998 Olympics and hadn't skated on the same
line since 1990 for the Red Army team in Russia. Valeri Bure
assisted on two of his brother's goals and nearly set him up for a
fourth in the third period on a two-on-one, but Pavel couldn't get
off a good shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the second period, I told him that if we have a
two-on-one, go to the off post, I will give you a pass, and shoot
it right away,'' Pavel Bure said. ``But he tried to get me the
fourth goal and gave it back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he didn't shoot, Valeri Bure said, ``The younger
brother never listens to the older one.''
</P>
<P>
   The only happier member of the Bure family Sunday was their
mother, Tatiana, who traveled from Moscow this week. Afterward, she
could be seen clutching Pavel's MVP Trophy. No word if she's also
going to get the MVP winner's truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a special night because she was here,'' Pavel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bures took over the game in the second period, after the
World had taken a 3-2 lead. Just 33 seconds into the period, Valeri
left a drop pass in the left circle for Pavel, who slapped a
15-footer past Brodeur. Eight minutes later, Valeri fed Pavel in
the right circle for another blast to make it 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   The North America team rallied with goals by Tony Amonte to make
it 5-4. But Pavol Demietra increased the World lead to 6-4 at 8:52
of the third, and just 39 seconds later, Pavel buried a backhander
past Mike Richter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an electrifying player,'' Valeri said of his brother.
``He brings fans out of their seats and sometimes I found myself
watching him and I do a lot of standing. It's easy to play with
him. When you give him the puck, 99 percent of the time it's a
goal. He doesn't make many mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   World coach Scotty Bowman of the Detroit Red Wings had only one
regret Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only had him for one game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
