<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-WARRIORS-NYT     02-06 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WARRIORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITTLES RESPONDS TO CRITICISM WITH 21 POINTS AS NETS DOWN
WARRIORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There was no telling how Kerry Kittles
would respond to the disparaging comments his coach made about him
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Would the player whose tentativeness has frustrated the New
Jersey Nets' officials throughout his four-year professional career
become even more diffident after being criticized for his lack of
assertiveness?
</P>
<P>
   Or would the harsh words ignite his pride and propel him toward
the kind of stalwart performance that the Nets were counting on
when they signed him to a six-year, $49 million contract extension
last season?
</P>
<P>
   With a six-game losing streak quickly sucking the relevance out
of this season, the Nets were desperately hoping that Kittles would
react like a champion Sunday in their game against the Golden State
Warriors, bringing not only the skill that can make him such a
dangerous player but also the aggressiveness, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles answered the challenge admirably by sinking 3-pointers,
driving rigorously to the basket and craftily defending both his
man and the passing lanes. In his finest game since Jan. 13,
Kittles recorded 21 points, four assists, four steals and three
rebounds to key the Nets' 110-90 victory before 14,336 fans at
Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   In the decisive third quarter, in which the Nets turned a 54-51
halftime lead into an 85-75 advantage, Kittles hit three 3-pointers
in scoring 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Don Casey, who Saturday had chastised Kittles to reporters
for not being assertive, was so pleased that he played Kittles the
entire fourth quarter, and the rangy shooting guard defied his
recent custom of disappearing late in games by scoring five more
points and making a steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into the game, I just really, really wanted to be
focused on trying to be active and all over the court,'' said
Kittles, who had averaged only 11 points over the previous 10
games. ``I just told myself no matter how many shots you make, no
matter how many times your man scores or whatever, just try to run
all over the court and be as active as you can. And that's what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Kittles' fine performance notwithstanding, the Nets (18-29) won
for only the third time in 12 games because of the unforeseen
excellence of several other players.
</P>
<P>
   Personal bests were in vogue Sunday. Kendall Gill, who hit nine
of 15 shots and turned a miss by Jim McIlvaine into a Vince
Carter-type dunk in the third quarter, led the Nets with a
season-high 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Newman, the reliable reserve, buried three of four
3-pointers in scoring 23 points. And McIlvaine, the 7-foot-1-inch
center, played the game of his professional life, notching career
highs in rebounds (16) and minutes (38) and tying a season high in
points (eight) and blocks (five).
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked McIlvaine what he ate, what he put in his body, how
much he slept, because whatever he did, he needs to do it every
night,'' said Keith Van Horn, who scored 13 points and grabbed 11
rebounds. ``It was a tremendous effort.''
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine's looming presence inside was both unusual and
commanding. Because of his propensity for committing fouls _ he
averages one every 4.4 minutes played _ he averages about 14
minutes a game. His extended play Sunday enabled him to establish
himself as a defensive force in the paint and powered a Nets
defense that held the Warriors to 37.6 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I didn't get into foul trouble more often,'' McIlvaine
said. ``I basically went out and did what Jamie Feick does on a
regular basis: Get a lot of boards and help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their 10-point lead, the Nets and everyone else knew
this game was far from settled. On Friday, the Nets had led the
Boston Celtics by 17 points late in the third quarter before being
outscored, 30-13, in the fourth quarter of their loss. So Sunday
Newman and Gill continually warned their teammates against letting
up.
</P>
<P>
   Newman then added action to his words by opening the fourth
quarter with a 3-pointer that Van Horn followed with a tip-in.
Kittles made a steal, and Stephon Marbury (15 points, 11 assists)
passed to Newman for a driving dunk. Newman made another steal.
Marbury sank a jump shot, and then Newman hit one of two free
throws to complete a 10-0 run that put the Nets ahead by 20 points
with seven minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   While his teammates scored, McIlvaine handled things
defensively, blocking four shots in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   ``McIlvaine's presence was huge,'' Casey said.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was as well. While the Warriors, who were led by
Antawn Jamison with 25 points, have only a 12-33 record, they
entered the matchup on a four-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Having returned to the victory column, the Nets are pointing
toward Tuesday's rematch with the Celtics in the Meadowlands. The
Nets are hoping that Kittles and McIlvaine can have repeat
performances.
</P>
</TEXT>
