<HEADER>
A8434 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MJUICE-MP3-SFCHRON &LR;      02-06 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MJUICE-MP3-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 BY BENNY EVANGELISTA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 S.F.'s Mjuice.com Signs Agreement To Add MP3 Plug-In
to  RealJukebox  c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mjuice.com Inc. has struck a deal that will allow the San Francisco
Internet music company to reach the 23 million users of the popular
RealJukebox audio software.
<P>
   Starting today, RealNetworks Inc. will offer Mjuice's software,
which encodes MP3-formatted songs in a way that protects against
illegal copying of music, as a free plug-in for its RealJukebox
program.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Mjuice is the latest in a series of deals by
Seattle's RealNetworks to make RealJukebox as compatible as
possible for people who download music from the Internet or are
using their computers as stereo components.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks is trying to fend off a strong attack by Microsoft,
which wants to make its Windows Media Player the dominant Web
multimedia program.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks has added other secured-audio formats like Liquid
Tracks, from Redwood City's Liquid Audio Inc., and IBM's Electronic
Music Management System.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about the people who are now building digital
music collections,'' said Dave Richards, RealNetworks vice
president for consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   Mjuice, formerly known as Audio Explosion, is a year-old startup
that offers about 30,000 songs encoded in its secure MP3 format.
Most of the songs are by little-known artists, but Mjuice does have
a selection of promotional tracks from major labels like BMG
Entertainment and Sony Music.
</P>
<P>
   A promotional release of the song ``Anything'' by San Francisco
band Third Eye Blind during two weeks in November generated 50,000
downloads, said Mjuice Vice President Andrew de Vries. Mjuice will
offer promotional songs today from Geffen Records' artist Beck and
RCA Records' Foo Fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with RealNetworks further extends the visibility
of Mjuice, a small Potrero Hill company with just 30 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The company cut a similar plug-in deal last year with Nullsoft
Inc., the makers of WinAmp, a software program used by an estimated
10 million MP3-music fans. WinAmp is now owned by America Online,
which will push Internet music sales when it completes mergers with
Time-Warner and EMI Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2047EST &QL; 
