r s BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN     02-06 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC NEEDS FIVE MORE WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As if USC needed further motivation before playing
its crosstown rival, Wednesday's meeting with UCLA could be
critical for the Trojans' NCAA hopes.
</P>
<P>
   USC (13-8, 6-3) needs at least five more victories to reach the
magical number of 18, and that means they must win one more road
game, assuming they sweep their four remaining home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a big game,'' USC forward David Bluthenthal
said. ``They do have an advantage playing at Pauley Pavilion, but
we can't let that get to us. We have to come out with energy. We
know we have to win at least five more games.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Brian Scalabrine tried to downplay placing too much
significance on any one game affecting the Trojans' postseason
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, but we can't change the way we look at things,''
Scalabrine said. ``I don't even look at the tournament right now. I
don't see us as if we're down, and can't make it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Deceiving stat: USC has held its past four opponents to under 70
points, but the Trojans are 1-3 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Another mark that didn't translate into a victory was the
Trojans' seven turnovers against Stanford, their lowest mark of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Recruit watch: Two recruits in attendance for the Stanford game
were the Laguna Beach High duo of 6-foot-6 forward Travis Hanour
and 6-9 forward Chris Manker.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby went to watch the pair play Wednesday
night, and assistant coach Silvey Dominguez attended Friday's game.
Coaches from Arizona and San Diego State also showed up for
Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Long weekend: Forward David Bluthenthal struggled against Cal
and Stanford, making only 5 of 19 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was more of what I did to myself than anything they
did to me,'' Bluthenthal said. ``I rushed shots, I got myself in
foul trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bluthenthal also admitted he was bothered by Stanford's size
advantage inside, with 6-foot-10 Jarron Collins and 6-foot-11 Jason
Collins often guarding him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact I was trying to post-up a 7-footer is harder than a
6-5 guy,'' Bluthenthal said. ``Playing against (Arizona forward)
Luke Walton is a lot different than these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Another record: Guard Jeff Trepagnier has already set USC's
single-season record for most steals, and point guard Brandon
Granville is closing in on the single-season mark for assists.
Granville moved past Robert Pack into second place Saturday with
170 assists, and is now seven short of breaking Larry Friend's
record set in 1984-85.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the game plan: Bibby was upset after the loss to
Stanford that the Trojans didn't work more on his pregame strategy
of getting the ball inside against the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we worked hard enough to get the ball inside,''
Bibby said. ``We wanted to get the ball inside and get their big
guys in foul trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
