u i BC-AFGHAN-HIJACKING-NYT &LR;      02-06 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-HIJACKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIJACKED AFGHAN AIRLINER STOPS IN MOSCOW, ENTERS BRITISH AIRSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Will be updated.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A hijacked Afghan airliner left Moscow early Sunday
morning after it was seized by a group of armed men in Afghanistan
and taken on an odyssey through Russia and Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear when the hijackers left Moscow what their plan
for a final destination might be. But, officials in Britain said
the plane, after flying over Germany, had entered its airspace.
</P>
<P>
   While in Moscow the hijackers asked for maps of European
countries, fuel for the airplane and 181 meals. As an apparent
good-will gesture, the hijackers released 10 male passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The hijacking began when several men with pistols and grenades _
an Afghan news agency put the number at six _ seized the Ariana
Airlines plane on a flight from Kabul, the Afghan capital, to
Mazar-e-Sharif, a city in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   They demanded the release of Ismail Khan, an opposition leader
who has been jailed by the Taliban, the Islamic group that now
controls most of Afghanistan, since 1997. Afghan officials said the
plane, a Boeing-727, took off with 186 passengers, including 32
children.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the plane flew to Tashkent, the capital of the Central
Asian republic of Uzbekistan. Soon after it took off from there, a
fuel leak forced it to land at Aktyubinsk in Kazakhstan. It was not
clear if the leak was fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen passengers were released at those two stops. Russian
television said the hijackers had told Russian authorities that
they planned to fly to Britain, France, Spain or Germany.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear why the plane flew to Moscow. The Taliban have
been supporting the breakaway southern Russian republic of Chechnya
and have charged that Moscow is backing the anti-Taliban opposition
in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan state-run airline is under international sanctions
and is not permitted to fly international routes. The United
Nations imposed the sanctions in November to punish the Taliban for
their refusal to extradite Osama bin Laden, who is suspected of
terrorism and has been living in Afghanistan for the last few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Federal Security Service, a successor to the Soviet-era
KGB, held talks with the hijackers.
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan ambassador to Moscow was with the Russian
negotiators, and talks with the hijackers were conducted by radio
in English.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
