<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8442 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-VOICE-RECOGNITION-SFC     02-06 1713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICE-RECOGNITION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY KELLY ZITO
</HEADLINE>
  
 Technology is Gradually Helping People Talk to Machines  &HT;        &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
From microwaves and cars to the biggest corporate phone systems,
more and more machines are letting you talk to them.
<P>
   Just don't expect your PC to fully understand you.
</P>
<P>
   Voice recognition software, which lets consumers verbally find a
phone number and dictate e-mail, is poised to take up residence in
a host of ``smart'' gadgets, just like on Star Trek.
</P>
<P>
   Already, several hundred motorists in the United States can tell
their Auto PCs to change the radio station to 98.1 FM or suggest
the way to San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   And in the not-too-distant future, owners of General Electric's
prototype Advantium oven will be able tell the appliance to cook
three pork chops at 350 degrees for 45 minutes using only their
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies aren't to be left out, either. BeVocal, a new
Mountain View firm, lets customers call up the Web using an 800
number and orally request traffic reports, restaurant reviews or
stock quotes in any form they want, including voice, e-mail, fax or
pager.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the voice recognition software that was to
supplant the keyboard and save consumers' aching wrists and
fingers?
</P>
<P>
   While the technology is proliferating within large organizations
_ particularly those with busy customer service centers where voice
recognition helps them route calls _ few consumers use voice
recognition on their own desktops.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the software is touted as a way to let people speak to
their PCs to compose e-mail, write reports, browse the Internet and
navigate around the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the primary users of voice recognition have been
medical and legal professionals who often find themselves typing
reams of patient reports and briefs. It's also popular among the
disabled, people who suffer from repetitive strain injuries, and
computer users in Asian countries where it often replaces
complicated keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is, despite all the advances and crossover
success of voice recognition, most dictation programs are still
fairly clunky and haven't caught on with the masses.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to software market researcher PC Data, retail
sales of voice recognition software actually fell almost 4 percent
in 1999, after dramatic growth for five consecutive years. And in
the fourth quarter of 1999 alone, unit sales fell more than 13
percent, compared with the last quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say part of the problem is that many workplaces
simply aren't conducive to a bunch of employees yakking to their
workstations. What's more, consumers expect the software, and by
extension, their computers, to actually ``understand'' them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference between speech recognition and speech
communication,'' said Chin-Hui Lee, head of the dialogue systems
research department at Bell Labs in New Jersey. ``Recognition is
transcribing spoken language into text, but a more challenging task
is getting a machines to do what Hal can do in `2001,' which was
get information from humans to solve problems.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason and others, many say QWERTY and keystrokes are
here to say. And speech recognition software users like Dan Cornell
say that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell, a Palo Alto lawyer, admits that he's a terrible typist
and hoped that dictation software would help shoulder some of his
heavy word processing load. But after trying about half a dozen
different brands, Cornell said the programs never matched his
old-fashioned typing and editing in speed and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Zac Weiner, an East Bay resident, feels much the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found using voice recognition to be more cumbersome than it
was worth,'' he wrote in an e-mail. ``All in all, voice recognition
isn't worth it to me. A mouse is just fine, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Others subscribe to Roger Matus's &LR;  view that ``typing is an
aberration of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 10 years, it will be very rare that you'll get a device
with a keyboard,'' said Matus, the vice president of marketing for
Dragon Systems, one of the softwaremakers. ``And in 100 years,
people will barely remember keyboards.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Newman, founder and president of Say I Can Inc., a Berkeley
company that has trained several hundred people to use speech
recognition software, believes that the increasing incidence of
repetitive stress disorders will necessitate the demise of the
keyboard. But even he admits that the current technology requires
patience and tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get used to speaking aloud, and you have to stick
with it and train the computer when it makes mistakes,'' he said.
``If you don't, you're not going to get adequate results.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Mistake Prone
</P>
<P>
   Most unsuccessful users of dictation software cite a laundry
list of problems: poor microphone technology, hypersensitivity to
environmental noise, laborious editing, long training exercises for
the computer to learn your voice and the large amount of memory
such programs require.
</P>
<P>
   But by far the sorest spot for users is accuracy. IBM, Dragon
Systems and Lernout &AMP; Hauspie _ the top dogs in the industry _ all
tout accuracy above the 90 percent mark. But even one mistake every
10 words isn't good enough for Rozanne Weissman, who has been using
Dragon products for about a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're using a keyboard, you're not typing a mistake
every 10 words,'' said Weissman, director of marketing for the
Alliance to Save Energy in Washington, D.C. ``It's frustrating
because for people who are fast and multitasking, you're trying to
produce the work with tools that aren't up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the technology itself, however, even 90 percent accuracy is
pretty amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four years ago, dictation programs required users to
``speak ... like ... this ...'' and even then, they goofed up
plenty. Today, users can speak in a natural, quick cadence, and
generally, the programs keep up. What's more, computer memory and
speed continue to improve, accommodating the vast libraries and
bulky engines behind the software.
</P>
<P>
   But until it becomes much smarter, voice recognition will face
the inevitable comparison to the fantastic machines in novels and
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been sitting around watching James Bond and `Star Trek'
where you can use your voice to do anything,'' said David Jennings,
lead planner for Microsoft's speech products group. ``But that's
all done with smoke and mirrors, it's not real. It's built the
wrong perception of the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Where such technology is playing a larger and larger role, he
said, is in very specific contexts, like 411 call centers or large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Small Vocabulary
</P>
<P>
   Both dictation and so-called enterprise applications run on the
same basic engine. The software ``hears'' a user's voice and uses
both acoustic and statistical models to translate that into a word.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two is that the ``domain'' or the
words and context necessary to retrieve the phone number for Rose
Smith in Santa Cruz is far narrower than the 60,000-plus-words
dictation programs need to construct an e-mail or sales report.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, consumers are more likely to see speech
recognition systems replace those annoying phone trees that prompt
you to press numbers to weave your way to a customer service
representative.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't end there.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon is exploring a different kind of application called
``audio mining,'' in which the software ``listens'' to broadcasts
or conversations and creates searchable databases. For instance, a
clothing retailer could tap into the company's call center data and
find out how many people called and asked about the red sweater on
page 126 of its catalog. Then it could cross-reference that with
the number of people who also mentioned the black shoes on page 14.
</P>
<P>
   It might sound a little scary to consumers, but companies appear
more willing to shell out money for solutions that let them market
more efficiently and profitably.
</P>
<P>
   While voice-systems developers say those kinds of solutions are
definite moneymakers, even they concede that dictation and
corporate systems aren't necessarily the ``killer apps'' for the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some are moving far beyond dictation. Belgium's Lernout
&AMP; Hauspie recently signed a deal with a unit of Fox Networks for a
joint venture to integrate voice technology in broadcast and
Internet content in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe voice is the interface of the future,'' said L&AMP;H
chief executive Gaston Bastiaens, ``whether that's taking the voice
of a newscaster and putting it on your computer so it speaks with
that voice, or integrating speech technology in games over the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, all advances in speech recognition will be limited by the
fact that computers, no matter how fast or loaded with bells and
whistles, will probably never be able to replicate the mysterious
intuitions of the human brain when it comes to languages and
accents. Right now, most of the leading players in the voice
recognition arena are focused on gathering more data on dialects
and improving the algorithms within the software to better mimic
humans when it comes to comprehending complex phrases and concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell the software to `Bold that last line,' and it
will do it,'' said Krishna Nathan, director of consumer voice
systems at IBM. ``So the rudiments of (natural language
understanding) are there, but it still has a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan envisions applications that eventually will allow a
person to log onto her PC while taking her coat off and sipping
coffee, tell the PC to jump on the Internet, and  &LR; find the cheapest
plane ticket to Hong Kong and book it.
</P>
<P>
   But even that may require some keyboard intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of the keyboard is that every key is labeled,''
said Bruce Balentine, director of speech recognition for EIG, a San
Ramon company that designs customer service software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voice recognition is a medium that's useful in certain
contexts _ when your eyes or hands are busy or when you're mobile _
and not in others. A new user interface doesn't replace the old
one. It simply appears and becomes part of a larger suite of
interfaces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
