<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8443 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE-VANDALS-SFCH     02-06 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-VANDALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Note that `AT SIGN' and `TILDE' should be replaced
in  e-mail addresses and Web addresses with appropriate symbols)   Vandalism Hurting Case Against Genetically Engineered Foods 
 &HT;       
 BY TOM ABATE  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A handful of vandals are undermining the legal effort to question
the safety of genetically engineered foods.
<P>
   Since last July, eco-vandals have broken into greenhouses and
stomped on genetically altered crops in at least 18 separate
incidents in several states. UC Berkeley has been targeted twice,
and UC Davis has been hit four times.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent attack occurred in January when vandals broke
into a greenhouse at a U.S. Department of Agriculture field office
in Albany and stomped some genetically altered wheat.
</P>
<P>
   This burst of vandalism prompted campus police from the
University of California at Berkeley and the University of
California at Davis to organize a daylong seminar on outdoor
security last week, where FBI officials briefed university cops on
the latest in monitoring systems.
</P>
<P>
   This vandalism is not only cowardly but tactically stupid, since
food critics have been making plenty of headway in the courts, the
markets and the regulatory arena.
</P>
<P>
   For instance:
</P>
<P>
   _ International negotiators in Montreal recently agreed that
exporters can be required to label shipments that contain
genetically altered grains. Under what is called the Biosafety
Protocol, individual nations also won greater latitude to restrict
genetically engineered food imports in the future.
</P>
<P>
   This was a huge victory, coming after the recent World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle, which ended without adopting the
laissez-faire position favored by U.S. trade officials.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last week, Frito-Lay became the most prominent mainstream food
producer to say it would not buy genetically engineered corn.
Gerber Baby Food and French-fries maker McCain Foods Ltd. had taken
similar stances earlier. Such moves have started to make farmers
leery of planting GE seeds.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Center for Food Safety in Washington, D.C., recently won
an important procedural victory in federal court, challenging the
Environmental Protection Agency's decision to allow crops to be
grown, using BT.
</P>
<P>
   BT, a natural insecticide that organic farmers spray on crops,
kills bugs quickly before evaporating. Because it doesn't linger,
pests never develop the sort of resistance that occurs when bugs
eat a less-than-lethal dose of pesticide and survive to breed
progeny inoculated against that pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   But biotech firms have spliced the BT gene into corn, cotton and
other crops, trying to build this pest killer into plants. Their
intention was to reduce aerial applications of pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Organic farmers, afraid BT crops would breed pesticide resistant
bugs, asked the EPA in 1997 to study this issue. Attorney Joe
Mendelson, who is leading the lawsuit on this issue, said the EPA
had refused to reply, until a federal judge recently gave the
agency until March 20 to explain its reasoning on the
pest-resistance issue.
</P>
<P>
   Mendelson said the center can use that EPA response as
ammunition in its lawsuit seeking to force the agency to rescind
its endorsement of BT crops.
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Academy of Sciences will soon release a report
offering the first comprehensive assessment of the ecological and
safety concerns arising from BT crops.
</P>
<P>
   The NAS effort was initially marred by controversy after the
staff member coordinating the project quit to take a job with a
biotech industry group. The NAS responded by adding members with
avowedly environmental views.
</P>
<P>
   The NAS draft report is now being circulated for criticism and
revision, and should be out within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Similarly, some 400 European scientists, environmentalists,
industry and consumer advocates will assemble in Scotland at the
end of this month for what is shaping up as perhaps the biggest
public debate so far on the risks and benefits of genetically
engineered foods.
</P>
<P>
   With these and other efforts focusing attention on the issue,
there's simply no reason to go around stomping crops to get
attention _ especially when Bay Area people who want to get
exercised about this issue have a more productive outlet for their
energy coming up soon.
</P>
<P>
   UC Berkeley Professor Miguel Altieri will hold an international
seminar from March 2 to March 4 on the ``ecological impacts of
transgenic crops.'' His guests will include Cornell researcher John
Losey, who did the monarch butterfly study, and Swiss scientist
Angelika Helbick, who has looked at how transgenic crops affect
beneficial insects like ladybugs.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the discussions will be limited to students and
scientists, Altieri is planning at least two public events: one on
campus the afternoon of March 2, and the other in the city of
Berkeley the evening of March 3.
</P>
<P>
   Altieri hopes to finalize the logistics early this week. For
details, e-mail him at  &LR; agroeco3(AT SIGN)nature.berkeley.edu &LR;  or
call (510) 642-9802.
</P>
<P>
   _ DETERRING BIO WARFARE: On a truly terrifying topic, CIA
Director George Tenet warned Congress last week that the United
States was becoming increasingly vulnerable to potential biological
attack, as the sophisticated tools of biotechnology become
accessible to small nations and even terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Policymakers have raised such fears before, and the standard
response has been to increase research funding for super-vaccines
and improved civil defense (see my story on this subject: ``Bio-War
Games,'' Chronicle Business section, Aug. 9, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Harvard biologist Matthew Meselson, a longtime activist on
chemical and biological warfare issues, has a different approach.
He wants the nations of the world to make it an international crime
to make or use biological weapons. Any nation would be able to
imprison, try and punish any person, whether a private terrorist or
a government official, who broke this international law.
</P>
<P>
   Meselson has modeled his statute on current international law
that makes slavery and torture international crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Former dictator Augusto Pinochet has discovered to his chagrin
that some nations take seriously their right to prosecute him for
tortures perpetrated while he ruled Chile.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface Meselson's idea sounds like a quixotic exercise.
Some nations would have to adopt the proposal, and ask the United
Nations to begin the convoluted process of getting the world's
nations to agree to make biological warfare a crime.
</P>
<P>
   But the alternative, says Meselson, is crazier still. One day
our CIA gets wind that terrorist X or nation Y is planning a
biological attack. We try to bluff, bully or bomb them into
quitting, which may or may not work.
</P>
<P>
   Why not instead put these wannabe bioterrorists on notice that
they'll never be free to travel in civilized nations if they embark
on this uncivilized course of action.
</P>
<P>
   To find out more, visit  &LR; www.fas.harvard.edu/(TILDE)hsp/ &LR;  and
click on ``what's new.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your bio-feedback to Tom Abate, abate(AT SIGN)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
