<SLUG> BC-HKN-ALLSTAR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HOCKEY: COLD RUBBER AT 100 MPH
</HEADLINE>
   (See also NHL-ALLSTAR-GAME) 
(rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Mike Richter, the New York Rangers goalie, was talking
Sunday about how Al MacInnis of St. Louis injured two goalies this
season with his hard, heavy slap shot. Chris Osgood of Detroit and
Jocelyn Thibault of Chicago hurt their hands trying to stop pucks
fired by the veteran defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both were hurt on one shot,'' Richter said of the injuries.
``He shot it right through Chicago into Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Richter was kidding, as he often is. But MacInnis'
shot has the sort of mythic power that leads to legends. During
this weekend's All-Star game festivities at the Air Canada Center
here, MacInnis again won the hardest-shot competition, his fourth
consecutive victory and his sixth since 1990. He fired the puck at
100.1 mph, into an empty net, about the speed of a fastball thrown
by pitchers like Nolan Ryan and Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   When goalies talk about the MacInnis shot, they usually open
with a wisecrack before turning respectfully serious.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Joseph of Toronto, who was MacInnis' teammate on the
North America team Sunday, said he usually thought, ``Don't hit
me!'' when MacInnis wound up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're hoping you catch a pad or that he misses the net,''
Joseph said.
</P>
<P>
   Olaf Kolzig of the Washington Capitals, who played for the World
team, which won, 9-4, was thankful that he did not have to face
MacInnis much Sunday or during the regular season. They play in
different conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a shot that keeps a direct line,'' Kolzig said of
MacInnis' shot. ``It has a gradual rise. It's from the unusual
curve in his stick. You think you have it pinpointed and it comes
so fast and it rises so quickly you can't adjust to it. It's so
deceptive.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter recalled stopping one shot by MacInnis that hit him in
his chest protector but still left him with a bruised stomach.
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis, 36, has other skills. He won the Norris Trophy last
season as the NHL's best defenseman and he is a leader on the
Blues, who lead the Western Conference and are only three points
behind the league-leading Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues are there despite several serious injuries, two of
them to MacInnis. A week ago his appearance here was doubtful
because of a collapsed lung.
</P>
<P>
   This season he missed 12 games with a fractured fibula after he
was hit by a shot from Edmonton's Jason Smith. So he knows and
respects the damage a shot can do.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned that Brian Leetch, the Rangers defenseman, had
missed more than two months with an arm broken by the shot of Tampa
Bay's Fredrik Modin. The conversation turned to Montreal's Trent
McCleary, who was nearly killed last weekend when a shot by
Philadelphia's Chris Therien hit the Canadiens player in the
throat.
</P>
<P>
   Does the possibility of injuring someone run through MacInnis'
mind when he cocks his stick back to fire? ``All the time,''
MacInnis said. ``I've injured some guys with broken hands. I've
broken a couple ankles and toes and what have you. And people ask
me, `Do you intend to hurt anybody?' I just can't imagine doing
that to any colleague. I know how hard it is to get to this
league.''
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis got here through Calgary, via juniors in Kitchener and
home in Inverness, Nova Scotia. As a boy in the late 1960s and
early 1970s, he fired pucks on summer days off a sheet of plywood
toward a homemade net set in front of his father's barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was the manager of the arena in my hometown,'' MacInnis
said. ``As a kid, I used to collect pucks during the wintertime
when I helped close up.''
</P>
<P>
   On some summer days, MacInnis would hit ``150 or 200'' pucks.
``It was a pastime,'' he said. ``I had no idea it would lead to
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The barn no longer stands, although MacInnis said he did not
knock it down with his shots or even put one through the wall. But
he did acknowledge: ``My dad would have to reshingle some of it in
the fall'' to repair the seasonal damage.
</P>
<P>
   Richter said MacInnis was effective because he got the shot away
quickly and fired while in motion. Other goalies speculated that
the unusual curve in MacInnis' stick blade caused the puck to do
strange things. MacInnis said that the curve made his stick look
like a 7-iron golf club and that teammates had been unable to use
it when they had borrowed it. But he said he had cut down the curve
in recent years because ``with the ice being as bad as it is now''
the puck tended to bounce over the blade.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Pronger, another Blues defenseman in the All-Star game,
said MacInnis perfected his swing of the stick with ``a lot of hard
work and time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The repetition,'' he added. ``It's got a certain torque, a
certain movement.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to elaborate, Pronger shrugged and described the
MacInnis technique in primitive terms, the way a man might swat a
rock with a tree branch. ``Just grip and rip it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
