<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8455 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-ART     02-06 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECLARING HERSELF A `NEW DEMOCRAT,' MRS. CLINTON MAKES IT
OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT4-11 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Her husband seated as a mere onlooker at the
rear of the stage, Hillary Rodham Clinton declared her candidacy
for the U.S. Senate Sunday afternoon, presenting herself as a ``New
Democrat'' who viewed government as neither the cause of nor the
solution to the nation's problems, as she adopted the message
President Clinton rode to the White House in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In a spectacle of media and politics, all packed into a loud and
raucous gymnasium at the western tip of the State University of New
York campus here, Mrs. Clinton formally inaugurated what was as
much a rite of family passage as a political one. It was Mrs.
Clinton who was the center of attention Sunday; Bill Clinton, whose
term in office ends in just 11 months, did not utter a single
public word during the 32 minutes he spent on stage.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not have to. Mrs. Clinton borrowed heavily on his
oratory and record _ much the way Vice President Al Gore has during
his campaign for president _ as she sought to begin what her aides
hoped would be a new, and less troubled, phase of her campaign
against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a new Democrat,'' Clinton declared. ``I don't believe
that government is the source of all our problems or the solution
to them. But I do believe that when people live up to their
responsibilities, we ought to live up to ours, to help them build
better lives. I believe that's the basic bargain we owe to one
another in America today.''
</P>
<P>
   With her announcement, a ceremony in American politics that has
traditionally offered candidates an unfettered chance to make a
case to voters, Clinton went to great pains to present herself as a
public figure in her own right, and not just a product of her
husband's success. The day, choreographed down to the last camera
shot, was filled with reminders of this, from the gauzy 18-minute
biographic video that introduced her, to the personal anecdotes
sprinkled through her speech, to what was written on the huge red,
white and blue banner at her back: ``Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had looked forward to her speech Sunday, hoping that
she would restore their confidence in her candidacy after what they
viewed as an unsteady start and also hoping that she would offer a
compelling case for New Yorkers to elect someone to the Senate who
has not held public office or lived in the state until a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know, some people are asking why I'm doing this, here
and now,'' she said. ``And that's a fair question. Here's my
answer, and why I hope you'll put me to work for you: I may be new
to the neighborhood, but I'm not new to your concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, politicians tend to step aside on the days when their
rivals formally declare their candidacy. But Giuliani, who takes
some pleasure in defying traditional political rules, was anything
but reclusive. He took to the morning talk show circuit with vigor,
presenting the case for his candidacy, and the case against
Clinton, on five separate news programs. He took great pains to
note his long years in public service, and he repeatedly referred
to his official duties in contrast to what he called the
Hollywood-style event unfolding just a few miles outside the city,
in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think ultimately it's bigger than any one issue or any one
personality,'' Giuliani said of a viable candidacy for the Senate.
``It's a sense of trust that people have to have. And I guess what
I would say to them is, in my case, they have a record of public
service in the state of New York for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor shuttled from studio to studio, replenishing himself
at one point by grabbing sausage on the buffet table at the Green
Room at ABC studios on Times Square. From there, he went to the
studio being used by ``This Week'' and indicated he might forgo
announcing altogether, because he had, in the past, won the
elections where he had never announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you have sort of superstition about it?'' asked Cokie
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' he responded. ``I have to admit.''
</P>
<P>
   In pomp and scale and sheer spectacle, Clinton's announcement
was, almost certainly, unlikely any other staged by a candidate
running for public office in New York before. The gym at Purchase
College, which is about 10 miles south of Clinton's new home in
Chappaqua, began filling up with press at 7 a.m.; by 1 p.m., there
was not a spot to be had on the risers that were set up for
photographers and television crews. It was broadcast live on CNN,
C-Span, New York One, and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Blumenthal, the White House aide and longtime adviser to
Bill Clinton, and Ann Lewis, the president's communications
director, milled around in a gymnasium along with a crowd that
included John Podhoretz, the conservative commentator and New York
Post columnist, and Lucianne Goldberg, the literary agent who
encouraged Linda Tripp to tape her conversations with Monica
Lewinsky. Most of the state's Democratic members of Congress had
been flown up from a party retreat in Virginia as a show of support
for Clinton's entry. Other prominent New York politicians were
lined up outside the gym trying in vain to get in.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention Giuliani's name during her speech.
However, she made some obvious references to her opponent as she
signaled some some of the roads of attack she intended to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one other thing I'll fight against: The politics of
revenge and retributions,'' she said, as shouts of ``Yes'' could be
heard in the by-invitation-only crowd. ``If you put me to work for
you, I'll work to lift people up _ not push them down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
