<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McCAW-IRIDIUM-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAW GROUP EXPECTED TO OFFER FINANCING FOR IRIDIUM  
(EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A group of investors led by Craig O. McCaw, the
cellular telephone pioneer, is expected to provide at least $20
million of emergency financing to Iridium LLC, the troubled global
satellite telephone company that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection last August, according to people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The investment, which is expected to be announced early this
week, would allow Iridium to continue to operate its network of 66
low-orbit satellites for the next few months while McCaw and his
team of investors negotiate to take control.
</P>
<P>
   The investment is part of McCaw's strategy to restore confidence
in the struggling satellite telephone industry and create a
consortium of huge global satellite companies that would offer
everything from telephone service in the most remote parts of the
globe to high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Iridium, McCaw agreed late last year to raise at
least $1.2 billion to gain control of ICO Global Communications
Ltd., another global satellite telephone company, and help take
that company out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. He is also a
large investor in Teledesic LLC, the ``Internet in the sky''
satellite venture scheduled to begin operating in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But people close to the negotiations say McCaw recently proposed
spending $600 million to take over Iridium, which is 18 percent
owned by Motorola. But that offer was shelved in favor of a
short-term financing proposal which gives McCaw the option of
dropping out of Iridium if the deal does not work out.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ratliffe, a spokesman for Eagle River Investments LLC in
Bellevue, Wash., McCaw's private group, said: ``We are continuing
to look at Iridium. Craig remains interested, but a decision has
not been made.''
</P>
<P>
   McCraw is negotiating to gain voting control over Iridium, which
has over $4.4 billion in debt. Iridium shares, which traded as high
as $70 in May 1998, fell to about $3 a share after the company
filed for bankruptcy. After the reorganization, the company said
its shares were expected to be worthless.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw's planned investment in Iridium, which must be approved by
a federal bankruptcy judge, would amount to so-called
debtor-in-possession financing, or DIP financing, to a company in
Chapter 11 reorganization. It would come at a time when Motorola,
the telecommunications giant that helped conceive of the $5 billion
global satellite telephone venture, moves to cut its own financing
of Iridium.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Motorola agreed to commit $20 million so that
Iridium could continue to operate through mid-February. At that
time, a spokesman for Motorola said the company would suspend
operations of the satellite service by Feb. 15 if a reorganization
plan was not in place. Motorola said it was operating the system at
no charge. According to people close to the negotiations, Iridium
may not meet the Feb. 15 reorganization deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Although Motorola has been a backer of the Iridium system, the
company has taken charges against earnings in the last year because
of its exposure to the satellite venture. Now, Motorola _ which
also makes satellite phone handsets for Iridium _ is trying to cut
its losses and appease concerned shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Armand Musey, an analyst who follows the satellite industry for
Banc of America Securities, said McCaw might be investing in
Iridium to establish a foothold in the satellite telephone
industry. Some of those subscribers could be linked to ICO Global
Communications, which begins operating next year, and Teledesic,
which begins operating in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Musey believes that the Iridium network is too expensive to
operate over the long run but that it may prove worthwhile in the
short run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real thing for McCaw is you have the spectrum,'' Musey
said. ``You have the experience dealing with customers. You have
marketing and distribution. Iridium may be too costly but maybe he
can roll those customers into ICO or Teledesic.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Iridium and Motorola were unavailable for comment
over the weekend.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But last week McCaw moved ahead with a planned investment in ICO
Global, which expects to begin service in 2001. A spokesman for ICO
Global said on Friday that the company had recently met the
conditions set by McCaw to receive a second round of financing
worth $275 million. The company had already received $225 million
in financing.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium, however, continues to struggle. Papers recently filed
with the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York indicated that Iridium
had revenues of just $1.5 million in December while losses topped
$114 million. The company had earlier suffered from technical
glitches and weak demand for its bulky satellite telephones and
expensive service.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Iridium has drastically reduced prices and Motorola
recently introduced a much smaller handset. No sales figures have
been released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
