<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8464 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-06 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE BUSH COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A tradition in this space has been to exhort
flattened candidates to get off the floor. Ten tips for George W.
Bush to become the latest ``Comeback Kid'':
</P>
<P>
   1. Fear not to admit error. In my last column, I showed how the
``can't-win'' device stopped the favored Henry Clay from getting
nominated in 1840. This did not lead, as I mistakenly wrote, to the
election of President Benjamin Harrison, but to William Henry
Harrison, his grandfather. (Indeed, Democrats a half-century later
campaigned against the grandson with the slogan ``Grandpa's pants
don't fit Benny.'')
</P>
<P>
   See? The trick in eating crow is to pretend it tastes good. You
should say: ``After years of that negative stuff, I thought the way
to win this was to be Mr. Nice Guy. But the people want, and have
the right to expect, a scrapper. So _ I have just begun to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Instead of derogating Yankee maverickism, adopt the notion
that your New Hampshire loss was a necessary awakening slap. Blame
nobody but yourself; this will show leadership and force others to
absolve you.
</P>
<P>
   3. Don't try to turn into Mr. Tough Guy. Resist panicky advice
to go for John McCain's jugular. Your South Carolina supporter's
assault on him as no friend to veterans backfired, and that awful
picture of you clinging to old Admiral Moorer made us wonder who
was propping up whom. In that regard _
</P>
<P>
   4. Forget endorsements; they only make McCain's point that you
are a captive of the Old Guard. Honor thy father and mother by
letting them root for you at home; ``that's my boy'' is hardly a
suitable label for a man of 53. And get those crowds of politicians
and hangers-on off those platforms; he stands the tallest who
stands alone.
</P>
<P>
   5. Let your surrogates call into question the fairness of media
coverage. It's not just the character of a hero that turns the
media on. We need a contest, we tilt toward underdogs, we admire
candidates who know their stuff and we consider accessibility a
mark of mutual respect _ and so we've welcomed your opposition with
open arms. The trick for you is not to exploit resentment of the
media, which often comes across as whining, but to make journalists
jittery about impartiality _ which can make us lean against our
instincts, as I do here.
</P>
<P>
   6. Develop a rousing stump speech. Your themeless pudding
contains no rhetorical punch. Don't worry about boring the
traveling press; get three major messages firmly in your mind and
deliver them without the crutch of notes.
</P>
<P>
   7. Come out of hiding. Your second-biggest enemy is the
suspicion that you don't trust yourself beyond scripted answers.
But you have shown you can do better than expected in interviews.
So display some confidence and mix it up with the press. After a
year of front-running, if you don't have a good grasp of every
major issue, foreign and domestic, then the great corps of policy
advisers you assembled has been wasting its time.
</P>
<P>
   8. Don't rely on spots alone; prove your readiness on
unrehearsed TV. Your biggest enemy is the growing worry among
Republicans that Al Gore would clean your clock in debate. Overcome
this by challenging McCain to one-on-one debates now, without the
buffering of fringe candidates. If you can hold your own with him,
you will astound the skeptics and be more than ready for the best
the Democrats have to offer.
</P>
<P>
   9. Don't try to win the nomination in a way that would ensure
your election defeat. In moving rightward, you seem to cede the
independents to McCain. Strategic error. You had to retreat after
trying to steal New York's delegates; if McCain wins the March 7
popular vote in California, but you take all the delegates because
state election law counts only registered Republicans, a keening
wail of ``Thou Shalt Not Steal'' will go up across the nation to
ruin GOP chances in November.
</P>
<P>
   10. Compete more aggressively with McCain in zapping the
Clinton-Gore sleaze but scorch not the earth on our side. Remember
1980 and the route your patient father took to the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
