<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PFIZER-WARNER-LAMBERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PFIZER APPROVES $90 BILLION DEAL FOR WARNER-LAMBERT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pfizer's board of directors voted Sunday night to buy
Warner-Lambert for more than $90 billion in stock, and
Warner-Lambert's board was expected to follow suit, people close to
the two companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, word of which broke last week, would create the
largest drug company in the United States, with blockbuster drugs
like Lipitor, a cholesterol-fighting medication, and the
anti-impotence drug Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which is expected to be announced Monday, also
leaves American Home Products, the spurned suitor of
Warner-Lambert, alone again for the third time in two years. Two
other proposed marriages _ one with SmithKline Beecham, another
with Monsanto _ fell apart in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While American Home lost yet another partner, this time it walks
away with $1.8 billion _ the largest fee that any company has
received when a proposed merger broke apart.
</P>
<P>
   The company needs the money. It is now trying to defend itself
against thousands of lawsuits filed by people who said they were
harmed when they took the company's diet drug combination called
fen-phen.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer has agreed to exchange 2.75 of its shares for each share
of Warner-Lambert, people close to the companies said. They added
that new company would keep the Pfizer name and would be based in
New York City, where Pfizer's headquarters are.
</P>
<P>
   The new company's consumer products division _ with Warner
products like Listerine, Rolaids and Sudafed _ will be managed from
Warner-Lambert's current headquarters in Morris Plains, N.J. By
combining, the two companies expect to save as much as $1.6 billion
in operating costs by 2002. Few jobs are expected to be cut in the
companies' sales or research forces. Instead, the reductions will
be in management and administrative positions.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company's chairman and chief executive will be
William C. Steere Jr., Pfizer's chairman and chief executive, the
people close to the companies said. One person who will not be part
of the new Pfizer is Warner-Lambert's chairman, Lodewijk J.R. de
Vink, who has told Pfizer executives that he does not want a
management job in the new company, the people said. Pfizer
executives have asked de Vink to remain as a consultant after the
two companies are combined.
</P>
<P>
   The final vote by directors at Pfizer and Warner-Lambert ends a
three-month struggle for Warner. The fight began on Nov. 4, when
Warner-Lambert agreed to buy American Home for $70 billion in
stock. Just hours later, Pfizer made a hostile $82.4 billion offer
for Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer sells Lipitor with Warner under a joint marketing
agreement that gives Pfizer about half of the drug's profits.
Pfizer wanted all of Lipitor's profits as well as Warner's
fast-growing sales. The combined companies say they will grow about
25 percent a year, hoping to soon overtake the largest drug maker
in the world, Glaxo SmithKline, the combination of the British drug
makers, Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline, which announced last month
that they would merge.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders are expected to vote on the Pfizer-Warner deal
within two months, the people close to the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Sunday that American Home could survive on its own
because of its strong-selling drugs like Premarin, the hormone
replacement therapy for women, and consumer products like Advil,
Centrum vitamins and Chap Stick. But they said that if American
Home wants to compete with the giants in the rapidly consolidating
drug industry, such as Merck, it must try again to find a corporate
mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Home is a very strong company,'' said Hemant K. Shah,
an independent pharmaceutical analyst at H.K.S. and Co. in Warren,
N.J. ``But they need a partner to move into the first tier.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding American Home's competitive problems are its
fen-phen liabilities. The company agreed in October to pay $3.75
billion to settle those claims, but many analysts say that might
not be enough. Plaintiffs have until the end of March to opt out of
the settlement and continue their lawsuits in a bid for more money.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say American Home needs to clear up the fen-phen
lawsuits if it is to become an attractive partner again. The
company is also trying to sell its troubled agricultural business,
but many pharmaceutical and chemical companies are trying to do the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with such problems, American Home is viewed as an
attractive partner. John R. Stafford, American Home's 62-year-old
chairman, has made it clear that he is willing to step aside if the
right partner emerges. With many drug companies looking for
partners these days, stock analysts say there is a long list of
potential suitors, including Novartis, Bristol-Myers Squibb and
Merck.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis, a Swiss company, is trying to get approval to list its
shares on the New York Stock Exchange, a step that would help it
acquire another company.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell B. Weiner, American Home's spokesman, said that the
company would be fine on its own, but that it would not turn down a
good offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our pipeline of new products and our growth, the company
does not need a merger, but we're always open for opportunities,''
he said. ``Like James Bond said, `Never say never.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
