<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PUFFDADDY-FASHION-ART     02-06 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUFFDADDY-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEMS ASIDE, PUFF DADDY DAZZLES ON THE CATWALK 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is all of 29, likes diamonds, occasionally swears,
wears a rosary, and let's not forget the matter of his indictment
on charges of possessing illegal handguns or, for sheer tabloid
value, whether he is still involved with actress Jennifer Lopez.
Life isn't easy for Sean Combs, music mogul and aspiring fashion
star. But he's persevering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to put on an incredible show, put out an incredible
record,'' he said in the Manhattan offices of his clothing label,
Sean John, a few days before his first fashion show, which took
place at the Bryant Park tents on Saturday night. ``I'm going to go
on tour and I'm going to go to court and handle this like a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Combs was referring to the handgun charges, stemming from
shootings on Dec. 27 at a nightclub. Lopez was with him at the
time, but was not charged. Indeed, in Combs' showroom last week,
Lopez looked none the worse for wear, and every bit like an
interested girlfriend, as she waited for Combs to finish talking
and resume the heavy business of deciding, with the show's
stylists, which of the several million dollars' worth of Fred
Leighton diamond necklaces and crosses should be on the clothes.
Who said fashion isn't fun?
</P>
<P>
   Combs seemed calm, even contrite, about the gun charges, and
said he was innocent. ``Life has to go on,'' he said
philosophically. ``I get upset when I read what people say about
me, but it just makes me fight harder to make sure people will
understand who I am.'' He paused, nodding toward a rack of clothes.
``I can't do all that I do and be running around and throwing guns
out windows,'' he added. ``That's not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Combs said that it was unfortunate that the shootings at the
club may have chilled the warmth that emanated from his brilliant
performance at a Costume Institute gala in December, when many of
New York's rich overachievers, including Nan Kempner and Oscar and
Annette de la Renta, were swinging in the aisles and Henry
Kissinger, evidently still adjusting to this new display of radical
chic, was heard to remark, ``Tell me, why does he call himself
Fluffy?''
</P>
<P>
   But Combs said, ``I don't really live for knowing people, for
being a socialite.'' He said his arrest was ``truly disappointing
not to Oscar de la Renta, to Donald Trump or Ron Perlman, but to my
family, to my mother, to my kids and to my company that I was in
the wrong place at the wrong time.'' He added, ``I'd give anything
if I had stayed my butt at home.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Combs' fashion show, which concluded the men's
wear segment of the nine-day run of fall 2000 collections, is proof
of his ability to focus on business while sorting out his personal
life. He doesn't hide the fact that his line, Sean John, is
designed by a professional staff, but he's involved and, given his
own taste for diamonds and blue jeans, it's not surprising he knows
what he likes. ``My jeans are the only ones that fit the perfect
way,'' he said. ``They're not too baggy, they're not too tight.
It's hard to make a man look sexy in a jeans suit, know what I'm
saying?''
</P>
<P>
   But his did. And what was interesting about Combs' claim of a
perfect fit was that he was right. This has been a men's wear
season in which the fit of the clothes _ the quality of the cut and
tailoring _ has undermined many of the collections. Not every
designer can cut a suit as distinctively as Hedi Slimane of Yves
Saint Laurent, nor can every man wear it. But to look at the
wholesale sloppiness blossoming out on the runways at shows like
Liz Claiborne's and Kenneth Cole's, with jackets and trousers
seemingly cut to please everyone and no one, is to want to cry out,
``Is there a tailor in the house?''
</P>
<P>
   Combs' jeans fit in a way that one can imagine young men liking:
loose through the legs with some definition around the hips. So if
a man wants to show off his gym work in a sleeveless T-shirt, his
pants will look comfortable without taking anything away from the
picture he is hoping to create: that he is a total love machine.
It's a little thing, but the members of the Sean John design staff
got the details right with such touches as jeans embellished with
rhinestones or lynx fur cuffs, chunky nylon parkas in bright red or
sky blue, track suits in soft black leather, and loose-fitting
suede or denim coveralls for those times when a man is just
chilling and feels no need to assert himself.
</P>
<P>
   Cole will collect points from anyone who loves Bob Dylan, whose
ballads were played throughout his show. In addition to covering
most of the season's big sportswear trends _ wet-looking
synthetics, natty car coats and turtlenecks, lots of leather and
black _ Cole used the show to make points about ``closed-minded
people'' and issues like bigotry and homelessness. Cole can get
away with moralizing and merchandising on the same platform because
his commitment to public causes is genuine.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, his clothes, while earning his company
impressive profits and the approval of Wall Street, don't exactly
pulsate with genuine fashion news. They are all too often a reprise
of current urban looks, updated here with quilted leather, softened
there with knits, and supported by his strong accessories.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The bigger news makers of the men's shows were Gene Meyer and
John Varvatos. Meyer presented a sparkling collection of striped
knits and young-modern combinations of ivy and rust-colored shirts
worn with melon and robin's-egg-blue turtlenecks or ascots that
looked as if they had sprung out of the pages of Wallpaper. Meyer
has a knack, and a supreme sense of confidence, for putting a spin
on the Noel Coward ideal of witty sophistication, with such looks
as U-neck sweater vests, sky-blue velvet jeans and slate poplin
trousers that looked like dressed-up denim.
</P>
<P>
   This was Varvatos' first show, though he is hardly a newcomer,
having spent many years in the men's divisions at Ralph Lauren and
Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   Varvatos knows his stuff, all right. There was a conspicuous
sense in the clothes of a pro paying attention to details _ the
cut, for starters, but also harder-to-see touches like real
buttonholes on cuffs, little plackets at the top of a zip-front
vest so the metal pull won't scratch your neck and drive you crazy,
and tweed and herringbone overcoats that looked like Daddy's old
numbers but were new. Such details not only add polish to the
clothes, but also give a store owner or salesman something more
positive to romance than yet another black suit.
</P>
<P>
   Varvatos' style combines some of Jil Sander's brainy minimalism
with Joseph Abboud's mellowing-into-middle-age ease, without
looking completely like either. Wide denim trousers resembled old
world gray flannels, while a pair of the real things, shown with a
sailor's sweater buttoned at the shoulder _ and on a model who
looked as if he had spent all day on his back listening to Moby _
made a different antifashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   Varvatos' many coats _ in double-faced wool, aged-looking New
Zealand shearling _ were terrific, but his cropped trousers looked
dubious. His line is being financed by Nautica.
</P>
<P>
   It sometimes seems as if young designers purposely mix the worst
clothes in some kind of preshow test: if it looks atrocious, it
must be fab. At his show on Thursday, Jason Bunin put a
zigzag-patterned sweater in deep browns with oatmeal trousers that
looked as if they had been cut from a blanket or a mohair throw or
both. But his collection of tight T-shirts and loud check pants had
a funky charm.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Dalal's show on Thursday night opened with fitted suits in
rugby stripes with cowboy-style boots that made the models look as
if they were walking on broken glass. There were boyish striped
sweaters and paisley shirts, but the show seemed off pace.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Abboud knows plenty about fit and comfort and what men
like. His show on Saturday was full of his soft tailoring and
reliable knits in spice tones and pebbly textures. Cargo pants
looked passe, but a group of velveteen suits in woodsy brown and
green tartan somehow brought to mind Cheever and the clink of
cocktail glasses.
</P>
<P>
   They were just square enough to be delicious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
