<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDROYALE WINS SAN ANTONIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- The leading characters are set for the Santa Anita
Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Budroyale, the tough, 7-year-old gelding, held off the
inconsistent Cat Thief to win the $300,000 San Antonio Handicap on
Sunday at Santa Anita to make himself the favorite for the March 4
Big 'Cap.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, General Challenge, the brilliant but
chicken-hearted 4-year-old gelding, confirmed he's a Big 'Cap
contender by winning the $500,000 Strub Stakes by 9 1/2 lengths
over a light field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all three can get the distance (1 1/4 miles),'' Ted H.
West, trainer of Budroyale, said of his horse, General Challenge
and Cat Thief. ``It should set up as a pretty solid Big 'Cap.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a quick comparison of the two
California-breds, consider that Budroyale covered 1 1/8 miles in
the San Antonio in 1:48.70, a theortical half-length faster than
General Challenge's 1:48.81 under similar dry and sunny conditions
in the Strub.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Consider that in the past 15 years the San Antonio has
sent three winners on to victory in the Big 'Cap -- four if you
include disqualified Big 'Cap winner The Wicked North in 1994 --
the Strub two.
</P>
<P>
   All of which points to Budroyale as the favorite, a role that
would have seemed impossible 21 starts and nine victories ago, when
owner Jeffrey Sengara claimed him for $50,000 at Santa Anita on
Feb. 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never is going to sink in totally,'' West said of Bud's
ascent from ``overachiever'' to leader of the local handicap
division.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Budroyale, with Garrett Gomez riding, left the starting
gate as a narrow third choice at 2-1 behind the horses who beat him
in his last two races. Cat Thief, the Breeders' Cup Classic winner
who skipped the Strub to face older horses in the San Antonio, was
the 8-5 favorite. Dixie Dot Com, the San Pasqual winner, also was
8-5.
</P>
<P>
   While Dixie Dot Com stalked longshot Moore's Flat and Elaborate
tucked in third, Budroyale sat in the clear in fourth and Cat Thief
was fifth last on the outside on the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   Budroyale attacked on the turn for home and took command at the
top of the stretch. Cat Thief, left with more ground to make up
than usual, closed in, but it was Budroyale by 1 1/4 lengths at the
finish.
</P>
<P>
   That kept Cat Thief winless in three appearances since he beat
Budroyale by 1 1/4 in the Breeders' Cup Classic Nov. 6 at
Gulfstream Park in Florida. ``I was not really pleased with his
performance,'' jockey Pat Day said of Cat Thief. ``For whatever
reason he seemed to struggle with the racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little sweet, getting revenge (for the Breeders'
Cup),'' Sengara said.
</P>
<P>
   Elaborate finished third, Moore's Flat fourth, nine lengths
ahead of disappointment Dixie Dot Com.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Dot Com was ridden by Corey Nakatani, replacing Pat
Valenzuela, who was removed from his Saturday and Sunday mounts by
the Santa Anita board of stewards after testing positive for
amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela faces a Wednesday morning hearing before stewards
Pete Pedersen, Tom Ward and Ingrid Fermin, who will have his career
in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   They must determine if the 36-year-old jockey violated the terms
of his unique, one-year ``conditional'' license, which require him
to pass random drug and alcohol tests and follow a substance-abuse
treatment program. Valenzuela, best known for riding 1989 Kentucky
Derby winner Sunday Silence, has served numerous suspensions for
drug-related violations, the latest stretching nearly two years
until that last-chance agreement with the California Horse Racing
Board was struck last fall. He'd had a spotless attendance record
-- while riding well enough to finish second to Laffit Pincay in
the Hollywood Park jockey standings -- until an unexcused absence
Friday prompted the drug test.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Budroyale was honored earlier in the day as the
California-bred Horse of the Year for 1999. Breeder Cecilia Straub
was presented with a trophy in a winner's-circle ceremony....
Scholars Studio ($11.40) and Corey Nakatani led for 1 1/8 miles to
upset Smooth Player in the La Canada Stakes for 4-year-old fillies.
It was the first stakes victory for the daughter of Bertrando....
Expected for the Santa Anita Handicap: Budroyale, Cat Thief,
Elaborate, General Challenge, Luftikus, Saint's Honor, Chester
House and Six Below.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
