<SLUG> BC-GLF-MIKE-SCHMIDT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHMIDT STILL STRIVING TO HIT A LONG BALL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (rk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Mike Schmidt was ready to tee off at the
10th hole of the Royal Caribbean Classic when someone yelled,
``Mike, you can't play every sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Famer smiled. At age 50, after hitting 548 home runs
and winning 10 Gold Gloves for the Philadelphia Phillies, Schmidt
is trying to forge a second professional career on the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole golf goal thing is probably going to fall into a
one- to three-year period of my life,'' Schmidt said after
finishing the tournament tied with Terry Dill and Jim Ferree for
61st among the 78 participants at the Crandon Golf Course. ``I
won't say I won't play golf the rest of my life. But as far as
seeing how far I can go on the serious side of golf, it'll probably
be a one- to three-year period. Four at the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, who works out three mornings a week for 1 1/2 hours and
plays golf about every day, said he has a weak lower back, faces
knee replacement surgery after already having four knee operations,
has waning eyesight and fair skin that makes him vulnerable to the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, my guess is at around 54, 55, 56, you'll get to a
point that physically you just don't have it any more to play at a
level you want to play at,'' said Schmidt, who seeks to join the
former Yankees pitcher Ralph Terry and the former 49ers quarterback
John Brodie as men who have had success on the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt has played golf since he was 10, when he and several
friends in Dayton, Ohio, would use a distant tree as a target. But
golf was purely recreational with him until his retirement from
baseball in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   During the last Senior Tour qualifying school, he made it to the
second round, but rounds of 80 and 74 left him short of gaining his
tour card. He played here at the Royal Caribbean Classic on a
sponsor's exemption, as officials chose him over Lee Elder, a
previous champion of the event. Schmidt expects to use his other
sponsor exemptions for two Florida tournaments, in Sarasota and
Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to play about 16 events on the Celebrity Players
Tour and the newly formed Golden Bear Senior Tour, which begins in
June.
</P>
<P>
   What are his chances of a successful conversion? Bruce Fleisher,
the 1999 Senior Tour rookie and player of the year, said it can be
done, but the difficulty shouldn't be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing against the Gary Players of the world, guys who
have been spoon-fed golf all their lives,'' Fleisher said. ``People
don't realize how good the guys are out here, that they've prepared
for tournament golf all their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, who frequently drives the ball 300 yards or more,
decided to get serious about his short game several years ago, but
it is still a work in progress. His biggest problem, however,
remains himself.
</P>
<P>
   He readily acknowledges that he needs to follow the approach: if
you want to gain control, you have to give up control.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be the greatest quote I've ever heard about hitting a
golf ball,'' Schmidt said. ``My nature is to try to be too perfect
with every shot. When I play that way, I have a tendency to
decelerate on my swing, try to guide the ball. I'm not flowing
freely, and straight golf shots are all about freedom of motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt allows his regular caddie, Paul Sankey, to control his
game during tournaments. Sankey chooses Schmidt's clubs, reads the
greens, tries to help unclutter his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He allows me to take as much thinking out of the game as I
can, because I tend to bind myself up,'' Schmidt said. ``I start
getting to many thoughts in my mind. The game's a lot simpler than
I make it. Some day I'll let it be that way. Let it get to that
point.''
</P>
<P>
   From Sankey's perspective, Schmidt clearly has the talent for
the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can get over the hump of staying out of his own way
mentally, not letting the negative thoughts creep in there and
alter his swing in any way, he could be a factor tomorrow,'' Sankey
said. ``He kind of gets it in his head that he's almost afraid to
fail. Therefore he tries to make everything perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his fellow golfers, Schmidt has been well received in his
debut on the tour. Several people have asked for autographs, and
more than a few have approached him to say they are delighted he is
giving the Senior Tour more exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Dougherty, who played with Schmidt on Saturday, even offered
him some golf advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the only mistake he saw me make all day was on the
par-5 13th,'' Schmidt said. ``He said I tried to overpower the hole
when I really didn't have to overpower it to get a birdie. He's
right. I'm learning as I go here. I consider myself where a lot of
these guys were when they played in college. I'm that far behind
experience-wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in another year or so, I'm hoping to be playing at a
different level.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
