<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLY OF JAPAN'S PRIME MINISTER IS FIRST WOMAN ELECTED GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A former civil servant from Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi's party on Sunday became the first woman to win a
governorship in Japan in a race seen here as an important gauge of
support for Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   The election victory by Fusae Ota, a former senior official of
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry, was in Japan's
second largest prefecture, Osaka. It was seen by many political
analysts here as the green light sought by Obuchi to dissolve
parliament quickly and call new legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
   Ota was supported by the national organizations of all three
parties of the governing coalition and, surprisingly, by the
Democratic Party, the country's leading opposition formation. She
was favored all along to win the special election called because
her predecessor resigned after a sexual harassment suit involving a
young campaign worker.
</P>
<P>
   But the local branch of Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party
considered the 48-year-old Ota to be an outsider imposed by the
capital, clouding the contest. In Japan, Osaka has something of the
electoral reputation of New Hampshire, distrusting candidates with
powerful national endorsements, and often producing surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Ota defeated Makoto Ajisaka, a philosophy professor whose
candidacy was supported by the Communist Party. In the last
election, Ajisaka came in a strong second behind Knock Yokoyama,
who resigned in December.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi, whose opinion poll numbers have remained low since he
formed a three-party coalition with a Buddhist-affiliated party
last fall, is now expected to push through a new budget and
promptly call new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure to call new elections has increased sharply in recent
days since Obuchi's allies pushed through passage of a
controversial parliamentary seat-reduction plan without debate. In
protest, the opposition parties have boycotted the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, in the first sign that the opposition might be backing
down, the leader of the Democratic Party, Yukio Hatoyama, said the
boycott would end if the governing parties would commit to future
debate of controversial items. He called his proposal ``a rule of
democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
