<HEADLINE>
GENERALS MASTERMINDED EAST TIMOR TERROR, LEAKED PAPERS PROVE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EXCLUSIVE `Independent' Report)   (RESENDING from Friday, Feb. 4)  
  
 (This EXCLUSIVE 400-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI _ Senior Indonesian generals masterminded a campaign of
repression and coercion in East Timor, in a desperate attempt to
prevent the territory from voting for independence, according to
secret military letters obtained by The Independent.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, recovered from military premises by human-rights
workers in the East Timorese capital, Dili, provide the first
conclusive evidence of what has long been suspected, but never
proved _ that, for months before the United Nations referendum on
East Timor's independence last August, it was being systematically
undermined by the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated denials by Indonesia, the documents show that
the army was supplying scores of automatic weapons to its local
militia groups and pro-Jakarta puppets in the local government who
used them to murderous effect in the first half of last year.
</P>
<P>
   In blatant violation of the agreement signed by their government
in the United Nations, officers in Dili asked for naval ships to
distribute free rice among the people, as a means of bribing voters
in last August's referendum to support continuing association with
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, having accepted the likelihood of defeat, the
military hatched and executed a plan for a massive so-called
``evacuation'' _ the forced deportation of 250,000 people into
Indonesian West Timor, after the overwhelming vote for independence
was announced in early September.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, copies of which have been provided by The
Independent to Indonesian human-rights investigators in Jakarta,
implicate officers at every level of the military hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the missing link,'' said one western diplomat, after The
Independent showed him the documents. ``It connects the military to
the use of repression and coercion, and it shows a clear chain of
command from close to the very top.''
</P>
<P>
   The most damning document is a letter from the army
chief-of-staff, General Subagyo Hadi Siswoyo to the then-military
commander in Dili, and copied to senior figures in the military
hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   It consists of an order, ``to prepare a security plan to prevent
civil war that includes... repressive/coercive measures and a plan
to move to the rear/evacuate if the second option (independence) is
chosen.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents will add to pressure for war crimes prosecutions
against those implicated in last September's violence.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's most powerful general, Wiranto, continued to defy
calls for his resignation by the country's president, Abdurrahman
Wahid, increasing fears of a dangerous split between the army and
civilian establishments. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 400-word EXCLUSIVE report from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
