<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPLORERS-VS-ADVENTURERS-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIST SEEKS VIRGIN TERRITORY FOR RESEARCH, NOT RECORDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from Friday, Feb. 4)   (This 575-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By CLARE GARNER  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are still unexplored places on the Earth; and in many
cases it is scientists, rather than adventurers, who want to get
there first.
</P>
<P>
   The seabed and space are not the only final frontiers; pockets
of the globe, from the impenetrable jungle in the center of South
America to the high ice desert of Greenland and the tributaries of
the Blue Nile in Ethiopia, remain virgin territory for scientific
explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel John Blashford-Snell, the chairman of Britain's
Scientific Exploration Society and an unstoppable explorer at 63,
is launching a five-year program to tackle as many untrodden areas
of the world as possible.
</P>
<P>
   He is seeking self-funded volunteers to go on the expeditions,
which would last between two and three weeks, but they must
understand that the emphasis is on research rather than
record-breaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the areas left are some of the most difficult and
inhospitable. The people who want to go in there and do exploration
have got to be slightly nuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between explorers and adventurers. An
adventurer goes somewhere and does something frightfully difficult
to find out something about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``An explorer sets out to find out something about the place.''
Physical challenges do not interest the colonel. ``Any fool can be
uncomfortable,'' he said. ``Soon there will be someone crossing the
Atlantic in a bath tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are interested in is finding new forms of medical
cures, new animals and new ways of helping people. You can't be in
this game without being a conservationist.''
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Blashford-Snell's last trip, in October, was a
reconnaissance for a three-month expedition through the
little-known Paraguayan Gran Chaco, an area of inhospitable thorn
forest where some of the Indian tribes have never had contact with
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a green desert,'' he said. ``I didn't see anyone. I
saw Indians' tracks, but they were afraid to approach me.''
</P>
<P>
   In March he is off to investigate herbal medicines in Guyana,
home to the Wai-Wai tribe of hunter-gatherers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most fascinating areas on his list is, he believes,
the Great Atrato Swamp in the Darien jungle between Panama and
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are pockets along the border which are pretty much
unexplored,'' he said. ``It's a fathomless swamp, a vast medieval
morass full of mosquitoes, alligators and very few people.
Expeditions try to go in there but fail.''
</P>
<P>
   The list includes the hill country of Burma, which has been
penetrated rarely since 1946 because of the closed border, and the
Kalahari desert. Unlike the Sahara with its sand dunes, it
comprises bush and scrub.
</P>
<P>
   There are rumors about treasures and lost cities, but Colonel
Blashford-Snell doubts they exist. The real reason for going would
be to learn about ``the bugs and beetles.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 575-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
