A8485 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-TULSA-`BLACK-HOLOCAUS     02-06 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TULSA-`BLACK-HOLOCAUST'-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TULSA CONFRONTS ITS 1921 RACIAL `ETHNIC CLEANSING'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: TIMELY for Black History Month!)   (RESENDING from Friday, Feb. 4)  
  
 (This compelling 725-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tulsa tried hard to forget its darkest days for
seventy years. But now, the city in Oklahoma is remembering one of
the worst racial atrocities in American history, and may act to
compensate the victims.
</P>
<P>
   White residents of Tulsa stormed the black part of town on May
31, 1921. When they had finished, perhaps 300 people were dead. And
a prosperous and thriving place which had been called the Black
Wall Street was still burning, with 35 city blocks left in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for decades the event was swept under the carpet; a black
man was even blamed for starting the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble started when a young black man was rumored to have
grabbed a white girl by the arm in an elevator. He was arrested,
and rumors swept the city that he would be lynched.
</P>
<P>
   A confrontation between white and black Tulsans exploded into
violence, and white rioters destroyed the black parts of the city.
The state's National Guard arrived, too late to be much help
anyway. But in the event, they used heavy machine guns to kill
blacks who had not fled the city.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the bodies have never been found and the death toll was
persistently given as much lower _ perhaps three dozen.
</P>
<P>
   One of the grimmest tasks of those probing the incident has been
to search the city cemetery for what are thought to be mass graves.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is often called a ``race riot,'' but it was much
more than a riot. Some reports from the time said that high
explosives and aircraft were used to destroy the area.
</P>
<P>
   This was ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no doubt about what the white residents of Tulsa
wanted to do. One of the postcards of the time (Americans would
often send each other postcards about these vile events) reads:
``Running the Blacks out of Tulsa.''
</P>
<P>
   The point, as in Croatia or Bosnia, was to remove the people,
not just to murder.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, white Americans were ethnically cleansing
communities during the period, sometimes called the Black
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   In Forsyth County in Georgia, a notorious nest of racism, over
1,000 black citizens were driven from the area in 1912 after the
rape and murder of a white woman and the lynching of her accused
assailant.
</P>
<P>
   Things don't change much. In the last census, Forsyth County had
28 black residents out of 75,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The Tulsa atrocity was by no means alone. Between the end of the
nineteenth century and the 1930s, American whites on many occasions
attacked blacks en masse.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Washington, East St. Louis, and across the country,
hundreds, perhaps thousands were killed. All the while, lynching
was claiming the lives of one black man every week at the height of
the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa has tried, since 1997, to investigate the killings. The
commission set up to investigate the Tulsa atrocity met Friday to
consider how to right the wrong, and was discussing an offer of $12
million in compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not feel that this will come close to making those
affected whole,'' said Jim Lloyd, a local lawyer on the commission.
But it would make a start, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of reparations is not new. Florida granted $2.1
million in reparations in 1994 for a riot that destroyed the black
community of Rosewood in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   A local politician has suggested that the city and state pay $3
million each for the Tulsa killings. At least one other such
atrocity, in Arkansas, is also being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an emotional issue. We don't want to limit any view, any
debate,'' said Bob Blackburn, who chairs the commission on the
issue. ``We want the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   America's leading black organization, the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP,) grew out of a
conference to protest against an atrocity in Springfield, Ill., in
1908, and it continues to press for justice for those who suffered
in the these atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general idea of reparations is to somehow make whole,''
said Julian Bond, chairman of the NAACP. ``There is no way that
money can make whole such a grievous wrong. It is more the
acknowledgment that some wrong has been done.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 725-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
