<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-REGROUP-NYT     02-06 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REGROUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETOOLING TO PORTRAY BUSH AS THE REAL MAN OF ACTION
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hoping to steal some of Sen. John McCain's
thunder, Gov. George W. Bush is poised to argue that McCain has
made little to no headway in his battle against the sway of special
interests in government and that Bush has accomplished much more in
this regard, advisers to Bush said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush and his aides emerged from discussions here this weekend
about how to regain the upper hand in the newly fierce contest for
the Republican presidential nomination, the Bush campaign signaled
that it was prepared to do more than simply question the honesty of
McCain's claim of being a lonely crusader against the corruption of
government. Bush began pursuing that line of attack late last week.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this week, Bush or his allies will point out that as
governor of Texas, Bush bucked trial lawyers to enact tort
legislation and took on teacher associations to carry out education
reforms. Simultaneously, the Bush campaign will note that McCain's
quest to overhaul campaign financing laws has been unsuccessful
thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator McCain doesn't have near the record of getting things
done,'' said one aide to Bush in an interview Sunday, giving a
preview of the oratory to come. ``Governor Bush is a reformer who
actually has a record of accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy is part of an array of adjustments that the
Bush campaign is plotting or considering, many of which are clearly
designed to strike at the heart of McCain's image and appeal, blunt
his impact, appropriate some of his themes and cast Bush in a newly
aggressive light.
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend in Texas, his first break from campaigning since
his overwhelming defeat by McCain in the New Hampshire primary,
Bush will hit the road again on Monday, bound first for Delaware,
which holds its primary on Tuesday, and then for South Carolina,
which holds its primary on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see Governor Bush come out charging,'' said Ari
Fleischer, a spokesman for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer declined to get into specifics, but others affiliated
with the Bush campaign outlined several ways in which Bush or his
allies will intensify their engagement of McCain. The developments
demonstrated that the Bush campaign, which seemed at first to
dismiss New Hampshire as an aberration, is taking the threat the
Arizona senator poses more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Bush campaign unveiled a new television
commercial in South Carolina that charged McCain with lying in one
of his advertisements by implying that Bush's tax proposal did not
save enough money for Social Security. The Bush campaign's
commercial further likened McCain to a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   This week, according to an aide to Bush, the campaign will run a
spot in South Carolina that asserts that McCain's advertisement
broke a pledge he made with the Bush not to engage in negative
attacks. The new Bush commercial will feature videotape of McCain
and Bush entering into that agreement with a handshake in a debate
in January.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also plans to divert attention from McCain's
unassailable military heroism, from which he derives much of his
popular appeal, to what it sees as a dearth of accomplishments in
McCain's nearly two decades on Capitol Hill. The campaign will also
emphasize the broad span of McCain's time inside the Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be anything negative against him personally and it
won't be anything disrespectful,'' said one adviser to Bush. ``But
there's a 17-year gap in the coverage of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a very distinguished record of military service that we
honor,'' the adviser continued. ``But he also has a 17-year record
as a Washington insider. We're going to make sure the voters know
what that record is. There's a gap between Senator McCain's
rhetoric and his record that's as wide as the Grand Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, the chief strategist for the Bush campaign,
articulated that theme in remarks about McCain in an interview with
CNN late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's failed in his major crusades and causes, which are and
have been and remain to reform campaign finance laws and to raise
taxes on tobacco, as best we can tell,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been discussions among officials in the Bush
campaign about how to counter impressions, which many of the
officials deem unfair, that Bush is insufficiently accessible and
overly guarded.
</P>
<P>
   These talks acknowledge the success of McCain's practice of
riding in a bus crowded with reporters who are able to talk with
him almost constantly, and who have come to regard him more
favorably as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign exhibits no doubt that Bush is the better,
worthier candidate. But aides recognize that the charm and mental
quickness that Bush exhibits in one-on-one interactions with voters
or reporters have not always come across in his campaign events. So
the nature of Bush's schedule, too, is under review.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a human touch, a personal touch, that most candidates
don't have,'' said one aide. ``The campaign needs to do a better
job in showing that.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bush began to do last week, the campaign will provide
forceful retorts not only to McCain's criticisms of Bush's tax
plan, but also to McCain's implications that Bush is not ready to
lead the country.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Fox News Sunday,'' former Gov. Carroll Campbell of South
Carolina, a major supporter of Bush, hammered home the point that
unlike McCain, Bush is a chief executive with ultimate
responsibility for affairs in the state he governs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had to sit in the chair,'' Campbell said. ``He's had to
make life-and-death decisions. He's had to handle crises, he's had
to handle storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is a good guy,'' Campbell added, but ``he's had no
experience with handling those types of things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2147EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
