<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8547 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-ALLSTAR-GAME-NYT &LR;      02-06 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ALLSTAR-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURES TALK, AND PLAY, A GREAT GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Jaromir Jagr, Pavel Bure, Paul Kariya and Eric Lindros
spent most of Friday on a frozen pond an hour and a half from here,
filming a television spot with Gordie Howe, Wayne Gretzky and Mario
Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   The segment served as an introduction to ABC's coverage of the
50th NHL All-Star game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Its premise was simple: that this season, and this game in
particular, represented a changing of the guard.
</P>
<P>
   Bure did not let the league down Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He recorded the 11th hat trick in All-Star game history, with
two assists coming from his brother, Valery. Pavel Bure's three
goals led the World team to a 9-4 victory over North America at a
sold-out Air Canada Center. It was the World team's first victory
since the current format of the game was started three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With his mother, Tatyana, watching from the stands while her
sons played on the same line for the first time in North America,
Pavel Bure of the Florida Panthers was selected the game's most
valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Bure, 28, leads the league with 37 goals, one more than
Jagr, the Pittsburgh Penguin. Calgary's Valery Bure, 25, has scored
28 goals, fifth most in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bure deferred to his brother and played left wing
Sunday on a line that was centered by their countryman Viktor
Kozlov, who is Pavel's linemate in Florida. Pavel Bure (three goals
and one assist), Valery Bure (two assists) and Kozlov (three
assists) combined for nine points.
</P>
<P>
   There could have been more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually kind of a funny situation,'' Pavel Bure said.
``After the second period, we were talking in the dressing room. I
said: `If we have a two-on-one, just go to the off post. I will
give you a pass and you shoot it right away.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers right wing had already scored two goals in the
second period and completed the hat trick midway through the final
period when his words became reality. With three minutes left, the
Bure brothers were skating on a two-on-one break against Rangers
goaltender Mike Richter.
</P>
<P>
   But Valery did not listen to his brother. Instead of shooting
when Pavel gave him the puck, Valery tried to set Pavel up for a
fourth goal. Philadelphia defenseman Eric Desjardins broke up the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Valery Bure said afterward with a smile. ``Younger
brother never listen to older one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bure brothers did become the first siblings to team up on an
All-Star game goal since Maurice Richard and Henri Richard did so
in the 1957 and 1958 games. Bure's nickname, the Russian Rocket,
derives from Maurice Richard's, which is the Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of fitting,'' said Devils goaltender Martin Brodeur, who
allowed Pavel Bure's two second-period goals.
</P>
<P>
   If the sport's symbolic torch had been passed from Gretzky to
Jagr last April 18, when Jagr scored the game-winning goal in
overtime at Madison Square Garden in Gretzky's final game, it might
have been passed from Jagr to Bure here Sunday, even though Jagr
also had a goal and an assist.
</P>
<P>
   But even in retirement, Gretzky remains the league's foremost
spokesman. And his presence this weekend seemed to overshadow the
game itself, which often lacked the kind of excitement that Gretzky
routinely provided.
</P>
<P>
   Beforehand, Gretzky's No. 99 was retired throughout the league
in a banner-raising ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   During the second intermission, Gretzky gave an unofficial state
of the game address, much more candid that the one that NHL
Commissioner Gary Bettman had delivered in the same setting the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   Most interesting was Gretzky's discussion of the Canadian
government's recent reversal and rejection of a tax-based
assistance plan.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described traditionalist, Gretzky cannot imagine a league
without small-market Canadian teams, especially the Edmonton
Oilers, whom Gretzky led to four Stanley Cups in five seasons in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But Gretzky also said something that might not go over well with
Bettman. ``It's pretty simple,'' he said. ``The whole country is
based upon hard-working, 9-to-5 parents who do the best they can to
provide for their families. And a small percentage of the country
is people who are making over a million dollars a year. The average
person can't understand how people who are making $5 million to $6
million a year American need tax benefits. And how can you blame
them?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
