<HEADER>
A8543 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SOAP-OPERAS-WASHED-UP     02-06 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOAP-OPERAS-WASHED-UP?-600&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAS THE BUBBLE BURST FOR AMERICAN SOAP OPERAS?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Note 150-word trim; total uncut is 950)   (This excellent 800-word (trimmed) ``separate-buy'' article is from
the current (week beginning 5 February 2000) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her
e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``e''
entertainment news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buzz feels terrible about ratting on Michelle, Vanessa is ill
because someone has secretly poisoned her lip balm, and Josh is
dithering between Reva and Olivia _ another typical week in
Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Over in Oakdale, meanwhile, Abigail and Chris have awakened
locked in the library, while Phillips has been bribing Chinese-food
delivery men to slip menacing fortune cookies to Carly and Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Tales of thwarted love, vengeful scheming and family anguish
have been at the heart of American television from its earliest
days.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the longest-running soap operas _ ``Guiding Light,'' home
to the unhappy Buzz, and ``As the World Turns,'' the annals of
Oakdale _ are well into their fifth decades on CBS (and ``Guiding
Light'' had run since 1937 on the radio before switching medium in
1953).
</P>
<P>
   Yet this durable form is showing signs of weariness. Audiences
for daytime soap opera have declined by 83 percent since 1991; the
11 shows that now run on the three old national networks each lost
viewers over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that soap and household-goods manufacturers such as
Procter &AMP; Gamble, which owns both ``Guiding Light'' and ``As the
World Turns,'' sponsored ``soap'' operas in the first place was the
size of their female audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Yet among women aged between 18 and 49, the bulk of the viewers
of the interminable sagas, the fraction watching the shows fell by
up to a quarter in the year between the autumn season of 1998 and
autumn 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The worst performing of the bunch, ``Sunset Beach'' on NBC, a
relative youngster launched as recently as 1997, has been cancelled
after failing to hook enough viewers (although it has roared ahead
in other markets such as Britain).
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not that torrid goings-on in the suburbs are
losing their appeal, but that increased work outside the home means
that fewer women are free to watch during the day and, for those
that do still have the time, there are more alternatives vying for
their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Courtroom dramas, such as ``Judge Judy'' and ``Divorce Court,''
in which actual cases are heard by a jurist, bring to the screen
some of the same elements of family vituperation that keep soap
fans in a lather. But they have the added frisson that the
disasters they depict are for real.
</P>
<P>
   They are also cheaper to make than soap operas, requiring only
one set and generally a smaller cast.
</P>
<P>
   As their audiences have grown, these shows have proliferated
across the daytime television schedules _ seven more are in the
works, including such alarming sounding titles as ``Moral Court''
and ``Judge Hatchett,'' both bought by networks at NATPE, the
television industry's big annual trade fair, held in New Orleans in
late January.
</P>
<P>
   Other relatively cheap programs that have thrived at the expense
of the soaps are chat and quiz shows, although the success of ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' on ABC is pulling the newest quiz
programs into the evening ``prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is having a mixed effect on the soaps. While online
browsing for books, beanie babies and mutual funds does eat into
the time available to spend in front of a television screen, the
Internet has acres of chat rooms devoted to favorite soaps.
</P>
<P>
   These stoke their fans' enthusiasm with discussions of whether
characters are behaving true to their family history or whether
things have gone downhill during the decades that the fans have
been following the series. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 600) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the longer term, the Internet's interactive potential may
increase the appeal of soap operas by allowing fans not merely to
gasp at what the characters have been getting up to, but actively
to meddle in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the hottest new ideas for prime time involve an
online element which, if successful, could be injected into daytime
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The networks, for example, have just been involved in a bidding
war for the right to make an American version of ``Big Brother,'' a
Dutch program which puts a group of young people in a house
festooned with cameras and then lets the audience vote on who gets
to remain on the program as it proceeds from day to day.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of several European programs being adapted for
American television that have been picked up by the networks in the
aftermath of the success of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,''
which started in Britain. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 950) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The networks persevere with traditional soap operas because,
despite the erosion of their audience, they remain the best way to
offer advertisers the chance to reach a lot of women viewers with
one commercial. Once they take hold, they generate tenacious
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   And continuity from episode to episode does not depend on one
person, as it does with chat shows, which live and die by their
host, and court programs, each of which relies on a powerful
personality in the judge's chair. Rather they rely on a rich, not
to say overripe, stew of characters.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the networks is to keep on hooking new viewers
who can take over from the older ones. To this end, they are
introducing younger characters into their programs and even aiming
to entice some of the teenagers who make ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' a big hit on evening television.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, a witch with a magic doll in one new
show, ``Passions,'' launched on NBC in July last year. Her potions
might spell bad news for Buzz. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this lively 800-word (trimmed) ECONOMIST article, it
must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York
Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480,
or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-STERLING-FOREST-43     02-06 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STERLING-FOREST-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 NEW YORK ACQUIRES FINAL PIECES OF STATE PARK JUST NORTH OF NEW YORK
CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, environmentalists dreamed of acquiring and
preserving for all time the vast, privately owned tracts of
beguiling woodlands, rugged ridges, hiking trails and crystalline
streams and lakes known as Sterling Forest, 40 miles northwest of
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 New York state acquired 15,280 acres, the bulk of the
property, for $55 million in federal, state and private funds.
Since then, environmental groups and the state have added 1,500
acres through purchases and gifts. But that still left some 2,200
acres exposed to developers and their bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, however, Gov. George Pataki, who hiked and skied
through the forest as a boy and was a major force in the deal two
years ago, is to go to Bear Mountain State Park and formally
announce arrangements to acquire three last parcels, completing the
consolidation of 19,000 contiguous acres into Sterling Forest State
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stand on top of Bear Mountain, to see Manhattan to the
southwest and New Jersey to the southeast and now to have this
unbroken string of wilderness preserved, is very gratifying,'' the
governor said Sunday. ``It will be important to future generations,
and it is an opportunity that we will never have again.''
</P>
<P>
   In a complex arrangement, the state is to acquire a total of
2,218 privately held acres in three parcels for $9.47 million, with
most of the money coming from the state, and much of the rest from
the federal government, environmental groups and the Palisades
Interstate Park Commission. Not all the financing is in place, and
the Pataki administration hopes that New Jersey will contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Besides enlarging the forest, which straddles the New York-New
Jersey border the deal to be announced Monday will marginalize
development to a few areas, blocking plans that once called for
13,000 homes, 8 million square feet of commercial buildings, golf
courses and other projects in what is now forest.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said the enlargement of one of New York state's
largest parks would also help to protect the quality of the
forest's streams, which flow through the Ramapo River Watershed and
supply drinking water for most of northern New Jersey, about 25
percent of the state's 8 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Title to the new parcels will be taken by the Palisades
Interstate Park Commission, which operates Sterling Forest State
Park and 23 other parks in New York and New Jersey. The commission
has begun to implement plans for parking areas, picnic tables,
beaches and bathrooms, but has said it does not intend to encourage
overuse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The new acquisitions involve several intricate arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   In one, Pataki said the state had reached an agreement with the
Zurich Centre Group, a Swiss insurance company, to purchase the
largest of the three parcels _ 1,350 acres, including a 100-acre
conference center on the south end of Sterling Lake _ for $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Of that total, the state will contribute $4 million and the
Federal Forest Legacy Program will put up $2 million. The
administration hopes to raise the rest from a partnership of
environmental groups and from the state of New Jersey, which
contributed $10 million to the 1998 purchase. The state hopes to
close the transaction by January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The second parcel, 659 acres of rugged terrain bordering the
eastern edge of the forest west of Tuxedo Park, has already been
purchased from New York University for $860,000. The state's
Environmental Protection Fund, which provides $125 million a year
for a wide range of environmental programs, put up $360,000, while
the Trust for Public Land and the Palisades Interstate Park
Commission contributed $250,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   The third parcel, 209 acres in the Town of Warwick on the west
side of the forest, has been bought for $610,000 from B. Sears
Hunter and the Lawrence W. Copans Trust. The Environmental
Protection Fund contributed the money for the acreage, some of
which borders on Greenwood Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who has been praised by environmentalists for his role
in arranging a series of land purchases by the state, including
large tracts in the Adirondacks, was buoyant Sunday as he spoke
about the forest where he hiked as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very personal thing for me, no question about it,''
he said. ``I've lived in the Hudson Valley all my life. This
magnificent undeveloped property, so close to New York City _ it
was just critical to preserve this. The recreational opportunities,
the Ramapo watershed, are just added bonuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of what is now Sterling Forest, the scene of a thriving
iron industry in the 19th century, was bought in 1895 by the
Harriman Railroad family, which sold it in 1953 to a real estate
developer who set up Sterling Forest Co. The company developed 250
homes and offices in scattered areas but ran into financial
problems and tried for years to unload the property.
</P>
<P>
   The public acquisition of Sterling Forest was first envisioned
in 1985 by Paul Dolan, an ABC News executive, and his wife, JoAnn,
executive director of the New York-New Jersey Trail Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was given some urgency in 1993 when the private
owners spoke of a utopian city for 35,000 inhabitants and 20,000
workers, a complex that would dwarf all but a few communities
between New York City and Albany. Critics said the development
threat was a bargaining strategy to raise land prices and get top
dollar from environmental groups and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of government and private groups, with Pataki
playing a major role, finally raised $55 million for the bulk of
the forest _ $17.5 million in federal funds, $16 million from New
York, $10 million from New Jersey, $5 million from the Doris Duke
Charitable Foundation, $5 million from the Lila Acheson and DeWitt
Wallace Fund for the Hudson Highlands and the rest from other
private groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``By working together, we have created an incredible state park
for generations of New Yorkers to hike its trails, gaze over its
scenic vistas and enjoy the peaceful sounds of the forest,'' Pataki
said. ``At the same time, we are continuing to protect drinking
water for millions of New York and New Jersey residents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
