u p BC-NY-BRADLEY-NYT     02-06 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARPTON CALLS FOR DEBATE ON RACIAL ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.Y., S.C.)   (jw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rev. Al Sharpton called on Vice President Al Gore
Sunday to debate former Sen. Bill Bradley on race and urban issues,
and he hinted that he would encourage black voters in New York to
support Bradley if Gore did not do so.
</P>
<P>
   With Bradley at his side in a news conference at the Allen
A.M.E. Church in Jamaica, Queens, Sharpton said that he had only
found what he characterized as disturbing signals or feigned
indifference from the Gore campaign on racial issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we want a response by the end of the week,'' Sharpton
said of the proposal for a debate. If Gore does not accept, he
added, ``then certainly some of us may mobilize against his
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said he wanted the debate to be held in front of a
black audience in New York City before the primary on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Sunday, Gore had received no formal offer for a
debate from Sharpton or the Rev. Floyd Flake, the minister of the
church and a former congressman from Queens, said Peter Ragone, a
spokesman for Gore's campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ragone repeated Gore's offer to debate Bradley twice a week in
exchange for eliminating television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   With most polls showing Gore and Bradley in a tight race in New
York, support from black voters is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has won the endorsement of State Comptroller H. Carl McCall
and Rep. Charles Rangel of Harlem and has garnered the support of
many black organizations and prominent blacks around the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, with his stop Sunday in Queens and with other
events, was making race relations a central issue. On Tuesday, he
will be in South Carolina, where the Republicans, but not the
Democrats, will hold a primary on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley aides said he would use the trip to discuss whether the
Confederate flag should fly over the State Capitol and to criticize
Gov. George W. Bush's recent speech at Bob Jones University, the
fundamentalist Christian college that lost its tax-exempt status in
1970 for racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, in a speech at the church in Queens, Bradley repeated
many of his familiar themes: race relations, health care, gun
control and poverty. But he also suffused his remarks with a tinge
of religion, a subject he normally shies away from.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, he watched as Sharpton and Flake praised
his efforts to reach out to minority voters and criticized those of
his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said that Gore needed to make amends with blacks in New
York over his 1988 presidential campaign. That year, Gore was
competing against the Rev. Jesse Jackson, among others, and during
the New York primary, Gore's ally, Mayor Ed Koch, was engaged in a
public and ugly feud with Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said Gore also needed to visit more black neighborhoods
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he was unhappy that Housing Secretary Andrew M.
Cuomo, a supporter of Gore, was considering a bid for governor in
2002, a race McCall was expected to enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that you want to marry you usually court,'' Sharpton
said. ``You don't expect a marriage before courting, and so far,
we've only been dated by Sen. Bradley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
