<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-PEBBLE-BEACH-NYT &LR;      02-06 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PEBBLE-BEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDERS SHARE LEAD; WOODS IN HUNT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ After the fog lifted at Pebble Beach
Sunday, nobody gained a clear advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The leader board will be crowded heading into Monday's final
round, in a weather-delayed tournament that could finally reach its
conclusion. Two unexpected names shared the lead after Sunday's
third round of the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am: Mark Brooks,
who has not won since the 1996 PGA Championship, and Matt Gogel, a
tour rookie who spent the last three years on the Nike Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tiger Woods closed to within five strokes of the
lead, in his attempt to become the first player since Ben Hogan in
1948 to win six consecutive tour starts. So with Woods in the hunt,
and at least a dozen players in contention, a tournament that has
taken too long to finish may at least have a finish worth
remembering.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks and Gogel shared the lead at 12-under (204), one stroke
ahead of Vijay Singh (11-under), and two strokes ahead of Notah
Begay III (10-under). Three more players were bunched at 8-under _
Chris DiMarco, Jimmy Green, and Jay Williamson, while Woods joined
four others at 7-under _ Jay Don Blake, Jim Furyk, Jerry Kelly and
Rory Sabbatini.
</P>
<P>
   So many contenders, 18 holes left, and a Monday weather forecast
that called for possible showers. Nothing this weekend has been
easy. But Woods still believed he could win the hard way. ``It's
realistic,'' said Woods, when asked to assess his chances. ``If
it's a calm day, and you shoot around the mid-60s, you will be
right in the hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Gogel, who shot a 67 Sunday at Pebble Beach, was threatening to
win in only his second month on the tour. A six-time winner on the
Nike Tour, Gogel has already been in contention once this year,
finishing tied for seventh at the Bob Hope Chrysler Invitational.
Could Gogel overcome final-day pressure and outplay former major
winners like Singh, Woods and Brooks? Gogel was about to find out,
and he admitted that he expected Woods to make a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is certainly the best player in the world by quite a large
margin right now,'' Gogel said. ``You know he is going to put on a
charge. I can't control what Tiger is going to do. I'm going to
have enough worries just handling myself in the final group.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day eight strokes behind Singh, the second-round
leader, Woods shot a 68 in a round that included five birdies and
one bogey. However, Woods' bogey at No. 8 could have easily been a
double-bogey, or worse, if not for a remarkable recovery shot.
</P>
<P>
   After his second shot at No. 8 drifted right of the green into
tall grass near a cliff by the ocean, Woods was fortunate that
marshals found his ball after a two-minute search, saving him a
penalty stroke. The ball was buried deep in the grass behind a
greenside bunker, about 40 yards from the pin, and only a few feet
from a cliff edge that dropped about 50 feet to the ocean. The edge
of the cliff prevented Woods from taking a normal stance, but he
somehow muscled the ball out of the deep grass high into the air
and onto the green, about 20 feet from the pin. Woods two-putted
for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get my balance, hit it as hard as I could, and
somehow get it to where I could play it again,'' Woods said. ``I
was just hoping to get it out of there, maybe in the front bunker
or something. It could have been a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks surged into a tie for the lead with one of the best
rounds of the day, a 66 at Poppy Hills, while Furyk had the day's
best round, a 64 at Pebble Beach. Singh settled for an even-par 72
at Spyglass Hill Sunday, as did Begay, and their failure to pull
away allowed their pursuers to close ground.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, eyes will be on Woods, who spent 25 minutes after
Sunday's round working on his putting stroke with his coach, Butch
Harmon. The celebrity pro-am format has made it difficult for all
the professionals to establish a rhythm, with some rounds taking
longer than six hours. Woods played the first three rounds behind a
foursome that included two comedians, Tommy Smothers and Ray
Romano. Smothers joked with spectators at every hole, and Woods'
round on Saturday took 6 hours 17 minutes to complete.
</P>
<P>
   But it remained to be seen if anyone would get in the way of
Woods' streak. A five-stroke deficit will be difficult for Woods to
overcome, but Begay, who was Woods' teammate at Stanford, knew that
it was always dangerous to count Woods out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of Stanford guys chasing,'' said Begay,
referring to himself and Woods. ``Matt might be hearing footsteps
behind him tonight.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
