<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN MAKES BRIEF STATE STOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the day before Arizonans can begin voting for or against him
for president, John McCain swept into Phoenix on Sunday for a
festive rally and declared he would win the state. Then he boarded
a plane for Michigan, not to return perhaps until close to the
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still the underdog, we're still running an insurgency
campaign. But I can't tell you how excited I am,'' McCain told a
crowd of about 250 during a 15-minute appearance at Sky Harbor
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's quick visit was sym bolic of how the campaign ap pears
to developing here, and does not bode well for those who hoped the
GOP primary in Ari zona would rivet the nation. The primary is Feb.
22, but voters can begin mailing in ballots Monday.
</P>
<P>
   None of the candidates is ex pected to campaign in the state
much over the next two weeks, preferring to concentrate on South
Carolina and Michigan. Aides to Texas Gov. George W. Bush said he
will make one more visit, and Publisher Steve Forbes is expected to
fly in once.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he didn't know how much time he would spend in
Arizona before the primary.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's stopover, and his recent ascension in South Caro
lina polls, come at an opportune time for his Arizona campaign, as
early voting commences. Cam paign observers have said they believe
as many as 35 percent of voters will mail in ballots.
</P>
<P>
   McCain entreated his support ers to help continue the momen tum
he began building when he walloped Bush in New Hamp shire last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about `big mo' is that it has been known to leave
you at the most inopportune times,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bush have been running about evenly in Arizona. The
most recent KAET poll showed McCain with a 7-point advantage over
Bush, with Forbes in third place.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, McCain has overcome a 20-point disadvan tage
and, according to a CNN/Time poll released Satur day, now holds a
4-point lead there over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport rally, McCain criticized Bush for running what he
called negative attack ads in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush spokesman said the ads, which focus on McCain's tax
proposal, are legitimate, and he accused McCain's campaign of
wanting to avoid normal cam paign scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically some pre-emp tive whining designed to make it
seem as though the legitimate scrutiny of their campaign is not
appropriate,'' said Jay Heiler, Bush's Arizona spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also responded to a story that appeared in The Ari zona
Republic on Sunday detail ing the investigation into the murder of
Ron Bianchi, a former Phoenix Gazette columnist.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who was questioned by authorities in the matter but
immediately ruled out as having been involved, declined to dis cuss
the story.
</P>
<P>
   `It's just so bizarre,` McCain said. `It speaks for itself.`
</P>
<P>
   McCain supporters who at tended the rally said the senator's
recent victory has sparked re newed interest in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought it?` said Irv Shuman, an independent
voter who recently re-registered as a Republican to vote for
McCain. ``The momentum is defi nitely swinging in John's favor and
I just see him going all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Sunday, McCain was asked on ABC's This Week about his
intention to hold several high dollar fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has made cam paign finance reform a center piece of
his campaign, defended the events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome the support of anyone in the form of $1,000
contributions, but they know clearly well where I stand, they know
clearly I want to break the iron triangle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was accused Friday by Bush of engaging in ``Washington
double talk'' for attacking special interests while courting their
support. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
