<SLUG> BC-NEIGHBORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKE BRINGS NEW LIFE TO NEIGHBORHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ELVIA DIAZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Tempe's forgotten neighborhood, a cheap rent ha ven where
Latin American im migrants huddled together in cramped homes, stray
bullets reverberating over their heads. Then came Town Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the used syringes and empty beer cans that covered the
streets and lawns have disappeared. Sidewalks soon will be paved.
Streets are get ting cleaned. Police officers are chasing homeless
people from nearby parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so scared to live here,'' hotel maid Adela Urbano said.
Now, the fear is gone.
</P>
<P>
   The community of 352 house holds just north of the Salt River is
being transformed into a chic, expensive spot, some residents say.
They credit _ or blame _ the two-mile artificial lake. It is touted
as a future site of a billion dollars in private development,
including luxury condominiums, expensive ho tels, specialty shops
and res taurants.
</P>
<P>
   The mere prospect of high-end resorts and classy apart ments is
contributing to soar ing property values in East Rio and the entire
north Tempe area, an enclave nestled be tween Scottsdale and east
Phoe nix.
</P>
<P>
   New condominiums and homes are selling as fast as they're being
built, real estate agents say. A few streets away from the Urbanos,
real estate agent Glenda Chase listed a 1,300-square-feet,
three-bed room home for roughly $143,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a lot of money for such a small home,'' Chase
said.
</P>
<P>
   To her surprise, the single house sold quickly and now the
owners are attempting to lease it for $1,200 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That high price is because of the lake,'' said Chase, an agent
with Clements East Valley Real ty-Better Homes and Gardens. ``It
has been an amazing change.''
</P>
<P>
   FIELDS ARE GONE
</P>
<P>
   Charles Sotomayor has seen the transformation. He bought his
three-bedroom home nearly three decades ago north of Tem pe's dry
Salt River.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was all cotton fields and mesquite,'' remembers Sotoma
yor. ``Nothing is left of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Urbanos, a young immi grant couple with two small chil dren,
bought one of the nicest houses in a neighborhood known as East
Rio.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it was far from a dream home. Adela and Heri berto
Urbano say they couldn't sleep at night, fearing random bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Dismayed by the empty beer cans covering the streets, syrin ges
scattered all over and homes splashed with graffiti, Adela fig ured
it had been mistake to buy the property.
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't dare stroll onto streets in the afternoon with her
children.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD INVESTMENT NOW
</P>
<P>
   But in less than a year, the crime-plagued ``barrio'' is quickly
catching up with more affluent neighboring enclaves. The Urbanos
know now that buying a home less than a mile north of the river bed
is turning into a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   Sotomayor bought his home for $10,000 nearly 30 years go. Last
year, it was worth $98,000. The Urbanos bought theirs for $75,000.
Now it's valued about $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   SOARING HOME PRICES
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors nearby in affluent pockets west of Scottsdale Road are
noticing the soaring home market, partly because of the proximity
to the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Homes for up to $250,000 west of Scottsdale Road are selling in
less than a week, said Jim Lem mon, head of North Tempe
Neighborhood Associations, which includes about 10 organiza tions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is phenomenal,'' Lem mon said. ``There is still a lot to
improve in some sections. But this area offers great opportuni
ties.``
</P>
<P>
   The Urbanos and Sotomayor welcome the attention and are glad
Tempe is cracking down on crime such as burglaries, drugs and
random shootings.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Urbano and others fear Latin American
immigrants that can't afford to pay pricey rent will also be chased
out. Monthly rent had averaged $500 in East Rio. Now, for instance,
a refurbished three-bedroom home is listed at $1,300 per month in
the Urbanos' neigh borhood.
</P>
<P>
   Like Urbano, Sotomayor said he is concerned that the ``Latino
barrio'' where he has spent half of his life will soon disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling developers will soon bulldoze this entire
area,'' Sotomayor said. ``The La tino barrio that kept me here will
probably be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Sotomayor prefers to stay, he would be willing to sell
and settle elsewhere else where cost of living isn't as expensive
as in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agent Chase says those living in north of the river
will keep seeing a lot more wealthy people and young profes sionals
flocking to the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the next five years,'' Chase said, ``the lake's area
will be an even greater magnet for homeowners.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2235EST &QL; 
