<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MEXICO-UNIVERSITY-BOS     02-06 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-UNIVERSITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SEIZE OCCUPIED MEXICO CITY CAMPUS?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican authorities raided the national university
before dawn Sunday, rapidly seizing control of the campus and
ending a nine-month siege that had frustrated Mexicans and
paralyzed the hemisphere's largest university.
</P>
<P>
   While hundreds of occupying students slept or huddled in
meetings with sympathetic professors, more than 2,000 federal
police officers, armed only with billy clubs, riot shields and a
court order, descended on the buildings and sprawling grounds of
the National Autonomous University of Mexico, known as UNAM, the
country's most prominent institution of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
   The strikers offered no resistance, police and witnesses said,
as they were quickly rounded up and taken into custody. Authorities
said there were no injuries and that 632 people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The quick recovery of the campus, which had been under the
strikers' control since April 20, 1999, was a major setback for the
rebel student movement. The students' extensive and often-changing
list of demands has ranged from free public education to a greater
role in administrative matters and amnesty for jailed strikers.
</P>
<P>
   The action was also a bold and unexpected move by the
government, which for months hesitated to use force against the
strikers for fear of reviving painful memories of a government
massacre of UNAM students in 1968. Those responsible for organizing
Sunday's sweep repeatedly emphasized that they carried out the
court order efficiently and nonviolently.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small group of radicals acted above the law and against the
will of 180,000 of their university colleagues,'' Interior
Secretary Diodoro Carrasco said at a media briefing after the
police sweep. ``A democratic society cannot allow the kidnapping of
its national university.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did not appear that the conflict was completely over or
that classes would resume any time soon for UNAM's 260,000 students
or its dozens of affiliated institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Angry relatives and strike supporters vowed to continue pushing
the students' agenda, which began as a protest against a proposed
tuition hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we have to find out where and how our children are,''
said Marcelino Gonzalez, whose 13-year-old son was among those
arrested at the campus and taken by government-chartered buses to
one of several Mexico City jails. ``Then we have to show the
government that we support the students and that violence and force
is not the way to resolve this.''
</P>
<P>
   The operation began just before dawn, when 2,500 officers
quickly assembled outside the barricades built by strikers. At 6
a.m. they moved in, heading first for the strikers' most important
posts, like Che Guevara auditorium in the philosophy building.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the occupiers were warned only moments before the
police arrived by students who were on lookout duty and came into
to the auditorium yelling, ``Comrades, they're coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students escaped by running out side doors and into the
surrounding neighborhoods and hills. Others tried to hide in crawl
spaces. Most of them, however, surrendered to police, raising
clenched fists as they were led onto the buses.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has been an embarrassment for university and
government authorities and a disruption _ severe, at times _ of
daily life for Mexico City residents. The strikers frequently
conducted marches along the city's main thoroughfares, clogging
rush-hour traffic and angering motorists.
</P>
<P>
   The students' initial demand was for administrators to rescind a
proposed tuition hike that would have raised the annual fee from a
few cents to $140. That request was met by the university in June,
when officials agreed to make the new tuition a voluntary expense
for students who could afford it.
</P>
<P>
   But by then, the strikers had broadened their list of demands,
calling for the resignation of Rector Francisco Barnes and
increased student involvement in university decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Officials persisted in their attempts to negotiate an agreement
with the students, who became increasingly fragmented along radical
and moderate lines.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Barnes reluctantly resigned. He was replaced by
Ramon de la Fuente, health minister under President Ernesto
Zedillo. Yet, even under the new rector, the chances of a peaceful
settlement appeared to have diminished in recent weeks as the
threat of violence between the strikers and their opponents grew
larger.
</P>
<P>
   Striking students burned American flags and clashed with police
outside the US Embassy. Several students were arrested and injured
as a result of the protest.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, students opposed to the strike, backed by university
security guards, took control of a UNAM-affiliated high school on
the east side of the capital. But the strikers returned later in
the day and retook the school. Three dozen security guards were
injured and 250 strikers were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Attorney General Jorge Madrazo obtained 432 arrest
warrants from a Mexico City judge for charges ranging from theft
and vandalism to trespassing on public property.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-hour negotiating session on Friday ended in a deadlock. The
students asked for talks to resume Monday, but officials refused.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationally broadcast speech Sunday night, Zedillo
acknowledged that he had ordered police to go into the campus
unarmed and that the operation was conducted under the watch of
government human rights observers. He also called for all Mexicans
to support the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that from this point forward, the national university
will begin its transformation to continue serving the people of
Mexico,'' Zedillo said. ``And it will continue to be our top public
university.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
