<SLUG> BC-COLUMBIA-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN STUDENT'S SLAYING, MOURNING AND MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They clung to one another in the stricken,
uncomprehending manner of young people confronting death for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Columbia University students poured into the campus
chapel on Sunday until every seat was taken, until the balconies
were full, until the entrance itself was impassable. The first rows
were reserved for Kathleen A. Roskot's family and her teammates on
Columbia's women's varsity lacrosse team, who filed in one by one,
eyes red and swollen by tears and anger.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas Valenti, a Columbia chaplain, began with an
ancient question from the Book of Job. ``Why,'' he asked, ``do bad
things happen to good people?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a question without a satisfactory answer on Sunday, the
day after Roskot, 19, a fearless and determined lacrosse player,
was found dead in her dormitory room, her throat slashed. The
police believe she was killed by her troubled former boyfriend,
Thomas G. Nelford, a Columbia dropout who killed himself by leaping
in front of a subway train shortly after Roskot's body was
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``God desires to grasp you by the hand and help you up
tonight,'' Father Valenti told Roskot's coaches, friends and family
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The university's president, George Rupp, also spoke.
``Kathleen's death is an enormous loss for all of us,'' he said.
``Even those who did not know her well feel the pain of her being
snatched from us.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others described Roskot as a supremely accomplished young
woman. ``Kathleen was a competitor who had a signature shot that
sometimes would make the team stop and gaze in amazement,'' one of
her teammates, Maureen Koons, said near the end of the service. ``I
hope she's some place where her shot hits the crossbar and sails to
the back of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll miss you, Kathleen.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the words to ``Amazing Grace'' echoed off the ornate
brickwork of St. Paul's Chapel, Roskot's team filed out along with
her family, who, like so many of her friends and neighbors on
Sunday, would not publicly discuss their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here want to grieve in peace,'' said the Rev. Thomas M.
Coogan, the associate pastor at St. Patrick's Roman Catholic
Church, which the Roskot family attends in Bay Shore, Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, another shattered family also asked for
privacy. ``My son's body has not even been identified yet,''
Nelford's mother, Carolyn Nelford, said from her apartment in
Oxnard, Calif., some 70 miles north of Los Angeles. Ms. Nelford
said that many of the allegations about her son, including media
accounts of heavy drug use, were ``very cruel.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelford, like Roskot, was a teen-ager who drew attention and
acclaim. In a 1994 profile, The Los Angeles Times described him as
``arguably the best wrestler in Ventura County.'' At the time,
Nelford was a senior at Rio Mesa High School, a two-time wrestling
champion in his high school league, an honor student, and an
enthusiastic artist and musician.
</P>
<P>
   To this day his old high school wrestling coach keeps over his
fireplace a chalk and pencil portrait that Nelford, 23, drew of him
when he was in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not an angel who fell from heaven, but he was a good
kid,'' the coach, Todd Stoke, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   How two young people with so much promise could meet such a
terrible fate at one of the nation's finest colleges remained an
impenetrable mystery Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil Renzulli, the associate vice president for public affairs
at Columbia, said Sunday that the university was satisfied that
there had not been any security lapses at Ruggles Hall, the
dormitory where Roskot was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Students must show university identification when entering the
residence hall, and visitors must show photo identification and be
signed in by the resident student. Roskot signed Nelford into
Ruggles Hall about 12:30 a.m. Saturday. Students who shared her
fifth-floor suite reported hearing an argument about an hour later,
then silence.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said that Roskot began dating Nelford last year, after
he had dropped out of Columbia, where he had been a member of the
wrestling team. Roskot was an avid reader, drawn to writers like
Jack Kerouac and Tom Wolfe and bands like Phish and the Grateful
Dead. Nelford fashioned himself as someone completely devoted to
his art, bouncing from job to job while making a little extra money
painting murals for friends and students.
</P>
<P>
   Stoke recalled a long talk he had with Nelford last year about
his decision to drop out of Columbia. ``His thing at that point was
`I want to concentrate on my artwork and my music.' And my point
was `Finish at Columbia to have something to fall back on.' He was
awfully talented.''
</P>
<P>
   Roskot, meanwhile, continued to excel, both in school and on the
field. She made the dean's list at Columbia, friends said, and she
was a starter on the lacrosse team.
</P>
<P>
   At Bay Shore, Roskot's peers picked her to be their captain in
both her junior and her senior year, and she led by example. When
the coaches asked the players to show up at the start of the season
prepared to run the mile in under seven minutes and 30 seconds, she
did it in five minutes and 58 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one,'' Mrs. Pfeffer said, ``could influence Kathleen
negatively.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
