u a BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-NYT     02-06 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 TO TESTIFY OF INTERRUPTION IN GUNFIRE IN DIALLO KILLING
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The trial of the police officers charged with the
murder of Amadou Diallo will resume Monday, with at least two more
people who were near Diallo's apartment building on Wheeler Avenue
that night expected to say they heard a pause in the volley of
shots that killed him.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's witness list also includes a woman who has
told investigators that she overheard an officer say after the
shooting, ``This is what we are going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But should prosecutors call her, defense lawyers plan to
strenuously object to the testimony of the woman, Ida Vincent,
since she has not identified who made the remark _ one of the four
officers on trial or an officer who arrived after the shooting on
Feb. 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to avoid any indication that the officers tried to
concoct a story about how Diallo died, defense lawyers elicited
testimony last week from an officer who reported seeing the
defendants wandering in the street separately after the shooting,
in which 19 of 41 shots struck Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors hope to establish that there was a pause in the
gunfire so they can argue that it should have given the officers
time to realize their mistake. Last week, Debbie Rivera, who lived
on the block, described a brief pause in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Each witness from Wheeler Avenue is also expected to be
presented to try to buttress another assertion by the prosecution:
that the officers did not give any orders or commands to Diallo
before shooting him. No one on the street heard any such command,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers say that Diallo failed to respond to orders from
the officers, who mistakenly thought the man had a gun, and that no
one else heard the commands because the officers were relatively
close to Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also plan to call a ballistics expert who will try
to establish where each of the 41 shots came from. The climax of
the prosecution's case, and its last witness, is expected to be Dr.
Joseph Cohen, the medical examiner who performed the autopsy on
Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Because no one but the officers saw the shooting, Cohen is
essential to establish a premise that Eric Warner, the lead
prosecutor, made in his opening statement: that Diallo was falling
to the ground or on the ground when some of the shots were fired.
Defense lawyers plan to call a former medical examiner for the
city, Dr. Jon Pearl, to rebut the idea that an autopsy can
establish the order in which shots were fired.
</P>
<P>
   When the defense begins to present its case later this week, it
also plans to call civilians who were on Wheeler Avenue that night.
Some are expected to say they heard no pause in the shooting;
others are expected to describe Diallo's behavior just before the
shooting. Then the officers are to take the stand _ some of their
lawyers began preparing them over the weekend, in case the
prosecution rests quickly _ followed by expert witnesses who will
try to convince the jury that what the officers thought they saw,
and how they reacted, was reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   In just two days of trial, divergent strategies at best, and
strains at worst, among the defense lawyers are already becoming
clear. For example, Bennett M. Epstein, a lawyer for Officer Sean
Carroll, dwelt at length in his opening statement on what he called
the suspicious behavior of Diallo and his failure to obey commands
or orders from the officers. His co-counsel, John D. Patten,
questioned Diallo's roommate, Momodou Kujabi, about where Diallo
obtained the videotapes he sold. That line of questioning could
help lay the groundwork for the defense to suggest that Diallo was
selling bootleg videotapes, and thus had reason to fear the police.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Steven Brounstein, the lawyer for Officer Kenneth
Boss, did not raise the issue of Diallo's behavior and said he did
not plan to. Boss began firing only after Officers Edward McMellon
and Carroll did, and he fired only five shots from behind the other
officers, Brounstein said. ``What Diallo did is not my issue,'' he
said. ``My client does not know what Diallo did; he didn't see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll and McMellon each fired 16 shots; their lawyers have not
said which of the two fired first. Richard Murphy is the fourth
officer on trial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
