<HEADER>
A8585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-FRAZIER-DAUGHTER-     02-06 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FRAZIER-DAUGHTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAZIER'S DAUGHTER HAS FAST DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Va., Alaska, Wash., Calif., Washington D.C., Ohio) 
 (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCRANTON, Pa. _ After four hours of undercard bouts that
included a 6-foot-7-inch Bosnian heavyweight and a bout with a
last-minute substitute for a boxer who slipped on a jelly package
at the Philadelphia Airport and ended up with double vision, Jacqui
Frazier-Lyde climbed into the ring at the Scranton Cultural Center
here for her professional debut.
</P>
<P>
   It ended at 1 minute 23 seconds of the first round with a dazed
and confused Teela Reese huddled in the corner like a frightened
kitten and Frazier-Lyde raining punches upon her body. Referee Gary
Rosatto put Reese and the 3,500 fans out of their misery by
stopping the bout. The fans were not happy, and they started a
chant to display their disapproval. It was not the type of chant
that should be uttered in a cultural center.
</P>
<P>
   Never have so many waited so long for so little. ``I'm a slow
starter, and I was looking to warm up,'' Frazier-Lyde said. ``It
was over before I could get into it.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much of a fight. Frazier-Lyde bulled into Reese..
Reese did a 360-degree pirouette. She slipped punches as best she
could, and that was by turning her back when Frazier-Lyde threw
wild, looping punches. Many of them landed, but Reese was never
knocked off her feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like she couldn't defend herself with what I was doing
so she started to turn,'' Frazier-Lyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, another daughter of a famous fighter has leaped into the
ring. Laila Ali, Muhammad Ali's 21-year-old daughter, started
boxing last fall and has a 3-0 record. Frazier-Lyde is hoping to
meet her for a lucrative showdown in the Ali-Frazier blood feud.
``Laila Ali, you wanted to know if I was a professional boxer; now
you see,'' Frazier-Lyde said. ``Laila Ali, I will kick your butt.
I'm challenging you. I want the answer. Don't make me come and get
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Based upon her performance Sunday night, Frazier-Lyde has a long
way to go before she can make a compelling match with Ali, who is
polished and much more skillful than her counterpart. Frazier-Lyde,
who earned $25,000 for Sunday night's bout, will fight again on
March 19 at Chester, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's show seemed to be a more calculated attempt to
trade on a famous father's name than Laila Ali's venture into
boxing. Frazier-Lyde, a 38-year-old lawyer and mother of three
children, saw her father fight Muhammad Ali in the ``Thrilla in
Manila'' in 1975. She saw her father not come out for the 15th
round against Ali. Frazier-Lyde said it would be sweet to get a
measure of revenge for that against Ali's daughter. Mike Acri,
Laila Ali's promoter, said he would have to wait and see if
Frazier-Lyde could fight before considering a bout against Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very serious because of the serious history between
our fathers, and they should be,'' said Khaliah Ali, Laila's sister
and a friend of Frazier-Lyde. ``Jacqui Frazier is fighting for a
cause. She wants to bring our families together. She doesn't just
want to win for the Fraziers, she wants to win for the Alis, too.
May the best woman win.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's fight was short on celebrities. Larry Holmes, the
former heavyweight champion from nearby Easton, Pa., was at
ringside with his wife, Diane, who said she would never allow her
son or her daughter to box. Holmes shook Frazier-Lyde's hands
before the fight.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Frazier was also at the fight and was part of the ring
entrance for his daughter, who was also accompanied by her three
children and her husband, Peter.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier helped train his daughter, along with his son, Marvis,
who had an undistinguished boxing career. Marvis Frazier finished
with a 16-2 record, but the two losses were to Holmes and Mike
Tyson. Tyson scored the fastest knockout of his career against
Marvis Frazier, knocking him out at 30 seconds of the first round.
He said he was proud of the way that his sister fought.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did a good job,'' Marvis Frazier said. ``I was as nervous
as a cat, but she got the victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Frazier said he was not going to comment about his
daughter's performance, because he was not happy with promoter Don
Elbaum and was not going to do anything to help the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   This is Frazier-Lyde's second go round on the athletic circuit.
She was the captain of the American University basketball team
before going on to get a law degree from Villanova University. She
has a law office over her father's gym in Philadelphia and
primarily handles legal matters for her father. As a matter of
fact, she is due in court on Tuesday in a legal wrangle to wrest
her father's papers from the estate of his former lawyer, Bruce
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   That fight might be tougher than the one that Reese, who earned
just $800, put up. The original opponent was a Philadelphia
hairdresser who made the mistake of training in front of someone
who could report back to Frazier-Lyde that she was too tough.
</P>
<P>
   So, they arranged for an easier opponent by calling Cleveland
Burgess, a trainer and booking agent who is a friend of
Frazier-Lyde's husband, Peter. The two of them came up with Reese.
She was born in Anchorage, Alaska, and has lived in Seattle and
California, and now resides in Ashtabula, Ohio, and trains in
Washington, D.C. She has a 3-year-old son named Nightshade. Before
her pro debut, Reese said the extent of her experience was street
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what she knew about Smokin' Joe Frazier, Reese said,
``The name doesn't mean anything. He's just another guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
