<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SLEUTHS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA AIR CRASH INVESTIGATORS HAVE A WEALTH OF DATA TO WORK WITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, D.C. _ On the fifth floor of a nondescript office
building here just off the National Mall, super-sleuth technicians
and aerospace engineers with high-tech equipment are once again
looking for answers after a major air disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, as they begin the tedious process of deciphering
data from the two ``black boxes'' that were on Alaska Airlines
Flight 261, investigators with the National Transportation Safety
Board have an unusually abundant amount of information from the
plane and its crew.
</P>
<P>
   There is much more information to analyze from this jetliner's
flight data and cockpit voice recorders than there was with several
recent high-profile crashes, including TWA Flight 800 and the crash
late last year of EgyptAir Flight 990 off the Massachusetts coast.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a while, perhaps as long as a year or more, but
aviation experts say there is little doubt that the board's
experienced investigators will solve the mystery of why the Alaska
Airlines MD-83 jet fell out of the sky one week ago. The plane
crashed into the Pacific with the loss of all 88 people on board,
including 50 from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   More details about the crash should emerge soon, perhaps as
early as Monday, when the board makes public the first tidbits of
information from the plane's flight data recorder. The device
monitored the plane's performance, beginning with the takeoff Jan.
31 from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, on the plane's return flight to
Seattle, with a scheduled stop in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 261 was being diverted to Los Angeles International
Airport for an emergency landing when it crashed.
</P>
<P>
   The data recorder will help give up the doomed plane's secrets,
which include two loud, mysterious noises, one of which is clearly
audible on the voice recorder just before the plane went out of
control for the final time and crashed. Some 11 minutes earlier,
the voice recorder captured a flight attendant telling the pilots
she had heard a loud noise in the rear of the plane. The pilots
said they had heard it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Did the jet suffer a structural failure in the tail as the
pilots battled a jammed stabilizer that was making control
difficult? Could the two noises be nothing more than what's known
as an engine compressor stall, a loud bang made by a jet engine
when the air flow is disrupted, usually because the plane is making
extreme maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fairly strong suggestion there was a catastrophic
failure of something,'' said Charles Eastlake, a professor of
aerospace engineering at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in
Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FDR (flight data recorder) will be very helpful in
verifying what actually happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The data recorder on Flight 261 was much more sophisticated than
older models found on some planes. It measured 48 so-called
parameters, such as air speed, attitude and engine performance. It
should tell investigators if the jet's engines had a compressor
stall.
</P>
<P>
   The recorder also measured the all-important stabilizer trim
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The stabilizer is the wing-like structure on the top of the
MD-83 tail. The leading edge of the stabilizer moves up or down on
command of the crew or the autopilot during flight to counter the
tendency of a plane to pitch up or down because of the aerodynamics
of the wing. The trim keeps the plane stable.
</P>
<P>
   Based on conversations the pilots of Flight 261 had with an
Alaska mechanic on the ground as they attempted to troubleshoot the
problem, the stabilizer apparently jammed in the up position, which
pitched the nose of the jet sharply down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stabilizer is the most critical control surface on the
airplane,'' Eastlake said. ``If it was badly messed up, then it is
fairly likely there was nothing the pilots could have done to
change the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The cockpit voice recorder on Flight 261 had a 30-minute loop
tape, so only the final half hour of cockpit conversation was
recorded. When the tape starts, the pilots are already talking
about the stabilizer problem with Alaska personnel in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 261's data recorder, meanwhile, has two hours and 45
minutes of information, including everything after the takeoff from
Puerto Vallarta. Since the device monitored the plane's entire
flight, it should provide important clues to help investigators
pinpoint when the stabilizer problem first occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Piece by piece, this is the kind of crucial information that
investigators will use to eventually solve the crash puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   They have solved previous crashes with much less.
</P>
<P>
   The flight data recorder on USAir Flight 427, which dived into a
ravine near Pittsburgh on Sept. 8, 1994, recorded only 11
parameters. The voice recorder shed little light on the crash. The
National Transportation Safety Board, after the longest
investigation in its history, finally determined last year that the
rudder system on the Boeing 737 probably malfunctioned. The
investigation might not have taken nearly as long had the flight
data recorder measured rudder movement.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the flight data recorder on EgyptAir Flight 990
last year measured nearly twice as many parameters as the one on
Alaska Airlines Flight 261. But the Alaska jet's recorder may prove
much more helpful to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Both black boxes (they are actually painted bright orange) on
the EgyptAir jet stopped working near the end of the plane's
initial dive from its cruising altitude of 31,000 feet _ the same
altitude Alaska Airlines Flight 261 was at when it first went out
of control, dropping nearly a mile before the pilots recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Radar showed the EgyptAir plane subsequently climbed nearly a
mile after its dive before it plunged into the Atlantic Ocean. But
there is nothing on the two black boxes to help explain what was
happening in the cockpit or with the airplane, which will make the
EgyptAir investigation much more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, there was little on the two black boxes of TWA Flight
800 to help investigators. Electrical power to both boxes was cut
when the center fuel tank of the 747 exploded after the plane took
off for Paris from Kennedy Airport in New York in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The four cockpit voice recorder microphones, however, picked up
vibrations that were transmitted through the airframe by the
explosion aboard the TWA flight. They also picked up the final
sound of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Vibrations traveled through the airframe faster than the speed
of sound. By measuring the tiny difference, the safety board's lab
experts concluded the sound patterns did not match those that would
have been produced by a bomb, as some had speculated.
</P>
<P>
   Good detective work also helped solve two mysterious thumps that
were heard on the cockpit voice recorder of the USAir Flight 427
before it rolled over and spun into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators knew the USAir plane had passed through the wake
turbulence of another jet just before it went out of control. In
searching for clues, one of the board's investigators rode in a 737
as it passed through the wake of another jet. He found that when
the 737 hit the wake at a certain angle, it made the distinctive
thump sounds heard on the voice recorder of Flight 427.
</P>
<P>
   A loud bang also was heard on the cockpit voice recorder of
Valuejet Flight 592, which crashed into the Florida Everglades in
May 1996 after a fire erupted in the cargo hold.
</P>
<P>
   After synchronizing the sound of the bang on the cockpit voice
recorder with information from the flight data recorder,
investigators had an explanation: The noise was a tire exploding in
the cargo hold from the heat of the fire. The resulting pressure
surge affected the plane's altimeter and airspeed indicators,
giving the screwball readings that didn't seem possible on the
flight data recorder.
</P>
<P>
   It is just that kind of detective work that may tell
investigators what caused the two loud noises on Alaska Airlines
Flight 261 as they attempt to solve yet another airline crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
