<HEADLINE>
PAPERS SEEK OPEN PROCEEDINGS IN MOXLEY MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
 (With MOXLEY-MURDER) 
(jw) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ The presiding judge in the Michael Skakel
murder case, Maureen Dennis, is to meet on Monday with lawyers for
five newspapers that have asked her to open the proceedings to the
public and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, who was 15 on Oct. 30, 1975, the night Martha Moxley was
killed, was charged last month as a juvenile, and the prosecutor
refused to discuss details of the case or even mention Skakel's
name, citing laws protecting juvenile suspects.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, The New York Times, Newsday, The Hartford
Courant, The Advocate of Stamford and Greenwich Time filed a
request with Dennis, of Juvenile Court in Stamford, to open the
case to the public, a move Skakel's lawyer supports and which
prosecutors say they do not oppose.
</P>
<P>
   In their motion before Dennis, lawyers for the newspapers argued
that the courts did not need to shield Skakel, an adult, from
public exposure, as they would a juvenile defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's lawyer, Mickey Sherman, said he wanted an open hearing
for his client. ``We have no objection to it,'' he said Sunday in a
phone interview from Florida. ``Our whole position has been he is
innocent and that the more people that are exposed to the evidence
here, the better we will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan C. Benedict, the state's attorney prosecuting the case,
also said he would not fight the motion. ``We're taking no position
on it,'' he said in a telephone interview on Friday. ``He's an
adult; I don't feel it's incumbent on me to protect him. The
Juvenile Court may have a different opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are trying to have the case moved to State Superior
Court, and a preliminary hearing is scheduled for Tuesday in
Juvenile Court in Stamford. If Dennis grants the newspapers'
request, the hearing, which is scheduled to be closed, could become
a high-profile event, like his arrest on Jan. 19. Skakel, now 39,
will be the oldest person ever to appear in a Connecticut juvenile
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason for secrecy in juvenile proceedings is to
protect the child,'' Mark R. Kravitz, the lawyer who filed the
motion, told The Associated Press on Friday. ``We have someone who
is not a child, and someone who is agreeing to have it open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
