<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-GIULIANI-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR HAS BUSY MORNING ON TV NEWS PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-SENATE-MRSCLINTON) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long before Hillary Rodham Clinton took the stage
Sunday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had spent hours in interviews,
hopping from one television studio to another to promote his Senate
candidacy on five morning news programs, and then tending to
mayoral obligations including a hospital party for children with
heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on the media interest in Clinton's gala campaign
announcement, the mayor appeared live on three of the news
programs. At each stop, he was relentlessly focused on promoting
his record as mayor, which he said would be the centerpiece of his
Senate campaign. In each interview, he recited his accomplishments
and sought to underscore the point that Clinton has never served in
elective office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been the United States attorney, the mayor of New York
City, and I have a record of success on issues that are very, very
important,'' Giuliani said on ``Face the Nation,'' the CBS program.
``From my point of view, that's what the campaign should be about.
It should be about ideas, and it should be about your record, where
you've had a chance to put your ideas into practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani used the word ``record'' _ either to refer to his own
or to say that Clinton does not have one _ at least 18 times, a
half-dozen times alone on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' And he
suggested that his performance in two terms as mayor gave voters a
sense of what he could accomplish for the rest of the state in the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view this campaign is about 540,000 fewer
people on welfare, 360,000 new jobs in New York City, taking New
York City from one of the largest crime cities in the country to
the safest large city in the United States and then trying to do
that for the rest of the state of New York from a philosophy that's
a proven one, and a record of performance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the questioners sought to point out that he and
Clinton hold the same view on a number of issues, including welfare
reform, gun control and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Meet the Press,'' Giuliani, who has been in favor of
abortion rights during his years as mayor, explicitly rejected a
ban on late-term abortions and acknowledged that his position could
cost him the nomination of the state Conservative Party. Giuliani
deflected questions Sunday about whether he would seek the
Conservative line.
</P>
<P>
   And he said that as a senator he would vote against any measure
to ban the abortions. ``I would vote to preserve the option for
women,'' Giuliani said. ``I think that choice is a very difficult
one, it's one in which people of conscience have very, very
different opinions. I think the better thing for America to do is
to leave that choice to the woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani faced perhaps his toughest questioning in the NBC
studios in Rockefeller Center. He arrived there moments after
taping his appearance on ``Fox News Sunday,'' and paused briefly in
the green room to wolf down a couple of breakfast sausages before
facing its host, Tim Russert.
</P>
<P>
   Russert confronted Giuliani with the similarity of his and
Clinton's views on several issues, including health care, gays in
the military and abortion. The mayor pointed out, however, that he
favored the deep Republican tax-cut proposal, and less government
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   He disavowed some mailings made by conservative groups in
support of his candidacy, but countered that Clinton's backers have
portrayed him as part of a ``right wing'' conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Giuliani went to the CBS studios on West 57th
Street, to the ABC studios in Times Square for an appearance on
``This Week'' and finally to tape an interview at CNN. At City
Hall, Giuliani met briefly with the family of Kathleen A. Roskot,
the Columbia University student who was killed in her dormitory
room on Saturday, apparently by a former boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor then went to New York University Medical Center to
attend the sixth annual Mend-a-Heart party for the hospital's
pediatric cardiology patients, their families and hospital staff
members. Wearing a ``New York City Capital of the World'' jacket,
Giuliani worked the room like a candidate, posing for photographs,
signing autographs and hugging children.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Amid dozens of red heart-shaped helium balloons and a huge
banner proclaiming ``NYU Medical Center Welcomes Rudy Giuliani,''
several children presented the mayor with a white sheet cake, with
red icing that said, ``Rudy Has a Heart.'' The mayor praised the
hospital's cardiology program and congratulated the families.
</P>
<P>
   At his daily news conference, he talked again about his record.
He criticized Clinton and the White House for not releasing records
related to her use of government aircraft on political trips, and
he professed to be uninterested in her campaign announcement, again
referring to the hoopla surrounding her day as a celebrity-driven
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a record of proven success that people can measure,''
he said. ``I'm for real. So let's compare that to
Hollywood-on-the-Hudson.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his image of busy mayor, Giuliani also held
meetings at City Hall related to the release of the semiannual
Mayor's Management Report, which is scheduled for Thursday, and
with officials working on his administration's latest effort to
combat domestic violence, which has been a top public-safety goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
