<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IN AN ERA OF HYPERBOLE, PEOPLE CAN GO ADRIFT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Jarvis, the head basketball coach at St. John's
University, is one of a handful of big-time college basketball
coaches who takes his role as an educator seriously. But after
Saturday's narrow victory over Boston College, Jarvis used his
position and podium to lambaste the NCAA for its investigation of
Erick Barkley, the sensational point guard who was declared
ineligible by the university for an NCAA rules violation.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves Barkley's use of someone else's sports utility
vehicle. Ed Manetta, the St. John's athletic director, described
the episode as ``a simple exchange from one friend to another''
that was misinterpreted by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA is expected to rule Monday, and St. John's expects
Barkley to be exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``No rules were violated,'' Jarvis said Saturday. ``It will be
proven that Erick did nothing wrong. This is about America. This is
about an individual's rights. This is not a communist country;
there's no Gestapo here. This young man has done absolutely,
positively nothing wrong. I hope that none of you feel the way I
have the last two days, as if someone had come into my house and
raped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mentioning the Gestapo and rape in one postgame news conference
is excessive in an industry whose greatest problem is excess.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday night, Jarvis issued a statement, apologizing for
his remarks. ``I said something in an emotional moment that was
insensitive and I am deeply sorry for it.''
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the problem in college sports is that games have
grown beyond the boundary of rational priority. Coaches caught up
in the rush and heat of the moment freely use metaphor and
hyperbole to convey feelings of joy and, in Jarvis' case on
Saturday, anger. In the process they often trample on history and
minimize real pain.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the NCAA is often selective and wrong, sometimes even
rotten. But the organization is not the Gestapo _ ask anyone who
survived the Holocaust; an NCAA investigation is not a rape _ ask
anyone who has been sexually assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis' choice of images on Saturday obscured a legitimate
point: St. John's is coming on strong, making a return as a major
player in the recruiting wars and in Big East competition. He
wondered who had tipped the NCAA about Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about something else, he was put out there by
someone,'' Jarvis said. ``Some people are jealous of the program.
Maybe somebody is afraid of St. John's and where we're going.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Vacarro, who has worked for Nike and currently for Adidas,
knows the summer game and the viciousness of New York City
basketball. He agreed with Jarvis. ``As soon as he started driving
the truck,'' he said, ``one of the haters of either Jarvis or St.
John's turned him in.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA estimates that about 75 players in the last five years
have lost at least one season to NCAA-imposed penalties or were not
reinstated at all. There have been several high-profile cases this
season:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Missouri freshman Kareem Rush was suspended for nine games
because the NCAA determined that while he was at Pembroke Hill High
in Kansas City, Mo., he received improper benefits from his former
Amateur Athletic Union coach. His brother, the UCLA sophomore JaRon
Rush, who already sat out 15 games, has been suspended for the
remainder of this season and the first 17 games of the 2000-2001
season for receiving benefits _ valued at $6,125 _ from the same
AAU coach, Myron Piggie. JaRon was also cited for taking $200 from
an agent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oklahoma State's Andre Williams was suspended for five games
because of improper dealings with a summer league team booster.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jamal Crawford, a freshman at Michigan, was suspended until
Feb. 24 for receiving improper benefits from Barry Henthorn, the
president of Innovative Communication Technologies, Inc. Crawford
lived with Henthorn for the three years he attended Rainier Beach
High School in Seattle. Henthorn furnished Crawford with a room in
his house, clothes, spending money and a Jeep Grand Cherokee during
his final year in high school.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday Jarvis said he wanted to abolish the NCAA. ``I hope
and pray that I'll see a day when there is no NCAA,'' he said,
``and when we are guided by the values system which we are brought
up on, that we fight for every day in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Tear down the NCAA? And allow the coaches to police themselves?
I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Are there too many NCAA rules? Of course. Are the rules
convoluted? Sure they are. But the myriad regulations are in place
precisely because the coaches and the institutions they represent
do not trust one another. The coaches all use players as pieces in
a blood game that goes far beyond fun and games; the process is
skewed.
</P>
<P>
   But the culture that the NCAA attempts to put its arms around is
as bizarre as the process is flawed. Only parents who have had
children go through the meat grinder know the depth of this truth:
street agents, hustlers, ambitious coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is for the adults in the business to keep level
heads. Level-headedness has been Jarvis' signature from high school
to college: reminding his players in victory and defeat, good times
and bad that this is all about a journey.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday the coach went adrift. Erick Barkley is not being
hounded by the Gestapo; no one is being raped. These are games.
That's all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
