<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-SHELTERS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIFT TO NO-KILL SHELTERS LEAVES TOWNS DELUGED WITH STRAYS 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, N.Y. _ Dogs and cats do not just drop in at a private
animal shelter here. First comes the appointment. Then the
screening. And, if they are lucky, an invitation to stay. They must
endure the indignity of having their tails yanked and their mouths
pried open during the interview. If they hiss or claw or bite, they
are shown the door.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter, owned by the Ulster County Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, admits only those that are likely
to be adopted. It departed two years ago from a longstanding
tradition of taking in any stray or unwanted pet after the shelter
stopped euthanizing animals just to free up space in cages and
kennels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taught to take animals with a smile and `thank you,' but
people walked away and they figured they had done the right
thing,'' said Christine French, the shelter's executive director.
``Well, we're no longer the dumping ground for animals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster County SPCA has joined a growing revolt among animal
shelters in the New York region and nationally that have struggled
quietly for years to provide services ranging from dog-catching to
euthanasia while sources of public money have continued to shrink.
These shelters have canceled contracts with cities and towns,
accepted far fewer animals and sought peace of mind and more
private donations by adopting a ``no-kill'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   But as these private shelters are flourishing, they have created
new headaches for local governments and publicly financed shelters
left to cope with a deluge of unwanted dogs and cats. Some towns
have fashioned makeshift holding pens, while others pay high fees
to private kennels and veterinarians. Still others no longer bother
with stray cats, which, unlike dogs, are not required to be picked
up under state law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a problem telling the municipalities where to
take their animals,'' said Dr. John P. Huntley, the state
veterinarian for the Department of Agriculture and Markets, which
monitors more than 360 animal shelters around the state. ``They're
being refused entry into the traditional shelter system.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, nearly 60 shelter workers, animal rights advocates
and local residents pleaded for help during a nine-hour legislative
hearing in Albany. They called for more county shelters and laws
requiring that shelter animals be spayed or neutered. A Jan. 20
hearing in Syracuse drew more than 100 people, and a third meeting
is planned for next month in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials have also voiced concern over the rapidly
multiplying number of stray cats. ``It's potentially a reservoir
for the rabies virus,'' said Timothy Purcell, a public health
inspector for Onondaga County, adding that thousands of cats roam
the streets there. ``And because people have an attachment to
felines and are not as hesitant to go up and pet them, the
potential for exposure is higher than with wildlife.''
</P>
<P>
   The Central New York SPCA in Onondaga County adopted a no-kill
policy in June 1998, and people who want to give up their pets face
a waiting list, now at 843 cats and 52 dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The move away from euthanasia comes at a time when public
sentiment, and perhaps more importantly, wealthy donors, have
turned against it. Last year, Richard Avanzino, the former director
of the San Francisco SPCA, began a $200 million campaign to promote
a no-kill philosophy around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, financed by the owners of PeopleSoft, a Silicon
Valley software company, will give millions of dollars to
communities in which shelters pledge not to routinely euthanize
animals.
</P>
<P>
   The North Shore Animal League in Port Washington, N.Y., stopped
euthanizing animals in the 1940s, and dozens of other private
shelters in the state have followed suit in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals,
one of the nation's largest animal rights groups, also moved away
from euthanasia in 1994 after canceling a 100-year-old animal
control contract with New York City. Stephen Zawistowski, a senior
vice president of the ASPCA, said the agency's shelter used to take
in 80,000 animals a year while working for the city. Now the
society runs a private no-kill shelter in Manhattan that takes in a
fraction of that _ 1,979 animals last year.
</P>
<P>
   Animals that do not make it into the ASPCA or other no-kill
shelters usually end up at the Center for Animal Care and Control,
a city-financed group with shelters in the five boroughs that
euthanized almost 40,000 of the 61,000 cats and dogs it admitted
last year. ``We take everyone,'' said Kyle Burkhart, a spokesman
for the shelter. ``We don't have the luxury of saying, `That
animal's not adoptable, we don't want it.' ''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But many private shelters say their goal has become less about
sheer numbers than about improving life for the animals and for
shelter workers. Patricia Richards, manager of the Central New York
SPCA, said that last year her staff euthanized 400 cats and dogs,
most sick or vicious, down from as many as 6,000 animals a year
before the shelter started limiting admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like an assembly line,'' she said. ``It was very
stressful. The public was calling us killers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutchess County SPCA, which stopped euthanizing animals in
1993, is still trying to pay off a debt of $170,000 from years of
``miserly'' contracts with local towns, said Trish Adams, the
shelter's executive director. Many shelters are now shifting the
responsibility back to their communities, but the transition has
not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   Municipalities that once counted on the shelters have been
besieged by unwanted animals and frustrated residents. Barbara
Eichert, who lives along Route 32 near Kingston, said she no longer
has anywhere to take the dogs that she finds wandering along the
road. She said town officials tell her to call the Ulster County
SPCA And the SPCA tells her the shelter is full.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a moral responsibility to look out for living
things,'' said Eichert, who has seven cats and a dog. ``But does
that mean if you save it, you have to take care of it for the rest
of your life? That's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   French, the shelter's executive director, said her staff
shouldered that responsibility for years while county residents
simply looked away. The shelter took in as many as 5,500 animals a
year before changing its euthanasia practice. Last year, it
admitted 821 animals.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the shelter has become a haven for cats and dogs. French
poked her fingers playfully through the metal cages and cooed at
the cats dozing on striped cushions. Dozens of photos of cats and
dogs line a wall. ``These are the animals that have been adopted,''
she pointed out with a smile. ``They're our happy endings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
