<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-06 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER TRANSITION FOR AMERICA'S CUP AS ITALY PREPARES TO MEET NEW
ZEALAND
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ When the sleek, silver sloop
representing Italy's Prada Challenge skimmed across the finish line
Sunday to win the Louis Vuitton challenger series and the right to
face Team New Zealand for the America's Cup, it set off a symphony
of honking air horns and unrestrained cheers, beginning a
celebration that shook the Auckland waterfront until the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   It also turned the page on a new chapter in the history of
sailing's oldest, gaudiest, most coveted piece of silverware.
</P>
<P>
   For when the two yachts begin racing in the 30th cup match on
Feb. 19 in the Hauraki Gulf, it will be the first time in 149 years
that there will be no American boat contesting for the America's
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great for the event,'' said Sir Peter Blake, the
man in charge of defending the cup and keeping it within the
confines of its current home at the Royal New Zealand Yacht
Squadron. ``It shows you can come from a small nation like ours or
a fanatical, middle-sized country like Italy and still have a good
chance. It really doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always so. For 132 years, the America's Cup was the
proud domain of the New York Yacht Club, whose stewardship saw it
through flush times and lean, through war and peace, and through
competition in various classes of yachts ranging from the glorious,
unbridled J-Class sloops to the smaller, more utilitarian
12-Meters.
</P>
<P>
   If there was one common denominator spanning the decades, it was
the way in which cup campaigns were financed and conducted. For
years the racing was limited to irregular summertime forays fueled
by the fortunes of tycoons like the Irish tea merchant Thomas J.
Lipton, the American industrialist Harold Vanderbilt and the
Australian businessman Frank Packer.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed in 1980, when a young San Diegan named Dennis
Conner decided that the best way to win the cup was by mounting
multiple-boat campaigns that spanned the several years between
defenses on testing, training and refining.
</P>
<P>
   The additional commitment in time required more money to build
more boats and pay the sailors for the time they had once
volunteered. In many cases, those dollars were beyond the limit
that the cup's well-heeled patrons wished to spend. And so the cup
made an almost instant transition from a purely amateur endeavor to
one assisted by corporate backing. In essence, the cup went pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was doing it when I was younger, you'd just take the
summer off,'' said the current New York Yacht Club commodore,
George Isdale Jr. ``But that's changed. I think people decided they
wanted it to be more professional, and they wanted to make money
from it. You can be sure Dennis Conner makes money at it.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, rich syndicate patrons are still very much part of
the scene; the American multimillionaire Bill Koch and the late
Italian businessman Raul Gardini, who met in the 1992 match, fit
that description, as does the current challenger, Patrizio Bertelli
of the Prada fashion dynasty. But Conner remains the role model for
every modern America's Cup skipper.
</P>
<P>
   He was at the helm when the New York Yacht Club's tenure as cup
administrator ended in defeat to an Australian challenge in 1983.
For Conner, it turned out to be a great career move.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he made the covers of Time and Sports
Illustrated by reclaiming the cup in dramatic fashion in Fremantle,
Australia, and bringing it back to the San Diego Yacht Club, in his
hometown. It stayed there eight years, until a lean, talented New
Zealand crew spirited it away in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The outline for cup racing is governed by the Deed of Gift, a
document drafted in 1887 by the New York Yacht Club, which states
that the trophy ``shall be preserved as a perpetual Challenge Cup
for friendly competition between foreign countries.'' But the
defender of the cup is allowed to set the protocol for the ensuing
matches. In New Zealand's case, one such condition was the
five-year gap since the last match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one reason people want it,'' said Koch, who successfully
defended the cup in 1992 with a $75 million effort. ``You can
control the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   With the chance to return the cup to their own turf if
victorious, eleven challengers _ including five from the United
States, with two from San Francisco and the others with ties to New
York, Hawaii and San Diego _ were established in Auckland when the
challenger series began last October.
</P>
<P>
   Although each American team enjoyed financial support from
wealthy individuals, all competed for and received substantial
money from corporate sponsors as well. On the other hand, Prada's
$60 million effort was bankrolled exclusively by Bertelli, a
sailing enthusiast who was in it for the sport, not as a dedicated
marketing opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Prada not only outspent the competition, but it also out-trained
them, having taken a page from Conner's book and setting up camp
nearly two years before the regatta began. After four months of
trials, Prada and America One of San Francisco were still standing.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two weeks, the two syndicates waged a spectacular
back-and-forth battle. But on Sunday, in the deciding race of the
best-of-9 finals, Prada prevailed and earned the right to challenge
for the cup in another best-of-9 series.
</P>
<P>
   America One's skipper, Paul Cayard, was aware of the historical
implications. ``I'm conscious of the fact that we were America's
last hope,'' he said. But he also had criticism of the overall
American approach: ``I think one of the factors for America this
time is that we were too diluted. Having five teams from the U.S.
is probably not the best way to put our best foot forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Isdale of the New York Yacht Club agreed. ``We entertained and
talked with some other American syndicates about all kinds of
mergers and acquisitions,'' he said. ``Nothing happened. But we
might be better off next time with just one or two supersyndicates.
It might be more attractive to corporate interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The site for the next cup will be decided by early March. For
now, one thing is certain. It is, and shall remain for at least the
near future, a long way from American shores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
