<SLUG> BC-OBIT-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIP JONES, BRITISH TRUMPETER AND MUSIC EDUCATOR, DIES AT 71 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philip Jones, a leading British trumpeter and a music educator,
died Jan. 17. He was 71 and lived in London and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was born in Bath, England, into a family of brass
musicians. He began playing the trumpet as a boy, and in 1944 he
won a scholarship to the Royal College of Music. At 20 he was
appointed fourth trumpet in the Covent Garden orchestra, rising to
principal the next year.
</P>
<P>
   He was then, remarkably, principal trumpet with most of the
other major London orchestras in succession: the Royal Philharmonic
(1956-60), the Philharmonia (1960-64), the Philharmonic (1964-65),
the New Philharmonia (1965-67) and the BBC Symphony (1967-71).
During his career he played under most of the great conductors,
from Erich Kleiber to Pierre Boulez.
</P>
<P>
   During these years he was also performing regularly with a group
he had founded in 1951, the quintet known as the Philip Jones Brass
Ensemble, to which he was able to give his full attention after
1971. The ensemble played Baroque music, especially pieces by
Giovanni Gabrieli and Johann Pezel, and as the early-music revival
grew in the '60s and '70s the group was much in demand for
performances of choral music by Monteverdi and others. But the
ensemble also commissioned works from composers like Hans Werner
Henze, Richard Rodney Bennett and Toru Takemitsu.
</P>
<P>
   As a soloist, too, Jones lent his brilliance and beauty of tone
to new music, like Iain Hamilton's ``Circus'' for two trumpets and
orchestra (1969), written for him and his colleague, Elgar Howarth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 he retired from playing and devoted his energies to what
had been a secondary career, teaching. Two years later he was
appointed principal of Trinity College of Music, London, an
institution that was then in the doldrums. He invigorated it to a
point where it could reclaim equal status with the Royal Academy of
Music and the Royal College. He retired in 1994 and the next year
took on the chairmanship of the Musicians Benevolent Fund, the
leading British musical charity.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Ursula.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000206.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8717 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     02-06 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY NOT OUT OF SIGHT, NOR OUT OF MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mariners may or may not have been making a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the order to the T-shirt manufacturer went out before
November, when things started to go sideways. But for the Mariners
FanFest Sunday, the M's handed out complementary T-shirts bearing
the name and number of their All-Century center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he sinks birdies in Pebble Beach and reiterates his
desire to be traded to Cincinnati, Ken Griffey Jr. remains a
Mariner.
</P>
<P>
   So everywhere you looked, there was No. 24. Griffey, Griffey,
Griffey, Griffey and more Griffey. Hundreds of him, on kids of all
shapes and sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old boys in Griffey shirts paraded in packs around the
Stadium Exhibition Center, throwing fastballs and testing their
play-by-play skills.
</P>
<P>
   Legions of parents were seen holding infants and toddlers who
were swimming in the bright white cotton freebies.
</P>
<P>
   And there were even several adult fans dressed in Griffey
jerseys, either as a sign that they want the man back or that until
he's gone, he's one of the gang.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey. Griffey. Griffey. Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   If these are dark days in Marinerville because of the
up-in-the-air fate of Griffey, someone forgot to tell the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they have their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'd like to see him go to Cincinnati. That's where
he said he wants to go,'' said Aulista Holman from Auburn. ``And I
think deep down, we would know that he doesn't want to be here. I
really feel he just wouldn't have his heart in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one was crying bitter tears one way or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more optimism going into this spring than any other
time I can think of, other than '96, when we were all flying high
after the '95 postseason,'' said Mariners broadcaster Dave Neihaus.
``I think fans just want this thing resolved one way or another. Is
he staying or is he going? I think there's a feeling of let's move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, on that subject, the public was offered a temperature
reading from Mariners general manager Pat Gillick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting here right now, I think No. 24 will be here playing
against Pedro Martinez on Opening Day,'' Gillick said to a captive
audience of several hundred.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers erupted from the crowd as Gillick addressed Question No.
1 in Marinerville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fans have to understand Ken has the right to veto
where he might go. He's a guy who really sold baseball here, who
had a lot to do with Safeco Field being built. And I think that
he'll play with the same vigor he played with during his last 11
years as a Mariner.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, no member of the M's organization escaped the two-day
FanFest event without facing The Big Question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, this guy's the greatest player to step on grass,'' said
Shane Monahan, an outfielder who played center field in high school
and college and who would like a shot at it again, only not under
these circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to stay away from the whole Ken Griffey
thing, but I think he's such an integral part of Seattle. Junior is
Seattle and Seattle is Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   Monahan isn't alone in that thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to talk with our general manager about that, but in
my job as manager, I've got him penciled in at center field and in
the No. 3 spot of the lineup,'' Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   The skipper, looking tanned, rested and ready, smiled broadly
upon delivering his ``If Junior's Here, I'll Be A Happy Camper''
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   More applause broke out through the Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see what's happening here. It really has made me sad
during the off-season,'' Piniella said. ``Junior has had such a
great career here. There's no need for this. Things just need to
quiet down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's requested a trade. The club wants to get what's fair
value. But if that doesn't happen, I'll have the thrill of having
him in our lineup and helping us win the division.''
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, Mariners president Chuck Armstrong and owner/CEO
Howard Lincoln settled into a faux leather couch and, patiently
answered a predictable and ad nauseum string of inquiries on ``The
Griffey Situation'' (their words not ours.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing everything we can to try and accommodate him,''
Lincoln said.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite the Mariners' willingness to grant Griffey his
wish, Lincoln reiterated the organization has a bottom line to
which they will adhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between accommodating someone's heartfelt
request and being taken to the cleaners,'' Lincoln said.
</P>
<P>
   Being ``taken to the cleaners'' would certainly involve any deal
with the Reds. Armstrong said Cincinnati has been insisting since
December that any trade for Griffey would have to include money
from the Mariners to pay Griffey's $7.9 million salary, and the M's
will not do that.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Sunday, two weeks before spring training is set to
begin, hundreds of pint-sized Mariners fans were running around in
Griffey T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Reminders of Griffey everywhere. As if anyone is thinking about
anything else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
