<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-NORWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COACH, NEW CONTRACT, NEW EXPERIENCE IN LOSING FOR U.S.
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ In her debut Sunday as head coach of the
U.S. women's soccer team, April Heinrichs decided to follow a
philosophy embodied in a quotation she particularly likes: Leaders
begin with the end in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The end this team has in mind for this year is winning the gold
medal at the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia. But
Heinrichs reasoned that it is only February, so by the end of the
international friendly match against Norway Sunday, she had
experimented liberally, including using six players under 20 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   The result was atypical for the U.S. women, a last-minute 3-2
loss before 12,031 at Lockhart Stadium that snapped the team's
21-game unbeaten streak in the United States. The team's previous
loss on American soil came last April 25 when it lost by 2-1 to
China at Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   This was the American women's first game following the
settlement of a monthlong boycott by the team's veterans over
increased remuneration, and the first game since October for the
team's nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common word I heard was `rusty,''' Heinrichs said.
``Even Julie Foudy joked when she came off the field, `I was trying
to do what you said to do, but I was so tired I kicked the ground.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Their legs got tired and wouldn't let them play the ball that
their brain was thinking about. We can take care of that problem
over the next two to three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight of Sunday's 11 starters for the United States were
significant contributors on the celebrated World Cup championship
team last July. The new faces included the 17-year-olds Nandi
Pryce, a defender, and Aleisha Cramer, a midfielder. Saskia Webber,
a Rutgers alumnus who is the veteran backup, started in goal over
Briana Scurry. The team played without Michelle Akers, Lorrie Fair,
Cindy Parkow and Tisha Venturini, all members of the World Cup
team.
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs, whose early mantra for her players is ``if you've
peaked, you're gone,'' substituted so freely in the second half
that there were five players under 20 on the field when Dagny
Meligren of Norway shocked the partisan crowd with the 25-yard game
winner in the game's waning seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. defenders gave Meligren too much room to maneuver,
Heinrichs said. ``One of my assistant coaches turned to me and
said, `They didn't earn that, we gave it to them,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mistake by Pryce, who was otherwise praised by
Heinrichs afterward, that allowed Norway to take a 1-0 lead in the
game's 19th minute. She tapped a back pass too softly toward Webber
near the goal and, as the Norwegian forward Marianne Pettersen
rushed toward the ball, Webber dived on it, tripping Pettersen in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   Pettersen then scored on the resultant penalty kick, driving the
ball by Webber into the left corner.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, not accustomed to playing from behind, countered
in the 25th minute. Going out of bounds, forward Shannon MacMillan
kept the ball in play with a nifty play, then spun and charged
along the right side with the ball. Her 25-yard cross found a
diving Mia Hamm at the goal's mouth, and Hamm's bouncing header
eluded goalie Bente Nordby to tie the game at 1-1. It was the 115th
goal of Hamm's international career.
</P>
<P>
   The United States took a 2-1 lead in the 71st minute on Kristine
Lilly's unassisted goal, but 10 minutes later the veteran defender
Carla Overbeck, a substitute Sunday, was charged with an own goal,
though Heinrichs acknowledged that it was more Webber's fault than
Overbeck's.
</P>
<P>
   That Overbeck, the most valuable player in the United States'
glorious World Cup final, did not enter the game until the 77th
minute had a chilling effect on her veteran teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carla's been our leader for a very long time,'' Hamm said.
``Her not being out there is a huge adjustment for all of us. To
not hear her voice from the back kind of organizing everyone _ she
has such a calming effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to respect the coach's decision. We have to play
with the decisions that are made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
