r s BC-GLF-WOODS-STREAK-TEX     02-06 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-STREAK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME QUESTION MERITS OF WOODS' STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it's better this way. After all, Tiger Woods is only 24
years old. He has an entire career to pursue the records of Ben
Hogan and Byron Nelson that were once regarded as untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, maybe Woods is better off not putting Hogan's
1948 run of six consecutive victories to the test. Heading into
Monday's final round of the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am,
Woods, with five consecutive PGA Tour victories stuffed in his
Nikes, is five strokes out of the lead and in need of a magical
performance along the picturesque Pacific shoreline to capture No.
6.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the enigmatic Hogan did throughout his career, Woods
has come to teach the golfing world that there is no limit to the
number of rabbits he can pull out of his bag, whether he's equipped
with his A-game or not.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Woods were to complete a remarkable comeback Monday at
Pebble Beach, his Midas touch would not make converts of longtime
golf followers who dismiss his current streak. They argue that
Woods' six-pack is not a true streak because the victories were,
plain and simple, not consecutive.
</P>
<P>
   Woods won his final four starts of the 1999 PGA Tour, then lost
two non-PGA Tour events in between the 1999 and 2000 PGA seasons.
Detractors say Woods' streak ended at four and his new streak of
one started with his victory at the Mercedes Championship on Jan.
9.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other feeling to have, frankly. It's not six in a
row,'' said Dan Jenkins, the Fort Worth golf writer who followed
Hogan's career while reporting for the now-defunct ``Fort Worth
Press,'' then 24 years at ``Sports Illustrated'' and finally ``Golf
Digest'' for the past 15 years. ``Sensible people would not call it
six in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   PGA officials, Jenkins said, notwithstanding. This is the
organization that does not count the British Open in its record
books. Hogan won five in a row in 1953, but his British Open
victory is virtually erased from those record books, leaving him
tied with Jackie Burke's four consecutive victories in 1952, and
now one behind Woods' five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we were surprised that Hogan didn't win every time he
played, same with Byron,'' said Jerre Todd, a former sports writer
for the ``Fort Worth Press'' in the 1950s, who then had a 25-year
career as Colonial Country Club's public relations and media
relations director. ``So, winning six, as I recall, wasn't a big
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   If Woods does pull out the improbable victory Monday, his name,
controversies aside, will sit next to Hogan's in the PGA record
books and the countdown to Nelson's 11 in a row _ justifiably or
not _ will go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (the PGA) do, they are going to get laughed at,''
Jenkins said. ``They'll have to put an asterisk by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny,'' Jenkins said. ``Tiger not winning six in
a row has called attention to the fact that Ben did.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods seems to believe his streak is a non-factor. As
little fanfare as Hogan's streak of six received 52 years ago,
Woods has downplayed the attention his run has produced.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said a streak should be contained within one season the
way Hogan and Nelson achieved theirs, although a streak extending
into two seasons would still qualify for the record books. After
the '99 season, Woods finished sixth at the Johnnie Walker Classic
in Taiwan, first at the PGA Grand Slam of Golf in Koloa, Kauai,
Hawaii, and 10th at the Williams World Challenge in Scottsdale,
Ariz. That was prior to the 2000 PGA season that started with his
fifth consecutive PGA Tour victory at the Mercedes Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I still don't really consider it (five)
because it's over two seasons,'' Woods said Wednesday. ``People
forget that I played three tournaments in between the two regular
seasons. I've won two out of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that counts for something, but I don't know if it's
(five) or not. I'm counting that I've won this year once and trying
to win two in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is trying to discount what Woods has accomplished. And
most, like Jenkins, regard Woods as the lone tour player capable of
one day making a run at Nelson's record.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' streak is ``still an amazing streak no matter what,
however you calculate it,'' said Marty Leonard, the daughter of
Colonial founder Marvin Leonard, who bankrolled Hogan during his
early years on the PGA Tour. ``(Hogan) was just so good and so
methodical, for him to win six in a row it wasn't all that big a
deal. It was, but it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks as if Woods will let everyone off easy this time by not
winning his sixth consecutive PGA Tour event and leaving any
controversy for another day. By that time, however, other Hogan
marks of excellence might be under attack once Woods' career spans
a decade or two.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, who was 36 when he won six in a row, was a four-time PGA
Player of the Year; one of four players to win all four Grand Slam
titles; won nine majors (four U.S. Opens, two Masters, two PGA
Championships and one British Open) in an eight-year stretch from
1946 to 1953. He is the only player to win three of the four
current majors in one year when he won the Masters, U.S. Open and
the British Open in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   The greatness of Hogan will almost assuredly be tested by the
evolving greatness of Woods. Just not on this current streak. Or
whatever it should be called.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't a streak,'' Jenkins said. ``That's all I can tell
you.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
