<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SILBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMUEL SILBERMAN, EXECUTIVE AND PHILANTHROPIST, DIES AT 84 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.Y., Conn., Mass., N.J.)  (jw) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Samuel J. Silberman, a philanthropist and former cigar
manufacturing executive, died Jan. 29 in Manhattan. He was 84 and
lived on the Upper East Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Silberman was born in Manhattan, grew up in West Hartford,
Conn., and attended Harvard College. In 1934, he went to work for
the Consolidated Cigar Corp., which had been founded by his
maternal grandfather, Julius Lichtenstein. Silberman's father,
Alfred, who was a tobacco grower, became Consolidated's president
later.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Silberman rose to be the chief executive and chairman of
the corporation, based in Manhattan, and by 1964, had headed many
charity campaigns in the cigar industry.
</P>
<P>
   In that year, he donated $4 million to New York City for social
work education and research. His largess led to, among other
things, the construction of the Hunter College School of Social
Work building, on East 79th Street between Park and Lexington
avenues, and the creation of awards for educators and scholarships
for students.
</P>
<P>
   He was president of the Federation of Jewish Philanthropies of
New York from 1966 to 1969 after serving the federation as a
campaign chairman in 1957 and 1958.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, another beneficiary of his support, Fairleigh Dickinson
University's Samuel J. Silberman College of Business
Administration, was named in his honor. It has its headquarters in
Teaneck, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Silberman was on the national board of trustees of the
Conference of Christians and Jews and a chairman of the Association
of Governing Boards of Universities and Colleges. In addition, he
was co-chairman of the Lois and Samuel Silberman Fund, which is now
a supporting organization of the New York Community Trust. His
daughter Dr. Jayne Silberman, a social worker, is now the fund's
vice chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Silberman was also on a number of other boards in the worlds of
philanthropy, education and business.
</P>
<P>
   The honors he received included the Hunter College President's
Medal and a Brotherhood Award of the National Conference of
Christians and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   An early marriage ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his daughter Jayne, Silberman is survived by his
wife of 39 years, the former Lois Voltter; four sons, Douglas,
Allen, Alfred and Peter; another daughter, Rita Rothenberg; and six
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-00 2328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
