u a BC-CRASH-FAMILIES-SPI &LR;      02-06 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FAMILIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES OF ALASKA CRASH VICTIMS HEADING HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACY JOHNSON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXNARD, Calif. _ As Navy ships continued to scour the waves for
remnants of Flight 261 Sunday, the families of the 88 people killed
in the jet crash were heading for home.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow tape that closed the Port Hueneme beach for nearly a
week was gone, and this city of small shops and berry farms was
slowly returning to normal.
</P>
<P>
   But heaps of bouquets, Teddy bears and candles reminded those
walking the sandy shoreline of Port Hueneme that something had gone
terribly wrong off the coast.
</P>
<P>
   A few people who lost relatives in last Monday's crash came to
the beach to say a final goodbye, said Red Cross spokesman
Christopher Thomas. But most, he said, were leaving the Los Angeles
area after a week of leaning on each other and trying to come to
grips with their losses.
</P>
<P>
   Loaded with luggage, shopping bags and souvenirs, dozens boarded
airport-bound buses at the Wyndham Hotel. Others stood outside in
the hazy sun, hugging one another and vowing to stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Some toted plastic bottles of water they had dredged from the
ocean, a memento of the lives lost in it.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines set up a full-service ticket counter in the
hotel lobby, where workers helped people arrange their return
flights.
</P>
<P>
   Some had come from the Seattle area; others from across the
country and beyond. Most were headed back to homes that would never
feel the same.
</P>
<P>
   The past week brought both pain and healing for the families,
who visited the crash site and were updated daily about the
National Transportation Safety Board investigation.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 climbed aboard a Coast Guard vessel Thursday to see
the fateful place the jet hit the water and crumbled. Being so
close was heartbreaking, said one man who had two relatives on the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oil and the foam was still rising to the top,'' he said.
``Everybody was crying. Even some of the Coast Guard (crew) had
tears in their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   And more than 1,000 people crowded into a fieldhouse Saturday at
Pepperdine University, nestled on a palm-tree-lined Malibu hillside
overlooking the ocean, for a formal memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   They placed roses in baskets, which were flown to the crash site
by two Coast Guard helicopters and released.
</P>
<P>
   They prayed by the light of 88 white candles, and they watched
88 doves take to the sky.
</P>
<P>
   At sea Sunday morning, the U.S.S. Cleveland and other Navy
vessels worked to salvage debris and human remains. The Conifer and
the Steadfast, two Coast Guard cutters, kept other boats out of the
area in the recovery effort's sixth day.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the ships had returned to shore, where crews planned
to rest and replenish their supplies. They will return to sea
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred human remains had been brought ashore by Sunday
afternoon, but investigators believed they would only be able to
identify between 30 and 50 of them, said Ventura County Sheriff's
spokesman Eric Nishimoto.
</P>
<P>
   The process would be tricky and time-consuming, but would be
helped by information the victims' relatives had provided about
jewelry, scars and tattoos, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plane hit the water at a very high speed,'' Nishimoto
said. ``There is extensive trauma to all of the remains that we've
recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the MD-83 jet rests hundreds of feet under water, and
NTSB officials will decide in the coming weeks which parts they
will raise to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday they continued video-taping the ocean floor, piecing
together a map of the wreckage to glean answers about what caused
the plane to topple from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   On shore, waves rolled and retreated over soggy flowers people
had tossed from the Port Hueneme pier.
</P>
<P>
   People continued bringing flowers to the memorials that dotted
the beach, and others crowded around them silently. Two young girls
struggled to light some of the candles in the afternoon wind.
</P>
<P>
   A monument stood in the sand, erected for South San Francisco
Fire Department veteran Bob Ost, his wife, Ileana, and their
newborn daughter, Emily.
</P>
<P>
   All three were killed in the crash. A family friend had written
a poem in their memory, which read in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``The earth will be less happy tonight, but heaven above will
shine with their light.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
