<SLUG> BC-HKN-ALLSTAR-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOKING IN A LANGUAGE THEY UNDERSTAND 
A BIT OF NOSTALGIA 
FOCUSING ON MESSIER
</HEADLINE>
   (With HKN-ALLSTAR-GAME, HKN-ALLSTAR-COLUMN) 
(rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Scotty Bowman, the Detroit coach, was behind the bench
for the World team, which won Sunday's NHL All-Star Game by 9-4
over North America at the Air Canada Center. Although the European
players speak English at various levels of skill, Bowman was aware
of the linguistic variety on his roster and pretended to warn them
about talking in their native tongues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `I know you have had all this diversity
training,''' said Bowman, a Montreal native who speaks French.
``But I said, `As soon as I finish talking' _ I was kidding them _
I said, `I don't want to hear another word of Russian, Czech,
Slovakian, Finnish, Swedish.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they kind of believed me for about a second. I said,
`Look, do what you have to do.' They all have friends and they talk
together.
</P>
<P>
   A Bit of Nostalgia
</P>
<P>
   ABC Sports began its new contract with the NHL Sunday, and one
of the highlights of the telecast was a video that was also played
on the screen at Air Canada Center.
</P>
<P>
   It showed the retired players Gordie Howe, Wayne Gretzky and
Mario Lemieux visiting an outdoor pond and talking about missing
the game. Playing on the ice were Eric Lindros, Pavel Bure, Jaromir
Jagr and Paul Kariya, the current stars. Instead of joining in, the
older players walk away, essentially turning the game over to the
younger players.
</P>
<P>
   The video got a positive reaction from the fans in the seats and
also from the players on the ice. Some of them applauded with their
hands and others tapped sticks on the ice in tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Quenneville, the coach of St. Louis and an assistant for
the World team, said: ``When I first heard that they were going to
do it, I was almost shivering. When I saw it, I almost had a tear
going down my cheek. It was a special moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky said it took four or five hours to tape the video but
that the players enjoyed doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just nice to talk to all of them, to be around them and
see the new guys, the young guys, and talk to them about the game
today and listen to Gordie and Mario tell stories about hockey,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on Messier
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky, whose No. 99 was retired from use in NHL games
Sunday, addressed the question of when the Rangers should retire
his number.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I told them was that I felt that Mark Messier deserved to
have his sweater hung there before anyone else,'' he said. ``So I
probably won't do anything until after that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 14th All-Star Game, Mark Messier of the Vancouver Canucks
had an assist Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He also had the Devils' 20-year-old rookie, Scott Gomez, as his
linemate. ``Unreal,'' Gomez said of the experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
