<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8734 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-VOTING-NYT     02-06 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-VOTING-NYT </SLUG>
 
VOTING RIGHTS UNDERMINED  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Feb. 7:
</P>
<P>
   In a deeply troubling voting rights decision last month, the
Supreme Court greatly weakened a powerful tool that the federal
government has long used to end racial discrimination in voting
rights. The tool, known as ``preclearance,'' has acted as an
important deterrent to efforts by local communities to change their
voting laws in ways that could discriminate against minority
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves the Bossier Parish School Board in Louisiana,
which after the 1990 census drew up 12 districts, none of which had
black majorities even though African-Americans make up about 20
percent of the parish's population. Under Section 5 of the 1965
Voting Rights Act, Bossier Parish, like other jurisdictions with a
history of discriminatory voting practices, was required to seek
preclearance from the Justice Department or a federal court before
enacting any voting change. The jurisdiction had to prove that the
change ``does not have the purpose and will not have the effect of
denying or abridging the right to vote on account of race or
color.'' The Justice Department found that the school board's plan
had a discriminatory purpose and refused to preclear it after the
NAACP proposed an alternative plan showing that it was possible to
create two majority-black districts. For years, the Justice
Department has denied preclearance unless the jurisdiction could
show that its plan had no discriminatory purpose and would not
weaken black voting power. Both tests are important because there
have been cases where there was a discriminatory purpose but no
actual backsliding because minority voting strength was so low that
it was almost impossible to make things worse.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing for the 5-4 majority, defied
decades of practice and precedent in reinterpreting the ``purpose''
test. He argued that general discriminatory intent was not reason
enough to deny preclearance. Instead, he maintained that the only
prohibited purpose under Section 5 was the specific intent to cause
backsliding. That severely weakens the Justice Department's power
to stop discriminatory plans before they take effect.
</P>
<P>
   The majority points out that illegal discriminatory intent and
practices, though they cannot be stopped in advance, can still be
challenged in court. But the victims of discrimination would have
to bear the burden of proof and spend years in litigation. As
Justice David Souter wrote in dissent, the point of Section 5 is to
prevent defiant jurisdictions from staying one step ahead of court
challenges to any particular voting scheme by replacing it with an
equally discriminatory alternative.
</P>
<P>
   This harmful decision comes on the eve of the 2000 census, which
will be the basis for redistricting plans in all states.
Discrimination in voting rights is still a problem. Yet the federal
government will now be forced to preclear illegal redistricting
schemes intended to perpetuate that evil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
