A8736 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DRUGTRAFFICKING-KAN &LR;      02-06 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER'S QUESTIONS AT AIRPORT TRIGGER DRUG INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
 TRAFFICKING-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The drug investigation that has rattled Kansas City football
fans began with an officer asking a couple of questions of four men
who arrived at a California airport from Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Since that start in November 1997, the case has led to
drug-trafficking convictions of at least six men in California and
Missouri and pending criminal charges against seven others, court
records show.
</P>
<P>
   Already the investigation has shut down a drug pipeline that for
years brought more than 200 pounds of cocaine into the Kansas City
area every month, court records say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very productive investigation,'' said Kevin
Rooney, an assistant U.S. attorney in Fresno, Calif. ``We're very
pleased with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those convicted are cooperating with federal authorities
and have begun identifying their contacts in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the release of an affidavit in support of new charges
in the case revealed that a current and a former member of the
Kansas City Chiefs have come under FBI surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors recently filed charges against Gregory E. Burns of
Lee's Summit, Mo., who has described himself as kick returner
Tamarick Vanover's personal assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show the drug-trafficking charges against Burns
stemmed from a 27-month inquiry of a cocaine ring based in Fresno
and extending to Kansas City and Nashville, Tenn. Burns has pleaded
not guilty to the charges, and his lawyer has declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Vanover, who has not been charged, declined on Saturday to
discuss the case or his role in it with The Kansas City Star. He
would not say whether he had retained a lawyer to represent him in
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment,'' Vanover said.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit links Vanover to at least two stolen cars and
notes that he came under surveillance during the investigation of
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Former Chiefs running back Bam Morris was found riding in a
vehicle that FBI agents said was used to transport drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' agent has denied that his client, who also has not been
charged, had any role in the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   `At the top'
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is unusual in that it started with the
prosecution of people who were allegedly at or near the top of the
trafficking conspiracy, Rooney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got lucky and had a hit at the top and worked out,'' Rooney
said. ``Usually we start at the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a Fresno police officer stopped four men getting off a
plane from Kansas City, according to testimony in a federal drug
case prosecuted last year in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men, Ricky Gray, already had been convicted of
federal drug offenses in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The officer's supervisor soon obtained a search warrant for the
Fresno home of Victor L. Brown, a young financier who accompanied
Gray.
</P>
<P>
   At Brown's home, police recovered $1.1 million in cash, a
money-counting machine and loaded weapons, Dennis Vasquez of the
Fresno Police Department testified in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez said prosecutors held off charging Brown, hoping to
learn who else was involved.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 7, 1998, agents raided the home of Brown's father and
recovered about 12 pounds of cocaine, three firearms and $12,000 in
cash, Vasquez said.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery led directly to drug-trafficking charges against
Brown, who has pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   KC connection
</P>
<P>
   Brown's arrest put an immediate crimp in the cocaine supply
coming into Kansas City, testimony in federal court in Kansas City
showed.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Nunez, a convicted drug broker from Fresno, testified
that he supplied Brown with about 100 pounds of cocaine in the year
before Brown's arrest. Without Brown's money, he testified, finding
cocaine in Mexico to ship to Kansas City became almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brown) had a lot of money,'' Nunez testified. ``When you had
money, you could pretty much find cocaine anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But hoping to re-establish a California-to-Missouri cocaine
link, Nunez began talking to Gray in late November 1998, telling
Gray he needed to come up with at least $500,000 in cash to get
back into the cocaine business. Gray could scrounge together only
about $9,000, however, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them it wasn't nearly enough, but we can go to Fresno
and see...what we can do,'' Nunez said.
</P>
<P>
   With the promise of full payment from his Kansas City
connection, Nunez persuaded a drug source in Nogales, Mexico, to
supply about 100 pounds of cocaine on credit. On Jan. 15, 1999,
Nunez delivered the cocaine to Gray in Phoenix. Gray packed it away
in a rented motor home and began driving to Kansas City, court
records show.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez then boarded a Southwest Airlines flight from Phoenix to
Kansas City, where he hoped to be paid $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   That plan collapsed the next day. Gray was pulled over by an
Oklahoma Highway Patrol trooper who discovered the drugs. Gray
immediately began cooperating with the FBI, according to an FBI
affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 17, Nunez and Clarence Burnett, a self-employed Kansas
City real estate broker with four felony tampering and burglary
convictions, were arrested by FBI agents as they approached Gray's
Grandview home.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nunez, Gray and Burnett were convicted of
drug-trafficking charges in federal court in Kansas City. Nunez and
Gray have begun cooperating with authorities, court records say.
Burnett also has supplied the FBI with information but has
requested a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett soon identified Burns, Vanover's personal assistant, as
one of Victor Brown's cocaine customers, according to recent court
records.
</P>
<P>
   And Gray has acknowledged selling Burns about 12 pounds of
cocaine a month from the 200-pound deliveries he would make to
Kansas City before Brown was arrested, the records state.
</P>
<P>
   New developments
</P>
<P>
   Three other men _ Chad Pollard and Logan Gearheart, both of
Kansas City, Kan., and Anthony West of Kansas City _ have been
charged in Kansas City with drug trafficking. Court records
indicate that both Gearheart and West are cooperating with the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Court records also show that Pollard is a suspect in the 1997
drug-related shooting deaths of two Kansas City, Kan., men. He has
pleaded not guilty to the drug charges and has not been charged in
the homicides.
</P>
<P>
   And in California, Brown and two other men are awaiting trial in
the drug case. Three others, including Brown's father, James D.
Brown, and a Tennessee man have pleaded guilty and are cooperating,
Rooney said.
</P>
<P>
   As Nunez noted in his testimony last year, there is not a lot of
trust in the drug business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of greed and a lot of people (who) would go rob
somebody or kill them to take their cocaine from them,'' Nunez
said. ``It is a lot easier, sometimes, than stealing from a bank.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
